(144, 140, 28, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hi Linda, <\\/p><p>My back ground in childcare is based on raising my 2 children aged 11 and 8. I did however, complete work based training at a SEN school in Stoke on Trent. I started&nbsp; new career after my son was born within the care industry. This was providing care and support for Independent Living in the Community. The support I provided could be anything from&nbsp;personal care to encouraging&nbsp;social activities independently or accompanied. I progressed&nbsp;my career by becoming a senior career in a local Nursing\\/Residential Home, where I had a team of careers who I managed. &nbsp;The home specialised in&nbsp;Dementia Care. I left this role due to relocation to Stockport. I am currently employed as a Personal Assistant to Director in a small office. I deal with HR issues, payroll and day to day administration. I am not currently able to volunteer, however I do help out at the&nbsp;local dance school.&nbsp;I assist with show preparations, and local&nbsp;organised events. This can be anything from assisting with costumes, hair, make-up to helping the principle with ticket&nbsp;sales, advertising,&nbsp;and&nbsp;organising the children. I am hoping to volunteer in one of the local schools.&nbsp;<\\/p><p>I am really looking forward&nbsp;to getting started with the course, and would like to start the units in order as displayed&nbsp;?<\\/p><p>Thank you for your message. Can I confirm, is email\\/message the only form of contact I have with you ? <\\/p><p>Many Thanks<\\/p><p>Elizabeth (Lizzie)<br><\\/p>\"}', 1516194710, 1, 0, 0),
(145, 65, 134, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hi Emma,<\\/p><p>Thank you for your message and submission. I have total faith that you can do it and I am here to help you through.<\\/p><p>I am going to have to start by asking you to resubmit this though, because something has gone wrong with the upload and I am not able to open it! It is no reflection of your learning or grades. Please ensure that you submit it as a doc or docx file. Thank you so much.<\\/p><p>Kind regards<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Sarah<br><\\/p>\"}', 1516195755, 1, 0, 0),
(146, 28, 82, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Ok<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-size: 1rem;\\\">Leave it with you then<\\/span><br><\\/p><p>I, here is you need any help with your Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools course though<\\/p><p>Bye for now<\\/p><p>Linda<\\/p>\"}', 1516216451, 1, 0, 0),
(147, 28, 140, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello Elizabeth<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Thank you for responding to my welcome email so quickly<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Your years of experience in social care will no doubt help you to understand these units, and your experience of working alongside young people and adults, and so will all be useful to your future studies if you wish to pursue a Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools full qualification later.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>The Level 3 \\u2013 Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools AWARD, is a great start to your journey as a qualified Teaching Assistant.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>The course will encourage you to read and research for the information needed in order to answer the questions, and allow your study skills to develop.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Later, if you decide to further your training to a full&nbsp; Level 2 or Level 3 Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools Qualification, these units will be of great use t you.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I look forward to working alongside you in your studies Elizabeth&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I am afraid that emails, are the only way we can communicate.&nbsp; But if you have any questions regarding your coursework, or need any other advice, please feel free to ask me<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I will now be sending you some further emails with Advice Sheets for you to look at.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I hope you will find them useful for your studies.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Bye for now<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Linda Broome-Smith<\\/p><div><br><\\/div>\"}', 1516217095, 1, 0, 0),
(148, 28, 140, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello Elizabeth<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Just thought I would send this advice note to you, so you can understand how to make the most of your feedback forms.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Even if, at first glance, you can see that your work has received a PASS grade, you should still always read through your \\u2018Feedback Form\\u2019 carefully.&nbsp; There could be things I have asked you to address in your next unit, or study skills to undertake, or text and references to read through, before your next unit of work is submitted for marking.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>So here is the following explanation on how to successfully read through your feedback Forms.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>At the very top of your form you will see the time and date when your work was marked.&nbsp; The date and time here will reflect being marked within 10 working days of receipt of your submission.&nbsp; (Ten working days, being \\u2018Two Weeks\\u2019)&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Your own name, and the name and level of your course will also be here, at the top of the page.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>There is also a section highlighted to say YES \\/ NO \\u2013 Whichever is highlighted, will tell you a quick glance, whether your unit submission has received a PASS grade or has been Referred back to you, for amendments.&nbsp; &nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The next section is entitled - Learner Achievement Summary:<\\/p><p>This is the overall summary and general comments about the work that you have submitted for marking.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The next section is entitled - Specific Areas of Noteworthy Recognition:<\\/p><p>This is a list of the Knowledge and Understanding Questions and the Practical Placement Assessment Criteria, which have been successfully completed.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The next section is entitled - Further Areas of Development Required:<\\/p><p>Here will be listed any Knowledge and Understanding Questions or Practical Placement Assessment Criteria, which still need amending.&nbsp; This section will also have my own feedback comments, in order to help you to successfully resubmit your work next time.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The next section is entitled - Action Plan including date(s): This will remind you what you need to do, in order to resubmit your work again successfully for marking.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>When you have resubmitted your work again for marking, (if indeed necessary to do so) you will be sent a new \\u2018Feedback Form\\u2019.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\uf0d8<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Please always save a copy of your \\u2018Feedback Forms\\u2019 for your own reference.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>If you have any further questions, please do not hesitate to contact me<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Regards<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Linda Broome-Smith<\\/p><p>NCC \\u2013 Support Tutor<\\/p><div><br><\\/div>\"}', 1516217144, 1, 0, 0),
(149, 28, 140, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Advice for answering your course questions effectively<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>In your studies, you will be challenged to show your knowledge and understanding of particular topics in the form of questions to answer.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p><p>Whilst answering the criteria, you will need to provide evidence of your knowledge and understanding of the topic set.<\\/p><p>In order to challenge you in this way, the criteria are worded in particular ways, and it is extremely important that you present your evidence in the particular way it has been set.&nbsp; If you do not, you might find that your work is referred back to you due to the answer not being fully met in the way it was asked to be presented.<\\/p><p>Please have a look at the tips provided below, and also look through the \\u2018Glossary of Terms\\u2019 that I have also sent, in order to help you to understand the ways in which the questions should be answered.<\\/p><p>If you need any further help, please do not hesitate to ask me.<\\/p><p>&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>#1 - Before you try to answer any questions \\u2018ALWAYS\\u2019 read the question fully and carefully at least twice. Take your time to be sure exactly what is being asked of you.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>#2- The first word of the criteria question explains in which way the question should be answered.&nbsp; This verb is very important in order to understand the way in which the question needs to be answered.&nbsp; Please refer to the \\u2018Glossary of Terms\\u2019 that I have sent through to you, in order to fully explain this.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>#3 - After you read through the question twice, it could be helpful for you to highlight the FIRST word, and then underline all the important features of the question.&nbsp; Then you can focus on these words throughout your answer and also remind yourself not to miss them out.&nbsp; For example:<\\/p><p>\\u201cExplain the importance of reflecting practice in continuously improving the quality of service.\\u201d<\\/p><p>Your answer therefore would not be just as statement of what reflection is, but why it is such an important skill to use, and why it should be a continuous practice in order to improve service.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>#4 - Some questions may ask you for a \\u2018Range\\u2019 of ideas.&nbsp; When the word \\u2018Range\\u2019 appears in the criteria question, you must give at least \\u2018three\\u2019 examples for the range to be valid.&nbsp; You can have as many as you like BUT a minimum of three is required.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>#5- Some questions have more than one part to them.&nbsp; That is why it is important to read them through at least twice.&nbsp; Some questions will be bullet pointed.&nbsp; In this case you will not be able to fully answer the question unless all the elements have been addressed.&nbsp; For example;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\u201cExplain what is meant by:&nbsp;<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Diversity<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Equality<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Inclusion<\\/p><p>In order for you to answer this question fully, all three headings would have to be used and answered separately.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>#6 \\u2013 Don\\u2019t forget that the questions are asking you to show YOUR knowledge and understanding, not just repeating what your study materials are stating.&nbsp; In order for you to portray your own knowledge and understanding make sure you have done some independent reading and research as well as using the NCC study materials.&nbsp; This will give you perspective in your work.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p><p>However, the best way to do this is to ALWAYS try to back up what you are writing with an example from your own practice, sharing what you have said or done to bring the information to life. This shows that you both understand the information AND how it can be used in good practice.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>#Finally:<\\/p><p>I hope that this advice sheet has been useful to you.<\\/p><p>If you need any further assistance, please do not hesitate to contact me<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Regards<\\/p><p>Linda Broome-Smith<\\/p><p>NCC Support Tutor<\\/p><div><br><\\/div>\"}', 1516217185, 1, 0, 0),
(150, 28, 140, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello Elizabeth<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I hope you are well.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Please find attached two advice handouts that I have recently created, which may be of help to you when answering the criteria questions for your course evidence.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Glossary of Terms<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Advice on how to answer your course questions effectively.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I hope they are useful to you. If you need any further advice, please do not hesitate to ask me<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Glossary of Terms<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Analyse<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>You will need to examine the topic in detail.&nbsp; Exploring the meaning, covering essential features and their significance.&nbsp; This often requires providing more than one perspective on the topic.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Therefore you should make your statement, explain the importance of this practice and then consider the consequences of not following the good practices through.&nbsp; This will allow you to show a well rounded knowledge of the question.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Assess<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Fully \\u2018analyse\\u2019 a topic and then make at least one reasoned judgement or conclusion for it.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Consider<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Examine a topic in detail to explore its features and significance.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Compare<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Provide clear and comprehensive details about similarities and differences of the topic in question<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Complete<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Do everything that is asked of you within the question \\/ task.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Current and relevant<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>This means making sure that you have the most up to date information about the topic.&nbsp; You can make use of traditional theories to support your arguments if relevant \\/ or \\/ use current research from a variety of sources to support your work.&nbsp; Reading and research would be required in order to answer this type of question thoroughly.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Describe \\u2018HOW\\u2019<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Provide clear and comprehensive details about the topic in order to show the processes that are essential for good practice.&nbsp; The answer MUST describe details of HOW something is done.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Describe \\u2018WHY\\u2019<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Provide clear and comprehensive details about the topic in order to show the processes that are essential for good practice.&nbsp; This could be based on observation, own practices, theories etc of good practice.&nbsp; The answer MUST contain a rationale as to WHY something is done and its importance.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Develop<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Expand or give a fuller or greater meaning to a topic.&nbsp; Add extra ideas or plan a way to extend or add extra components to the topic.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Discuss<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Examine a topic from more than one aspect.&nbsp; You need to show the different issues that should be considered.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Evaluate<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Review theory or your practices, in a way that shows clearly the points both for and against and then make a reasonable judgement.&nbsp; This would involve pros and cons or other points of view<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Explain<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Provide details about a topic, with reasons or examples based on practice, observation, and \\/ or \\/ theories which will help others to understand the topic.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Identify<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Recognise and use main points.&nbsp; You could use bullet points, but make sure that you also add a sentence to briefly explain, or describe too.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Include<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Add or put in specific information.&nbsp; If the question has asked you to \\u2018include\\u2019 certain elements, you must have these in your answer.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Plan<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Organise information in a suitable way for the topic\\/question\\/task involved.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Reflect<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Consider in depth, your practices and provide reasons for current experiences or situations which will inform your future practice\\/judgement\\/change.<\\/p><p>If the question asks you to reflect on your own practice, you will need to give examples of what you have down or said, within your own practice experience.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Summarise<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Present all of the main points in a concise way, by rounding up what you mean to say.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Demonstrate<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>If this appears on the question, you MUST demonstrate this skill or skills to you assessor \\/ mentor \\/ expert witness.&nbsp; Their report MUST be written on the Witness Testimony reports provided in the appendices of your study book.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>By all means have some written evidence to back this up, such as a Reflective Journal entry, but the skill MUST be demonstrated by observation also, in order to demonstrate your competence.<\\/p><p>Show<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>If this appears on the question, you MUST show that this skill or skills are present to you assessor \\/ mentor \\/ expert witness.&nbsp; Their report MUST be written on the Witness Testimony reports provided in the appendices of your study book.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>By all means have some written evidence to back this up, such as a Reflective Journal entry, but the skill MUST be demonstrated by observation also, in order to show your competence.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p>\"}', 1516217276, 1, 0, 0);
INSERT INTO `message` (`id`, `sender`, `receiver`, `text`, `created_at`, `viewed`, `hide_to_sender`, `hide_to_receiver`) VALUES
(151, 28, 140, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>During your course, there will be a lot of reading and research needed, in order to find the information you will need to show your knowledge and understanding of the Assessment Criteria questions, asked of you.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Your reading and research will take on many forms, such as:&nbsp;<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Your NCC course materials<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Books&nbsp;<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Internet research<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Magazines, articles<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Television programme<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Own placements policies and procedures\\u2026\\u2026..to name but a few\\u2026\\u2026.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>When using these sources you will need to cite them in your work accordingly, and will need to list them in a bibliography which you will need to create at the end of your Assessment Criteria, for the unit assignment.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Please find attached an advice sheet, which will help you to do this.&nbsp; You also will find pages about referencing in your NCC Study materials<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>If you have any further questions, please do not hesitate to ask me<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Referencing<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>In order to successfully complete you course, you must ensure that your work is correctly referenced throughout!<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Referencing is a simple practice that you the learner must complete when producing your activities for this course. When completing your assessments, although for the most part you should answer in your own words from what you have learnt and your own experiences, you will also be expected to refer to knowledge found in academic texts (where relevant), to back up your arguments.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>How to Reference<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>When completing assignment questions, it is important that any quotations or material produced by others that you use include in your answer, are \\u2018cited\\u2019 and included in a \\u2018bibliography\\u2019. This is to ensure that others reading your text can find the original source and more importantly to show that the quoted material is originally produced by someone else and is not your own.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\u2018Citing\\u2019 is simple enough to complete but is very important. It is basically an acknowledgement of who wrote the material you are including (the author) and what year the book was published (date). NOTE: Only the authors surname needs to be used.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Citing should be included appropriately at some point in the quote that you are using at either the beginning or end of the quote would be most logical.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Cited quotes, need to also make up part of your bibliography, which is explained in a moment.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>For example:<\\/p><p>You may decide to include the following quote you have found in a book:<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Current thinking, based on research, supports the view that parental involvement\\u2026<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>This needs to be cited and it should be changed to look like the below:<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Current thinking, based on research, supports the view that parental involvement\\u2026<\\/p><p>(Kay 2005)<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>OR<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>As Kay (2005, p.5) said, \\u2018Current thinking, based on research, supports the view that parental involvement\\u2026\\u2019 we are now lead to believe\\u2026<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>How are sources referenced in the main text of the answer?<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>If you are using direct quotes from sources or writing other peoples\\u2019 ideas in your own words, you need to give their surname and date in the main body of the report.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Example:<\\/p><p>&nbsp;Smith (2010) suggested that etc....<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>A direct quote should be indented in the text. Miss a line before and after the quote. Place author\\u2019s surname, date and page number that quote was on in brackets after the quote.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Example:<\\/p><p>Hucker (2001) wrote that up until the 1800\\u2019s, children were regarded as little adults.No special provision was made for them. Babies were swaddled in close fitting blankets to prevent too much movement.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Or<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\u2018Children had to work from a young age. Once laws were established<\\/p><p>regarding child labour, the number of children went down as children became a burden rather than an asset\\u2019. (Hucker 2001 p.g.45).<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Or<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Rousseau, a French philosopher, was revolutionary in his call for children to be able to roam freely. He was the first thinker to identify the importance of play.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>NOTE:&nbsp; - This is only a simple explanation of how to cite quotes, for detailed guidance on this and producing your bibliography, you may find the following website useful:<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>http:\\/\\/www.bournemouth.ac.uk\\/library\\/local-assets\\/how-to\\/docs\\/citing-references.pdf<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Your Bibliography<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>At the end of your assignment you will need to provide a Bibliography, showing all the sources you have used (including any material you may have downloaded from the internet.)<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>What is the purpose of a bibliography?<\\/p><p>It enables the reader to check the sources that you have used in the report. It<\\/p><p>acknowledges the people that you have quoted in the main body of the report<\\/p><p>and thus avoids plagiarism<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>&nbsp;How is it written?<\\/p><p>The conventional method for writing a bibliography is the Harvard system.<\\/p><p>Use the following formats below when referencing your bibliography.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Bibliography for use of a Book<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Author (surname, initial) date title publisher place where published.<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The title of the book is usually written in italics, bold, or underlined to make it stand out.<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The date of publication is in (brackets)<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The name of the publisher<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>The town of the publisher<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>However, there are slightly different ways to do this according to how many authors were involved with the writing of the book.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>If only one author is involved, their surname and initial is used.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>For example:<\\/p><p>DAVIES. A (1999) Women\\u2019s Roles Penguin, New York<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>If there are two authors involved, then both their surnames and initials are used.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>For example:<\\/p><p>TASSONI. P &amp; HUCKER.K (2000) Planning Play and the Early Years, Heinemann,Oxford.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>If there are more than two authors involved, then the first authors surname and initial is used and the words \\u2018et al\\u2019 (which is latin for&nbsp; \\u2018and others\\u2019) is put in the place of the authors.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>For example:<\\/p><p>TASSONI. P. Et Al . 2000) Planning Play and the Early Years<\\/p><p>Heinemann, Oxford<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Bibliography for use of a Journal, magazine, newspaper<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>The Title is placed in \\u2018inverted commas\\u2019 because the article is part of a magazine, the exact page numbers need to also be indicated.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Example:<\\/p><p>\\u2018Body Survey\\u2019 Marie Claire. No.153, May 2001, pp.75-78.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Bibliography for use of Websites<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>For websites found the required elements for a reference are:<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Authorship or Source<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Year of publication<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>Title of web document or web page.&nbsp;<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>(latest update) available at: web site address&nbsp;<\\/p><p>\\u2022<span style=\\\"white-space:pre\\\">\\t<\\/span>[Accessed date].<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Example:<\\/p><p>Wikipedia (2010). Genie (Feral child). (Updated 28 Jan 2010)<\\/p><p>Available at: http:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Genie_%28feral_child%29<\\/p><p>[Accessed 31 Jan 2010].<\\/p><p>The title of a web page is normally the main heading on the page and the URL should be underlined.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>It is good practice to keep a copy of the front page of any website you use, then you can easily refer to it again another time.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Plagiarism and Academic Malpractice<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>When you become an NCC student, it is understood that you will present your completed assignments having undertaken your own study or research. It is important to note that NCC will not accept plagiarism or other forms of academic malpractice.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>NCC reserves the right to withdraw a student from their programme of learning where it is clearly identified that academic malpractice including plagiarism, collusion, fabrication or falsification of results has occurred.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>For additional information, please contact student services and request a copy of NCC\\u2019s policy.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>For more guidance on plagiarism please see: http:\\/\\/www.plagiarism.org\\/<\\/p><div><br><\\/div>\"}', 1516217365, 1, 0, 0),
