(212, 28, 179, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Thank you for responding to my welcome email so quickly<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>It is nice to know a little about you Jade.&nbsp; Your experience looking after your nephew and having working experience in a nursery and a school, will no doubt, allow you to see the working environments that are open to you.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>The Level 3 \\u2013 Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools AWARD, is a great start to your journey as a qualified Teaching Assistant.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>The course will encourage you to read and research for the information needed in order to answer the questions, and allow your study skills to develop.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Later, if you decide to further your training to a full&nbsp; Level 2 or Level 3 Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools Qualification, these units will be of great use t you.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I look forward to working alongside you in your studies&nbsp;<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>If you have any questions, please feel free to ask me<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I will now be sending you some further emails with Advice Sheets for you to look at.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I hope you will find them useful for your studies.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Bye for now<\\/p><div>Linda<\\/div>\"}', 1517188240, 1, 0, 0),
(213, 28, 179, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello Jade<\\/p><p>Thank you for your email.<\\/p><p>I am afraid, that I am not your tutor for the Autism Awareness Course, only for the Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools Level 3 AWARD<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>I am sorry, but you will need to talk to student support team, in order to find out who your other tutor may be<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Regards<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Linda Broome-Smith<\\/p><p><br><\\/p>\"}', 1517188423, 1, 0, 0),
(214, 28, 179, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello Jade<\\/p><p>Thank you&nbsp; for your email<\\/p><p>I think that we need to establish if you are talking about your Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools AWARD course or your Autism Awareness?<\\/p><p>If you are talking about your Supporting Teaching and Learning in Schools AWARD then here is some advice for question 1.1.1&nbsp;<\\/p><p>Please DO NOT worry about the word count for this question.<\\/p><p>You will need to cover the main S.P.I.C.E developmental areas between the ages from birth to 19 years of age .<\\/p><p>S - Social<\\/p><p>P \\u2013 Physical&nbsp;<\\/p><p>I - Intellectual<\\/p><p>C \\u2013 Communication&nbsp;<\\/p><p>E - Emotional<\\/p><p>S - Social<\\/p><p>You can do this free hand or use a grid system to cover all areas.&nbsp; You only need a few main points for each area and age range<\\/p><p>In order to answer this question fully, you will need to show your understanding of the way in which children develop their new skills in all areas, throughout the ages of birth through to 19 years of age.<\\/p><p>There is no need to recreate pages and pages of text, as you might see in developmental books and charts......an overview of the main developmental changes is more than adequate<\\/p><p>The main thing is to cover birth to 19 and use all SPICE areas as you go<\\/p><p>An Example might look like this:<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p>Birth to 1 Year<\\/p><p>Physical&nbsp;<\\/p><p>By 6 months<\\/p><p>Turn their head toward sounds and movement. Watch an adult\'s face when&nbsp; feeding.&nbsp; Smile at familiar faces and voices . Reach up to hold feet when lying on their backs, Look and reach for objects , Hold and shake a rattle,&nbsp; Put everything in their mouths<\\/p><p>Between 6 months and 1 year:<\\/p><p>Move from sitting with support to sitting alone. Roll over from their tummy to their back. Begin to creep, crawl or shuffle on their bottom, Pull on or push against adult hands or furniture to reach a standing<\\/p><p>Intellectual\\/cognitive<\\/p><p>Enjoys games like peek a boo, will turn head to the source of different sounds.<\\/p><p>Communication<\\/p><p>&nbsp;Between 0 and 3 months<\\/p><p>Makes a variety of \\u201chappy\\u201d sounds. Will respond to a variety music and other sounds, Babies watch their carers face especially the mouth and try to copy its movements<\\/p><p>Between 6 and 12 months:<\\/p><p>Babbling sounds begin and Baby will make four or five different sounds.&nbsp; Laugh and chuckle to show enjoyment<\\/p><p>Social, behavioural and moral<\\/p><p>0-3 month<\\/p><p>Responds to adults especially mothers face and voice. Smiles, concentrates on adults face during feeding, Very dependent on adults for reassurance and comfort, quietens when held and cuddled<\\/p><p>Emotional&nbsp;<\\/p><p>Will show feelings by squealing with pleasure or crying to get attention of the caretaker.<\\/p><div>I hope this is useful to you<\\/div><div><br><\\/div><div>Regards<\\/div><div><br><\\/div><div>Linda Broome-Smith<\\/div><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><br><\\/p>\"}', 1517188666, 1, 0, 0),
