(297, 28, 140, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello Elizabeth<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-size: 1rem;\\\">Thank you for your email<\\/span><br><\\/p><p>Please do read through the feedback on your feedback form for UNIT 1 - Re-Sub - 1<\\/p><p>The theorists and their link to the current practice is no longer the issue.&nbsp; &nbsp;<\\/p><p>BUT you still need to talk about either the EYFS or the National Curriculum and briefly look at how these have affected current practices.<\\/p><p>In fact your example about SEN children being a part of the current practices now is great....but you have not connected it to a code of practice \\/ a legislation \\/ or one of the frameworks in any way.<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-size: 1rem;\\\">If you look at the wording of the question, this is also required to fully complete this answer.<\\/span><br><\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-size: 1rem;\\\">Regards<\\/span><br><\\/p><p>Linda<\\/p>\"}', 1517932707, 1, 0, 0),
(298, 140, 28, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hi Linda, <\\/p><p>I have included the EYFS research in my 2nd answer. I have had to add the extra details at the end of the assignment ? I will copy and paste below the details I have included;<\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\nI am finding it difficult to use \'real life\' scenarios\' due not working in this environment. <\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>The early years foundation stage (EYFS)\\r\\nframework supports the approach to early learning and care. It provides common\\r\\nprinciples and commitments that are to be delivered in quality education and\\r\\nchildcare experiences by all professionals. It also provides confidence to\\r\\nparents of the children who receive early education, that their child is been\\r\\nprovided with the statutory principles and commitments. <\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>The early years foundation seeks to\\r\\nprovide;<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>&nbsp;<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>Quality and consistency <i style=\\\"mso-bidi-font-style:normal\\\">\\u2013 in all early year\\u2019s settings, so that\\r\\nevery child makes good progress and no child gets left behind<\\/i>. This is similar\\r\\nto theory of Pavlov\\u2019s that structure is of a great importance to a child\\u2019s\\r\\ndevelopment. Practitioners working with the youngest children are expected to\\r\\nfocus strongly on the three prime areas, which are the basis for successful\\r\\nlearning. (communication and language, physical development, personal, social\\r\\nand emotional development) <\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>&nbsp;<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>Secure Foundation - <i style=\\\"mso-bidi-font-style:normal\\\">through learning and development\\r\\nopportunities which are planned around the needs and interests of each\\r\\nindividual child and are assessed and reviewed regularly.<\\/i> This is similar\\r\\nto the theory of Paiget. She believed that all children should be recognised as\\r\\nindividuals, with their own individual needs. Practitioners must consider the\\r\\nindividual needs, interests, and stage of development of each child in their\\r\\ncare, and must use this information to plan a challenging and enjoyable\\r\\nexperience for each child in all of the areas of learning and development.<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>&nbsp;<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>Partnership Working - <i style=\\\"mso-bidi-font-style:normal\\\">between practitioners and with parents\\r\\nand\\/or carers. <\\/i>Is similar to the theory that Vygotsky had. This was to encourage\\r\\nand communicate at the correct level for the individual you are communicating\\r\\nwith. This is essential for a child\\u2019s development. Practitioners must discuss\\r\\nwith the child\\u2019s parents and\\/or carers of any cause of concern and agree how to\\r\\nsupport the child. Practitioners must consider whether a child may have a\\r\\nspecial educational need or disability which requires specialist support. They\\r\\nshould link with, and help families to access, relevant services from other\\r\\nagencies as appropriate.<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<br><\\/p><p style=\\\"margin: 0px; line-height: normal;\\\"><span style=\'margin: 0px; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>&nbsp;<\\/span><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<span style=\'margin: 0px; line-height: 107%; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>Equal of Opportunity <i style=\\\"mso-bidi-font-style:&#10;normal\\\">and anti-discriminatory practice, ensuring that every child is included\\r\\nand supported.<\\/i> This is similar to the theory of Bruner. He stated that\\r\\nchildren require encouragement to learn. Like the theory of Paiget, every child\\r\\nis a unique child, who is constantly learning and can be resilient, capable,\\r\\nconfident and self-assured<i style=\\\"mso-bidi-font-style:normal\\\"> <\\/i>in their\\r\\nsurroundings<\\/span><\\/p><p><span style=\'margin: 0px; line-height: 107%; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'><br><\\/span><\\/p><p><span style=\'margin: 0px; line-height: 107%; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>Did you get this piece ? <\\/span><\\/p><p><span style=\'margin: 0px; line-height: 107%; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>Thank you <\\/span><\\/p><p><span style=\'margin: 0px; line-height: 107%; font-family: \\\"Arial\\\",sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\'>Lizzie<br><\\/span><b><\\/b><i><\\/i><u><\\/u><sub><\\/sub><sup><\\/sup><strike><\\/strike><br><\\/p>\"}', 1517933158, 1, 0, 0),
(299, 28, 140, '{\"Message\":\"<p>Hello Elizabeth<\\/p><p>This is all I saw?<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-size:10.0pt;line-height:107%;\\r\\nfont-family:&quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;\\r\\nmso-ansi-language:EN-GB;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA\\\">. <b><i>After\\r\\ndiscussing with a relative, who schooled in the 1960\\u2019s, they became friends\\r\\nwith a child who had a hearing impairment. Both children were able to\\r\\ncommunicate with each other whilst building and maintaining a positive\\r\\nfriendship. When the child was around 7 years old, they were removed from\\r\\nmainstream school. A school \\u2018nowadays\\u2019 would accommodate for that child\\u2019s\\r\\nneeds. Children who have a physical disability, may not have attended school at\\r\\nall. This was due to buildings not been equipped (i.e. steps or doors not wide\\r\\nenough for wheelchair access.) Staffing levels and training was also not\\r\\navailable. During these periods, children who are recognised as Dyslexic in\\r\\ntoday\\u2019s society, may have been labelled as unwilling to learn (\\u2018thick\\u2019) or badly\\r\\nbehaved (\\u2018thick\\u2019). The support and guidance that a child is provided with now\\r\\nhas changed dramatically. Children are encouraged to attend mainstream school,\\r\\nregardless of disability. Inclusion of all children is a great importance in\\r\\ntoday\\u2019s society.&nbsp;<\\/i><\\/b><\\/span><br><\\/p>\"}', 1517933907, 1, 0, 0),
