(6, 'Module One - An Introduction to Genealogy', '<p>This introductory module provides learners with the basic information required to begin on their journey of tracing ancestors, first detailing considerations such as; starting tips, family search information and online search activities. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Genealogy and family history</li>\r\n<li>Where to start your family search</li>\r\n<li>Family search information</li>\r\n<li>Cost and time considerations</li>\r\n<li>Online search activities</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(7, 'Module  Two - Career or Hobby?', '<p>This module examines the practice of genealogy in relation to people who want to trace their own family tree and for those who wish to use this as an academic discipline to pursue genealogy as a career. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to find living people</li>\r\n<li>Safety and warnings</li>\r\n<li>Help with tracing relatives</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(8, 'Module Three - The History of Surnames', '<p>This module focusses on how the wide and varied nature of surnames dates back in history and how this information can be used to assist with the family search process, through the examination of name categorisation. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Local names</li>\r\n<li>Landscape and surnames</li>\r\n<li>Occupations</li>\r\n<li>Nicknames</li>\r\n<li>Baptismal names</li>\r\n<li>British names</li>\r\n<li>The most common historical surnames</li>\r\n<li>Contemporary surnames</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(9, 'Module Four - Using Birth, Marriage and Death Records', '<p>This module explores the process of locating and using birth, marriage and death records when tracing relatives and examines pertinent issues such as; registry policies and procedures, the information available and the importance of genealogy documents. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>UK registry policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>Problems with using BMD records</li>\r\n<li>Record location and information available</li>\r\n<li>Evolution of recording information</li>\r\n<li>The importance of genealogy documents</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(10, 'Module Five - Using the Census and Parish Registers', '<p>This module studies the compilation of the census which was created in Great Britain to determine the number of men able to fight in bygone wars. The history of this document is explored and the purposes and uses in tracing family trees, is examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>History of the census</li>\r\n<li>Use and access of information</li>\r\n<li>How many people take part?</li>\r\n<li>Payment and prices</li>\r\n<li>How much does it cost to view an image?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(11, 'Module Six - War/Prison/Immigration Records', '<p>This module explores specific areas of archived records, relating to people who were recorded as being either military heroes, criminals or migrants. Advice on how to find and search such records and their importance, is examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Social spectrums of ancestry</li>\r\n<li>Find and searching for military/prison/immigration records</li>\r\n<li>The importance of military/prison/immigration records</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(12, 'Module Seven - Using Workhouse Records and Tracing Noble Ancestry', '<p>This module looks at how to trace ancestors from various walks of life; from those in poverty to those of aristocracy, through the study of resources such as; workhouse records, coats of arms and occupations. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Workhouse births and baptisms</li>\r\n<li>Civil registration and poor law union records</li>\r\n<li>Workhouse deaths and burials</li>\r\n<li>Other useful workhouse-related records</li>\r\n<li>Searching workhouse records</li>\r\n<li>Noble Ancestors</li>\r\n<li>Titles and coats of arms</li>\r\n<li>Heraldry and genealogy</li>\r\n<li>Occupations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(13, 'Module Eight - Other Sources Available: Wills, Newspapers, and Research Centres', '<p>This module looks at the various other, less thought of resources which can be used to trace ancestors. Legal documents such as wills are explored, as are published pieces such as newspapers; and advice on how to find and use these documents is detailed. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Wills, newspapers and research centres</li>\r\n<li>Information available</li>\r\n<li>Unusual/uncommon sources of information</li>\r\n<li>Benefits and drawbacks of using certain sources</li>\r\n<li>Source importance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(14, 'Module Nine - Recording a Family Tree Online and Other Ways', '<p>This module shifts focus from the searching and gathering of information relating to ancestors, to recording these findings in an online family tree and in other ways. Guidance on building this family chart and the numerous sources which can advise in this process, is detailed. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Online recording methods</li>\r\n<li>Available resources</li>\r\n<li>Benefits and drawbacks of using certain sources and websites</li>\r\n<li>Source importance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(15, 'Module Ten - What to Do with Your Findings and How to Write Up a Family Tree', '<p>This module provides an insight into what you can do after you have gathered your ancestry findings. Considerations such as creating a family history book, producing treasured mementos and even taking your search further is explored. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Publishing your family history book</li>\r\n<li>Other ideas for your research</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(16, 'Module Eleven - DNA Testing', '<p>This concluding module is focussed specifically on one of the latest techniques used in genealogy that is testing DNA to establish ancestry. The materials look at the different types of DNA testing along with the various processes involved and what can be achieved through it. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>DNA testing and family history</li>\r\n<li>The testing options: Y-DNA</li>\r\n<li>Testing options: Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA)</li>\r\n<li>Testing options: Ethnic tests</li>\r\n<li>Testing options: Biogeographical tests</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(17, 'Module One - Introduction', '<p>This module is a detailed introduction defining exactly what counselling is, focussing on its specific functions. To enhance this knowledge the module goes on to detail the history of the subject area before discussing why counselling might be needed. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What counselling is and isn&rsquo;t</li>\r\n<li>How counselling differs from other helping skills (such as advice-giving, guidance, befriending, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Core skills involved in counselling</li>\r\n<li>Confidentiality issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(18, 'Module Two - Models and approaches of helping', '<p>This module explores all the ins and outs relating to the theoretical techniques which are applied, in order to help individuals deliver effective counselling practice to their clients. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Counselling approaches</li>\r\n<li>The principles of skilled helping</li>\r\n<li>The use and effects of questions</li>\r\n<li>Challenges to clients&rsquo; views</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(19, 'Module Three - Working with feelings', '<p>This module summarises how the role of thoughts and particularly flawed thinking can affect people. The content goes on to explore the various ways in which thoughts can be challenged and how you can help motivate people to make a change. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Exploring the subject of change: its impacts and challenges</li>\r\n<li>Consideration of Boundaries and Ethics</li>\r\n<li>Setting goals, planning action &ndash; and dealing with resistance</li>\r\n<li>Ending the counselling skills relationship</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(20, 'Module Four - Goals and moving on', '<p>This module expands on previous knowledge to establish a counsellor&rsquo;s role in helping aid client recovery, through the implementation of numerous techniques. Following this the content goes on to explore counselling as a career. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Supervision: its importance in good practice</li>\r\n<li>Competence in record-keeping</li>\r\n<li>The importance of Continuing Personal Development (CPD) and taking care of YOU</li>\r\n<li>Using your counselling skills</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(21, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(22, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(23, 'Module One - Definition, Qualification & Registration', '<p>This introductory module defines what the practice of counselling is and also explains how individuals can become qualified practitioners. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<p>What is the difference between Counselling and Psychotherapy? Directive Counselling Rational-emotional behavioural therapy Cognitive behaviour therapy Non-directive counselling Psychodynamic counselling Transactional analysis counselling Psychodrama Therapy</p>', 1),
(24, 'Module Two - Freud and the Psychoanalytic Approach', '<p>This module provides a theoretical perspective to the study of counselling through the \'Freud Psychoanalytical Approach\' and examines how this methodology shapes current counselling techniques. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Psychoanalysis, origins and orientation</li>\r\n<li>Freud\'s Structural Model of Personality</li>\r\n<li>The Psychosexual Stages of Development</li>\r\n<li>Evaluation of Freud\'s Approach</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(25, 'Module One - Introduction to Criminology', '<p>This introductory module looks to provide a broad perspective of what the study of criminology is and examines relevant areas such as; types of crime, models of criminology and positivist criminology.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is criminology?</li>\r\n<li>Defining crime</li>\r\n<li>Types of crime</li>\r\n<li>The media and crime</li>\r\n<li>Models of criminology</li>\r\n<li>The classical school</li>\r\n<li>Positivist criminology</li>\r\n<li>Responding to the crime problem</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(26, 'Module Two - The UK Criminal Justice System', '<p>This module is focussed on the role of the UK Criminal Justice System and looks at how criminologists seek to develop an understanding of how it works, in order to determine its effectiveness in either reducing or dealing with crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining the Criminal Justice System</li>\r\n<li>Criminal justice in context</li>\r\n<li>Criminal Justice and Human Rights</li>\r\n<li>A System under stress: Reforming Criminal Justice</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(27, 'Module Three - Crime Data and Criminal Statistics', '<p>This module introduces the subject of crime data, looking specifically at the two main types and how these differ in terms of the information they obtain and how it is recorded.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of crime data</li>\r\n<li>Main sources of crime data</li>\r\n<li>The importance of crime statistics</li>\r\n<li>Difficulties in interpreting data</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(28, 'Module Four - Theories of Crime 1: Individuals and Crime', '<p>The materials highlight the differing theories as to why different individuals commit crime and how these can contribute to criminal justice policy and law enforcement practice.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The basis of individual theories</li>\r\n<li>Personality theories</li>\r\n<li>Individual Deviance and Anomie Theories</li>\r\n<li>Differential Association</li>\r\n<li>Understanding individual offending</li>\r\n<li>Offenders and Crime Control Policy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(29, 'Module Five - Police and Policing', '<p>This module is concerned with the process of policing in England and Wales and explores the current role of the police and how this has changed over time.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The role of the police</li>\r\n<li>Police organisation and accountability</li>\r\n<li>Policing styles and models of policing</li>\r\n<li>Public order policing</li>\r\n<li>Police powers and civil liberties</li>\r\n<li>Contemporary policing issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(30, 'Module Six - Crime Prevention', '<p>This module considers the contemporary debates about how we can prevent crime and scrutinises the various approaches and perspectives that have and continue to shape this methodology.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Situational crime prevention</li>\r\n<li>Social crime prevention</li>\r\n<li>Perspectives on crime prevention</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(31, 'Module Seven - Victims and Victimisation', '<p>This module looks at the issue of victims and victimisation in order to help criminologists gain a deeper understanding of the nature of crime and the impact it has on those who are affected.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining the victim</li>\r\n<li>Victim statistics</li>\r\n<li>Victimisation and repeat victimisation</li>\r\n<li>Victim support</li>\r\n<li>Recognising victims\' rights</li>\r\n<li>Compensating victims of crime</li>\r\n<li>A brief perspective on victims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(32, 'Module Eight - The Courts and Sentencing', '<p>This module studies the role of the court and the sentencing process and broadly examines its primary function for the administration of justice through sentencing offenders, either by imposing a fine or setting a prison term.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Theories of punishment</li>\r\n<li>Sentencing policy</li>\r\n<li>Juries</li>\r\n<li>The role of the judiciary</li>\r\n<li>Criticisms of the judiciary</li>\r\n<li>The Judiciary, Crime, and Human Rights</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(33, 'Module Nine - Prisons and Probation', '<p>This module discusses the use of prisons and probation and examines the effectiveness of prison as a criminal justice tool, through the study of areas such as; prison crisis, the effectiveness of prison and probation services.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purpose of prisons</li>\r\n<li>The prison crisis</li>\r\n<li>The effectiveness of prison</li>\r\n<li>Probation services</li>\r\n<li>Overview of prison and probation issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(34, 'Module Ten - Theories of Crime 2: Society and Crime', '<p>This module explores theories of society in relation to determining reasons for crime and looks at the extent to which crime is considered to be caused by social conditions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Control theories</li>\r\n<li>Differential association</li>\r\n<li>Labelling theories</li>\r\n<li>Social policy approaches to crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(35, 'Module Eleven - Inequality and Crime', '<p>This module considers the relationship between inequality and crime and looks at how factors such bias, race and poverty can all act as factors in the occurrence of criminal activity.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bias in the criminal justice system</li>\r\n<li>Race and Crime</li>\r\n<li>Poverty and crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(36, 'Module Twelve - Youth Crime', '<p>This module investigates how criminologists strive to understand why young people commit crime and examines specific behaviours involved in youth offending.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Social concerns about youth crime</li>\r\n<li>The causes of youth crime</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with youth crime</li>\r\n<li>Youth justice policy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(37, 'Module Three - Jung and the Development of the Psycho-dynamic Approach', '<p>This module provides a theoretical perspective to the study of counselling through the \'Jung Psychodynamic Approach\' and examines how this methodology shapes current counselling techniques. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Jungian Approach - Analytical Psychology</li>\r\n<li>Jung\'s Personality Structure</li>\r\n<li>The Ego</li>\r\n<li>Superior (Primary)/Inferior (Less used) Functions</li>\r\n<li>The Unconscious</li>\r\n<li>Attitude Types</li>\r\n<li>Archetypes</li>\r\n<li>Symbols and Dreams</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(38, 'Module Thirteen - Drugs and Crime', '<p>This module explores the nature of drug crime in the UK. Through the examination of subject areas such as; defining illegal drugs and contemporary drug policy, the materials look at the link between the involvement with drugs and committing crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining illegal drugs</li>\r\n<li>Drug use and crime</li>\r\n<li>Drugs and criminal justice policy</li>\r\n<li>Contemporary drug policy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(39, 'Module Fourteen - Corporate Crime', '<p>This module is concerned with the phenomenon of corporate crime. The rise of globalisation has created an opportunity for corporations to commit crimes and the materials look at the nature of these crimes and how they are dealt with.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The nature of corporate offending</li>\r\n<li>Corporate environmental crime</li>\r\n<li>Enforcing corporate crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(40, 'Module Fifthteen  - Transnational and Organised Crime', '<p>This module looks at crime on a larger scale, in relation to criminal organisations who often operate globally. Prominent examples include the Mafia and Triads and the materials study areas such as; theories of organised crime and organised crime structure, in order to provide a better insight into the objectives of such organisations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining transnational crime</li>\r\n<li>Theories of organised crime</li>\r\n<li>Structure of organised crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(41, 'Module Sixteen - Environmental Crime', '<p>This module studies a developing criminology field which is concerned with acts of harm against the environment and wildlife that are classified as crime. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining environmental crime</li>\r\n<li>A green perspective on crime</li>\r\n<li>The illegal wildlife trade</li>\r\n<li>Perspectives on environmental crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(42, 'Module Four - The Adlerian Approach – Individual Psychology', '<p>This module provides a theoretical perspective to the study of counselling through the \'Adlerian Individual Approach\' and examines how this methodology shapes current counselling techniques. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Social Determination of Meaning</li>\r\n<li>Individual development</li>\r\n<li>Inferiority Theory</li>\r\n<li>Personality types</li>\r\n<li>Goals of individual psychology</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(43, 'Module Seventeen - Cyber Crime', '<p>This module explores the emerging prevalence of crime in which computer technology of any kind is used by the individual to commit an offence, and the materials consider relevant areas such as; hacking and cyber terrorism.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining cyber criminality</li>\r\n<li>Computer hacking and cracking</li>\r\n<li>Cyber Terrorism</li>\r\n<li>Offences involving children</li>\r\n<li>Overview of cybercrime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(44, 'Module Eighteen - Sexual Offences and Violent Crime', '<p>This module examines violent crime and sexual violence, discussing some of the criminological issues raised, by examining areas such as; sexual violence and perspectives on violence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Masculinity and the nature of violent offences</li>\r\n<li>Sexual violence</li>\r\n<li>Domestic violence</li>\r\n<li>Perspectives on violence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(45, 'Module Five - Existential Psychotherapy', '<p>This module explores the approach to counselling which is based upon the notions of being, of existing in the world and the individual\'s freedom, responsibility and ability to choose. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Otto Rank</li>\r\n<li>The four major themes of existential therapy</li>\r\n<li>Atheistic and Spiritual Existentialism</li>\r\n<li>The Therapeutic Process</li>\r\n<li>The Goals of Existential Psychotherapy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(46, 'Module Nineteen - Criminal Profiling', '<p>This module considers the work of FBI profilers in identifying and understanding repeat offending among murderers and examines relevant areas such as; geographical profiling and critical perspectives on criminal profiling.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The role of profiling</li>\r\n<li>Geographical profiling</li>\r\n<li>Psychological profiling</li>\r\n<li>Critical perspectives on criminal profiling</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(47, 'Module Twenty - Crime and the Media', '<p>This concluding module examines the relationship between the media, crime, and the public, and through the study of areas such as; moral panics, media crime narrative and ideologies, evaluates some issues around media crime reporting.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Media and crime a social constructionist view</li>\r\n<li>Moral panics</li>\r\n<li>Dimensions of media crime narratives</li>\r\n<li>Good versus evil: Ideology in media crime narratives</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(48, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 1),
(49, 'Module Six - Gestalt Psychotherapy', '<p>This module studies a counselling therapy which is based on the theory of Gestalt who believed that the human mind and human behaviour should be viewed as a whole. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gestalt Psychology</li>\r\n<li>Gestalt Psychotherapy</li>\r\n<li>The Gestalt View of Personality</li>\r\n<li>Theory of the Organism and self</li>\r\n<li>The Therapeutic Process</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(50, 'Module Seven - Psychodrama Therapy', '<p>This module looks at the counselling technique in which people are assigned roles to be played spontaneously within a dramatic context devised by a therapist, in order to understand the behaviour of people with whom they have difficult interactions. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The social atom</li>\r\n<li>Moreno\'s stages of personality development</li>\r\n<li>Roles and Role Playing</li>\r\n<li>The auxiliary egos</li>\r\n<li>Warm up</li>\r\n<li>Post Action</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(51, 'Module One - Facial and Skincare', '<p>This introductory module explores the structure of skin and looks at how its health and condition is essential to those provides beauty therapy services. The knowledge contained looks at the process of implementing facials and explains how to deal with facial skin issues.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Facial treatments</li>\r\n<li>Skin structure</li>\r\n<li>Skin types</li>\r\n<li>Skin analysis</li>\r\n<li>Treatments</li>\r\n<li>Contra-indications</li>\r\n<li>Conditions</li>\r\n<li>Mask therapy</li>\r\n<li>Massage</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(52, 'Module Eight - Carl Rogers – Client Centred Counselling', '<p>This module is concerned with the approach developed by Carl Rogers, which focusses on seeing the world through the client\'s eyes in order to help them help themselves. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Rogerian Approach</li>\r\n<li>Self-Actualisation</li>\r\n<li>The concept of self</li>\r\n<li>Core Conditions</li>\r\n<li>Positive Regard</li>\r\n<li>Congruence/Incongruence</li>\r\n<li>The counselling relationship</li>\r\n<li>Strengths and weaknesses of client centred counselling</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(53, 'Module Two - Eyelash and Eyebrow Treatments', '<p>This module is focussed on the types of treatment available for eyelash and eyebrows and examines considerations that should be taken when engaging clients with services such as eyelash tinting, eyebrow shaping and applying false lashes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Skin test</li>\r\n<li>Eyelash tinting</li>\r\n<li>Contra-indications</li>\r\n<li>Eyebrow tinting</li>\r\n<li>Eyebrow shaping</li>\r\n<li>False eyelashes</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(54, 'Module Three - Manicure and Hand Treatments', '<p>This module looks specifically at the hands in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained examines the nails in relation to maintaining hand health when providing services such as; manicures and nail art.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Nail facts</li>\r\n<li>Common nail problems</li>\r\n<li>Nail disorders</li>\r\n<li>Manicure consultation</li>\r\n<li>Manicure procedure</li>\r\n<li>Enamelling the nails</li>\r\n<li>Nail art</li>\r\n<li>Nail piercing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(55, 'Module Nine - Transactional Analysis', '<p>This module is focussed on the counselling technique that was developed by numerous theorists to categorise emotional states and then help the client move into one that is most healthy. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Parent - Adult - Child Model</li>\r\n<li>Complementary or reciprocal transactions</li>\r\n<li>Ulterior Transactions</li>\r\n<li>Games</li>\r\n<li>Strokes</li>\r\n<li>Life Scripts</li>\r\n<li>The TA Contract</li>\r\n<li>Criticisms of Transactional Analysis</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(56, 'Module Four - Pedicure and Foot Treatments', '<p>This module specifically studies the feet in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained looks at health care considerations of the feet and explores treatments such as, pedicures, Garra Rufa fish pedicures and artificial nails.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Common Foot and Nail Diseases</li>\r\n<li>Pedicure procedures</li>\r\n<li>Foot care products</li>\r\n<li>Luxury and Specialist Hand, Foot, and Nail Treatments</li>\r\n<li>Garra Rufa Fish Pedicures</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n<li>Artificial nails</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(57, 'Module Five - Waxing and Temporary Methods of Hair Removal', '<p>This module explores the practice of hair removal in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained examines a range of relevant subject areas such as; the types and colour of hair, strong hair growth and waxing.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Body and facial hair</li>\r\n<li>Hair colour</li>\r\n<li>Causes of Superfluous and Strong Hair Growth</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with male clients</li>\r\n<li>Waxing</li>\r\n<li>Hair growth cycle</li>\r\n<li>Effects of different methods of removal on the hair</li>\r\n<li>Bleaching</li>\r\n<li>Permanent Methods of Hair Removal</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(58, 'Module Six - Advanced Nail Techniques', '<p>This module is concerned with the application of more advanced nail beauty techniques when offering treatments and examines how to practice procedures such as; gel nails, fibreglass nails and acrylic nails.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Allergies</li>\r\n<li>Gel nails</li>\r\n<li>Fibreglass nails</li>\r\n<li>Acrylic nails</li>\r\n<li>General Homecare Advice for Artificial Nails</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(59, 'Module Ten - Neuro – Linguistic Programming', '<p>This module studies the method in which the counsellor assesses an individual\'s dominant perceptual mode and restructures this, if appropriate, to help them achieve their goals. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Presuppositions in Neuro-linguistic Programming</li>\r\n<li>Modalities and Submodalities in NLP</li>\r\n<li>Anchors in NLP</li>\r\n<li>Meta and Milton models of NLP</li>\r\n<li>Generalisations, Deletions and Distortions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(60, 'Module Seven - Make-Up Application to the Face', '<p>This module studies the practice of applying makeup to the face as part of beauty therapy treatment and looks at a range of relevant considerations such as; conducting a make-up consultation, product usage and treatment times.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Make-up consultation</li>\r\n<li>Record Card and Treatment Plan</li>\r\n<li>Product Formulations</li>\r\n<li>Mineral Make-up</li>\r\n<li>Product Use and Information</li>\r\n<li>Preparation for Make-up</li>\r\n<li>Client Preparation</li>\r\n<li>Brushes and tools</li>\r\n<li>Make-up application</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(61, 'Module Eight - Science and Cosmetology', '<p>This module details the make-up of products used and made available when providing beauty therapy services and also relevant sterilisation, hygiene and safety issues that also need to be considered when providing treatments.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Products for the skin</li>\r\n<li>Results</li>\r\n<li>Cost</li>\r\n<li>Convenience</li>\r\n<li>Animal testing</li>\r\n<li>Ingredients</li>\r\n<li>Products</li>\r\n<li>Sterilisation and hygiene</li>\r\n<li>Safety</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(62, 'Module Nine - Anatomy and Physiology', '<p>This module now looks at the biological terms that individuals working in the beauty industry should have an understanding of, in order to provide safe and effective treatments. Important subject areas such as; blood, tissue and muscles are examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Anatomical terms</li>\r\n<li>Cells</li>\r\n<li>Tissue</li>\r\n<li>Blood</li>\r\n<li>The lymphatic system</li>\r\n<li>The human skeleton</li>\r\n<li>Muscles</li>\r\n<li>The skin</li>\r\n<li>Hair</li>\r\n<li>Other body systems</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(63, 'Module Ten - Health and Safety', '<p>This module looks specifically at health and safety when working in a beauty therapy setting and examines important areas that need to be considered, such as; the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974, safety signs and waste disposal.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Health &amp; safety at work act (HASAW) 1974</li>\r\n<li>Acts applicable to all workplaces</li>\r\n<li>Manual handling operations regulations 1992</li>\r\n<li>Control of substances hazardous to health regulations 2002 (COSHH)</li>\r\n<li>Safety signs</li>\r\n<li>Accidents/ injuries and disease</li>\r\n<li>Hazard management</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining hygiene</li>\r\n<li>Salon environment</li>\r\n<li>Waste disposal</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(64, 'Module Eleven - Consultation', '<p>This module details the practice of providing consultations to clients as part of the beauty therapy process to ensure needs are met, and examines important factors such as; the record card, skin consultation and methods of communication.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Record card</li>\r\n<li>Consultation for facial treatments</li>\r\n<li>Signs of skin ageing</li>\r\n<li>Skin consultation</li>\r\n<li>Methods of communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(65, 'Module Twelve - Promotions and Retailing', '<p>This module explores the process of selling your services when working in beauty therapy. This broad term encompasses the selling actual products over the counter in addition to promoting the actual treatments that you provide.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Retailing in the beauty salon</li>\r\n<li>Setting and meeting targets</li>\r\n<li>Consumer legislation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(66, 'Module Thirteen - Reception', '<p>This module is concerned with the reception duties required in order to run successful beauty services and examines important considerations, such as; welcoming clients, dealing with complaints and insurance.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Salon systems and operations</li>\r\n<li>The reception area</li>\r\n<li>Welcoming clients</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with complaints</li>\r\n<li>Insurance</li>\r\n<li>Employment law</li>\r\n<li>Security</li>\r\n<li>Stock</li>\r\n<li>Emergency procedures</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(67, 'Module Fourteen - Career Opportunities and Continuing Professional Development', '<p>This concluding module draws upon the knowledge conveyed in the previous modules and examines how to apply what you have learned to career opportunities and professional development within your role.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Employability: Skills for finding and keeping a job</li>\r\n<li>Code of conduct</li>\r\n<li>Code of ethics</li>\r\n<li>Code of practice</li>\r\n<li>Personal and professional development</li>\r\n<li>Time management</li>\r\n<li>Team work</li>\r\n<li>Curriculum Vitae</li>\r\n<li>Further techniques</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(68, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email support@ncchomelearning.co.uk (note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(69, 'Module Eleven - Egan and the Skilled Helper Approach', '<p>This module explores the technique which encourages clients to become active interpreters of the world, giving meanings to actions, events and situations; facing and overcoming challenges, exploring problem issues, seeking new opportunities and establishing goals. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Counselling Orientation</li>\r\n<li>Stage I Exploring the client\'s Existing Situation</li>\r\n<li>Stage II Helping the client to establish aims and goals</li>\r\n<li>Stage III Helping the client to develop strategies</li>\r\n<li>Non verbal communication and the skilled helper model</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(70, 'Module One - Working Effectively with Other People', '<p>This introductory module looks at how individuals should apply themselves in order to work effectively with other people in the business environment, studying areas of relevance such as; communication, work goals and plans.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of working effectively with other people</li>\r\n<li>Working with others to achieve positive outcomes</li>\r\n<li>Effective communication</li>\r\n<li>Communicating with colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Work goals and plans</li>\r\n<li>The strengths of others</li>\r\n<li>Team diversity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(71, 'Module Two - Carrying out your Responsibilities effectively', '<p>This module explores effective ways in which individuals should carry out their job and examines relevant areas that should be considered, such as; effective communication, planning work and contribution.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Importance of effective communication</li>\r\n<li>Focussing on the communication of others</li>\r\n<li>Clear and accurate information</li>\r\n<li>Communication adaption</li>\r\n<li>Discussion and meeting contribution</li>\r\n<li>Written information</li>\r\n<li>Planning work</li>\r\n<li>Work targets</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(72, 'Module Three - Work within your Business Environment', '<p>This module is focussed on the type of work and considerations relevant to an administrator&rsquo;s role and examines areas such as; employment law, the contract of employment and working to achieve your organisation&rsquo;s purpose and values.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Responsibilities at work</li>\r\n<li>How your role relates to organisational structure</li>\r\n<li>Policies, procedures, systems and organisational values</li>\r\n<li>Employment law</li>\r\n<li>Your contract of employment</li>\r\n<li>Working to achieve your organisation&rsquo;s purpose and values</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(73, 'Module Twelve - Albert Ellis and the Rational Emotive Behavioural Approach', '<p>This module looks at the counselling approach in which a client is taught to recognise irrational thoughts and teach themselves to believe in a more helpful perspective. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Irrational Ideas and Beliefs</li>\r\n<li>Inferences and Evaluations</li>\r\n<li>The ABC model of personality functioning and the 3 core absolutes</li>\r\n<li>Intervention techniques</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(74, 'Module Four - Health and Safety', '<p>This module is concerned with health and safety in the workplace and how this affects individuals working in an administrative role. The contained knowledge examines areas of relevance such as; workplace hazards, dealing with risks and safe working practices.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legal duties required by the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974</li>\r\n<li>Your health and safety duties as defined by specific legislation covering your job role</li>\r\n<li>Workplace hazards</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with risks</li>\r\n<li>Your responsibility for health and safety in your job description</li>\r\n<li>Suppliers&rsquo; and manufacturers&rsquo; instructions for the safe use of office equipment, materials and products</li>\r\n<li>The safe working practices for your job role</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(75, 'Module Five - Managing Customer Relations', '<p>This module studies the process of liaising with customers in a business and explores how this relates to those working in administration, through the examination of areas such as; customer needs, customer relations and customer complaints.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who customers are</li>\r\n<li>Effective and efficient customer service</li>\r\n<li>Positive working relationships with customers</li>\r\n<li>Customer needs</li>\r\n<li>Quality standards</li>\r\n<li>Customer problems</li>\r\n<li>Customer complaints</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(76, 'Module Six - Storing, Retrieving and Archiving Information', '<p>This module details the steps involved in processing information in a business and examines areas that administrators should consider, such as; collecting information, accessing information systems and providing information within agreed timescales.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Information systems and their main features</li>\r\n<li>Legal and organisational requirements covering the security and confidentiality of information</li>\r\n<li>Collecting information</li>\r\n<li>Accessing information systems</li>\r\n<li>Accurate information</li>\r\n<li>Information system problems</li>\r\n<li>Providing information in the required format and agreed timescales</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(77, 'Module Thirteen - Beck and the Cognitive Behavioural Therapy Approach', '<p>This module considers the counselling approach developed by Aaron Beck that focuses on how individuals perceive and interpret events, examining methods on how negative perceptions can be changed. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Negative Automatic Thoughts</li>\r\n<li>Underlying Assumptions and Rules</li>\r\n<li>Core Beliefs</li>\r\n<li>Delivering the Therapy</li>\r\n<li>Social Anxiety-Phobia</li>\r\n<li>Depression</li>\r\n<li>Obsessive Compulsive Disorder (OCD)</li>\r\n<li>Panic Disorder and Agoraphobia</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(78, 'Module Seven - Using IT effectively to exchange information', '<p>This module studies the use of IT facilities in a business and examines how those working in administration need to efficiently utilise communication software such as email, in order to exchange information.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Send and receive emails using an address book</li>\r\n<li>Email archiving and compression</li>\r\n<li>Email problems and how to avoid them</li>\r\n<li>How to keep the difficulties of sending &amp; receiving large emails to a minimum</li>\r\n<li>Email storage limitations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(79, 'Module Eight - Operating Office Equipment', '<p>This concluding module looks at the use of office equipment in a business environment and details what is relevant to those working in administration and how this should be used safely.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of office equipment, their features and use</li>\r\n<li>Relevant equipment and resources</li>\r\n<li>Following manufacturers&rsquo; instructions when operating equipment</li>\r\n<li>Limiting waste</li>\r\n<li>Keeping equipment clean and hygienic</li>\r\n<li>Equipment faults</li>\r\n<li>Meeting work standards and deadlines</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(80, 'Module Fourteen - Reality Therapy', '<p>This module studies the counselling therapy that is concerned with addressing the problems arising at the interpersonal level of human functioning as a result of relationship difficulties. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Glasser\'s View of the Development of Psychological Problems</li>\r\n<li>The Goal of Reality Therapy</li>\r\n<li>The Individual in Reality Therapy</li>\r\n<li>The Individual\'s Quality World</li>\r\n<li>Personality Development and Identity</li>\r\n<li>The Therapeutic Process</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(81, 'Module Fifteen - Post Traumatic Stress Counselling', '<p>This module examines the specific counselling technique that is concerned with the range of symptoms a person may develop as a result of experiencing a traumatic event outside their normal range of experience. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Susceptibility to Post Traumatic Stress Disorder</li>\r\n<li>Causes of Post Traumatic Stress Disorder</li>\r\n<li>Symptoms of Traumatic Stress Disorder</li>\r\n<li>Symptoms of Traumatic Stress Disorder in Children</li>\r\n<li>Treatments for Post Traumatic Stress Disorder</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(82, 'Module Sixteen - Verbal Communication Skills in Counselling', '<p>This module aims to provide guidance on how counsellors should use verbal communication appropriately with their clients. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Purpose of Communication in the Counselling Context</li>\r\n<li>The Elements of Communication</li>\r\n<li>The Communicators (client and counsellor)</li>\r\n<li>The Messages</li>\r\n<li>Feedback</li>\r\n<li>Context</li>\r\n<li>Questioning</li>\r\n<li>Silence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(83, 'Module Seventeen - Non Verbal Communication', '<p>This module aims to provide guidance on how counsellors should use non-verbal communication appropriately with their clients. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The functions of non-verbal communication</li>\r\n<li>Types of nonverbal communication and body language</li>\r\n<li>Improving nonverbal communication by the promotion of calm</li>\r\n<li>Evaluating nonverbal signals</li>\r\n<li>Facial expressions and Eye contact</li>\r\n<li>Gestures</li>\r\n<li>Posture and body orientation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(84, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(85, 'Module One - Principles of personal responsibilities and working in a business environment', '<p>This introductory unit is about employment rights; health, safety and security; how to work with others and how to manage and improve own work in a business environment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Employment rights and responsibilities</li>\r\n<li>Health, safety and security procedures</li>\r\n<li>Planning your work and supporting colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Improving your performance</li>\r\n<li>Problems in a business environmentEmployment rights and responsibilities</li>\r\n<li>Health, safety and security procedures</li>\r\n<li>Planning your work and supporting colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Improving your performance</li>\r\n<li>Problems in a business environment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(86, 'Module Two - Principles of providing administrative services', '<p>This unit considers the range of different tasks which are relevant to an administration role. The materials explore duties such as; handling the mail, arranging meetings and diary management and looks at their importance to the smooth running of a business.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to make and receive telephone calls</li>\r\n<li>Handling the mail</li>\r\n<li>Different types of office equipment</li>\r\n<li>Keeping waste to a minimum</li>\r\n<li>Arranging meetings</li>\r\n<li>Travel and accommodation arrangements</li>\r\n<li>Diary management</li>\r\n<li>Effective customer service</li>\r\n<li>Reception services</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(87, 'Module Three - Principles of managing information and producing documents', '<p>This unit looks at how information technology can be used effectively in an organisation and also how this information should be used when producing documents to ensure information is communicated clearly.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purpose of information technology in a business environment</li>\r\n<li>How to manage electronic and paper based information</li>\r\n<li>Fit for purpose documents</li>\r\n<li>Procedures to follow when producing documents</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(88, 'Module One - What is Autism?', '<p>This introductory module defines what the term Autism actually means and explores the common problems associated with this condition in addition to the potential strengths that people with autism may have.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Triad of Impairments</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social interaction</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social communication and language</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social imagination</li>\r\n<li>Sensory problems</li>\r\n<li>Asperger&rsquo;s Syndrome</li>\r\n<li>The strengths of children with autism</li>\r\n<li>Conditions related to autism</li>\r\n<li>Who has autism</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(89, 'Module Two - Autism and Education', '<p>This module studies the occurrence of autism in children within educational environments, looking at how to be aware of this and provide appropriate support to help with the numerous barriers that these children may face.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Educational service for autistic children</li>\r\n<li>Key principles of good practice in education</li>\r\n<li>Recognising ASC&rsquo;s in Schools</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(90, 'Module Three - What is Challenging Behaviour?', '<p>This module looks specifically at the different types of behaviour that children with autism may present in an educational environment that could be seen as challenging, focusing on why these may occur and how they can be controlled.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reasons children with autism display challenging behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Challenging behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Physical causes of challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Labelling and challenging behaviour</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(91, 'Module Four - Learning Styles and Autism', '<p>This module looks at the range of varying learning styles which can be applied to individuals with autism to help promote their positive learning experience in a learning environment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Different learning styles</li>\r\n<li>Typical autism associated learning styles</li>\r\n<li>Key features of learning styles</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(92, 'Module Five - Supporting Understanding of Other People', '<p>This module is concerned with how people working in an educational setting can help children with autism to gain an understanding of other people through the focus on relevant areas such as eye contact, turn taking and play.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Using eyes for communication</li>\r\n<li>Shared attention with others</li>\r\n<li>Feeling other people&rsquo;s emotions</li>\r\n<li>Making and maintaining friends and relationships</li>\r\n<li>Personal space and proximity</li>\r\n<li>Turn taking</li>\r\n<li>Understanding other people think differently than us</li>\r\n<li>Understanding facial expressions and body language</li>\r\n<li>Play</li>\r\n<li>Different settings</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(93, 'Module Six - Supporting Communication', '<p>This module highlights problems that children with autism are likely to experience with regards to applying communication skills and how these can be identified and dealt with in terms of staff providing appropriate support to individuals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Visual communication</li>\r\n<li>Intensive interaction</li>\r\n<li>Verbal communication</li>\r\n<li>Musical communication</li>\r\n<li>Awareness of own communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(94, 'Module Eighteen - Counsellor/Client Listening Skills', '<p>This module examines in more detail the listening skills which need to be developed by the counsellor and considers areas such as; eye contact, reflective listening and personal characteristics. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eye contact (if culturally appropriate)</li>\r\n<li>Demonstrating attention</li>\r\n<li>Reflective Listening</li>\r\n<li>Eliminating Blocks to Listening</li>\r\n<li>Counsellor\'s Personal Characteristics</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
