(95, 'Module Nineteen - Counselling and the Law', '<p>This module details important information regarding the law and how this affects counselling practitioners. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The legal implications for counselling</li>\r\n<li>The Mental Health Acts</li>\r\n<li>Health and Safety at Work Act 1972</li>\r\n<li>Risk Assessment</li>\r\n<li>Employers\' Liability Compulsory Insurance Act 1969</li>\r\n<li>The Data Protection Act 1998 (Amended by the Data Protection Act 2003)</li>\r\n<li>The Freedom of Information Act 2000</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(96, 'Module Twenty - Counselling and the Law', '<p>This concluding module looks at the various requirements that must be fulfilled in order to fully qualify to be a counsellor and examines considerations such as; practical experience, the counselling contract and the DBS check. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Practical experience</li>\r\n<li>Volunteering for counselling practice</li>\r\n<li>Evidencing practical training</li>\r\n<li>The counselling contract</li>\r\n<li>Ethical Code of Practice</li>\r\n<li>The DBS Check</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(97, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(98, 'Module One -  Idea to reality, why set up in the first place', '<p>This module provides learners with an introduction to the steps of transforming an idea into a realistic business proposition, highlighting the various factors that should be considered and implemented. Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Getting started</li>\r\n<li>Getting organised</li>\r\n<li>Developing a plan</li>\r\n<li>Motivation</li>\r\n<li>Role models</li>\r\n<li>Business success and failure</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(99, 'Module Two - Market Research - What do you need to know?', '<p>This module outlines the various factors that you need to know when conducting research into the market. The module aims to give a detailed overview that answers questions such as: &lsquo;who or what is the competition? Who are their customers? What is generally happening in the marketplace? How much completion is there? How big is the market?&rsquo; Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is Market Research?</li>\r\n<li>Where to start?</li>\r\n<li>Conducting telephone or face to face research</li>\r\n<li>Ways of conducting market research</li>\r\n<li>How to manage data</li>\r\n<li>Analysing your strengths and weaknesses</li>\r\n<li>Marketing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(100, 'Module Three - Business Legalities for the Entrepreneur', '<p>This module details the various legalities that must be considered, implemented and abided by when starting up and running your own business. Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legal form</li>\r\n<li>Deciding on a business name</li>\r\n<li>Taking legal advice</li>\r\n<li>Trade Marks</li>\r\n<li>Legislation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(101, 'Module Four - Idea to reality, why set up in the first place', '<p>This module looks at the complexities of project planning and provides ideas on how you can manage each aspect through to successful conclusion. The module also explains how project planning is essential to ensure that your business gets off to a smooth start. Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Project planning</li>\r\n<li>What is a project?</li>\r\n<li>Project types</li>\r\n<li>Project stages</li>\r\n<li>Implementation and control</li>\r\n<li>Project closure</li>\r\n<li>Problems, issues and solutions</li>\r\n<li>Post project plan review</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(102, 'Module Five - Customer Service', '<p>This module explains the importance of having good customer service in order to run a successful business and explores the various factors that should be considered and implemented in order to ensure that this is achieved. Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is a customer?</li>\r\n<li>When you are a customer</li>\r\n<li>What customers expect</li>\r\n<li>Who are your customers?</li>\r\n<li>The need for exceptional customer service</li>\r\n<li>Identify your customer&rsquo;s expectations and needs</li>\r\n<li>Representing your business</li>\r\n<li>Providing customers with information on products or services</li>\r\n<li>Customer feedback</li>\r\n<li>Ways of improving customer service</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(103, 'Module Six - Working with a Team', '<p>This module explains the implications of acquiring a business team and provides guidance on being a successful leader to ensure the effective running of your business. Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Leading a team</li>\r\n<li>Leading and motivating</li>\r\n<li>Leadership styles</li>\r\n<li>Organising yourself and your time</li>\r\n<li>Setting objectives</li>\r\n<li>Planning</li>\r\n<li>Decision making</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining the quality of work</li>\r\n<li>Feedback and working relationships</li>\r\n<li>Help individuals to develop performance</li>\r\n<li>Develop yourself</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(104, 'Module Seven - Managing Operations', '<p>This module establishes and provides guidance on how to manage the various operations that need to be maintained in order for your business to run efficiently and sustain. Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Where should you work from?</li>\r\n<li>Security</li>\r\n<li>Health and safety</li>\r\n<li>Finance</li>\r\n<li>Coping with the day to day minutiae</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(105, 'Module Eight - Managing OperationsWriting a Business Plan', '<p>This module enables you to consider the knowledge gained from the rest of the course and explores the various ways in which you can implement this effectively by providing detailed guidance on constructing a successful business plan. Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>So, what should be in a business plan?</li>\r\n<li>Getting the pitch right</li>\r\n<li>Tips for success</li>\r\n<li>Constructing your business plan</li>\r\n<li>What to do next?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(106, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(107, 'Module One - What is Autism?', '<p>This introductory module defines what the term Autism actually means and explores the common problems associated with this condition in addition to the potential strengths that people with autism may have. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Triad of Impairments</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social interaction</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social communication and language</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social imagination</li>\r\n<li>Sensory problems</li>\r\n<li>Asperger&rsquo;s Syndrome</li>\r\n<li>The strengths of children with autism</li>\r\n<li>Conditions related to autism</li>\r\n<li>Who has autism</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(108, 'Module Two - Autism and Education', '<p>This module studies the occurrence of autism in children within educational environments, looking at how to be aware of this and provide appropriate support to help with the numerous barriers that these children may face. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Educational service for autistic children</li>\r\n<li>Key principles of good practice in education</li>\r\n<li>Recognising ASC&rsquo;s in Schools</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(109, 'Module Three - What is Challenging Behaviour?', '<p>This module looks specifically at the different types of behaviour that children with autism may present in an educational environment that could be seen as challenging, focusing on why these may occur and how they can be controlled. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reasons children with autism display challenging behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Challenging behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Physical causes of challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Labelling and challenging behaviour</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(110, 'Module Four - Learning Styles and Autism', '<p>This module looks at the range of varying learning styles which can be applied to individuals with autism to help promote their positive learning experience in a learning environment. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Different learning styles</li>\r\n<li>Typical autism associated learning styles</li>\r\n<li>Key features of learning styles</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(111, 'Module Five - Supporting Understanding of Other People', '<p>This module is concerned with how people working in an educational setting can help children with autism to gain an understanding of other people through the focus on relevant areas such as eye contact, turn taking and play. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Using eyes for communication</li>\r\n<li>Shared attention with others</li>\r\n<li>Feeling other people&rsquo;s emotions</li>\r\n<li>Making and maintaining friends and relationships</li>\r\n<li>Personal space and proximity</li>\r\n<li>Turn taking</li>\r\n<li>Understanding other people think differently than us</li>\r\n<li>Understanding facial expressions and body language</li>\r\n<li>Play</li>\r\n<li>Different settings</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(112, 'Module Six - Supporting Communication', '<p>This module highlights problems that children with autism are likely to experience with regards to applying communication skills and how these can be identified and dealt with in terms of staff providing appropriate support to individuals. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Visual communication</li>\r\n<li>Intensive interaction</li>\r\n<li>Verbal communication</li>\r\n<li>Musical communication</li>\r\n<li>Awareness of own communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(113, 'Module Seven - Building Positive relationships and achieving diversity', '<p>This module studies the concerning realisation that children with autism may be vulnerable to bullies and examines the ways in which teachers can help to support children in building positive relationships to reduce this vulnerability. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bullying</li>\r\n<li>Why are children with autism vulnerable to bullying?</li>\r\n<li>Positive relationships</li>\r\n<li>The circle of friends approach</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(114, 'Module Eight - Supporting work and the curriculum', '<p>This concluding module examines the ways in which teachers can provide appropriate support to help children with autism achieve in school subjects, focusing on relevant factors such as structured time and promoting the hidden curriculum. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The hidden curriculum</li>\r\n<li>The planned curriculum</li>\r\n<li>The National Curriculum</li>\r\n<li>Supporting Literacy</li>\r\n<li>Supporting Numeracy</li>\r\n<li>Support during IT</li>\r\n<li>Support throughout the school day</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(115, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(116, 'Module One - Facial and Skincare', '<p>This introductory module explores the structure of skin and looks at how its health and condition is essential to those provides beauty therapy services. The knowledge contained looks at the process of implementing facials and explains how to deal with facial skin issues. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Facial treatments</li>\r\n<li>Skin structure</li>\r\n<li>Skin types</li>\r\n<li>Skin analysis</li>\r\n<li>Treatments</li>\r\n<li>Contra-indications</li>\r\n<li>Conditions</li>\r\n<li>Mask therapy</li>\r\n<li>Massage</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(117, 'Module Two - Eyelash and Eyebrow Treatments', '<p>This module is focussed on the types of treatment available for eyelash and eyebrows and examines considerations that should be taken when engaging clients with services such as eyelash tinting, eyebrow shaping and applying false lashes. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Skin test</li>\r\n<li>Eyelash tinting</li>\r\n<li>Contra-indications</li>\r\n<li>Eyebrow tinting</li>\r\n<li>Eyebrow shaping</li>\r\n<li>False eyelashes</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(118, 'Module Three - Manicure and Hand Treatments', '<p>This module looks specifically at the hands in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained examines the nails in relation to maintaining hand health when providing services such as; manicures and nail art. Specific areas covered include: &nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Nail facts</li>\r\n<li>Common nail problems</li>\r\n<li>Nail disorders</li>\r\n<li>Manicure consultation</li>\r\n<li>Manicure procedure</li>\r\n<li>Enamelling the nails</li>\r\n<li>Nail art</li>\r\n<li>Nail piercing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(119, 'Module Four - Pedicure and Foot Treatments', '<p>This module specifically studies the feet in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained looks at health care considerations of the feet and explores treatments such as, pedicures, Garra Rufa fish pedicures and artificial nails. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Common Foot and Nail Diseases</li>\r\n<li>Pedicure procedures</li>\r\n<li>Foot care products</li>\r\n<li>Luxury and Specialist Hand, Foot, and Nail Treatments</li>\r\n<li>Garra Rufa Fish Pedicures</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n<li>Artificial nails</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(120, 'Module One - What is Autism?', '<p>This introductory module defines what the term autism actually means and explores the common problems associated with this condition and who is likely to be affected by it.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A history</li>\r\n<li>Autism today</li>\r\n<li>Symptoms</li>\r\n<li>Who is affected</li>\r\n<li>Related conditions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(121, 'Module Five - Waxing and Temporary Methods of Hair Removal', '<p>This module explores the practice of hair removal in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained examines a range of relevant subject areas such as; the types and colour of hair, strong hair growth and waxing. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Body and facial hair</li>\r\n<li>Hair colour</li>\r\n<li>Causes of Superfluous and Strong Hair Growth</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with male clients</li>\r\n<li>Waxing</li>\r\n<li>Hair growth cycle</li>\r\n<li>Effects of different methods of removal on the hair</li>\r\n<li>Bleaching</li>\r\n<li>Permanent Methods of Hair Removal</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(122, 'Module Six - Advanced Nail Techniques', '<p>This module is concerned with the application of more advanced nail beauty techniques when offering treatments and examines how to practice procedures such as; gel nails, fibreglass nails and acrylic nails. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Allergies</li>\r\n<li>Gel nails</li>\r\n<li>Fibreglass nails</li>\r\n<li>Acrylic nails</li>\r\n<li>General Homecare Advice for Artificial Nails</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(123, 'Module Seven - Make-Up Application to the Face', '<p>This module studies the practice of applying make up to the face as part of beauty therapy treatment and looks at a range of relevant considerations such as; conducting a make-up consultation, product usage and treatment times. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Make-up consultation</li>\r\n<li>Record Card and Treatment Plan</li>\r\n<li>Product Formulations</li>\r\n<li>Mineral Make-up</li>\r\n<li>Product Use and Information</li>\r\n<li>Preparation for Make-up</li>\r\n<li>Client Preparation</li>\r\n<li>Brushes and tools</li>\r\n<li>Make-up application</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(124, 'Module Two - Legislation and Autism', '<p>This module examines the legislative acts enforced within work settings to assist in the promotion of fair treatment for people who have autism.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Equality Act (2010)</li>\r\n<li>Making reasonable adjustments in employment</li>\r\n<li>Making reasonable adjustments in education</li>\r\n<li>The Autism Act (2009)</li>\r\n<li>The Autism Act outcome 1: The Autism Strategy</li>\r\n<li>The Autism Act Outcome 2: The statutory guidance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(125, 'Module Three - Triad of Impairments', '<p>This module looks at the main three problems that people with autism often contend with as a result of their condition and aims to instil the learner with an understanding of how to recognise these.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Figure 3.1 The triad of impairments</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social interaction</li>\r\n<li>Other problems with social interaction include:</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social communication and language</li>\r\n<li>Verbal</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(126, 'Module Eight - Science and Cosmetology', '<p>This module details the make-up of products used and made available when providing beauty therapy services and also relevant sterilisation, hygiene and safety issues that also need to be considered when providing treatments. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Products for the skin</li>\r\n<li>Results</li>\r\n<li>Cost</li>\r\n<li>Convenience</li>\r\n<li>Animal testing</li>\r\n<li>Ingredients</li>\r\n<li>Products</li>\r\n<li>Sterilisation and hygiene</li>\r\n<li>Safety</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(127, 'Module Nine - Anatomy and Physiology', '<p>This module now looks at the biological terms that individuals working in the beauty industry should have an understanding of, in order to provide safe and effective treatments. Important subject areas such as; blood, tissue and muscles are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Anatomical terms</li>\r\n<li>Cells</li>\r\n<li>Tissue</li>\r\n<li>Blood</li>\r\n<li>The lymphatic system</li>\r\n<li>The human skeleton</li>\r\n<li>Muscles</li>\r\n<li>The skin</li>\r\n<li>Hair</li>\r\n<li>Other body systems</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(128, 'Module Four - Explaining Autistic behaviours', '<p>This module studies the different types of behaviour that someone with autism is likely to display and explores the possible reasons why these may occur.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Challenging behaviour: biting other people</li>\r\n<li>Possible causes of behaviour:</li>\r\n<li>Obsessions</li>\r\n<li>Repetition</li>\r\n<li>Routine</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(129, 'Module Five - Causes of Autism', '<p>This module explores what the likely causes of autism are, focussing on possible contributing factors such as genetic differences and environmental influences.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Autism or autistic traits</li>\r\n<li>Genetics</li>\r\n<li>Twin and other genetic studies</li>\r\n<li>Environmental factors</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(130, 'Module Six - Diagnosing Autism', '<p>This module considers the increasing number of people being diagnosed with autism and explores how to obtain a diagnosis and what the implications of this may be.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Factors contributing to increased awareness and diagnosis</li>\r\n<li>Models of disability</li>\r\n<li>Pros and cons of diagnosis</li>\r\n<li>How to get a diagnosis</li>\r\n<li>Getting support of the GP</li>\r\n<li>Young adults and older people</li>\r\n<li>Younger children</li>\r\n<li>All ages</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(131, 'Module Seven - Approaches to Autism', '<p>This module focuses on the variety of approaches which can be enforced to help promote the well-being of people who have autism, looking at areas such as; helping to improve behaviour and the benefit of assistance dogs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Behavioural approaches</li>\r\n<li>Dietary approaches</li>\r\n<li>Medical interventions</li>\r\n<li>Intensive Interaction</li>\r\n<li>Alternative communication systems</li>\r\n<li>Therapy</li>\r\n<li>Assistance dogs</li>\r\n<li>Autism friendly places</li>\r\n<li>Autism friendly websites</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(132, 'Module Eight - Practical Suggestions when Working with Autistic Individuals', '<p>This module looks specifically at the different actions that individuals can implement to actively help people with autism in everyday life.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Assisting with anxiety</li>\r\n<li>Behavioural strategies</li>\r\n<li>Speak clearly</li>\r\n<li>Identify emotions</li>\r\n<li>Remove sensory causes of stress</li>\r\n<li>Support with organising</li>\r\n<li>Technology</li>\r\n<li>Changes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(133, 'Module Nine - Explaining the Myths', '<p>This concluding module examines some of the beliefs that individuals may have about autism (and the people who have it) and the accuracy of these beliefs is critiqued.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>MMR vaccine has been shown to cause autism?</li>\r\n<li>People with autism have extraordinary abilities?</li>\r\n<li>Autism only affects children?</li>\r\n<li>Autism is new?</li>\r\n<li>Autism is a result of bad parenting and/or neglect?</li>\r\n<li>Asperger&rsquo;s syndrome is a made up condition to excuse bad parenting?</li>\r\n<li>Autistic people do not want social contact?</li>\r\n<li>Autistic people cannot be educated?</li>\r\n<li>People with autism cannot make eye contact?</li>\r\n<li>People with autism do not show affection, or are not capable of loving?</li>\r\n<li>Autism is a rare condition?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(134, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(135, 'Module Ten - Health and Safety', '<p>This module looks specifically at health and safety when working in a beauty therapy setting and examines important areas that need to be considered, such as; the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974, safety signs and waste disposal. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Health &amp; safety at work act (HASAW) 1974</li>\r\n<li>Acts applicable to all workplaces</li>\r\n<li>Manual handling operations regulations 1992</li>\r\n<li>Control of substances hazardous to health regulations 2002 (COSHH)</li>\r\n<li>Safety signs</li>\r\n<li>Accidents/ injuries and disease</li>\r\n<li>Hazard management</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining hygiene</li>\r\n<li>Salon environment</li>\r\n<li>Waste disposal</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(136, 'Module Eleven - Consultation', '<p>This module details the practice of providing consultations to clients as part of the beauty therapy process to ensure needs are met, and examines important factors such as; the record card, skin consultation and methods of communication. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Record card</li>\r\n<li>Consultation for facial treatments</li>\r\n<li>Signs of skin ageing</li>\r\n<li>Skin consultation</li>\r\n<li>Methods of communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(137, 'Module Twelve - Promotions and Retailing', '<p>This module explores the process of selling your services when working in beauty therapy. This broad term encompasses the selling actual products over the counter in addition to promoting the actual treatments that you provide. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Retailing in the beauty salon</li>\r\n<li>Setting and meeting targets</li>\r\n<li>Consumer legislation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(138, 'Module Thirteen - Reception', '<p>This module is concerned with the reception duties required in order to run successful beauty services and examines important considerations, such as; welcoming clients, dealing with complaints and insurance. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Salon systems and operations</li>\r\n<li>The reception area</li>\r\n<li>Welcoming clients</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with complaints</li>\r\n<li>Insurance</li>\r\n<li>Employment law</li>\r\n<li>Security</li>\r\n<li>Stock</li>\r\n<li>Emergency procedures</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(139, 'Module Fourteen - Career Opportunities and Continuing Professional Development', '<p>This concluding module draws upon the knowledge conveyed in the previous modules and examines how to apply what you have learned to career opportunities and professional development within your role. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Employability: Skills for finding and keeping a job</li>\r\n<li>Code of conduct</li>\r\n<li>Code of ethics</li>\r\n<li>Code of practice</li>\r\n<li>Personal and professional development</li>\r\n<li>Time management</li>\r\n<li>Team work</li>\r\n<li>Curriculum Vitae</li>\r\n<li>Further techniques</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(140, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(141, 'Module One - What is behaviour?', '<p>This introductory module examines the range of actions and mannerisms displayed by a person or animal in their environment, that make up behaviour, as a basis of understanding for the rest of the course.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Biological influences on behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Emotions and behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Environmental Influences on a child&rsquo;s behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Poverty</li>\r\n<li>Caregiver behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Role models</li>\r\n<li>Media</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(142, 'Module Two - What is challenging behaviour?', '<p>This module specifically looks at what constitutes challenging behaviour through the examination of relevant considerations, such as; what behaviours are challenging, feelings and behaviour and physical causes of challenging behaviour.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who displays challenging behaviour?</li>\r\n<li>What behaviours are challenging?</li>\r\n<li>Social model of disability</li>\r\n<li>Causes of challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Communication and challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Feelings and behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Mental health</li>\r\n<li>Physical causes of challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Labelling and stereotyping</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(143, 'Module Three - Assessment of challenging behaviour', '<p>This module is focussed on the approaches taken to assess why young people might display challenging behaviours and examines areas of relevance, such as; the child-centred approach and outcome of assessments.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Child-centred approach</li>\r\n<li>Functional assessment</li>\r\n<li>Recording behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Other assessments</li>\r\n<li>Outcome of assessments</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(144, 'Module Four - Strategies to minimise effects', '<p>This module studies the strategies that can be put in place by carers to help minimise the negative effects which can be caused by certain behaviours that are seen as challenging.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reactive strategies</li>\r\n<li>Understanding feelings</li>\r\n<li>Fight or Flight?</li>\r\n<li>Practical tips for remaining calm</li>\r\n<li>The five stages of emotional arousal</li>\r\n<li>Proactive strategies</li>\r\n<li>Routine and structure</li>\r\n<li>Maslow&rsquo;s Hierarchy of Needs (1959)</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(145, 'Module Five - Physical intervention', '<p>This module is concerned with sensitive issue of restraint and provides guidance of what kind of restraint is appropriate and in what situations it should be used.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of physical intervention</li>\r\n<li>Risks of physical intervention</li>\r\n<li>Recording physical intervention</li>\r\n<li>Smacking</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(146, 'Module Six - Recording, monitoring and record keeping', '<p>This module assesses the processes involved in keeping track of challenging behaviour in young people and looks at areas of relevance, such as; ABC charts, management guidelines and identification cards.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reporting and recording challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>ABC charts</li>\r\n<li>Health, safety and risk</li>\r\n<li>Management guidelines</li>\r\n<li>Identification card</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(147, 'Module Seven - Challenging behaviour and mental health', '<p>This module examines the relationship between challenging behaviour and mental health, studying the types of mental problems to look out for and what treatment can be implemented to help.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What does self-harm feel like?</li>\r\n<li>What causes self-harm?</li>\r\n<li>How can self-harm be managed?</li>\r\n<li>Getting help</li>\r\n<li>Possible treatment</li>\r\n<li>Family, friends and caregivers</li>\r\n<li>Eating disorders</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(148, 'Module Eight - Learning Disabilities', '<p>This module looks at the link between learning disabilities and challenging behaviour, and examines actions carers should take with regards to an individual&rsquo;s environment, in order to reduce the likelihood of challenging behaviour occurring.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of environment for people with learning disabilities</li>\r\n<li>The effect of environment on behaviour</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(149, 'Module Nine - Sensory issues and autism', '<p>This module explores the relationship between behaviours that challenge and common traits associated with sensory issues and autism, examining how the root cause of these behaviours can be identified and then managed with the appropriate understanding and support.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The triad of impairments</li>\r\n<li>Sensory issues and autism</li>\r\n<li>Challenging behaviour or not?</li>\r\n<li>Obsessions</li>\r\n<li>Routine</li>\r\n<li>Supporting positive behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Intensive interaction</li>\r\n<li>Autism friendly places</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(150, 'Module Ten - Legislation', '<p>This concluding module details specific laws which are in&nbsp;place with regards to challenging behaviour in children and young people. The main points that are of important relevance to those studying this course are examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Human Rights Act (1998)</li>\r\n<li>Types of discrimination</li>\r\n<li>Harassment</li>\r\n<li>Reasonable adjustments</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(151, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(152, 'Module One - Understand Child and Young Person Development', '<p>This module introduces the study of child care and early learning by first examining the process of how a child develops. The materials look at relevant considerations, such as expected development patterns, in order to underpin your understanding of a young person&rsquo;s learning requirements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The expected pattern of development for children and young people from birth-19 years</li>\r\n<li>Factors that influence children and young people&rsquo;s practice</li>\r\n<li>How to monitor children and young people&rsquo;s development and interventions that should take place if this is not following the expected pattern</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(153, 'Module Two - Safeguarding the Wellbeing of Children and Young People', '<p>This module studies the various ways in which children and young people are safeguarded and considers what your duty is in ensuring that this is maintained in line with the relevant legislative and other requirements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The main legislation, guidelines, policies and procedures for safeguarding children and young people</li>\r\n<li>The importance of working in partnership with other organisations to safeguard children and young people</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(154, 'Module Three - Children and young People\'s Health and Safety', '<p>This module considers what actions need to be taken to ensure children and young people learn in a safe environment and the materials examine how you can help facilitate this and support them to assess and manage risk for themselves.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to plan and provide environments and services that support children and young people&rsquo;s health and safety</li>\r\n<li>How to support children and young people to assess and manage risk for themselves</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(155, 'Module Four - How to Develop Positive Relationship with Children, Young People and Others Involved in Their Care', '<p>This module looks at how you can develop positive relationships with those associated with your care and studies the importance of positive communication in order to achieve this.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to develop positive relationships with children and young people</li>\r\n<li>How to build positive relationships with people involved in the care of children and young people</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(156, 'Module Five - Working Together for the Benefit of Children and Young People', '<p>This module is focussed on exploring the need to work with a variety of people in order to achieve the best knowledge about a child or young person, to help fulfil their needs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Integrated and multi-agency working</li>\r\n<li>How to communicate with others for professional purposes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(157, 'Module Six - Understand How to Support Positive Outcomes for Children and Young People', '<p>This module examines how children and young people can be affected by a range of factors, some of which may be life-limiting and considers what you can do to help them overcome these boundaries and achieve positive outcomes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How the social, economic and cultural environment can impact on the outcomes and life chances of children and young people</li>\r\n<li>The possible impact of disability, special requirements (additional needs) and attitudes on positive outcomes for children and young people</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(158, 'Module Seven - Promote communication in children’s and young people\'s settings', '<p>This module examines the importance of effective communication in order to achieve positive outcomes for children and young people and the materials look at how this can be promoted in the learning setting.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why effective communication is important in the work setting</li>\r\n<li>How to overcome barriers to communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(159, 'Module Eight - Promote equality and inclusion in children and young people\'s settings', '<p>This module is focussed on the importance of promoting equality and inclusion in a children and young people setting and considers relevant factors, such as; relevant legislation and how to overcome barriers to equality.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of diversity, equality and inclusion</li>\r\n<li>How to work in an inclusive way</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(160, 'Module Nine - Principles for implementing duty of care in children and young people\'s settings', '<p>This module looks at your responsibility in an early year&rsquo;s setting to adhere to a standard of reasonable care while performing any acts that could cause foreseeable harm to others. This is known as a duty of care and the materials examine how this should be provided for children and young people in your care.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How duty of care contributes to safe practice</li>\r\n<li>How to address conflicts or dilemmas that may arise between an individual&rsquo;s rights and the duty of care</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(161, 'Module Ten - Context and principles for early years’ provision', '<p>This module studies the need to apply a framework approach when catering for the needs of children and young people and considers the likely benefits which can be sought from doing so.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purposes and principles of early years frameworks</li>\r\n<li>How to provide environments within the work setting that support and extend children&rsquo;s development and learning in their early years</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(162, 'Module Eleven - Promote learning and development in the early years', '<p>This module focusses specifically on the process of promoting the learning and development of children and young people and considers relevant areas such as; the purpose and requirement of a learner&rsquo;s needs and how to plan appropriate support.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purpose and requirement of the areas of learning and development in the relevant early years framework</li>\r\n<li>How to plan work with children and support children&rsquo;s participation in planning</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(163, 'Module Twelve - Promote children’s welfare and well-being in the early years', '<p>This module is an expansion of module 2, however, it is more focused on how you should promote the well-being of children and young people within the early years setting. As such the materials look more specifically at how you can promote a positive environment that is both safe and secure and is in line with the relevant early year&rsquo;s framework.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The welfare requirements of the relevant early years framework</li>\r\n<li>How to keep early years children safe in the work setting</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(164, 'Module Thirteen - Professional practice in early years’ settings', '<p>This module examines the need to adopt a professional approach when providing services or support in an early years settings and considers actions which constitute this, such as; following specific legislation and evaluating your own work.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The scope and purpose of the early years sector</li>\r\n<li>How to support diversity, inclusion and participation in early years settings</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(165, 'Module Fourteen - Support children’s speech, language and communication', '<p>This concluding module again looks at the importance of communication, however, it looks at what you can do to promote this for children and young people who are having difficulties. As such the materials are focussed on the strategies you should implement to help achieve this goal.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of speech, language and communication for children&rsquo;s overall development</li>\r\n<li>How to provide support for the speech, language and communication development of the children in your own setting</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(166, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(167, 'Module One - The Nature of Type 1 Diabetes', '<p>This introductory module provides a general overview of what diabetes is and aims to explain the bodily system changes that cause the condition, looking in detail at areas such as; how the pancreas works and understanding insulin.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is diabetes?</li>\r\n<li>What is type 1 diabetes</li>\r\n<li>How the pancreas works</li>\r\n<li>Understanding glucose</li>\r\n<li>Understanding insulin</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(168, 'Module Two - Identification of Young People with Diabetes', '<p>This module examines the ways to detect whether a young person at various different ages has or may develop some type of diabetes, through the exploration of areas such as; type 1 and 2 diabetes symptoms, diabetes in teenagers and diabetes insipidus.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Recognising the symptoms of type 1 diabetes</li>\r\n<li>Recognising the symptoms of type 2 diabetes</li>\r\n<li>Diabetes in babies</li>\r\n<li>Diabetes in children</li>\r\n<li>Diabetes in teenagers</li>\r\n<li>Type 2 diabetes in children</li>\r\n<li>Older people with type 1 diabetes</li>\r\n<li>Diabetes Insipidus (DI)</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(169, 'Module Three - Understanding Medication', '<p>This module studies the type of medication needed to treat and help individuals live with diabetes and explores important considerations such as; how to administer the appropriate medication and why certain medication is needed.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Understanding medication and what is needed</li>\r\n<li>How to administer medication</li>\r\n<li>What the medication does</li>\r\n<li>Why medication is needed</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(170, 'Module Four - Complications of Diabetes', '<p>This module instructs the learner about the complications that arise from diabetes, exploring problems such as; heart disease, diabetic eye problems and ketones. It teaches about what symptoms to look out for and how to deal with the problems as they happen.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Atherosclerosis</li>\r\n<li>Heart disease</li>\r\n<li>Strokes</li>\r\n<li>Diabetic kidney disease &ndash; Nephropathy</li>\r\n<li>Diabetic eye problems</li>\r\n<li>Diabetic neuropathy</li>\r\n<li>Skin and mouth conditions</li>\r\n<li>Ketones</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(171, 'Module Five - Diet and Lifestyle Changes', '<p>In this module, the learner will discover why good nutrition is so significant to health in general but more so in diabetes. It explains the effects diets have on the condition and how to eat to control blood glucose levels.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eating diabetic foods</li>\r\n<li>Sweets and treats</li>\r\n<li>Diets to avoid</li>\r\n<li>Eating plan for a diabetic</li>\r\n<li>Experimenting with alcohol</li>\r\n<li>Understanding carbohydrates</li>\r\n<li>Fats</li>\r\n<li>Drinks</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(172, 'Module Six - Living with Diabetes', '<p>This module is dedicated to understanding how it is for a young person to live with their diabetic condition, having a perspective on the problems that they face and the worries they have.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How the service user deals with the condition</li>\r\n<li>How the parents/carers deal with a diagnosis</li>\r\n<li>Caring for children with diabetes</li>\r\n<li>What teachers need to know about their students</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(173, 'Module Seven - Growing up with Diabetes', '<p>This module introduces the learner into the life of a young person who has diabetes growing up and explores areas of relevance in this journey, such as; typical problems faced, limitations of being diabetic and common questions that sufferers have.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Living with the condition as they age</li>\r\n<li>Problems faced in teenage years</li>\r\n<li>The limitations of being a diabetic</li>\r\n<li>Questions that the sufferers ask</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(174, 'Module Eight - Diabetic Emergencies', '<p>This module explores the numerous contraindications of diabetes and the seriousness of their nature. Areas such as hypoglycaemic and hyperglycaemia are detailed and guidance on how to spot such conditions and when to call for help is examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Having a hypoglycemic episode</li>\r\n<li>Having a hyperglycaemic episode</li>\r\n<li>Ketoacidosis</li>\r\n<li>When to contact to medical professional</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(175, 'Module Nine - Pregnancy', '<p>This final module assesses the sensitive subject area of pregnancy in youngsters and how having diabetes in likely to impact this, through the study of relevant areas such as; contraindications of pregnancy and gestational diabetes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Teenage pregnancy in a diabetic</li>\r\n<li>What to consider when deciding to have a baby</li>\r\n<li>Contraindications of pregnancy</li>\r\n<li>Gestational diabetes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(176, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(177, 'Module One - Understand safeguarding in adult health and social care', '<p>This unit studies the issues relating to safeguarding adults in health and social care and explores relevant considerations such as; legislation and the roles of different agencies involved in protecting individuals from abuse or harm.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The national and local context of safeguarding and protection from abuse</li>\r\n<li>How to recognise potential and actual abuse and harm</li>\r\n<li>How to respond if potential, suspected or actual harm or abuse is disclosed, suspected or alleged</li>\r\n<li>Ways to reduce the likelihood of harm and abuse in the health and care sector</li>\r\n<li>Information and support in relation to abuse or harm</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(178, 'Module Two - Principles of dignity in adult health and social are practice', '<p>This unit explores issues relating to dignity, self-worth and well-being and studies how to apply the principles of dignity and gain an understanding of the importance of professional relationships for supporting dignity in service provision.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The principles of dignity in adult health and social care</li>\r\n<li>The potential impact for individuals when accessing and using health and social care services</li>\r\n<li>How to apply the principles of dignity in adult health and social care</li>\r\n<li>How a person-centred approach contributes to dignity in adult health and social care</li>\r\n<li>The role of the health and social care worker in relation to promoting dignity</li>\r\n<li>The importance of professional relationships for dignity and service provision</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(179, 'Module Three - Understanding duty of care in adult health and social care', '<p>This unit considers the issues relating to duty of care within the context of adult health and social care and examines relevant considerations such as; the possible conflicts and dilemmas faced between duty of care and individuals&rsquo; rights and the implications of unsafe practice.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is meant by \'duty of care\'</li>\r\n<li>Dilemmas and conflicts relating to duty of care</li>\r\n<li>How to recognise and report unsafe practices</li>\r\n<li>The impact of own actions on individuals and others</li>\r\n<li>The importance of consent in health and social care practice</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(180, 'Module Four - Understand dilemmas and public concerns in adult and social care', '<p>This unit examines the potential dilemmas and issues of public concern in adult health and social care and also studies wider issues, such as how media reporting and people\'s perception has impacted on adult health and social care practice.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dilemmas that may be encountered in adult health and social care</li>\r\n<li>Issues of public concern in adult health and social care</li>\r\n<li>Serious case reviews and independent case reviews which have impacted on adult health and social care practice</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(181, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(182, 'Module One - Pioneers of Forensic Science', '<p>This introductory module explores the general process of forensic science in terms of how it has developed over time and which individuals made great strides with this progression.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Developmental history</li>\r\n<li>Development of forensic science techniques</li>\r\n<li>Pioneers of forensic science</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(183, 'Module Two - Case Study 1 – The Bodies in the Stream (The Jigsaw Case)', '<p>This module details the first case study of the course and studies the apparent murder of a person who was found disembodied in a stream below a bridge. The various processes that were involved in establishing this murder are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Forensic specialities</li>\r\n<li>Picture of events</li>\r\n<li>Chain of evidence continuity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(184, 'Module Three - Forensic Pathology', '<p>This module examines the concept of forensic pathology in terms of how changes in the structure and function of parts of the body can help discover the cause of death. Relevant areas such as; the autopsy procedure and the determination of sex, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Discovering how death occurred</li>\r\n<li>At the scene of the crime</li>\r\n<li>The autopsy procedure</li>\r\n<li>Dissection of the corpse</li>\r\n<li>Collection of samples</li>\r\n<li>Steps in determination of sex</li>\r\n<li>Determining why death occurred</li>\r\n<li>Other duties of a pathologist</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(185, 'Module Four - Forensic Anthropology', '<p>This module studies the process of forensic anthropology in terms of its role in analysing human remains for medico-legal purposes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Role of the forensic anthropologist</li>\r\n<li>Osteology</li>\r\n<li>Dentition</li>\r\n<li>Biological profile</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(186, 'Module Five - Entomology and Botany', '<p>The study of insects and their role in relation to the examination of dead bodies is the main focus of this module and relevant considerations such as; colonisation of the corpse and blowfly development, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Colonisation of the corpse</li>\r\n<li>The role of the forensic entomologist</li>\r\n<li>External influences affecting blowfly development</li>\r\n<li>Drawing conclusions</li>\r\n<li>Forensic botany</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(187, 'Module Six - Case Study 2 The Body in the Carpet', '<p>This module is concerned with the second case study of the course, the discovery of a body found a few feet below the earth, rolled up in a rotting carpet. The relevant considerations involved in establishing the cause of death, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The \'ologists</li>\r\n<li>Forensic Artist/Sculptor</li>\r\n<li>DNA analysis</li>\r\n<li>The confession</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(188, 'Module Seven - Cranio-facial Reconstruction', '<p>This module explores the technology of Cranio-facial Reconstruction and its role in reconstructing the head of a dead or missing person to assist in murder investigations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>History of craniofacial construction</li>\r\n<li>The Russian technique</li>\r\n<li>The American technique</li>\r\n<li>The Manchester technique</li>\r\n<li>The forensic artist/sculptor</li>\r\n<li>Video superimposition</li>\r\n<li>Computer assisted facial reconstruction</li>\r\n<li>Computer tomography</li>\r\n<li>Colour mapping</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(189, 'Module Eight - Body Fluids and DNA', '<p>This module looks at the importance of bodily fluids in determining the cause of a crime. The pertinence of contact between the victim and the attacker is established and methods of examining fluids of relevance is detailed.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Identification of body fluids</li>\r\n<li>Recovery of items stained with body fluids</li>\r\n<li>Blood typing</li>\r\n<li>DNA and the development of DNA profiling techniques</li>\r\n<li>National DNA Database</li>\r\n<li>Potential to contaminate?</li>\r\n<li>The first case to be solved using DNA Profiling &ndash; The Colin Pitchfork Case</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(190, 'Module Nine - Case Study 3 – Who Killed Bambi?', '<p>The third case study of the course is the focus of this module and the death of a young woman on a farm is examined in terms of the controversy surrounding the investigation process.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ideas and evidence</li>\r\n<li>Professional crime scene management</li>\r\n<li>Different evidence interpretations</li>\r\n<li>Misinterpreting evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(191, 'Module Ten - Crime Scene Management and the Chain of Evidence', '<p>This module details the process of examining the crime scene in order to provide possibilities for advancing an investigation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Chain of evidence</li>\r\n<li>Senior Investigating Officer</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene manager</li>\r\n<li>Investigator</li>\r\n<li>The golden hour principle and fast track action</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene</li>\r\n<li>Photographs</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene sketch</li>\r\n<li>Fingerprints</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(192, 'Module Eleven - Ballistics', '<p>This module is focussed on the study of firearm usage in crimes and explores areas such as; how they are used, why they are used and why they are used frequently in the commission of crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of firearms</li>\r\n<li>Firearm evidence submitted to forensic laboratories</li>\r\n<li>The role of a forensic ballistic expert</li>\r\n<li>Firearms identification</li>\r\n<li>Restoration of serial numbers</li>\r\n<li>Ammunition comparison</li>\r\n<li>Identification of trace evidence</li>\r\n<li>Direction and angle of trajectory</li>\r\n<li>Gunshot wounds</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(193, 'Module Twelve - Fingerprints', '<p>The examination of fingerprints used for the purposes of a criminal investigation is the focus this module. Relevant information on areas such as the fingerprint classification system and how to take fingerprints at the scene of a crime, are explored. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Henry fingerprint classification system</li>\r\n<li>Prints at the scene of crime</li>\r\n<li>Taking fingerprints</li>\r\n<li>IDENT1</li>\r\n<li>The fingerprint expert</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(194, 'Module Thirteen - Forensic Photographer', '<p>This module explores the role and importance of using efficient photography techniques as part of the criminal investigation process.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Role of the Forensic Photographer</li>\r\n<li>Forensic Photography Career Paths</li>\r\n<li>Forensic Photography Skills Set</li>\r\n<li>Photographic Equipment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(195, 'Module Fourteen - Case Study 4 – Doctor Death', '<p>This module covers the fourth case study of the course and the focus is the forensic investigation behind the serial killings of Doctor, Harold Shipman. Relevant areas such as; the role of forensic experts and learning from mistakes are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Judgement errors</li>\r\n<li>Forensic expert figurations</li>\r\n<li>Role of forensic experts</li>\r\n<li>Consequences of offender incompetence</li>\r\n<li>Learning from mistakes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(196, 'Module Fifteen - Forensic Toxicology', '<p>This module examines the branch of forensic science that seeks to identify and quantify the presence of toxins (poisons) in the human body and explores the relevance of this process in relation to establishing a crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Role of the forensic toxicologist</li>\r\n<li>Toxicological investigation</li>\r\n<li>Forensic toxicology &ndash; Sample testing</li>\r\n<li>Toxicological testing techniques</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(197, 'Module Sixteen - Disputed Documents', '<p>This module looks at the prevalence of written or printed documents used for interaction between people and how these can be used for criminal purposes. The ways in which such documents can be examined is explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Disputed document examination</li>\r\n<li>Handwriting</li>\r\n<li>Alterations &amp; obliterations</li>\r\n<li>Gas chromatography &ndash; Mass spectroscopy</li>\r\n<li>Electrostatic detection apparatus</li>\r\n<li>Video spectral comparator</li>\r\n<li>Typewriter comparison</li>\r\n<li>Printed documents</li>\r\n<li>Papers</li>\r\n<li>Inks and dyes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(198, 'Module Seventeen - Computer Crime', '<p>This module looks at the use of networked computers or internet technology to commit or facilitate the commission of crime and examines the complexities and ways of gathering evidence in relation to this crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Old crimes</li>\r\n<li>New types of crime</li>\r\n<li>Increases in computer crime</li>\r\n<li>Police response</li>\r\n<li>Computer forensics</li>\r\n<li>Forensic computer investigation</li>\r\n<li>Computer evidence</li>\r\n<li>Investigative problems</li>\r\n<li>ACPO evidence gathering principles</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(199, 'Module Eighteen - Case Study 5 Miscarriages of Justice', '<p>This module features another case study and the focus here is on errors made within the criminal investigation process and how these led to noteworthy examples of miscarriages of justice.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Case study 5(a) The Lesley Molseed murder</li>\r\n<li>Case study 5(b) The Birmingham six</li>\r\n<li>Case study 5(c) Evidence of Roy Meadow</li>\r\n<li>Reason for miscarriages of justice</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(200, 'Module Nineteen - The Chain of Evidence/The Professionalisation of the Investigative Process', '<p><strong>The Chain of Evidence/The Professionalisation of the Investigative Process</strong></p>\r\n<p>This module is concerned with the accumulation of evidence relevant to a criminal investigation and examines how this should be treated with professionalisation in order to abide by applicable rules.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Forms of evidence</li>\r\n<li>Characteristics of evidence</li>\r\n<li>Admissibility of evidence</li>\r\n<li>Classification of evidence</li>\r\n<li>The chain of evidence</li>\r\n<li>Obtaining and preserving evidence</li>\r\n<li>Professionalising the investigative process</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(201, 'Module Twenty - Case Study 6 Cold Cases', '<p>The final case study of the course is the focus of this module and the investigation process involved in establishing results from older cases that were previously unsuccessful is explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Cold case problems</li>\r\n<li>New technology and investigative techniques</li>\r\n<li>Operation Phoenix</li>\r\n<li>Information required</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(202, 'Module Twenty One - Careers in Forensics', '<p>This concluding module explores forensic science in relation to establishing a career in this subject area. Learners will be equipped with knowledge on relevant areas such as, the relevant academic requirements and what training on the job would be necessary.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Scientific support within police forces</li>\r\n<li>Career opportunities</li>\r\n<li>Training to become a forensic scientist</li>\r\n<li>Academic requirements</li>\r\n<li>Person specification</li>\r\n<li>Training on-the-job</li>\r\n<li>Forensic medicine and forensic dentistry</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(203, 'Module One - Management and the Role of the HR Department', '<p>This introductory module explores the role a HR department plays within a business and examines relevant areas such as; management duties and corporate strategy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Role of management</li>\r\n<li>Management duties</li>\r\n<li>Corporate strategy</li>\r\n<li>The concept of HR Management</li>\r\n<li>The role of the HR department</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(204, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(205, 'Module Two - Employee Planning, Recruitment & Selection', '<p>The focus of this module is the key HR Management processes and activities of planning, recruitment and selection and examines their purpose to ensure an organisation is staffed with the right kind of people to meet the needs of the business.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Principles of Human Resource planning</li>\r\n<li>Job vacancy decisions</li>\r\n<li>The recruitment procedure</li>\r\n<li>Employment selection</li>\r\n<li>Employee selection interview</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(206, 'Module Three - Contract of Employment and Employee Induction', '<p>This module details a business&rsquo;s role in drawing up a contract of employment and examines the factors that need to be considered when preparing an effective induction programme.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Forming an employment contract</li>\r\n<li>Employment contract terms</li>\r\n<li>Employment induction process</li>\r\n<li>The employee induction programme</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(207, 'Module Four - Managing Performance and Employee Appraisal', '<p>This module is concerned with the performance of the team within an organisation and discusses the scope of performance management and explores the many factors that may be attributed to an employee&rsquo;s performance levels.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purpose of performance management</li>\r\n<li>Measuring performance levels</li>\r\n<li>Improving performance levels</li>\r\n<li>Employee appraisals</li>\r\n<li>Employee appraisal meeting</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(208, 'Module Five - Workplace Learning and Employee Development', '<p>This module highlights the importance of developing people within a work setting and examines how HR Management need to promote the use of effective employee development practices.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What learning is</li>\r\n<li>Conditions for effective workplace learning</li>\r\n<li>Employment development</li>\r\n<li>Stages of the employee development process</li>\r\n<li>Terms of coaching and development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(209, 'Module Six - Managing People and Developing Relations', '<p>This module looks at the broad nature of people management and covers a range of issues such as; the different approaches to managing people, dealing with difficult situations and building effective working relationships.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Approaches to managing people</li>\r\n<li>Organisational change</li>\r\n<li>Benefits of teamwork</li>\r\n<li>Conflict</li>\r\n<li>Equal opportunities and diversity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(210, 'Module Seven - Employee Retention and Commitment', '<p>This module explores the issues relating to labour turnover in terms of retaining employees and company loyalty. The problems caused by poor labour turnover is the main area examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Monitoring labour hand over</li>\r\n<li>Measuring labour handover</li>\r\n<li>Impact of labour handover</li>\r\n<li>Why people leave organisations</li>\r\n<li>Improving employment commitment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(211, 'Module Eight - Employee Absence and Well-being', '<p>This module examines the occurrence of employees within a business being absent from work and focusses on pertinent areas of relevance such as, categories of absence and measuring employee absence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Categories and types of employee absence</li>\r\n<li>Employee absence management</li>\r\n<li>Measuring employee absence</li>\r\n<li>Employee absence control and improvement</li>\r\n<li>Employee health, safety and welfare legislation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(212, 'Module Nine - Employee Discipline and Grievance', '<p>This module explores how a business needs to enforce effective employee disciplinary and grievance procedures and examines the importance of acting swiftly to effectively deal with any difficult issues as soon as they arise.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purpose of employee discipline procedure</li>\r\n<li>Handling a disciplinary situation</li>\r\n<li>Acts of gross misconduct</li>\r\n<li>Employee grievance</li>\r\n<li>Handling employee grievance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(213, 'Module Ten - Termination of Employment', '<p>This final module studies the termination of employment and explains the procedures that should be followed in the various situations where an employee&rsquo;s contract of employment may need to be terminated.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Termination of employment relationship</li>\r\n<li>Dismissal</li>\r\n<li>Fair dismissal</li>\r\n<li>Unfair dismissal</li>\r\n<li>Redundancy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(214, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(215, 'Module One - State Pensions', '<p>This introductory unit is concerned with one of the most important considerations when retiring, which is claiming a state pension. The materials provide a detailed explanation of this process and outline who to contact for advice.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What a state pension actually is</li>\r\n<li>The different elements within the state pension</li>\r\n<li>Who to contact for state pension advice</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(216, 'Module Two - Private Pensions', '<p>This unit studies the option of enrolling on a private pension in the workplace and examines a range of relevant factors on this process, such as; private pension types, drawdown and investment options.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What a private pension actually is</li>\r\n<li>The types of private pensions available</li>\r\n<li>Private pensions explained</li>\r\n<li>Annuities</li>\r\n<li>Drawdown</li>\r\n<li>Investment options</li>\r\n<li>Who to contact for financial pension advice</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(217, 'Module Three - Health and Fitness', '<p>This unit considers the importance of maintaining a healthy lifestyle during your retirement and looks at ways in which this can be achieved and the implications if it is not. Factors such as; nutritional needs, exercise and fluid intake are examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of a healthy lifestyle</li>\r\n<li>The effects of bad habits</li>\r\n<li>Nutritional needs as we grow older</li>\r\n<li>The right foods to be eating</li>\r\n<li>The importance of adequate fluid intake</li>\r\n<li>Benefits of exercise</li>\r\n<li>The need to visit the GP, optician and dentist</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(218, 'Module Four - Keeping Busy', '<p>This unit looks at the various ways in which you can keep yourself occupied during retirement and examines the importance of it. The materials outline a range of options available to you; from volunteering, to travel, to the option of continuing with work.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of keeping busy throughout retirement</li>\r\n<li>Different ways to keep busy</li>\r\n<li>Requirements when travelling</li>\r\n<li>The requirements when working through retirement</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(219, 'Module Five - Future Planning', '<p>This concluding unit is focussed on the sensitive and sometimes complex process of future planning during your retirement. The materials study areas such as &lsquo;wills&rsquo; and &lsquo;funeral&rsquo; planning and aim to explain the relevant considerations to promote ease when making such arrangements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What a will actually is</li>\r\n<li>The different types of wills available</li>\r\n<li>The &lsquo;witness&rsquo;, &lsquo;executor&rsquo;, &lsquo;beneficiary&rsquo; and &lsquo;trustee&rsquo;</li>\r\n<li>Inheritance tax</li>\r\n<li>Funeral planning options</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(220, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(221, 'Module One - Being a dog groomer', '<p>This module introduces the art of dog grooming and considers the range of tasks that are involved in this process, in addition to possible reasons why owners wish to have their dogs groomed and how the treatments can be beneficial to the dog.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why people have their dog groomed</li>\r\n<li>Dog dress and accessories</li>\r\n<li>Restraints, leads and collars and how they are used</li>\r\n<li>Health and safety</li>\r\n<li>Dog anatomy and physiology</li>\r\n<li>Adaptions to skin conditions a dog may have</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(222, 'Module Two - Equipment used and handling dogs', '<p>This module studies the various types of equipment which are used when dog grooming and considers the actions to take when you are confronted with a dog that is showing signs of aggression.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dealing with aggressive dogs to prevent bites and other injuries</li>\r\n<li>Dog equipment and how to use it</li>\r\n<li>Types of shampoos and other products used for grooming</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(223, 'Module Three - Preparation and bathing procedure', '<p>This module is concerned with the basic procedures that are required to inspect, brush or comb, and bathe a dog and considers relevant factors, such as; inspecting the dog&rsquo;s coat and paws, and techniques used.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preparing a dog for grooming and removing unwanted debris</li>\r\n<li>How to pre-brush a dog before bathing and its importance</li>\r\n<li>How to clip a dog&rsquo;s coat prior to bathing</li>\r\n<li>How to brush long or double-coated breeds</li>\r\n<li>The procedure of bathing a dog and how to prevent the dog from escaping</li>\r\n<li>Techniques of wet down, soap up and rinse</li>\r\n<li>Procedure for drying the dog</li>\r\n<li>How to trim the dog&rsquo;s nails and dew claws</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(224, 'Module Four - Clipping, stripping and using scissors', '<p>This module studies how to use clippers, scissors and other tools on a dog to remove hair and fur and looks at relevant considerations, such as; clipper blade sizes, clipping techniques and where on the dog&rsquo;s body the tools are used.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Clippers and clipper blades and which ones are used on specific dog breeds</li>\r\n<li>The procedure used to clip a dog with clippers</li>\r\n<li>How to clip or trim the hair around and on the dog&rsquo;s paws</li>\r\n<li>The different shapes and styles used to groom poodles</li>\r\n<li>The meaning of stripping hair from a dog with hands and specific tools</li>\r\n<li>Why the groomer uses scissors</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(225, 'Module Five - Setting up your business', '<p>This concluding module examines how you can start your own business as a dog grooming professional and looks at relevant considerations, such as; set up costs, creating a business plan and advertising.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The pros and cons of running a dog grooming business</li>\r\n<li>Where to run a business from and how to manage the setup costs</li>\r\n<li>Creating a business plan</li>\r\n<li>The importance of advertising and how to do it</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(226, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(227, 'Module One - An introduction to family support work', '<p>The module acts as an introduction to the area of family support work and offers a general overview of the types of issues a family might have, along with a study on the nature of multiagency working.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Assisting with family issues</li>\r\n<li>Family conflict</li>\r\n<li>Agency examples</li>\r\n<li>Usefulness of multiagency working.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(228, 'Module Two - Understanding the family and their problems', '<p>This module studies in greater detail, the nature of some of the most common family problems, such as addiction and finance struggles. The materials consider the application of child psychology to determine how younger family members might be affected by different issues and begins to consider solutions which could be implemented.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Psychology and child psychology</li>\r\n<li>Social and emotional development in children</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to child development</li>\r\n<li>Family problems</li>\r\n<li>Children with special needs</li>\r\n<li>Young carers and illness</li>\r\n<li>The benefit of spending quality time together.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(229, 'Module Three - Overcoming barriers', '<p>This module is concerned with the multitude of factors which may be causing a tense family situation, that is not easy to resolve without taking necessary steps to diffuse any initial conflict in order to break through to the underlying problem/s.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to establish problems when first meeting with the family</li>\r\n<li>How anger contributes to family conflict and how the family support worker can help resolve this</li>\r\n<li>Using counselling skills when working with families to overcome barriers</li>\r\n<li>How to meet parents needs in a variety of situations</li>\r\n<li>Helping with family budgeting needs.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(230, 'Module Four - Safeguarding', '<p>This module examines an essential part of the family support worker\'s role, which is ensuring that individuals that are deemed vulnerable, are safeguarded in line with relevant legislative procedures.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Safeguarding legislation that protects children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Signs of child abuse and neglect</li>\r\n<li>The role of the family support worker in child protection</li>\r\n<li>What constitutes a vulnerable parent and how this can affect the family unit.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(231, 'Module Five - Build and maintain relationships with parents', '<p>This module looks at what constitutes a positive relationship and examines the strategies which can be taken by the family support worker to establish a positive relationship with the family in order to help them build an effective one with their own family.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Values and principles that underpin relationships in a professional capacity</li>\r\n<li>The nature of working effectively with parents</li>\r\n<li>Barriers that may be presented to parents and ways these can be overcome</li>\r\n<li>Aspects of a successfully built and maintained relationship with parents</li>\r\n<li>Why counselling skills are an important role of the family support worker.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(232, 'Module Six - Working with parents to meet their children\'s needs', '<p>A further examination of the relationship with parents will be carried out here but this time with more focus on individual strategies to help parents with their children. Child development aspects will also be included so that knowledge of age-appropriate approaches can be enhanced.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The nature of the parent and child relationship</li>\r\n<li>Aspects of being a new parent</li>\r\n<li>How to assist parents in understanding the relationship they have with their children</li>\r\n<li>Bowlby&rsquo;s theory of attachment and how this applies to parent and child relationships</li>\r\n<li>What is meant by age-appropriate support examples of this</li>\r\n<li>Methods of helping parents provide age-appropriate support.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(233, 'Module Seven - Legislation', '<p>This module examines in more detail, the essential need to follow relevant legislation as part of the family support worker role and studies areas such as; risk assessment, equality and diversity.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Equality and diversity</li>\r\n<li>Hazard and risk</li>\r\n<li>Lone Worker policy</li>\r\n<li>The importance of assessment and planning.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(234, 'Module Eight - Effective communication with families', '<p>This module has a specific focus on communication where you will look at many types of communication and how to apply this within the role. The aim will be to improve communication with a variety of people and how to look for signs that communication barriers are present.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The difference between \'hearing and \'listening\'</li>\r\n<li>Types of verbal and non-verbal communication</li>\r\n<li>How to ensure parents are confident in communicating effectively</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to communication</li>\r\n<li>What resources can be provided to parents to help with communication.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(235, 'Module Nine - Positive relationship strategies', '<p>In this penultimate module, we will come back to parent and child relationships and look at how you as the support worker can help families in understanding their children&rsquo;s needs and how to respond to them appropriately. We will also discuss how you can help parents expand their own knowledge to help their children be successful.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Modelling behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Parenting styles</li>\r\n<li>Helping children to deal with their feelings</li>\r\n<li>How to overcome conflict within the parent and child relationship</li>\r\n<li>Assess possible hazards to children inside and outside of the home</li>\r\n<li>Ways of helping parents to get their child into a regular sleeping routine and healthy eating habits.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(236, 'Module Ten - Support parents to gain knowledge and access information and services', '<p>The final module will bring everything together and we will finish by assessing the importance of helping families to access services and information so that by the time their work with you is finished, they will be empowered to resolve some of their own issues and work towards autonomy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The difference between statutory, voluntary and private agencies</li>\r\n<li>How to identify parents&rsquo; needs</li>\r\n<li>Determining when parents need alternative formats of information and how to access these</li>\r\n<li>Potential barriers to information and explain how to overcome these</li>\r\n<li>Where to find up-to-date information for parents and how to check that it has been understood</li>\r\n<li>How to understand if parenting services are being carried out effectively.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(237, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(238, 'Module One - The History of Foetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorders', '<p>This module will detail the origins of the diagnostic term Foetal Alcohol Syndrome (FAS), identify the effects of alcohol and current guidance on safe alcohol limits during pregnancy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Definition of FAS</li>\r\n<li>FASD and Abortion</li>\r\n<li>What is Alcohol?</li>\r\n<li>Alcohol Use</li>\r\n<li>Alcohol Consumption in Pregnancy</li>\r\n<li>Measuring Alcohol Consumption</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(239, 'Module Two - Taking Responsibility for the Unborn Child', '<p>This module will introduce issues surrounding parental, corporate and government responsibilities with regards to alcohol consumption and will explain the key criteria for diagnosing Foetal Alcohol Syndrome (FAS).</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Candace Thorp v Jim Beam</li>\r\n<li>FAS from Diagnosis to Current Day</li>\r\n<li>What is Alcohol?</li>\r\n<li>Alcohol Consumption in Pregnancy</li>\r\n<li>Measuring Alcohol Consumption</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(240, 'Module Three - Prenatal Alcohol Exposure and Screening', '<p>This module will identify the screening tools used to help identify alcohol disorders, the effects of alcohol on the developing foetus and the range of foetal alcohol disorders experienced by children with prenatal alcohol exposure. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Screening for Alcohol Use</li>\r\n<li>Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (Audit)</li>\r\n<li>The CAGE questionnaire</li>\r\n<li>The T-ACE questionnaire</li>\r\n<li>Other Factors Affecting FASD</li>\r\n<li>In Utero Effects of Alcohol</li>\r\n<li>Risks During the 3 Trimesters</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(241, 'Module Four - Children with Foetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorders (FASD)', '<p>This module will explain the range of disabilities and difficulties experienced by children with FASD, as well as screening for the developmental and behavioural problems they may experience.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Primary Disabilities</li>\r\n<li>Neuropsychological Problems</li>\r\n<li>Secondary Disabilities</li>\r\n<li>Measuring Secondary Disabilities using VABS</li>\r\n<li>Measuring Adaptive and Maladaptive Behaviours</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(242, 'Module Five - Behavioural Phenotypes of FASD', '<p>behavioural capabilities and assist care givers in planning their support.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Behavioural Checklists</li>\r\n<li>Development of Children with FASD</li>\r\n<li>FASD in Infancy</li>\r\n<li>Neonatal Behavioural Assessment Scale</li>\r\n<li>FASD in Preschool</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(243, 'Module Six - Growing up with FASD', '<p>This module will explain the mental and behavioural difficulties faced by children with FASD as they progress from school age, through to adulthood. In addition, the possible interventions to assist individuals&rsquo; successful integration into school and society will also be explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>FASD in the School Age- Child</li>\r\n<li>FASD in Adolescence</li>\r\n<li>FASD in Adulthood</li>\r\n<li>FASD in Employment</li>\r\n<li>Living Alone with FASD</li>\r\n<li>FASD - Support in the Future</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(244, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(245, 'Module One - Communication and Positive Relationships', '<p>This module establishes your role as a HLTA in initiating, developing, supporting and maintaining positive relationships with a range of people within your working environment.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Communicating Effectively and Sensitively with Children, Young People, Colleagues, Parents and Carers</li>\r\n<li>Encouraging Children&rsquo;s Positive Behaviour to Maintain Positive Relationships</li>\r\n<li>The Importance of Communication and Being Professional in Your Approach to Working Relationships</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(246, 'Module Two - Curriculum, Planning and Assessment', '<p>All educational institutions teach within the framework of a curriculum that sets out the expectations and standards of each subject, within the age range of the students being taught or according to the qualification being studied. Within this module, you will look at the different aspects of curriculum, planning and assessment that are relevant to your role as a HLTA&rsquo;s.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The National Curriculum</li>\r\n<li>Special Educational Needs (SEN) Legislation and Codes of Practice</li>\r\n<li>ICT Curriculum</li>\r\n<li>Curriculum Planning</li>\r\n<li>Delivery of Learning Activities</li>\r\n<li>What Type of Support is Required</li>\r\n<li>Supervision</li>\r\n<li>Risks and Hazards</li>\r\n<li>Health and Safety</li>\r\n<li>Safety Equipment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(247, 'Module Three - Child Development', '<p>This module details the multiple factors that you as a HLTA must consider in order to aid child development.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered within the module include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Basic Principles &amp; Stages of Children&rsquo;s and Young People&rsquo;s Development</li>\r\n<li>What is a &lsquo;Safe and Healthy&rsquo; Environment</li>\r\n<li>Stages of Development</li>\r\n<li>Physical Development and Skills</li>\r\n<li>Communication and Intellectual Development</li>\r\n<li>Social and Emotional Development</li>\r\n<li>Supporting Children and Young People through Transitions in their Lives</li>\r\n<li>The importance of parents and carers in the development and well-being of children and young people</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(248, 'Module Four - Personal Professional Development', '<p>This module provides all the relevant guidance to help ensure that you develop both professionally and personally within your role as a HTLA.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Accessing and Evaluating Emerging Theory and Practice to Develop Professionally and Update Your Knowledge and Practice</li>\r\n<li>Knowing How to Use ICT to Support Professional Activities</li>\r\n<li>Evidencing the Required Qualifications</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(249, 'Module Five - Equality and Diversity and Inclusion', '<p>This module discusses the multiple factors you must consider in your role as a HLTA to ensure the equality, diversity and inclusion of children is achieved and maintained.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is equality &amp; diversity?</li>\r\n<li>Legislation</li>\r\n<li>Multi-Agency Teams</li>\r\n<li>Special Educational Needs (SEN)</li>\r\n<li>Models of disability</li>\r\n<li>How do we communicate effectively and develop working relationships with other practitioners and professionals?</li>\r\n<li>Removing Barriers to Learning for Pupils with Communication and Interaction Difficulties</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(250, 'Appendix 1 - 3', '<p>Please click on the relevant appendix/appendices below when you require additional information or when you are instructed to by the course materials. Please note: Some activities may require you to look at more than one appendix.</p>', 0),
(251, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(252, 'Module One - Recruitment, Selection and Induction', '<p>This module covers managing the acquisition of new staff and includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The requirement</li>\r\n<li>Job descriptions</li>\r\n<li>Person specification</li>\r\n<li>Equality, diversity and discrimination</li>\r\n<li>Advertising vacancies</li>\r\n<li>Application and short-listing process</li>\r\n<li>Interview and selection process</li>\r\n<li>Informing the successful candidate</li>\r\n<li>Managing notes and selection records</li>\r\n<li>Induction</li>\r\n<li>Contract and statement of employment</li>\r\n<li>Applicable legislation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(253, 'Module Two - Producing Personnel Records', '<p>All organisations and businesses need information or data to enable them to function effectively. The information needs to be readily available at all times for those who are authorised to see and use it. Equally, it must be stored, handled and disposed of in such a manner as to prevent access to it by those who are not authorised. It must therefore be managed effectively.</p>\r\n<p>Information about the organisation&rsquo;s human resources or personnel is part of this essential business information, and in this module, we will examine what personnel information is required, how it is used and how it is managed effectively.</p>\r\n<p>This includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Personnel data and record requirements</li>\r\n<li>Personnel data recording systems</li>\r\n<li>Record retention periods</li>\r\n<li>Data Protection Act</li>\r\n<li>Data security</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(254, 'Module Three - Staff Management and Relationships', '<p>Good employer/employee relationships are essential to the success of any business. Good relationships do not just happen; they must be established, built and developed over time.</p>\r\n<p>Relationships involve understanding and respecting the expectations and rights of each party, and ensuring that when disagreements arise they are dealt with in a fair, reasonable and consistent manner.</p>\r\n<p>This module covers:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Employment policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>Working time and time off policies</li>\r\n<li>Health and safety</li>\r\n<li>Smoking, drugs and alcohol</li>\r\n<li>Discrimination and diversity</li>\r\n<li>Pay and pensions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(255, 'Module Four -Staff Support, Training and Development', '<p>The recruiting and selection process is an expensive and time-consuming business. A new recruit is a significant investment for any organisation, and as with any investment, it needs to be protected. In this module, we will be looking at staff turnover and how this can be avoided and the issues involved in providing effective and appropriate staff support, training and development.</p>\r\n<p>This includes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Monitoring turnover</li>\r\n<li>Team building</li>\r\n<li>Developing and maintaining the shared purpose</li>\r\n<li>Team briefings</li>\r\n<li>Performance management and appraisals</li>\r\n<li>Training and development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(256, 'Module Five - Disciplinaries, Grievances and Tribunals', '<p>resolved in a fair and effective manner. In this module, we will be looking at the type of problems that can occur and how these are dealt with.</p>\r\n<p>This will include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Disciplinary issues</li>\r\n<li>Investigation</li>\r\n<li>Grievances</li>\r\n<li>Bullying and harassment</li>\r\n<li>Whistleblowing</li>\r\n<li>Employment tribunals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(257, 'Module Six - Employment Terminations', '<p>In this module, we will be looking at the role played by HR in managing the employee leaving process.</p>\r\n<p>There are a variety of reasons why an employee may cease working for an employer, some voluntarily and others not. Whatever the reason, it is important that the employment terminations are managed in an effective and professional manner. A poorly managed termination has many possible adverse consequences for an employer, including loss of business reputation, damage to employer/employee relationships, industrial unrest, and also legal and financial penalties.</p>\r\n<p>We consider the main types of employee termination, the reasons for these and the processes involved in their effective management.</p>\r\n<p>This will include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of termination</li>\r\n<li>Employee resignation</li>\r\n<li>Dismissing an employee</li>\r\n<li>Retirement</li>\r\n<li>Dismissal by reason of ill health</li>\r\n<li>Redundancy</li>\r\n<li>Death of an employee</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(258, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(259, 'Module One - Mental Capacity Act', '<p>This module will introduce the learner to the Mental Capacity Act, initially looking in detail at what it means to have or to lack mental capacity, why the act was introduced, who is covered by the act and how the act links to other UK legislation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legal principles that apply to the Mental Capacity Act</li>\r\n<li>The framework to be followed when an individual is suspected of lacking capacity</li>\r\n<li>Planning for the future</li>\r\n<li>Disagreements that can arise with regards to the Mental Capacity Act and what to do when they occur.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(260, 'Module Two - Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards', '<p>This module looks at what Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards (DOLS) are, the law defining DOLS, why they were introduced and who is affected by the act. Key elements of the DOLS legislation are studied, including the assessment process, the Code of Practice and the role of the Court of Protection.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Current legislation concerning Deprivation of Liberty Safeguards (DOLS)</li>\r\n<li>How DOLS is linked to the Mental Capacity Act and why protection from being deprived of liberties is required</li>\r\n<li>Who is affected by DOLS</li>\r\n<li>Principles of the DOLS legislation, including the; Code of Practice, assessment process, authorisations and best interest decisions</li>\r\n<li>The procedure to follow if it is suspected that a person is being deprived of their liberties.r.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(261, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(262, 'Module One - Understanding organisations', '<p>This introductory module examines the structural processes of a typical business and highlights the importance of a personal assistant understanding management and management processes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The management role in an organisation</li>\r\n<li>The business environment</li>\r\n<li>Corporate strategy</li>\r\n<li>Strategic planning process</li>\r\n<li>Activity and function structure</li>\r\n<li>Organisational culture</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(263, 'Module Two - Professional approach to work', '<p>This module is concerned with how a personal assistant should approach their working role and examines the importance of areas such as; professional attributes, business ethics and continuing professional development.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Role of the professional</li>\r\n<li>The value of professional employees</li>\r\n<li>Internal personal effectiveness</li>\r\n<li>Business ethics</li>\r\n<li>Corporate social responsibility</li>\r\n<li>Ingredients of professional development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(264, 'Module Three - Communication', '<p>This module is focussed on the process of communication and provides a thorough exploration of this skill within the workplace and studies techniques on how this should be implemented effectively.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Purpose and importance of communication</li>\r\n<li>Process and cycle of communication</li>\r\n<li>Types of workplace communication</li>\r\n<li>Communication with others</li>\r\n<li>Methods of business writing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(265, 'Module Four - Time management', '<p>The use of time within a business environment is the study of this module and the materials contained explore the resource of time, the concepts of time management and how people use time in different ways and to differing degrees of effectiveness.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dilemma and concept of time</li>\r\n<li>Time management</li>\r\n<li>Identifying time management problems</li>\r\n<li>Ineffective use of time</li>\r\n<li>Time usage strategies</li>\r\n<li>Benefits of effective use of time</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(266, 'Module Five - Managing business information', '<p>This module details the importance of information management within a business and examines how companies need to maintain information systems that correctly record all aspects of their business activities.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Maintaining business records</li>\r\n<li>Gathering, interpreting and presenting data</li>\r\n<li>Storage of personal data</li>\r\n<li>Financial accounting</li>\r\n<li>Budgets</li>\r\n<li>Costs</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(267, 'Module Six - Office management systems and procedures', '<p>This module examines the implementation and maintenance of effective office management systems and procedures in an organisation and looks at how these are applied in areas such as corporate strategy, communication and customer service.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Organisation structure</li>\r\n<li>Key Management processes</li>\r\n<li>Office administration systems and procedures</li>\r\n<li>Plan and design office administration procedures</li>\r\n<li>Effective business meetings</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(268, 'Module Seven - Customer service', '<p>The importance of a business ensuring they implement great customer service is the focus of this module. Fundamental issues such as being able to recognise and address the needs and expectations of customers and handling complaints/problems are examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Valuing customers</li>\r\n<li>Customer types</li>\r\n<li>Customer needs and expectations</li>\r\n<li>Consumer legislation</li>\r\n<li>Customer complaints and problems</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(269, 'Module Eight - Working with others', '<p>This module looks at the process of working with other people in an organisation. The unpredictable nature of working with a varied group of individuals is highlighted and the ways in which to deal with individuals to promote effective team work is explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Effective teams</li>\r\n<li>Types of teams</li>\r\n<li>Developmental needs of others</li>\r\n<li>Employee consultation</li>\r\n<li>Being assertive</li>\r\n<li>Group speaking</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(270, 'Module Nine - Legal and regulatory requirements', '<p>This module examines the key legal and regulatory areas that place obligations on all organisations and for which organisations are required to have formal policies and procedures in place to fully meet these obligations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Health and safety legislation</li>\r\n<li>Employer and employee health and safety duties</li>\r\n<li>Contract of employment</li>\r\n<li>Statutory employment legislation</li>\r\n<li>Anti-discrimination legislation</li>\r\n<li>Workplace disclosure and access of information</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(271, 'Module Ten - Handling difficult situations', '<p>This concluding module looks at the range of difficult situations that can materialise within a business organisation and examines methods of dealing with issues such as work conflict, stress, grievance and discipline.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Conflict in the workplace</li>\r\n<li>Employee problems</li>\r\n<li>Discipline and grievance</li>\r\n<li>Stress management</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(272, 'Module One - Principles of communication in adult social care settings', '<p>This introductory unit studies the principles of communication and examines how this should be implemented in adult social care settings through the exploration of areas such as; why people communicate, communication barriers and confidentiality.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reasons why people communicate</li>\r\n<li>The Importance of observing an individual&rsquo;s reactions when communicating</li>\r\n<li>The importance of finding out about an individual&rsquo;s communication and language needs, wishes and preferences</li>\r\n<li>Styles and methods of communicating</li>\r\n<li>Communication barriers</li>\r\n<li>Ways to check communication has been understood</li>\r\n<li>Support, resources and services</li>\r\n<li>Confidentiality</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(273, 'Module Two - Principles of personal development in adult social care settings', '<p>This unit looks at steps which individuals should take to develop their skills whilst working in adult social care settings and studies numerous areas of relevance, such as; reflecting on work activities, improving practise through a learning activity and the personal development plan.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How legislation and standards influence adult care job roles</li>\r\n<li>The importance of reflecting on work activities</li>\r\n<li>Ensuring attitudes and beliefs do not obstruct quality of work</li>\r\n<li>Improving practise through a learning activity</li>\r\n<li>Reflecting on how situations improve knowledge and practise</li>\r\n<li>How feedback from others develops knowledge, skills and understanding</li>\r\n<li>The personal development plan</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(274, 'Module Three - Principles of diversity, equality and inclusion in adult social care settings', '<p>This unit focusses on the principles of diversity, equality and inclusion and explores their importance in adult social care through the examination of areas such as; legislation and ways in which discrimination may be challenged in adult social care settings.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining diversity, equality, inclusion and discrimination</li>\r\n<li>How direct and indirect discrimination may occur in the work setting</li>\r\n<li>Practices that support diversity, equality and inclusion reducing the likelihood of discrimination</li>\r\n<li>Legislation and codes of practice</li>\r\n<li>How to interact with individuals in an inclusive way Communication and interaction- being involved</li>\r\n<li>Ways in which discrimination may be challenged in adult social care settings</li>\r\n<li>Sources of information or advice and support on diversity, equality, inclusion and discrimination</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(275, 'Module Four - Principles of safeguarding and protection in health and social care', '<p>The study of this unit is the principles of ensuring individuals within a care setting are protected and safeguarded from abuse and concentrates on areas of relevance such as; types of abuse, signs and symptoms of abuse and actions to take with regards to abuse.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of abuse</li>\r\n<li>Signs and symptoms of abuse</li>\r\n<li>Factors that may contribute to an individual being more vulnerable to abuse</li>\r\n<li>Actions to take with regards to abuse</li>\r\n<li>Identify ways to ensure that evidence of abuse is preserved</li>\r\n<li>National and local policies and systems relating to safeguarding and protection from abuse</li>\r\n<li>Roles of different agencies in safeguarding and protecting individuals from abuse</li>\r\n<li>Reports into serious failures to protect individuals from abuse</li>\r\n<li>Sources of information and advice about own role in safeguarding and protecting individuals from abuse</li>\r\n<li>The likelihood of abuse</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(276, 'Module Five - Introduction to duty of care in health, social care or children’s and young people’s settings', '<p>This unit introduces the practice of individuals providing important responsibilities in a care setting, a process known as &lsquo;duty of care&rsquo; and examines areas relevant to this, such as; obtaining additional support and advice to resolve dilemmas and responding to complaints.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining &lsquo;duty of care&rsquo;</li>\r\n<li>The effect of the duty of care on the care worker&rsquo;s role</li>\r\n<li>Dilemmas that may arise between duty of care and individual&rsquo;s rights</li>\r\n<li>Obtaining additional support and advice to resolve dilemmas</li>\r\n<li>Responding to complaints</li>\r\n<li>Agreed procedures for handling complaints</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(277, 'Module Six - Understand the role of the social care worker', '<p>This unit explores what the role of a social care worker entails and examines various areas of relevance such as; agreed ways of working, working in partnership with others and skills and approaches needed for resolving conflict.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Working and personal relationships</li>\r\n<li>Different working relationships in a social care setting</li>\r\n<li>The importance of adhering to the agreed scope of the job role</li>\r\n<li>Agreed ways of working</li>\r\n<li>Working in partnership with others</li>\r\n<li>Skills and approaches needed for resolving conflict</li>\r\n<li>How and when to access support and advice about partnership working and resolving conflict</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(278, 'Module Seven - Understand person-centred approaches in adult social care settings', '<p>This unit is concerned with person-centred approaches in adult social care settings and examines how carers should focus on the specific needs of individuals in their care, through the exploration of areas such as; consent, active participation and promoting an individual&rsquo;s well-being.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Person-centred values</li>\r\n<li>Implementing a person centred approach in an adult care setting</li>\r\n<li>Consent</li>\r\n<li>Active participation</li>\r\n<li>Supporting an individual&rsquo;s right to make choices</li>\r\n<li>Promoting an individual&rsquo;s well-being</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(279, 'Module Eight - Understanding health and safety in social care settings', '<p>This unit introduces knowledge and understanding of areas of health and safety required to work in a social care setting and examines relevant areas such as; reducing the spread of infection, how to manage stress and procedures regarding handling medication.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Responsibilities relating to health and safety in social care settings</li>\r\n<li>Risk assessment in relation to health and safety</li>\r\n<li>Responding to accidents and sudden illness</li>\r\n<li>Reducing the spread of infection</li>\r\n<li>Move and handle equipment and other objects safely</li>\r\n<li>Assisting and moving an individual</li>\r\n<li>How to handle hazardous substances</li>\r\n<li>Environmental safety procedure in the social care setting</li>\r\n<li>How to manage stress</li>\r\n<li>Procedures regarding handling medication</li>\r\n<li>How to handle and store food safely</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(280, 'Module Nine - Understand how to handle information in social care settings', '<p>This concluding unit is focussed on the knowledge required for good practice in recording, storing and sharing information in a social care setting and examines areas of relevance, such as; the importance of having secure systems for recording and storing information in a social care setting and advice about handling information.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation that relates to the recording, storage, and sharing of information in social care</li>\r\n<li>The importance of having secure systems for recording and storing information in a social care setting</li>\r\n<li>Guidance, information and advice about handling information</li>\r\n<li>Actions to take when there are concerns over the recording, storing and sharing of information</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(281, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(282, 'Module One - The Science of Psychology', '<p>This module introduces learners to the methods and approaches adopted by psychological researchers. The knowledge defines the term &lsquo;psychology&rsquo; and focusses on the history of its research to see how it has evolved to look at different aspects of humans.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is psychology?</li>\r\n<li>A little bit of history</li>\r\n<li>The science of psychology</li>\r\n<li>But is it right? The ethics of doing research</li>\r\n<li>From data collection to data analysis</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(283, 'Module Two - How We Learn', '<p>This module explores the various different ways in which we learn, focussing on some of the main psychological theorists involved in this research and details of their theories on the subject.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Classical conditioning</li>\r\n<li>Operant conditioning</li>\r\n<li>Observational learning</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(284, 'Module Three - How We Develop', '<p>This module explores the various ways in which we develop at different stages of our life. The knowledge focusses on different types and phases of development and how these become more sophisticated.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Cognitive development</li>\r\n<li>Social development</li>\r\n<li>Moral development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(285, 'Module Four - Relating To Others', '<p>This module focusses on the processes involved in our everyday understanding of others&rsquo; actions, and how these processes affect our social relationships.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Understanding others</li>\r\n<li>Stereotypes</li>\r\n<li>Attraction</li>\r\n<li>Love</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(286, 'Module Five - Social Influence', '<p>This module examines how psychologists have studied the different ways in which we are influenced by other people, and how we can influence others.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The persuaders</li>\r\n<li>You do as you&rsquo;re told: Obedience to authority</li>\r\n<li>Conformity</li>\r\n<li>To help or not to help</li>\r\n<li>The roles we play</li>\r\n<li>Take me to your leader</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(287, 'Module Six - Your Brain: A User Guide', '<p>This module provides a thorough exploration of the brain looking at the various different parts, their functions and how these work together to produce behaviour.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Neurons</li>\r\n<li>The basic structure of the brain</li>\r\n<li>The damaged brain</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(288, 'Module Seven - Consciousness and The Brain', '<p>This module explores the various states of consciousness and examines what psychologists can tell us about its nature and also how drugs, hypnosis, dreams and meditation affect our different states.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is consciousness?</li>\r\n<li>Altered States of Consciousness</li>\r\n<li>Brain vs. mind</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(289, 'Module Eight - Attention and Thinking', '<p>This module looks at what psychologists have learned from studying the mental processes involved in attention and thinking. The knowledge considers areas such as active psychological processes involved in perception and attention and key aspects of cognition.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bottoms up and tops down!</li>\r\n<li>Attention (and lack of it)</li>\r\n<li>The essence of thinking</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(290, 'Module Nine - Memory', '<p>This module introduces psychological theories about how our memory works. The knowledge explores areas such the processes that affect our memory and the reasons why we forget things.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Encoding</li>\r\n<li>Storage</li>\r\n<li>Retrieval</li>\r\n<li>Types of memory</li>\r\n<li>Forgetting</li>\r\n<li>False memories</li>\r\n<li>Improving your memory</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(291, 'Module Ten - Personality', '<p>This module explores the term personality in terms of the way we act, think and feel. The knowledge looks at how researchers attempt to measure personality and also how they try to explain why there seem to be so many different types of personality.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Measuring personality</li>\r\n<li>Understanding personality</li>\r\n<li>The unconscious personality</li>\r\n<li>Personality in the real world</li>\r\n<li>Explaining personality: Nature vs. nurture?</li>\r\n<li>The &lsquo;psychopathic&rsquo; personality</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(292, 'Module Eleven - Intelligence', '<p>This module looks at complex nature of the term &lsquo;intelligence&rsquo; focussing on how researchers have explored and defined this concept and also how they measure levels of it.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Measuring intelligence</li>\r\n<li>IQ vs. Intelligence</li>\r\n<li>So what is intelligence?</li>\r\n<li>Is intelligence innate?</li>\r\n<li>Can you change intelligence?</li>\r\n<li>Other types of intelligence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(293, 'Module Twelve - Applying Psychology', '<p>This module aims to bring together all the knowledge gained from previous modules by looking at how findings from research in psychology can be applied to our everyday lives through the focus on five main areas: Educational, Clinical, Forensic, Occupational, and Sport.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>So who are you?</li>\r\n<li>Do you do as you&rsquo;re told?</li>\r\n<li>Liar Liar</li>\r\n<li>To sleep, perchance to dream</li>\r\n<li>And relax</li>\r\n<li>And if you remember one thing!</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(294, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(295, 'Module One - The Agricultural Revolution', '<p>This introductory module rewinds back to explore Britain between the 17th and 19th century to provide the earliest perspective of British society in this course. It explores the boom in agricultural productivity and examines how this influenced society, and ultimately helped to drive the industrial revolution.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The move from open fields to enclosure</li>\r\n<li>Enclosure</li>\r\n<li>Agricultural improvers</li>\r\n<li>The domestic system</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(296, 'Module Two - The Industrial Revolution', '<p>This module relives the period of time, often regarded as a major turning point in human history. This was known as the industrial revolution and it involved significant changes in agriculture, manufacturing, mining, transport and technology. The materials look at how this major economic progression affected British society.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Industrial pioneers</li>\r\n<li>Life in a factory</li>\r\n<li>The cotton industry</li>\r\n<li>Coal and the industrial revolution</li>\r\n<li>Why was so little done to improve towns and cities in Britain\'s industrial zones?</li>\r\n<li>Crime, the industrial revolution and Victorian England</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(297, 'Module Three - The struggle for democracy – working class rights, political reform and the Chartist', '<p>This module studies the fight for democracy. The materials look at the divide between the upper and working class, in addition to other inequalities that occurred and examines the tactics that took place to try and rectify the problem through the political sphere.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The reform Acts</li>\r\n<li>The Chartist movement</li>\r\n<li>The 1848 petition</li>\r\n<li>Famous supporters of political reform</li>\r\n<li>Chartism and force</li>\r\n<li>Why did Chartism fail?</li>\r\n<li>Chartism - the Legacy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(298, 'Module Four - Political power and protest', '<p>This module examines the arm wrestle which endured during the 18th and 19th centuries between the few in power and the public which rebelled against the system. The materials study some of the significant disputes which took place during this time and examines how these lead to the birth of the early labour party.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Political radicalism</li>\r\n<li>The repeal of the Combination Acts (1824)</li>\r\n<li>Trade unions</li>\r\n<li>The Tolpuddle Martyrs</li>\r\n<li>\'New Model\' unionism</li>\r\n<li>Women workers</li>\r\n<li>The Fabian Society</li>\r\n<li>Social Democratic Federation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(299, 'Module Five - Social Policy and Development in the 19th and 20th century – Poverty and the Liberal Reform', '<p>This module looks specifically at poor people in British society during the 19th and 20th century and looks at the changing perceptions of vulnerable people over the years.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The problem of poverty</li>\r\n<li>How did people end up in a workhouse?</li>\r\n<li>What did people think of the poor Law?</li>\r\n<li>Was anything done to help the poor before the Liberal reforms?</li>\r\n<li>Acts dealing with children, workers, the elderly and slum dwellers</li>\r\n<li>The liberal government</li>\r\n<li>Limitations</li>\r\n<li>Contemporary criticism</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(300, 'Module Six - The Suffragettes and Women’s rights', '<p>This module is concerned with the pertinent issue of gender inequality and looks at the unfair treatment of women in Britain over a sustained period of time. The materials then look at how this has been challenged over the years, focusing particularly on the suffrage movement and how this helped in securing women\'s rights.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The women\'s suffrage movement</li>\r\n<li>The tactics of the different suffrage societies</li>\r\n<li>The attitudes of the political parties towards women\'s suffrage</li>\r\n<li>Arguments why women were eventually given the vote</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(301, 'Module Seven - Interaction, Society & Change', '<p>This module looks at the impact that 2 world wars had on Britain and examines how this influenced major societal changes in the post war era, particularly with regards to women (as discussed in the previous module), who had a new role in society.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The social impact of the two world wars on Britain</li>\r\n<li>The Defence of the Realm Act</li>\r\n<li>Rationing</li>\r\n<li>Conscientious objectors</li>\r\n<li>The lend lease agreement</li>\r\n<li>Protectionism</li>\r\n<li>How society changed due to the impact of the two world wars</li>\r\n<li>Government intervention</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(302, 'Module Eight - Post-war developments in social policy & the birth of the NHS', '<p>This module progresses on from the previous content to further explore the post-war developments in Britain. The materials look specifically at the introduction of the welfare system and the newly formed NHS, and examines how these changes have helped form modern day Britain.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Governance of welfare in the United Kingdom</li>\r\n<li>The post war development of social health policy</li>\r\n<li>The Beveridge report</li>\r\n<li>How British society changed due to the birth of the NHS, its original aims and its evolution over the latter half of the 20th century</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(303, 'Module Nine - The end of consensus politics - The Thatcher Years', '<p>This module studies the rise to political power of Margaret Thatcher during the 1970s and 80s and explores how the new conservative policies affected Britain, looking specifically how different aspects of society reacted to the radical changes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The rise to political power of Margaret Thatcher</li>\r\n<li>The economic and social policies of the conservative government in the 1970s and 80s</li>\r\n<li>Changes to welfare, the state and the economy under the conservative government</li>\r\n<li>How society reacted to the radical changes and reforms and how the conservative government eventually lost support</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(304, 'Module Ten - After Thatcher- the New Labour years', '<p>This concluding module looks at the introduction of the new labour party years which lasted during the late 90s into the new millennium. The materials study the party\'s new ideologies and their successes within British society and then conversely the controversy surrounding the Iraq war and their eventual loss of power.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The labour party</li>\r\n<li>Party ideology</li>\r\n<li>Clement Attlee: Labour Prime Minister, 1945-51</li>\r\n<li>Labour in government under Wilson (1964-1970 and 1974-1976)</li>\r\n<li>Return to government (1974-1979)</li>\r\n<li>\"New Labour\" - in government (1997-2010)</li>\r\n<li>Tony Blair: Labour Prime Minister, 1997-2007</li>\r\n<li>Iraq War</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(305, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 1),
(306, 'Module One - An Introduction to Sociology – key ideas and concepts', '<p>This introductory unit examines the subject of sociology as a whole and is concerned with providing a broad overview of key areas, such as; what sociologists study, love and marriage and health and illness.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The subject matter of sociology</li>\r\n<li>What sociologists study</li>\r\n<li>How sociologists study the social world</li>\r\n<li>What influences us as consumers</li>\r\n<li>Love and marriage</li>\r\n<li>Health and illness</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(307, 'Module Two - Sociological theory and perspectives', '<p>This unit looks at the nature of different sociological theories, such as; prerequisites, symbolic interaction and feminism and examines what their relationship is to each other.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Theories</li>\r\n<li>Prerequisites</li>\r\n<li>Evaluating sociological theories</li>\r\n<li>Symbolic interaction</li>\r\n<li>Explanations of social change</li>\r\n<li>Ethnomethodology</li>\r\n<li>Feminism</li>\r\n<li>Structuralism and post-structuralism</li>\r\n<li>Identity, structure and agency</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(308, 'Module Three - The Family', '<p>This unit specifically studies the family, exploring its function in society and examines its advantages and disadvantages with regards to the formation of our opinions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Family structure</li>\r\n<li>Family types</li>\r\n<li>Family diversity</li>\r\n<li>Ethnic minority families</li>\r\n<li>Gender and power relations</li>\r\n<li>Domestic labour</li>\r\n<li>The family and social policy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(309, 'Module Four - Social stratification, class and social mobility', '<p>This unit will explore the concept of &lsquo;social stratification&rsquo; which are the structural inequalities that exist in today&rsquo;s society, whether this is based on class, gender, ethnicity, age or disability.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What do Marxists say about social stratification?</li>\r\n<li>What does Weber say about social stratification?</li>\r\n<li>What do functionalists say about social stratification?</li>\r\n<li>The Marxist approach to an underclass</li>\r\n<li>Social mobility</li>\r\n<li>Social differentiation and class attitudes</li>\r\n<li>Wealth, income and inequality</li>\r\n<li>Class and identity</li>\r\n<li>Life chances and the findings of the National Equality Panel</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(310, 'Module Five - Mass media', '<p>This unit is concerned with the mass media and the materials assess how this industry is structured in order to influence society, through the study of areas such as; ownership and content in media and what makes news &lsquo;newsworthy&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Relationship between ownership and content in the media</li>\r\n<li>Four approaches which seek to explain the content of the media</li>\r\n<li>How the four approaches seek to explain how media content influences behaviour</li>\r\n<li>What makes news &lsquo;newsworthy&rsquo;</li>\r\n<li>Media amplification</li>\r\n<li>Marxist and interactionist approaches to media amplification</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(311, 'Module Six - Looking at Crime and Deviance', '<p>This unit will examine theoretical approaches that attempt to explain crime and deviance and look at the related concepts of deviance, norms and morals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is deviance?</li>\r\n<li>What is the difference between crime and deviance</li>\r\n<li>Types of deviance</li>\r\n<li>Functionalist approach to crime</li>\r\n<li>Patterns of crime</li>\r\n<li>The geographic distribution of crime</li>\r\n<li>The social distribution of crime &ndash; Age and gender</li>\r\n<li>Criminology and crime prevention</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(312, 'Module Seven - The Sociology of Health and Illness', '<p>This unit assesses the decisions made with regards to health and illness and looks at how these decisions impact upon society. The materials examine areas such as; health and gender and the sick role.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Health and gender</li>\r\n<li>Health and ethnicity</li>\r\n<li>&lsquo;The sick role&rsquo;</li>\r\n<li>Erving Goffman&rsquo;s contribution to health, medicine and mental illness</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(313, 'Module Eight - Sociology and Religion', '<p>This unit is focussed on the relationship between religion and society and looks at how practised beliefs are conveyed and impact the wider community.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Church</li>\r\n<li>Sects</li>\r\n<li>New religious movements (NRMS)</li>\r\n<li>Religion and classical sociology</li>\r\n<li>Differences between religions</li>\r\n<li>Magical belief systems</li>\r\n<li>Graphology: Modern magic?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(314, 'Module Nine - Gender, culture and identity', '<p>This module looks at the differences between men and women in relation to the social construct of gender, culture and identity and examines areas of relevance such as; the feminist perspective of gender inequality and the role of men and women in the home and workplace.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The unequal status of women historically and in contemporary society</li>\r\n<li>Feminist perspectives of gender inequality</li>\r\n<li>The role of men and women in the home and in the workplace</li>\r\n<li>Feminist perspectives of gender inequality</li>\r\n<li>The &lsquo;social construction&rsquo; of gender</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(315, 'Module Ten - Social Science Research Methods', '<p>This concluding module explores how sociologists go about gathering information and constructing theoretical explanations for various social phenomena, examine areas of relevance, such as; qualitative research and open and closed scientific systems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Methodology</li>\r\n<li>What is science</li>\r\n<li>Arguments for sociology as a science</li>\r\n<li>Critics of sociology as a science</li>\r\n<li>Strengths and weaknesses of qualitative research</li>\r\n<li>Strengths and weaknesses of quantitative research</li>\r\n<li>Open and closed scientific systems</li>\r\n<li>The scientific approach to social research</li>\r\n<li>Conducting research &ndash; detachment versus involvement</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(316, 'Module One - Understanding your role', '<p>This section introduces the practice of providing training and helps you to understand what exactly your role entails and what needs to be considered when planning and delivering training requirements in your workplace.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The modern trainer</li>\r\n<li>Defining your role</li>\r\n<li>What makes an exceptional trainer?</li>\r\n<li>Legislation and Codes of Practice</li>\r\n<li>Needs analysis</li>\r\n<li>Meeting the potential needs of trainees</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(317, 'Module Two - How adults learn and learning styles', '<p>This section is concerned with determining how different people learn and approaches to use, in order to ensure that the training methods implemented, are most appropriate to the employee\'s needs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Stages of learning</li>\r\n<li>How adults learn</li>\r\n<li>Learning styles</li>\r\n<li>Approaches to learning</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(318, 'Module Three - Planning and Designing Training', '<p>This section looks specifically at the creation of a training delivery method. It focuses on providing guidance on areas such as; ways to deliver the training and what kind of scope do the individuals need to learn.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning to deliver training</li>\r\n<li>Session planning</li>\r\n<li>Creating a formal plan- the process</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(319, 'Module Four - Delivering Training and Presentation Techniques', '<p>This section will help you to understand how to deliver effective training sessions which motivate trainees, through the study of areas such as; behaviour management, interpersonal skills and feedback methods.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Establishing ground rules and managing behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Good practice in giving feedback</li>\r\n<li>Interpersonal skills and communicating appropriately with trainees</li>\r\n<li>Practical tips for trainers delivering a direct training course</li>\r\n<li>Delivering effective PowerPoint presentations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(320, 'Module Five - Evaluating Training Programmes', '<p>This concluding section will help you to understand the use of different assessment methods and related record keeping, which should equip you with the skills required to continually improve the training services you provide.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The principles of evaluating training programmes</li>\r\n<li>Appropriate evaluation methods</li>\r\n<li>Collection and analysis of data for the purpose of evaluating training programmes</li>\r\n<li>Data analysis and recording</li>\r\n<li>Evaluating the effectiveness of own practice</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(321, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(322, 'Module One - What is ADHD?', '<p>This introductory module aims to give you an overview of what ADHD is and examines the various terms which are associated with it. In addition, the materials also examine a number of conditions that can also affect behaviour and considers how ADHD sits in relation to this range of social and behavioural difficulties.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Social and behavioural difficulties</li>\r\n<li>What is ADHD/ADD/ Hyperkinetic Disorder?</li>\r\n<li>The impact of ADHD on life activities</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(323, 'Module Two - Signs and symptoms of ADHD', '<p>This module considers some of the signs and symptoms that children and young people with ADHD may present and examines how the condition can be split into 3 subtypes as a basis for determining how individuals are affected.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Subtypes of ADHD</li>\r\n<li>The impact of ADHD on academic and life choices</li>\r\n<li>Strengths of children with ADHD</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(324, 'Module Three - Assessment and diagnosis of ADHD', '<p>This module looks at how ADHD is diagnosed and by whom. The materials consider how multiple tools may be needed, due to the complex nature of the condition and examines their usage and also the benefits of using self-check tests.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Difficulties associated with diagnosing ADHD</li>\r\n<li>Assessment tools</li>\r\n<li>ADHD diagnosis</li>\r\n<li>Self-check tests</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(325, 'Module Four - Support for parents', '<p>This module draws together information that parents may find helpful in order to manage behavioural issues that their children might present as a result of ADHD.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Strategies</li>\r\n<li>Managing sibling rivalry</li>\r\n<li>Establishing a behaviour management plan</li>\r\n<li>Parental support</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(326, 'Module Five - ADHD and education', '<p>This module is concerned with the challenges that children and young people with ADHD may face at school due to the nature of their impairment and outlines strategies that can be used in order to help with these difficulties.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Classroom strategies</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour management programme</li>\r\n<li>Other approaches</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(327, 'Module Six - To medicate or not', '<p>This module studies the range of treatment options available for individuals diagnosed with ADHD and looks at relevant considerations, such as; types of ADHD medication, advantages and disadvantages of ADHD drug treatment sources of support.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The main types of medication used to treat ADHD</li>\r\n<li>Other approaches to treating ADHD</li>\r\n<li>Advantages and disadvantages of drugs used to treat ADHD</li>\r\n<li>Support websites</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(328, 'Module Seven - ADHD and adults', '<p>This concluding module is specifically focussed on support for adults who struggle with ADHD. The materials are mainly concerned with individuals who may have gone through childhood without ever having their ADHD diagnosed and therefore look at relevant considerations, such as; symptom identification, the impact of ADHD on adult life and treatment options.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Key symptoms of ADHD</li>\r\n<li>The impact of ADHD on adults&rsquo; lives</li>\r\n<li>Treatment options</li>\r\n<li>Impairment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(329, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(330, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(331, 'Module One - Why is weight such an issue?', '<p>This introductory module examines the subject of weight problems and explores some of the reasons why this widespread concern is an issue for individuals, looking in particular at areas such as; confusion and reasons for weight control.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Confusion</li>\r\n<li>Why am I overweight?</li>\r\n<li>Reasons for weight control</li>\r\n<li>Why be a weight management consultant?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(332, 'Module Two - Understanding eating disorders and food sensitivities', '<p>This module is focussed on the examination of recognised problematic relationships with food, in other words eating disorders and studies areas of relevance such as; Anorexia, Bulimia and binge eating.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Anorexia nervosa</li>\r\n<li>Bulimia</li>\r\n<li>Men and eating disorders</li>\r\n<li>Binge eating</li>\r\n<li>Food allergies and intolerances</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(333, 'Module Three - Nutrition and health problems', '<p>This module studies specific health conditions, looking at how they affect, and are affected by weight gain, and examines areas of relevance such as; digestion, nutrition in pregnancy and weight gain linked to injury.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Digestion</li>\r\n<li>Health problems</li>\r\n<li>Normal weight, overweight and obese</li>\r\n<li>Nutrition in pregnancy</li>\r\n<li>Weight gain linked to injury</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(334, 'Module Four - Understanding food labels', '<p>This module looks specifically at food labels and examines the importance of taking note of the information provided on them in order to aid positive weight management, focussing on relevant considerations, such as; sugar, dates, and preservatives. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is a food label?</li>\r\n<li>Sugar</li>\r\n<li>Ingredients</li>\r\n<li>Date</li>\r\n<li>E Numbers</li>\r\n<li>Sweeteners</li>\r\n<li>Flavour enhancers</li>\r\n<li>Colour additives</li>\r\n<li>Preservatives</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(335, 'Module Five - Food composition', '<p>This module considers what different types of food are made up of and looks at what they contain, focussing specifically on areas such as; carbohydrates, what counts as five a day the importance of fruit and vegetables.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Carbohydrates</li>\r\n<li>Proteins and amino acids</li>\r\n<li>What counts as five a day</li>\r\n<li>Why eat fruit and vegetables</li>\r\n<li>Saints and sinners</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(336, 'Module Six - Vitamins and minerals', '<p>This module teaches about the nutrients in food known as vitamins and minerals and details what food contains what, what different nutrients do and how they affect the body.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Naturally occurring vitamins and what they do</li>\r\n<li>Macrominerals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(337, 'Module Seven - Index, portions, and diaries', '<p>This module promotes the understanding of the Body Mass Index and details various guidelines on how to calculate this for clients, BMI monitoring and the importance of portion control to maintain the correct index for the specific individual.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Conversion chart</li>\r\n<li>Calculating BMI</li>\r\n<li>Underweight, normal, overweight and obese</li>\r\n<li>Food pyramid</li>\r\n<li>Portion sizes</li>\r\n<li>Food diary</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(338, 'Module Eight - Records, goals, and body shapes', '<p>This module advises on how best to keep track of a client&rsquo;s progress. The materials contained predominantly examine; the production and usage of the record card, how to set goals and also teaching individuals to use weight loss charts.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Measurements</li>\r\n<li>Weight loss charts</li>\r\n<li>Body shapes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(339, 'Module Nine - Excuses and reasons for weight gain', '<p>This module studies the array of excuses individuals use in an attempt to justify why they gain weight. The materials explore some of the most commonly used explanations and examines ways in which you can respond in a positive way to challenge this reasoning and support individuals to make the right choices.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Commonly used excuses for weight gain</li>\r\n<li>I am on another diet</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(340, 'Module Ten - Diet types', '<p>This module is concerned with the various types of diets available and examines the specific benefits and pitfalls associated with different options in order to instil you with the knowledge on choosing what is best for your client&rsquo;s needs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Starvation</li>\r\n<li>The changing patterns of diets</li>\r\n<li>Types of diets</li>\r\n<li>Glycemic index diet</li>\r\n<li>Calorie counting</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(341, 'Module Eleven - The benefits of exercise', '<p>This module looks at the importance of exercise with regards to weight management. The materials contained study why we need to be active and examines how exercise can be tailored to the individual to assist them with their weight loss goals and help them to maintain a healthy lifestyle.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why do we need exercise</li>\r\n<li>Different types of exercises</li>\r\n<li>Exercising with others</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(342, 'Module Twelve - Everyday exercise', '<p>This module is an extension of module 11 in that it continues to explore the importance of exercise in helping to maintain a healthy weight. The materials contained here, however, look at more subtle ways in which exercise can be incorporated into everyday life, when other options such as attending a gym, for example, become a difficulty.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Walking</li>\r\n<li>Housework</li>\r\n<li>Exercise in the office</li>\r\n<li>Toning exercises</li>\r\n<li>Waistline trimmer</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(343, 'Module Thirteen - Creating a diet plan', '<p>This module focusses specifically on how to create a diet plan to suit the individual needs of your client, looking at a range of considerations, such as; different types of meal, snack considerations and hitting a plateau.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Creating a diet plan</li>\r\n<li>Breakfast, dinner and tea</li>\r\n<li>Snack considerations</li>\r\n<li>Daily serving recommendations</li>\r\n<li>Vegetarian diets</li>\r\n<li>Hitting a plateau</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(344, 'Module Fourteen - Business and making it work', '<p>This module considers weight management as a business, looking at how you can create and maintain your own company and manage your own clients. The materials contained looks at important considerations such as: legal aspects, sticking to a business plan and advertising.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why businesses fail</li>\r\n<li>Research</li>\r\n<li>Finances and budget</li>\r\n<li>Business plan</li>\r\n<li>Legalities</li>\r\n<li>Business location</li>\r\n<li>Advertising</li>\r\n<li>Day to day operations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(345, 'Module Fifteen - Diet tips and advice your clients will love', '<p>This concluding module adds to all the knowledge gained in the course so far by providing some final tips which you can teach your clients, to give them that final push in achieving their weight management goals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eating slowly</li>\r\n<li>Fruit</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t skip meals</li>\r\n<li>Increasing activity levels</li>\r\n<li>Blood sugar levels</li>\r\n<li>Moderation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(346, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(347, 'Module One - Child and Young Person Development', '<p>This introductory unit is concerned with the continuous, complex interaction of environmental and genetic factors in which the body, brain and behaviour become more complex, known as development.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The main stages of child and young person development</li>\r\n<li>Influences that affect children and young people&rsquo;s development</li>\r\n<li>The potential effects of transitions on children and young people\'s development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(348, 'Module Two - Safeguarding the Welfare of Children and Young People', '<p>This unit studies the duty of the support worker in schools to ensure the safety and well-being of children and young people and examines important considerations such as; e-safety and what to do when a child is ill.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The legislation, guidelines, policies, and procedures for safeguarding the welfare of children and young people including e-safety</li>\r\n<li>What to do when children or young people are ill or injured, including emergency procedures</li>\r\n<li>How to respond to evidence or concerns that a child or young person has been abused, harmed or bullied</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(349, 'Module Three - Communication and Professional Relationships with Children, Young People and Adults', '<p>This unit examines the need for school support workers to communicate with a range of people in the educational setting and considers the various ways in which appropriate interactions can take place and also the legislation that governs confidential information.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to interact with and respond to children and young people</li>\r\n<li>How to interact with and respond to adults</li>\r\n<li>How to communicate with children, young people, and adults</li>\r\n<li>Current legislation, policies and procedures for confidentiality and sharing information, including data protection</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(350, 'Module Four - Equality, Diversity, and Inclusion in Work with Children and Young People', '<p>This unit is focussed on the importance of promoting equality and diversity within the school setting and considers ways in which the school support worker can help encourage a fair and inclusive environment where no one is ostracised.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of promoting equality and diversity in work with children and young people</li>\r\n<li>The impact of prejudice and discrimination on children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Inclusive practices in work with children and young people</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(351, 'Module Five - Schools as Organisations', '<p>This concluding unit explores the overall make-up of the school environment and examines the various types of schools a support worker may be based and how each institution operates in order to help them adapt to their working environment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The different types of schools in the education sector</li>\r\n<li>How schools are organised in terms of roles and responsibilities</li>\r\n<li>How schools uphold their aims and values</li>\r\n<li>The laws and codes of practice that affect work in schools</li>\r\n<li>The range and purpose of school policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>The wider context in which schools operate</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(352, 'Completion`', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(353, 'Module One - Explore the Principles of Healthy Eating', '<p>The aim of this Unit is to explore the principles of healthy eating. This will include how diet is linked to health, components of a healthy diet, nutrients in food and also healthy food preparation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How diet is linked to health</li>\r\n<li>Components of a healthy diet</li>\r\n<li>Nutrients in food and their role in maintaining health</li>\r\n<li>Healthy food preparation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(354, 'Module Two - Consider Nutritional Needs of Different People', '<p>The aim of this Unit is to explore the nutritional needs of a variety of individuals. This will include nutritional needs of children, young and older people, special dietary requirements and barriers to healthy eating.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Nutritional needs of children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Nutritional needs of older people</li>\r\n<li>Special dietary requirements</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to healthy eating</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(355, 'Module Three - Use food and nutrition to plan a healthy diet', '<p>The aim of this unit is to explore how to use food and nutrition information to plan a healthy diet. We will look at food labelling, food additives and how we can apply principles of healthy eating to our diet.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Food labelling</li>\r\n<li>Food additives</li>\r\n<li>Apply principles of healthy eating</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(356, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email support@ncchomelearning.co.uk (note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 1),
(357, 'Module One - The Crime Scene', '<p>The introductory module is concerned with the scene in which a crime took place and examines all the relevant factors that should be considered in order to interpret and recover the relevant criminal evidence for analysis.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who&rsquo;s at the crime scene</li>\r\n<li>Evidence</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene analysis</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene procedure</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene sketch</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene kit</li>\r\n<li>The golden hour and fast track action</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(358, 'Module Two - Biological Evidence', '<p>This module explores the prevalence of biological evidence (i.e. any human traces that could have been left by the killer) in relation to the crime scene and looks specifically at considerations such as; any bodily fluids that may remain nearby and where evidence is likely to be found.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Body fluids</li>\r\n<li>Evidence from the scene</li>\r\n<li>Blood analysis</li>\r\n<li>DNA</li>\r\n<li>The forensic odontologist</li>\r\n<li>Health &amp; safety at the crime scene</li>\r\n<li>Hair at the crime scene</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(359, 'Module Three - Fingerprints', '<p>This module is focused on what is regarded as one of the most important types of evidence collected at a crime scene, the fingerprints. The materials look at considerations such as; what defines a fingerprint, how they can be obtained and how they can be traced back to the killer.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What are fingerprints?</li>\r\n<li>Best places to find prints</li>\r\n<li>Why are fingerprints important?</li>\r\n<li>Fingerprint types</li>\r\n<li>Fingerprint patterns</li>\r\n<li>Fingerprint identification</li>\r\n<li>The Henry fingerprint classification system</li>\r\n<li>Latent prints</li>\r\n<li>Automated fingerprint recognition</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(360, 'Module Four - Trace Evidence', '<p>This module studies the subtle method of obtaining intricate pieces of evidence that can be linked to the killer, and examines relevant considerations such as; fibres, impression evidence and collecting the evidence at the scene.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Einstein&rsquo;s 3 Rules of Work</li>\r\n<li>Class evidence</li>\r\n<li>Fibres</li>\r\n<li>Dust and dirt and soil</li>\r\n<li>Impression evidence</li>\r\n<li>Collecting the evidence at the scene</li>\r\n<li>Footwear Intelligence Technology (FIT) system</li>\r\n<li>Tool mark evidence</li>\r\n<li>In the laboratory</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(361, 'Module Five - Entomological Evidence', '<p>Simply put, this module studies the analysis of insects found on a dead corpse in order to determine evidence to assist with a criminal investigation and examines areas of relevance, such as; the life cycle of the blow fly, insects and toxicology and stages of decay.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Decomposition of the corpse</li>\r\n<li>Life cycle of the blow fly</li>\r\n<li>Forensic entomology</li>\r\n<li>The relationship between insects and corpses</li>\r\n<li>Insects and toxicology</li>\r\n<li>Recognition, collection and preservation</li>\r\n<li>Factors affecting PMI estimates</li>\r\n<li>Forensic entomology collection equipment</li>\r\n<li>Stages of decay</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(362, 'Module Six - The Fire Scene', '<p>This module focuses on the examination of a fire scene to determine if it was caused by criminal motives and examines what evidence should be analysed during this process. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Criminal damage and arson</li>\r\n<li>Investigating the fire scene</li>\r\n<li>Fire scene personnel</li>\r\n<li>The fire triangle</li>\r\n<li>Causes of fire</li>\r\n<li>The arsonist and his M.O.</li>\r\n<li>Crime scene victimology</li>\r\n<li>Processing the fire scene</li>\r\n<li>The basic science of fire</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(363, 'Module Seven - The Explosives Scene', '<p>This module considers the analysis crime scenes which have involved any kind of explosion. The materials contained looks at the complexity of establishing evidence from this particular crime and examines considerations taken in this process, such as; evidence sought, spectroscopy and chromatography.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Low and high explosives</li>\r\n<li>The explosives investigation</li>\r\n<li>Evidence sought after an explosion</li>\r\n<li>Dogs and explosives detection</li>\r\n<li>Spectroscopy</li>\r\n<li>Physical properties of chemicals</li>\r\n<li>Chromatography</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(364, 'Module Eight - Ballistics', '<p>This module is concerned with the collection of firearms found in relation to the crime scene and looks at the examination of these items in terms of their potential usage as a murder weapon.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Collection and preservation of firearms evidence</li>\r\n<li>Basic science of firearms investigation</li>\r\n<li>Examination of gunshot residue</li>\r\n<li>Firearms identification</li>\r\n<li>Restoration of serial numbers</li>\r\n<li>Ammunition comparison</li>\r\n<li>Scanning electron micrograph of GSR</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(365, 'Module Nine - Psychology and the Crime Scene', '<p>This concluding module looks at the practice of psychological profiling which is utilised in order to obtain psychological clues, which may compliment any physical evidence and assist in the solving of a criminal investigation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Psychological profiling</li>\r\n<li>The FBI profiling process</li>\r\n<li>Decision making process</li>\r\n<li>FBI classification of murder</li>\r\n<li>Profile applications</li>\r\n<li>Different approaches</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(366, 'Module Ten - Revision & Consolidation', '<p>This final module is designed to test you on the knowledge and skills you have learned so far. As such there is no specific data to read, only learning outcomes followed by a series of practical activities (designed for home completion) and theoretical questions.</p>', 1),
(367, 'Module One - Babies from Birth to One Year', '<p>This introductory module studies the initial development of a child during the first year of their life. The numerous occurrences at this time, such as: bonding, reflexes and a baby&rsquo;s needs, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Before birth</li>\r\n<li>Bonding</li>\r\n<li>Social and emotional development</li>\r\n<li>Reflexes</li>\r\n<li>Milestones</li>\r\n<li>A baby&rsquo;s needs</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(368, 'Module Two - Stages and Sequences of Social and Emotional Development (Part 1)', '<p>This module identifies the running order of social and emotional development within children, exploring a range of considerations and theories, such as: Biological theories, socialising and role models.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Biological theories</li>\r\n<li>Psychoanalytical theories</li>\r\n<li>Learning theories</li>\r\n<li>Social and emotional development</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to achieving milestones</li>\r\n<li>Socialising</li>\r\n<li>Security</li>\r\n<li>Rewards and punishment</li>\r\n<li>Role models</li>\r\n<li>Peers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(369, 'Module Three - Language and Linguistic Skills (Part 1)', '<p>This module details the essential tool of communication amongst humans and examines relevant areas such as reading and listening, to determine how this develops during our early years.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Pre-linguistic</li>\r\n<li>Language development aged two to five</li>\r\n<li>Body language</li>\r\n<li>Reading</li>\r\n<li>Drawing and writing</li>\r\n<li>Listening</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(370, 'Module Four - Cognitive Development', '<p>Through the exploration of areas such as memory, problem solving and learning theories, this module explores the development of thinking and understanding in children.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Imagination</li>\r\n<li>Creativity</li>\r\n<li>Memory</li>\r\n<li>Problem solving</li>\r\n<li>Concentration</li>\r\n<li>The Constructivist theory stages</li>\r\n<li>Behaviourist theory</li>\r\n<li>Biological theory</li>\r\n<li>Learning theories</li>\r\n<li>Psychoanalytical theories</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(371, 'Module Five - The Importance of Play', '<p>This module focusses on the concept of play and examines its role in child development, through the exploration of areas such as: child led play, observation of play and using play as a therapy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of activities</li>\r\n<li>Child led play</li>\r\n<li>Adult led play</li>\r\n<li>Spontaneity</li>\r\n<li>Observation of play</li>\r\n<li>Developing children&rsquo;s independence through play</li>\r\n<li>Using play as therapy</li>\r\n<li>What happens when children do not play?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(372, 'Module Six - Psychologists and Their Theories', '<p>This module studies the theorists associated with the study of child psychology, along with their theories and focusses on relevant areas such as memory and aggression, in order to advance learner understanding in this area.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Psychologist theories</li>\r\n<li>Psychology past and present</li>\r\n<li>Memory</li>\r\n<li>Reflection</li>\r\n<li>Imitation</li>\r\n<li>Aggression</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(373, 'Module Seven - The Nature Versus Nurture Debate (Part 1)', '<p>This module explores the pertinent debate of nature versus nurture in the context of child psychology and examines relevant areas such as: separated twins and feral children.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The debate</li>\r\n<li>Separated twins</li>\r\n<li>Feral children</li>\r\n<li>Compelling evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(374, 'Module Eight - Moral Development (Part 1)', '<p>This module looks at how a child&rsquo;s morality develops during their early years and examines how issues such as a violent society, the rights of a child and learning morals, can shape this development.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Never too young</li>\r\n<li>A violent society?</li>\r\n<li>Chronology of moral development</li>\r\n<li>The rights of the child</li>\r\n<li>Every Child Matters</li>\r\n<li>Social and moral development</li>\r\n<li>Learning morals</li>\r\n<li>Cultural diversity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(375, 'Module Nine - Difference in Gender (Part 1)', '<p>This module concentrates on the biological make-up of gender and explores the difference between boys and girls through the examination of areas such as: the endocrine system, physical features and gender roles.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gender</li>\r\n<li>Learning Gender Type Stereotypes</li>\r\n<li>The endocrine system</li>\r\n<li>Physical features</li>\r\n<li>Nature and nurture</li>\r\n<li>Gender roles</li>\r\n<li>How boys and girls learn</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(376, 'Module Ten - Developing Confidence in Children', '<p>This module examines the process of developing confidence in children and focusses on relevant areas such as: barriers to developing confidence, keeping the balance and a generation of unhappy children.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How do we help children develop confidence?</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to developing confidence</li>\r\n<li>Teaching children how to develop confidence</li>\r\n<li>Keeping the balance</li>\r\n<li>A generation of unhappy children</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(377, 'Module Eleven - Preparing Children for Nursery/School', '<p>This module looks at the appropriate ways in which you should help prepare children for nursery and school settings, examining relevant areas such as: making sense of their day and settling in.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preparing for nursery or school</li>\r\n<li>Make sense of their day</li>\r\n<li>Teaching children self-help skills</li>\r\n<li>Nursery</li>\r\n<li>School</li>\r\n<li>Put yourself in their place</li>\r\n<li>Settling in</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(378, 'Module Twelve - How to Have Happy Children', '<p>This module highlights the importance of ensuring children are happy, and examines relevant considerations used to achieve this, such as: love, protection and making time.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Begin at the beginning</li>\r\n<li>Love</li>\r\n<li>Protection</li>\r\n<li>Opportunities and experiences</li>\r\n<li>Get to know who they really are</li>\r\n<li>Make them feel special</li>\r\n<li>Positive and negative language</li>\r\n<li>Make time</li>\r\n<li>Fun and laughter</li>\r\n<li>Heroes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(379, 'Module Thirteen - Child Psychology as a science', '<p>This module studies the features of science and how various scientific methods are applied to the study of babies and children in Child Psychology. Theoretic approaches are then critiqued.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How babies and children are studied</li>\r\n<li>Approaches to child psychology</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(380, 'Module Fourteen - Early Socialisation', '<p>This module focuses on the early relationships that children make with their care-givers. It concentrates on the importance of these early relationships for future development and explores what happens when these bonds are broken.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Attachment</li>\r\n<li>Privation, deprivation and separation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(381, ' Module Fifteen - The Development of Language and Thought (Part 2)', '<p>The focus of this module is the development of language and thought. It explores stages of language and thought development and contrasts different theoretical views as to how these vital areas develop from birth through childhood.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Language development</li>\r\n<li>Cognitive development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(382, 'Module Sixteen - Gender and Moral Development (Part 2)', '<p>This module looks at how children acquire a gender identity and behave according to a recognised gender role. It also looks at how children develop a sense of what is right and wrong and examines stages in the development of moral reasoning.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Development of gender</li>\r\n<li>Moral development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(383, 'Module Seventeen - Social Development and the Family (Part 2)', '<p>This module examines the child&rsquo;s place within the family and the influence of the family on the child&rsquo;s social development. Factors such as: different parenting styles, self-esteem and childhood aggression are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Development of social cognition</li>\r\n<li>Parenting styles and their effects on development</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(384, 'Module Eighteen - The Nature/Nurture Debate (Part 2)', '<p>This concluding module expands on previous knowledge by exploring the long term debate of how much of our development is controlled by genes and how much is influenced by our environment. The debate is discussed with reference to the development of perception and intelligence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Development of sensory perception</li>\r\n<li>Development of intelligence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(385, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(386, 'Module One - Pioneers of Forensic Science', '<p>This introductory module explores the general process of forensic science in terms of how it has developed over time and which individuals made great strides with this progression.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Developmental history</li>\r\n<li>Development of forensic science techniques</li>\r\n<li>Pioneers of forensic science</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(387, 'Module Two - Case Study 1 – The Bodies in the Stream (The Jigsaw Case)', '<p>This module details the first case study of the course and studies the apparent murder of a person who was found disembodied in a stream below a bridge. The various processes that were involved in establishing this murder are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Forensic specialities</li>\r\n<li>Picture of events</li>\r\n<li>Chain of evidence continuity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(388, 'Module Three - Forensic Pathology', '<p>This module examines the concept of forensic pathology in terms of how changes in the structure and function of parts of the body can help discover the cause of death. Relevant areas such as; the autopsy procedure and the determination of sex, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Discovering how death occurred</li>\r\n<li>At the scene of the crime</li>\r\n<li>The autopsy procedure</li>\r\n<li>Dissection of the corpse</li>\r\n<li>Collection of samples</li>\r\n<li>Steps in determination of sex</li>\r\n<li>Determining why death occurred</li>\r\n<li>Other duties of a pathologist</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(389, 'Module One - What is meant by life coaching?', '<p>This introductory module explores the concept of being a life coach and briefly establishes the main areas the role involves. The knowledge also explores how the learner can first look at their own life and make suitable changes to make a positive difference.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What we mean by life coaching</li>\r\n<li>Positive and negative self-belief</li>\r\n<li>Focussing on what you really want</li>\r\n<li>Setting goals</li>\r\n<li>Preparing for success</li>\r\n<li>Confidence</li>\r\n<li>Looking good and feeling good</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(390, 'Module Two - Skills of effective coaching', '<p>Expanding on areas covered in module 1, this module provides further focus on self-treatment and taking necessary steps to progress in life. This focus is then tied in with the qualities necessary to become a life coach and explores if this is the career for you.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Commitment</li>\r\n<li>Our belief system</li>\r\n<li>Being good to ourselves</li>\r\n<li>Effective life coaching skills</li>\r\n<li>The practicalities of life coaching</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(391, 'Module Three - Areas of life coaching', '<p>This module explores the various areas of people&rsquo;s lives that you as a life coach can focus on. Detail is given on how to provide individuals with guidance on making a fresh start through focus on areas such as life de-cluttering and having good role models.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Home and lifestyle</li>\r\n<li>Love and relationships</li>\r\n<li>Work and career... time for a change?</li>\r\n<li>Time for a financial overhaul?</li>\r\n<li>Spirituality...The very essence of who we are!</li>\r\n<li>Make it real</li>\r\n<li>Give your dreams space to breathe</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(392, 'Module Four - Skills required for effective coaching', '<p>As previous modules delivered knowledge on what can be done to improve the quality of an individual&rsquo;s life, this module focusses primarily on how a life coach needs to apply these messages effectively to individuals, using appropriate skills.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Communication</li>\r\n<li>Self-esteem</li>\r\n<li>How to build confidence</li>\r\n<li>Active listening</li>\r\n<li>Empathy and understanding</li>\r\n<li>Encouragement and motivation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(393, 'Module Five - Life’s journey', '<p>This module explores life&rsquo;s journey and details how our life choices affect the path we take. The knowledge then focusses more specifically on these paths and explains how we can make the most of our ever changing life.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What sort of life are you going to have?</li>\r\n<li>The meaning of life</li>\r\n<li>Celebrate your achievements</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t dwell on past mistakes</li>\r\n<li>The secrets of success</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(394, 'Module Six - Let’s coach', '<p>This module focusses solely on the actual coaching of individuals. Guidance is given on effective coaching techniques and different styles that can be used. Learners will also be equipped with knowledge on areas such as the benefits of coaching and what to do if things go wrong.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Benefits of coaching</li>\r\n<li>Getting the most from your clients</li>\r\n<li>Coaching styles</li>\r\n<li>Moving on from coaching</li>\r\n<li>What if things go wrong?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(395, 'Module Seven - Life coaching as a career', '<p>This module looks at how all the skills learned so far can be put into practice by setting up a life coaching business. The knowledge focusses on how to make your career a reality and provides useful tips on becoming successful.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What type of coaching do you want to do?</li>\r\n<li>Setting up your business</li>\r\n<li>Your business plan</li>\r\n<li>Maximise your potential!</li>\r\n<li>Invest in your success</li>\r\n<li>Codes of practice</li>\r\n<li>Now you are a coach!</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(396, 'Module Eight - Overview', '<p>As the title suggests, this module aims to provide you with a thorough overview of the skills you will have gained from previous modules. To achieve this, the subject matter includes relevant knowledge from the other modules and applies this to various scenario based case studies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>CASE STUDY...Health coaching</li>\r\n<li>CASE STUDY...All issues coaching</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(397, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(398, 'Module One - Introduction to Marketing', '<p>This module provides an introductory overview to the subject of marketing. It defines exactly what marketing entails and examines areas such as; business values and famous marketing campaigns.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is marketing?</li>\r\n<li>How can marketing benefit a business?</li>\r\n<li>Business values</li>\r\n<li>Traditional marketing vs. digital marketing</li>\r\n<li>Famous marketing campaigns</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(399, 'Module Two - The Marketing Mix', '<p>This module explores the tool used by businesses and marketers when promoting products and services, known as the marketing mix. This encompasses four key elements known as the four P\'s and the materials contained examines each of these in detail.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Product: Defining the brand</li>\r\n<li>Price: Establishing a market position</li>\r\n<li>Place: Identifying the target market</li>\r\n<li>Promotion: Reaching customers</li>\r\n<li>Extended Marketing Mix</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(400, 'Module Three - Traditional Marketing Methods', '<p>This module is focussed on the study of traditional methods for marketing and explores well established techniques that utilize avenues such as; television advertising, public relations (PR) and personal selling.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Print advertising</li>\r\n<li>Television advertising</li>\r\n<li>Radio advertising</li>\r\n<li>Direct marketing</li>\r\n<li>Sales promotions</li>\r\n<li>Public Relations (PR)</li>\r\n<li>Word-of-mouth</li>\r\n<li>Personal selling</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(401, 'Module Four - Digital Marketing Methods', '<p>This module is concerned with the sub-branch of marketing that involves the promotion of products or brands, as well as communication with stakeholders, via different forms of electronic media. This method is known as digital marketing and it encompasses a range of areas such as; blogging, SEO and social networking.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Website</li>\r\n<li>Social Media</li>\r\n<li>Visual platforms</li>\r\n<li>Video</li>\r\n<li>Networking</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(402, 'Module Five - Getting Started', '<p>This module looks at the steps that should be made when you plan to get started with your marketing efforts. It examines relevant areas such as, the importance of self-assessment and provides guidance on creating an appropriate strategy for achieving your goals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>SWOT analysis</li>\r\n<li>Create and implement your marketing strategy</li>\r\n<li>Evaluation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(403, 'Module Six - Progression', '<p>This module studies the steps that should be taken in order to develop your marketing plans and turn these into achievable objectives. The materials contained examine a range of considerations that should be made in pursuit of your goals and looks at areas such as; consistency control and crisis management.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Consistency, development and goals</li>\r\n<li>Crisis management</li>\r\n<li>Outsourcing services</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(404, 'Module Seven - To finish', '<p>This concluding module aims to summarise all the content covered so far, provide indications as to how the marketing world is likely to develop and also equip you with useful tips on becoming a successful marketer.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The future of marketing</li>\r\n<li>Top marketing tips</li>\r\n<li>Glossary</li>\r\n<li>Multiple choice questions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(405, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(406, 'Module One - What is dyslexia?', '<p>This module introduces the term dyslexia and explores what is meant by the condition, looking at considerations such as; biological factors, literacy skills and who has dyslexia.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Normal development of literacy skills</li>\r\n<li>What is literacy?</li>\r\n<li>Biological factors</li>\r\n<li>Cognitive factors</li>\r\n<li>Behavioural level</li>\r\n<li>Disability, difficulty or difference</li>\r\n<li>Who has dyslexia?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(407, 'Module Two - Identifying dyslexia', '<p>This module begins by looking at some of the other reasons why children might have difficulties in becoming literate. This will, in turn, help you to avoid a possible misdiagnosis and understand exactly what signs to look out for with someone who has dyslexia.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dyslexia or delay?</li>\r\n<li>Socio-economic factors</li>\r\n<li>Speech, language and hearing difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Signs and symptoms of dyslexia</li>\r\n<li>Dyslexia in schools</li>\r\n<li>Maths</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour problems that might indicate dyslexia</li>\r\n<li>Adults with dyslexia</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(408, 'Module Three - Co-occurring conditions', '<p>This module studies some of the other specific learning disabilities that overlap with dyslexia and aims to instil a brief awareness of how these can affect individuals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dyspraxia</li>\r\n<li>Dyscalculia</li>\r\n<li>Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) and Attention Deficit Disorder (ADD)</li>\r\n<li>Asperger&rsquo;s and autism</li>\r\n<li>Irlen Syndrome</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(409, 'Module Four - How dyslexia is diagnosed', '<p>This module focusses on the process of obtaining a diagnosis for dyslexia. The materials stress that dyslexia is not a medical condition and as such it details the various tests that schools, colleges, universities and workplaces can implement to determine if an individual has the condition.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Screening tests</li>\r\n<li>The assessment procedure</li>\r\n<li>Universities and Further Education</li>\r\n<li>Disabled Students Allowance</li>\r\n<li>English as an Additional Language</li>\r\n<li>Reactions to diagnosis</li>\r\n<li>Ethical, legal and regulatory considerations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(410, 'Module Five - Dyslexia- friendly learning environment', '<p>This module considers how various educational settings can make adaptions to their teaching methods to make them more inclusive and achievable for those who have dyslexia.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Models of dyslexia</li>\r\n<li>Dyslexia friendly</li>\r\n<li>Primary settings</li>\r\n<li>Promoting literacy</li>\r\n<li>Secondary schools</li>\r\n<li>Different learning styles</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(411, 'Module Six - Solutions for dyslexia', '<p>Although dyslexia is a life-long condition that cannot be cured, this concluding module looks at the various management techniques which can be enforced to ensure the effects of the condition are minimised.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Early intervention</li>\r\n<li>Phonics</li>\r\n<li>Technology</li>\r\n<li>Jolly phonics</li>\r\n<li>The five main skills required for reading and writing</li>\r\n<li>Irlen</li>\r\n<li>Davis Dyslexia Correction</li>\r\n<li>DORE achievement centres</li>\r\n<li>Maths</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(412, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(413, 'Module One - Understand how to work in the end of life care', '<p>This unit introduces the process of working in end of life care and considers a range of factors which will impact individuals working in this areas, such as; perspectives on death, the aims of end of life care and communication.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Different perspectives on death and dying</li>\r\n<li>The aims, principles and policies of end of life care</li>\r\n<li>Factors regarding communication in end of life care</li>\r\n<li>How to access the range of support services available to individuals and others</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(414, 'Module Two - Understand how to provide support to manage pain and discomfort', '<p>This unit is concerned with the methods that carers should use to support dying individuals when they experience pain or discomfort and the materials study methods used to achieve this.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Approaches to managing pain and discomfort</li>\r\n<li>How to assist in minimising individuals&rsquo; pain or discomfort</li>\r\n<li>Know how to monitor, record and report on the management of individuals&rsquo; pain or discomfort</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(415, 'Module Three - End of life care and dementia', '<p>This unit specifically explores the process of caring for dying individuals who have dementia and the materials study relevant considerations, such as; supporting people in pain and distress and how to support family and friends of the individual.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How an individual&rsquo;s dementia can affect their end of life care</li>\r\n<li>How to support individuals with dementia affected by pain and distress at end of life</li>\r\n<li>How to support family, significant others and friends of an individual with dementia at end of life</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(416, 'Module Four - Understanding the role of the care worker in time of death', '<p>This unit looks to provide guidance on what a carer&rsquo;s role is at the time of death of an individual in their care and studies relevant considerations, such as; supporting the family and working in line with relevant laws and personal beliefs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to support an individual as they are approaching death</li>\r\n<li>How to care for a deceased individual</li>\r\n<li>The support needed by family, significant others and friends of the deceased individual</li>\r\n<li>Relevant legislation and policies</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(417, 'Module Five - Understand loss and grief in end of life care', '<p>This unit studies the difference between loss, bereavement, grief and mourning and provides guidance on how to identify loss and grief in others and be able to support the person in managing their grief.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The process of loss and grief</li>\r\n<li>Understanding loss in the context of end of life care</li>\r\n<li>How to support people following bereavement</li>\r\n<li>How to manage own feelings of loss and grief when working in end of life care</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(418, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(419, 'Module One - History of Firearms and Firearms Law', '<p>This module provides an introductory overview of the firearm by looking at the history of its creation and use. The materials then go on to consider the laws relating to firearms and looks at how forensic ballistics need to be fully aware of these.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Basic principle of a firearm</li>\r\n<li>History</li>\r\n<li>Firearms law</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(420, 'Module Two - Firearms and Ammunition Safety', '<p>This module is focussed on the key aspect of ballistics analysis, which is ensuring that individuals are working safely with firearms and ammunition. The materials examine relevant considerations, such as; safe receipt of items, handling during examination and safety after examination.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>General health and safety</li>\r\n<li>Safe recovery and collection from the scene</li>\r\n<li>Safe receipt of items</li>\r\n<li>Safe storage of items</li>\r\n<li>Handling during examination</li>\r\n<li>Ammunition safety</li>\r\n<li>Safety after examination</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(421, 'Module Three - Types of Firearms and Ammunition', '<p>This module considers the range of different types of firearms and ammunition that the ballistics team may come across during their work, looking at their specific features in order to instil an awareness of what to consider when assessing specific types of evidence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Common terminology</li>\r\n<li>Types of firearms</li>\r\n<li>Types of ammunition</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(422, 'Module Four - Overview of the Role of a Forensic Firearms Scientist', '<p>This module is concerned with the various roles and responsibilities of a forensic firearms scientist and studies a range of considerations, such as; item examination, reporting and court attendance.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>General job role</li>\r\n<li>Adherence to quality procedures</li>\r\n<li>Examined items</li>\r\n<li>Reporting</li>\r\n<li>Post mortem attendance</li>\r\n<li>Court attendance</li>\r\n<li>Participation in proficiently testing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(423, 'Module Five - Scene Examination and Firearms Recovery', '<p>This module studies the specific practice of examining a crime scene for evidence and the process of recovering firearms safely, whilst preserving the evidence. The materials look at a range of considerations, such as; scene assessment, collection of evidence and packaging labelling.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preservation of the scene</li>\r\n<li>Scene safety</li>\r\n<li>Scene assessment</li>\r\n<li>Types of forensic firearm evidence</li>\r\n<li>Scene examination, preservation and collection of evidence</li>\r\n<li>Making a firearm safe at the scene</li>\r\n<li>Packaging labelling</li>\r\n<li>Continuity of evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(424, 'Module Six - Examination of Firearms and Ammunition', '<p>This module deals with the examination procedures used in the forensic examination of the main types of firearms and ammunition that are common nowadays.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Submission of firearms and ammunition</li>\r\n<li>Firearms safety</li>\r\n<li>Examination of firearms and component parts</li>\r\n<li>Examination of ammunition</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(425, 'Module Seven - Comparison of Cartridge Cases and Bullets', '<p>This module studies the important practice of comparing firearm cartridge cases and bullets in order to determine the use of a firearm for criminal purposes and considers relevant areas, such as; marks on cartridge cases, theory of identification and the range of possible conclusions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Firearms manufacture</li>\r\n<li>Marks on cartridge cases</li>\r\n<li>Rifling on bullets</li>\r\n<li>Comparison macroscopy</li>\r\n<li>Theory of identification</li>\r\n<li>Characteristics of marks</li>\r\n<li>General comparison examination criteria</li>\r\n<li>Range of possible conclusions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(426, 'Module Eight - Determination of Range of Fire (Firearms Residue, FDR)) and Trajectories', '<p>This module is concerned with the role of a forensic firearms expert in determining the range of fire (muzzle to target) and examines relevant areas, such as; firearms residue analysis, shot (pellet) pattern analysis and estimation of trajectories.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Firearms residue analysis</li>\r\n<li>Estimation of trajectories (angles)</li>\r\n<li>Shot (pellet) pattern analysis</li>\r\n<li>An example of a case involving shot pattern analysis</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(427, 'Module Nine - Firearms Intelligence', '<p>This module explores the various ways in which forensic firearms experts can help aid future examinations by keeping abreast of current trends and issues relating to firearms, in order to keep their knowledge on gun related crime current.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>History</li>\r\n<li>NABIS (National Ballistic Intelligence System) UK</li>\r\n<li>How NABIS hardware works</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(428, 'Module Ten - Gunshot Residue- GSR', '<p>This concluding module examines the types of cases associated with GSR evidence, and in which GSR analysis may be useful in a range of different types of investigation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gunshot residue formation</li>\r\n<li>Gunshot residue detection</li>\r\n<li>Gunshot residue analysis</li>\r\n<li>Contamination issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(429, 'Module One - The Crime Scene', '<p>This introductory module focuses specifically on the crime scene and will provide you with an understanding of the importance of time, care and detail when evaluating a crime scene. Module 1 explores key concepts such as Locard&rsquo;s Exchange Principle, the &lsquo;Golden Hour&rsquo; and &lsquo;Fast Track Action&rsquo; and covers the identification, preservation, collection, documentation and presentation of evidence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Locard&rsquo;s Exchange Principle</li>\r\n<li>The difference between Crime Scene Investigation and Forensic Science</li>\r\n<li>Who is and who does what at the crime scene</li>\r\n<li>The golden hour</li>\r\n<li>Fast track actions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(430, 'Module Two - Evidence', '<p>Module 2 of the Level 4 Forensic Science Diploma looks at the legal categories of evidence in criminal investigation and identifies the difference between individual and class characteristics of evidence. This module then takes a more detailed look into trace evidence including how trace evidence is discovered, examined, collected, recovered, recorded, packaged and labelled.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is evidence?</li>\r\n<li>Class characteristics</li>\r\n<li>Individual characteristics</li>\r\n<li>What is trace evidence?</li>\r\n<li>Procedures for collection of evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(431, 'Module Three - Biological Evidence', '<p>Module 3 examines various examples of biological evidence and also explores how and why biological evidence is collected. In this module, learners will investigate how biological evidence connects victim and offender to the crime scene looking closely at how blood spatter patterns can be used to reconstruct a crime scene.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Semen</li>\r\n<li>Blood</li>\r\n<li>Blood spatter patterns</li>\r\n<li>Saliva</li>\r\n<li>Hair</li>\r\n<li>Fingernail scrapings</li>\r\n<li>Body tissue</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(432, 'Module Four - Non Biological Trace Evidence', '<p>Module 4 takes a closer look at non-biological trace evidence including how and why this is collected and how non-biological trace evidence connects victim and offender to the crime scene. This module also explores how impression and imprint patterns can be used to reconstruct a crime scene.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Impression and imprint evidence</li>\r\n<li>Fibres</li>\r\n<li>Paint</li>\r\n<li>Glass</li>\r\n<li>Dust, dirt and soil</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(433, 'Module Five - Fingerprint Evidence', '<p>This module investigates the uniqueness of fingerprints and their value as evidence. In module 5 of the Forensic Science Diploma Level 4, the student will discover how and why fingerprints are recovered and will investigate different types and characteristics of fingerprints found at the crime scene.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fingerprint evidence</li>\r\n<li>Prints at the scene of crime</li>\r\n<li>Taking fingerprints</li>\r\n<li>Fingerprint characteristics</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(434, 'Module Six - Ballistics Evidence', '<p>In this module of the Forensic Science Level 4 Diploma we will discover how and why Ballistics/Firearms Evidence, expended ammunition and gunshot residue (GSR) are recovered at the crime scene.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is Ballistics/ Firearm evidence</li>\r\n<li>Preserving and collecting evidence at the scene</li>\r\n<li>Expended ammunition</li>\r\n<li>Gunshot residue (GSR)</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(435, 'Module Seven - Evidence of Arson', '<p>Module 7 examines the difference between arson and accidental fires. This module looks at the fire triangle concept before going on to investigate what evidence is collected to establish the causes and origin of a fire, and the evidential value of accelerants and how these are collected at the scene. The difficulties and the continuing requirement of maintaining the chain of evidence at the fire scene will also be examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Arson or accident</li>\r\n<li>The fire triangle</li>\r\n<li>Heat</li>\r\n<li>Establishing the cause of the fire</li>\r\n<li>Accelerants</li>\r\n<li>Fire investigation search dogs</li>\r\n<li>Collecting the evidence</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining the chain of evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(436, 'Module Eight - Underpinning Knowledge', '<p>Module 8 explores the difference between an accidental explosion and the triggering of a bomb and investigates how and why the bomb scene is processed. In this module learners will discover how explosives differ and why this is important in assisting the Bomb Scene Investigator to determine what evidence to look for. Module 8 also delves into what evidence the Bomb Scene Investigator might collect and the particular difficulties presented at the bomb scene.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Accident or bomb</li>\r\n<li>Processing the scene</li>\r\n<li>Collecting the evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(437, 'Module Nine - Forensic Pathology at the Crime Scene', '<p>In module 9 of this Level 4 Forensic Science Diploma the role of both the Coroner and Pathologist will be explored. The student will investigate how and what evidence is collected at the murder scene and how biological processes are used to estimate the time of death. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The coroner</li>\r\n<li>The pathologist</li>\r\n<li>At the scene of the crime</li>\r\n<li>Estimating time of death</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(438, 'Module Ten - Forensic Pathology at the Mortuary', '<p>Module 10 of the Forensic Science Diploma examines how and why an autopsy is carried out, investigating some of the many ways in which death can occur and how the forensic pathologist recognises them. In this module the learner will also look at how and why an external and internal examination of a corpse is conducted at the mortuary.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Determining cause of death</li>\r\n<li>Arrival of the corpse at the mortuary</li>\r\n<li>Asphyxia</li>\r\n<li>Dissection of the corpse</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(439, 'Module Eleven - Forensic Anthropology', '<p>In module 11 of the Forensic Science Level 4 Diploma the student will examine the role of the forensic anthropologist, investigate the anthropological determination of gender, investigate the anthropological determination of age, the anthropological determination of ethnicity and the anthropological determination of height weight and individual differences.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Forensic Anthropologist</li>\r\n<li>Role of Forensic Anthropologist</li>\r\n<li>Determining the gender, age and ethnicity of the remains</li>\r\n<li>Determining the height, weight &amp; individual differences of the remains</li>\r\n<li>Disease and injury</li>\r\n<li>The Biological Profile</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(440, 'Module Twelve - Forensic Odontology', '<p>Module 12 examines the role of the Forensic Odontologist, how the characteristics of human dentition can be used to help identify human remains, how the characteristics of human dentition can be used to help establish the age of human remains and investigate how bite marks can establish connections between a suspect and the victim.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Forensic Odontologist</li>\r\n<li>Dentition</li>\r\n<li>Identification of human remains</li>\r\n<li>Determination of age</li>\r\n<li>Bite marks</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(441, 'Module Thirteen - Forensic Entomology', '<p>In module 13 the student will examine the role of the forensic entomologist, investigate arthropods and insects and their role in determining PMI, examine the actions of the forensic entomologist, crime scene investigator at the scene, investigate the life cycle of the blowfly, factors in its development and its importance in determining PMI and how the forensic entomologist maintains the chain of evidence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>At the scene</li>\r\n<li>Life cycle of the blowfly</li>\r\n<li>Factors affecting blowfly development</li>\r\n<li>Species succession</li>\r\n<li>Sources of Toxicological samples</li>\r\n<li>Associated evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(442, 'Module Fourteen - Forensic Botany', '<p>Module 14 examines the role of the forensic botanist, investigates the sub discipline of palynology, anatomy and dendrochronology, plant ecology and investigates limnology.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Palynology</li>\r\n<li>Anatomy and Dendrochronology</li>\r\n<li>Plant Ecology</li>\r\n<li>Limnology</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(443, 'Module Fifteen - Forensic Serology', '<p>In module 15 the student will examine the role of the forensic serologist, investigate blood typing, investigate the analysis of blood, semen, saliva other bodily fluids in the laboratory.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Semen analysis</li>\r\n<li>Presumptive testing for Acid Phosphatase</li>\r\n<li>Saliva analysis</li>\r\n<li>Urine analysis</li>\r\n<li>Analysis of Gastric Fluid</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(444, 'Module Sixteen - DNA Typing (Fingerprinting)', '<p>Module 16 of the Forensic Science Level 4 Diploma covers DNA and its structure, DNA coding, DNA testing and profiling and the National DNA database and the legislation that supports it.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The structure of DNA</li>\r\n<li>DNA coding</li>\r\n<li>DNA testing</li>\r\n<li>The DNA profile</li>\r\n<li>National SNA database</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(445, 'Module Seventeen - Forensic Toxicology', '<p>In module 17 the student will investigate toxicology and the role of the forensic toxicologist, examine presumptive and confirmatory testing for drugs and poisons and revise chain of evidence maintenance in respect of toxicological samples.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The role of the Forensic Toxicologist</li>\r\n<li>Drug analysis</li>\r\n<li>Searching for poisons</li>\r\n<li>Toxicological testing for poisons</li>\r\n<li>Chain of evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(446, 'Module Eighteen - Forensic Firearms Investigation', '<p>Module 18 looks into the role of the firearms examiner, firearms identification, ammunition comparison, distance and angle of trajectory, identification of trace evidence and analysis of gunshot residue and serial number restoration.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Firearms identification</li>\r\n<li>Ammunition comparison</li>\r\n<li>Distance and angle trajectory determination</li>\r\n<li>Chemical analysis for gunshot residue</li>\r\n<li>Serial number restoration</li>\r\n<li>Identification of trace evidence</li>\r\n<li>Gunshot wounds</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(447, 'Module Nineteen - Questioned Documents', '<p>In module 19 the student will examine questioned documents and the role of the questioned document examiner, examine handwriting analysis, investigate the examination of typewriters and typewritten documents, word processors and printed documents and investigate the examination of forged documents, the examination of inks and papers and document verification.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Role of a questioned document examiner</li>\r\n<li>Handwriting analysis</li>\r\n<li>Typewriters and typewritten documents</li>\r\n<li>Word processed and printed documents</li>\r\n<li>Forged documents</li>\r\n<li>Erasures, Alterations, Additions &amp; Obliterations</li>\r\n<li>Document verification</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(448, 'Module Twenty - Forensic Vehicle Examination', '<p>Module 20 of the Forensic Science Level 4 Diploma covers the investigate forensic vehicle examination and the forensic vehicle examiner, the role of the forensic vehicle examiner in respect of fatal road traffic accidents, motor vehicle paint chip analysis and motor vehicle glass analysis.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fatal road traffic accidents</li>\r\n<li>Vehicle paint chip analysis</li>\r\n<li>Vehicle glass analysis</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(449, 'Self Assignments (Optional)', '<p>These documents are self-assessments which you can use to test and reaffirm your current&nbsp;knowledge, any self-assessments that are completed will not be marked by your tutor. These documents do not add to your grading and have no effect on the overall outcome of the units they refer to.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1),
(450, 'Module One - Babies from Birth to One Year', '<p>This introductory module studies the initial development of a child during the first year of their life. The numerous occurrences at this time, such as: bonding, reflexes and a baby&rsquo;s needs, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Before birth</li>\r\n<li>Bonding</li>\r\n<li>Social and emotional development</li>\r\n<li>Reflexes</li>\r\n<li>Milestones</li>\r\n<li>A baby&rsquo;s needs</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(451, 'Module Two - Stages and Sequences of Social and Emotional Development (Part 1)', '<p>This module identifies the running order of social and emotional development within children, exploring a range of considerations and theories, such as: Biological theories, socialising and role models.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Biological theories</li>\r\n<li>Psychoanalytical theories</li>\r\n<li>Learning theories</li>\r\n<li>Social and emotional development</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to achieving milestones</li>\r\n<li>Socialising</li>\r\n<li>Security</li>\r\n<li>Rewards and punishment</li>\r\n<li>Role models</li>\r\n<li>Peers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(452, 'Module Three - Language and Linguistic Skills (Part 1)', '<p>This module details the essential tool of communication amongst humans and examines relevant areas such as reading and listening, to determine how this develops during our early years.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Pre-linguistic</li>\r\n<li>Language development aged two to five</li>\r\n<li>Body language</li>\r\n<li>Reading</li>\r\n<li>Drawing and writing</li>\r\n<li>Listening</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(453, 'Module Four - Cognitive Development', '<p>Through the exploration of areas such as memory, problem solving and learning theories, this module explores the development of thinking and understanding in children.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Imagination</li>\r\n<li>Creativity</li>\r\n<li>Memory</li>\r\n<li>Problem solving</li>\r\n<li>Concentration</li>\r\n<li>The Constructivist theory stages</li>\r\n<li>Behaviourist theory</li>\r\n<li>Biological theory</li>\r\n<li>Learning theories</li>\r\n<li>Psychoanalytical theories</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(454, 'Module Five - The Importance of Play', '<p>This module focusses on the concept of play and examines its role in child development, through the exploration of areas such as: child led play, observation of play and using play as a therapy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of activities</li>\r\n<li>Child led play</li>\r\n<li>Adult led play</li>\r\n<li>Spontaneity</li>\r\n<li>Observation of play</li>\r\n<li>Developing children&rsquo;s independence through play</li>\r\n<li>Using play as therapy</li>\r\n<li>What happens when children do not play?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(455, 'Module Six - Psychologists and Their Theories', '<p>This module studies the theorists associated with the study of child psychology, along with their theories and focusses on relevant areas such as memory and aggression, in order to advance learner understanding in this area.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Psychologist theories</li>\r\n<li>Psychology past and present</li>\r\n<li>Memory</li>\r\n<li>Reflection</li>\r\n<li>Imitation</li>\r\n<li>Aggression</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(456, 'Module Seven - The Nature Versus Nurture Debate (Part 1)', '<p>This module explores the pertinent debate of nature versus nurture in the context of child psychology and examines relevant areas such as: separated twins and feral children.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The debate</li>\r\n<li>Separated twins</li>\r\n<li>Feral children</li>\r\n<li>Compelling evidence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(457, 'Module Eight - Moral Development (Part 1)', '<p>This module looks at how a child&rsquo;s morality develops during their early years and examines how issues such as: a violent society, the rights of a child and learning morals, can shape this development.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Never too young</li>\r\n<li>A violent society?</li>\r\n<li>Chronology of moral development</li>\r\n<li>The rights of the child</li>\r\n<li>Every Child Matters</li>\r\n<li>Social and moral development</li>\r\n<li>Learning morals</li>\r\n<li>Cultural diversity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(458, 'Module Nine - Difference in Gender (Part 1)', '<p>This module concentrates on the biological make-up of gender and explores the difference between boys and girls through the examination of areas such as: the endocrine system, physical features and gender roles.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gender</li>\r\n<li>Learning Gender Type Stereotypes</li>\r\n<li>The endocrine system</li>\r\n<li>Physical features</li>\r\n<li>Nature and nurture</li>\r\n<li>Gender roles</li>\r\n<li>How boys and girls learn</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(459, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(460, 'Module Ten - Developing Confidence in Children', '<p>This module examines the process of developing confidence in children and focusses on relevant areas such as: barriers to developing confidence, keeping the balance and a generation of unhappy children.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How do we help children develop confidence?</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to developing confidence</li>\r\n<li>Teaching children how to develop confidence</li>\r\n<li>Keeping the balance</li>\r\n<li>A generation of unhappy children</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(461, 'Module Eleven - Preparing Children for Nursery/School', '<p>This module looks at the appropriate ways in which you should help prepare children for nursery and school settings, examining relevant areas such as: making sense of their day and settling in.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preparing for nursery or school</li>\r\n<li>Make sense of their day</li>\r\n<li>Teaching children self-help skills</li>\r\n<li>Nursery</li>\r\n<li>School</li>\r\n<li>Put yourself in their place</li>\r\n<li>Settling in</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(462, 'Module Twelve - How to Have Happy Children', '<p>This module highlights the importance of ensuring children are happy and examines relevant considerations used to achieve this, such as: love, protection and making time.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Begin at the beginning</li>\r\n<li>Love</li>\r\n<li>Protection</li>\r\n<li>Opportunities and experiences</li>\r\n<li>Get to know who they really are</li>\r\n<li>Make them feel special</li>\r\n<li>Positive and negative language</li>\r\n<li>Make time</li>\r\n<li>Fun and laughter</li>\r\n<li>Heroes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(463, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(464, 'Module One - Dementia awareness', '<p>The aim of this unit is to enable learners to gain knowledge of what dementia is, the different forms of dementia and how others can have an impact on the individual with dementia.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What dementia is</li>\r\n<li>Theoretical models of dementia care</li>\r\n<li>What causes dementia</li>\r\n<li>How to see each individual&rsquo;s experience of dementia as unique</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(465, 'Module Two - The person centred approach to the care and support of individuals with dementia', '<p>This unit provides the knowledge and understanding required to enable the individual with dementia to experience well-being. Learners will be able to develop their knowledge of the person centred approach to dementia care and support.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Taking a person-centred approach</li>\r\n<li>Person-centred care in relation to the role of carers and others</li>\r\n<li>Families and support</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(466, 'Module Three - Understand the factors that can influence communication and interaction with individual who have dementia', '<p>This unit considers the communication needs and abilities of individuals with dementia and how these can be catered for in order to enhance positive interaction.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The way in which people with a dementia can interact and communicate</li>\r\n<li>Applying communication techniques</li>\r\n<li>Effective communication techniques</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(467, 'Module Four - Understand equality, diversity and inclusion in dementia care', '<p>This unit introduces the concepts of equality, diversity, and inclusion that are fundamental to person centred care practice and looks at the ways of working to ensure individuals with dementia are treated fairly.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Diversity and dementia</li>\r\n<li>Person-centred approaches to dementia care</li>\r\n<li>Ways of working to ensure diversity needs of individuals with dementia are met</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(468, 'Module Five - Understand the administration of medication to individuals with dementia using a person centred approach', '<p>This unit is about knowledge and understanding of individuals who may have specific needs for receiving medication because of their experience of dementia. Learners will develop their knowledge of these medication requirements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>When should drugs be used to treat behavioural and psychological symptoms of dementia</li>\r\n<li>Person centred ways of administering medicines</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(469, 'Module Six - Understand behaviour in the context of dementia', '<p>This unit explores the different forms of behaviour and the factors that affect behaviour in someone with dementia. The materials then examine how to respond to behaviour some people many find &lsquo;challenging&rsquo; in an appropriate and supportive manner. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Behaviour as a means of communication</li>\r\n<li>Responding to dementia related behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Why some people with dementia will need additional support</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(470, 'Module Seven - Understand the benefits of engaging in activities in social care', '<p>This concluding unit studies the benefits for individuals with dementia, of engaging in activities to enhance physical, mental and social well-being in a diverse range of settings.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The impact of activity on physical and mental well-being</li>\r\n<li>The social benefits of activities</li>\r\n<li>Model of care and support</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(471, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(472, 'Module One - Principles of people management', '<p>This introductory unit provides a general overview of the process of managing people and considers important factors, such as; team building, performance management and conflict management.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The principles of workforce management</li>\r\n<li>Equality or opportunity, diversity and inclusion</li>\r\n<li>Team building and dynamics</li>\r\n<li>Performance management</li>\r\n<li>Training and development</li>\r\n<li>Reward and recognition</li>\r\n<li>Principles of conflict management</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(473, 'Module Two - Principles of business', '<p>This unit studies the specific nature of a business and examines the main undertakings involved to successfully sustain and build one.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Business markets</li>\r\n<li>Business innovation and growth</li>\r\n<li>Financial management</li>\r\n<li>Business budgeting</li>\r\n<li>Sales and marketing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(474, 'Module Three - Principles of leadership and management', '<p>This unit is focussed on the manager&rsquo;s role of applying themselves as a leader and considers techniques which can be implemented to help in leading a team by example.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Principles of effective decision-making</li>\r\n<li>Leadership styles and models</li>\r\n<li>Role, functions and processes of management</li>\r\n<li>Performance measurement</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(475, 'Module Four - Understand how to improve business performance', '<p>This unit examines the various actions that a manager can take in order to help improve business performance, exploring how these can be implemented and how they can be beneficial.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Principles of resolving business problems</li>\r\n<li>Improvement techniques and processes</li>\r\n<li>Principles of change management</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(476, 'Module Seven - Understand equality, diversity and inclusion in the workplace', '<p>This unit studies the manger&rsquo;s role to enforce and promote equality, diversity and inclusion within the work environment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Organisational aspects of equality, diversity and inclusion in the workplace</li>\r\n<li>Personal aspects of equality, diversity and inclusion in the workplace</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(477, 'Module Nine - Understand how to resolve customers’ problems and complaints', '<p>This unit explores the manger&rsquo;s role in overseeing the monitoring and resolution of customer problems and complaints through the application of suitable techniques.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Monitoring and resolution of customers&rsquo; problems</li>\r\n<li>Monitoring and resolution of customers&rsquo; complaints</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(478, 'Module Ten - Understand how to monitor customer service interactions and feedback', '<p>This concluding unit looks at how a manager should analyse the nature of customer service interactions and collect relevant data to ensure this is achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Monitoring the quality of customer service interactions</li>\r\n<li>How to gather, analyse and interpret customer feedback</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(479, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(480, 'Appendices', '<p>These documents are reflective statements which you can use to review the knowledge you have gained, any reflective statements that are completed will not be marked by your tutor. These documents do not add to your grading and have no effect on the overall outcome of the units they refer to.</p>', 0),
(481, 'Module One - Introducing Research Methods', '<p>This introductory module looks at the forensic psychologist&rsquo;s role in conducting research in order to inform a criminal case. Relevant areas such as; different types of research projects, experiments and research methods, are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Research design</li>\r\n<li>Exploratory, descriptive and explanatory projects</li>\r\n<li>Standardising the experiment</li>\r\n<li>Research methods</li>\r\n<li>Instruments</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(482, 'Module Two - Introducing Basic Statistics', '<p>This module studies the forensic psychologist&rsquo;s role in applying statistical probabilities to behaviours and events in order to obtain an understanding of criminal probability. Relevant techniques such as creating a likert scale and a histogram are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Probability</li>\r\n<li>Independent variable</li>\r\n<li>Relative frequency</li>\r\n<li>Likert scale</li>\r\n<li>Histogram</li>\r\n<li>Random Sample and population</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(483, 'Module 3 - Psychology and Violent Crime', '<p>This module examines the relationship between violent crime and psychological processes, critiquing particular mental illness explanations for crime and exploring the impact of areas such as anti-social lifestyles and football hooliganism. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schizophrenia and violence</li>\r\n<li>Psychopathy and violence</li>\r\n<li>Interpersonal traits</li>\r\n<li>Anti-social lifestyle</li>\r\n<li>Frustration and violence</li>\r\n<li>Football hooliganism</li>\r\n<li>Expressive aggression</li>\r\n<li>Instrumental aggression</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(484, 'Module 4 - Serial Killers', '<p>This module focusses on the exploration of different types of serial killer traits and covers a number of pertinent examples in order to gain a varied understanding of serial killer behaviour. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Frederick Harold Shipman murders</li>\r\n<li>The Yorkshire Ripper murders</li>\r\n<li>The Alton Coleman murders</li>\r\n<li>The Beverley Allit murders</li>\r\n<li>Causality and serial murder</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(485, 'Module 5 - Crime and Substance Abuse', '<p>This module covers the issue of substance misuse and examines how this impacts upon criminal activity. Relevant areas such as the social and economic costs of substance misuse and government approaches, are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Drug legality</li>\r\n<li>Costs of legal substance abuse</li>\r\n<li>The link between crime and substance abuse</li>\r\n<li>Government approaches to substance abuse related crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(486, 'Module 6 - Child Abuse', '<p>This module details the criminal act of child abuse in its many forms such as; physical, emotional, sexual or as a result of neglect and looks at pertinent issues such as the signs of abuse and what effect these may have. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Signs of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Effects of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Sexual offending explanations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(487, 'Module 7 - The Evidence of Children', '<p>This module looks at the rare usage of children in criminal proceedings and highlights the specific actions involved in this process before examining the multiple issues that this process can create. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Interviewing child witnesses</li>\r\n<li>Sources of child suggestibility</li>\r\n<li>A child&rsquo;s fitness to act as a witness</li>\r\n<li>Evidence of children in court</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(488, 'Module 8 - Criminal Responsibility and Psychiatric Defences', '<p>This module focusses on the assessment of a criminal&rsquo;s state of mind in determining whether they have any mental illnesses which would be likely to affect their sentencing procedures, in accordance with modern day laws. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The conflicting roles of the forensic psychologist</li>\r\n<li>Defining mental disorder</li>\r\n<li>Unfitness to plead</li>\r\n<li>The Domestic Violence, Crime and Victims Act, 2004</li>\r\n<li>Infanticide</li>\r\n<li>Diminished responsibility</li>\r\n<li>Not guilty by reason of insanity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(489, 'Module 9 - Mental Disorder as a Defence', '<p>This module looks at the occurrence of special mental disorders which have been used to support a defensive claim of diminished responsibility or freedom from criminal conviction and examines in which instances a claim is valid. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dissociative identity disorder (multiple personality disorder)</li>\r\n<li>Amnesia</li>\r\n<li>Post-traumatic stress disorder</li>\r\n<li>Dangerous and severe personality disorder</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(490, 'Module 10 - Eyewitness Testimony', '<p>This module focusses on eyewitness accounts of criminal activity, looking at the types of memories that are likely to be reaffirmed and examines their uses and possible problems with reliability. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eyewitness memory</li>\r\n<li>Conceptual memories</li>\r\n<li>Perception, memory and eyewitness testimony</li>\r\n<li>Personal perception and memory</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(491, 'Module 11 - Psychology in a Correctional Setting', '<p>This module is concerned with the study of prisoner mental health assessment and explores a number of relevant issues such as; suicides in prison, the psychological effect of imprisonment and re-offending. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Beginning the sentence</li>\r\n<li>Suicides in prison</li>\r\n<li>The psychological effects of imprisonment</li>\r\n<li>Re-offending and risk assessment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(492, 'Module 12 - Psychology and Police Selection, Recruitment and Training', '<p>This module studies the recruitment process involved in the selection of appropriate candidates for the police force. A range of relevant areas are covered such as; police training, personality tests and the police curriculum. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Selection and the police personality</li>\r\n<li>Psychology and police training</li>\r\n<li>Student officer training</li>\r\n<li>Curriculum</li>\r\n<li>The Professional Investigation Programme</li>\r\n<li>Police promotion</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(493, 'Module 13 - Police Stress', '<p>This module explores the relationship between stress and the police force and examines areas of relevance such as factors that contribute to stress and stress research. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining stress</li>\r\n<li>Stress factors</li>\r\n<li>Stress research</li>\r\n<li>Stress in the workplace</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(494, 'Module 14 - The Decision to Assist', '<p>This module assesses the behaviour of individuals in relation their response to witnessing crime in public places. Relevant areas such as the different types of public responses and the behaviour of the authorities, are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The unresponsive bystander</li>\r\n<li>An impulsive bystander</li>\r\n<li>Models for bystander behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour of the authorities</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(495, 'Module 15 - The Research Proposal and the Research Project Report', '<p>This concluding module studies the police practice of completing research proposals and research project reports, focussing specifically on areas such as the purpose of each document and how both should be constructed. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The research proposal</li>\r\n<li>The research project report</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(496, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(497, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(498, 'Self Assignments (Optional)', '<p>These documents are self-assessments which you can use to test and reaffirm your current&nbsp;knowledge, any self-assessments that are completed will not be marked by your tutor. These documents do not add to your grading and have no effect on the overall outcome of the units they refer to.</p>', 0),
(499, 'Self Assignments (Optional)', '<p>These documents are self-assessments which you can use to test and reaffirm your current&nbsp;knowledge, any self-assessments that are completed will not be marked by your tutor. These documents do not add to your grading and have no effect on the overall outcome of the units they refer to.</p>', 0),
(500, 'Module One - An introduction to Profiling Criminals', '<p>This module defines and explores various areas of knowledge that can be applied for the use of profiling criminals. This methodology provides the knowledge base which can be applied to the rest of the course.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Crime Scene Analysis</li>\r\n<li>Serial Murder</li>\r\n<li>Mass Murder</li>\r\n<li>Spree Killing</li>\r\n<li>Investigative Psychology</li>\r\n<li>Narrative of Crime</li>\r\n<li>Difference in Approach</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(501, 'Module Two - Cayetano Santos Godino', '<p>This module covers the first case study of the course which aims to build a criminal profile of serial killer Cayetano Santos Godino, commonly known as &lsquo;The Big Eared Pest&rsquo;, through the critically exploration of his life and traits. Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>The Reform School Graduate</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders committed by Godino, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The Arturo Laurora murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Jesaldo Giordano murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Maria Roca Foce murder</li>\r\n<li>The arrest</li>\r\n<li>A list of Godino&rsquo;s Victims</li>\r\n<li>The Trial</li>\r\n<li>Imprisonment</li>\r\n<li>Medical Reports</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(502, 'Module Three - The Monster of Dusseldorf', '<p>This module covers the case study of serial killer Peter Kurten, commonly known as &lsquo;The Monster of Dusseldorf&rsquo;. The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>A Criminal Career</li>\r\n<li>The Monster Strikes</li>\r\n<li>Flirting with Fire</li>\r\n<li>The Reign of Terror Begins</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders and attempted murders committed by Kurten, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The Rosa Ohlinger Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Maria Hahn Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The attempted murder of Gertrude Schulte</li>\r\n<li>Trial and Conviction</li>\r\n<li>Kurten&rsquo;s Victims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(503, 'Module Four - The Mad Bomber of New York', '<p>This module covers the case study of the serial Bomber George Metesky, commonly known as &lsquo;The Mad Bomber of New York&rsquo;. The content aims to build a criminal profile on the criminal, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>The Bombing Begins</li>\r\n<li>The Truce</li>\r\n<li>The Campaign Proper</li>\r\n<li>The Profile</li>\r\n<li>The Man</li>\r\n<li>The Arrest</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(504, 'Module Five - The Acid Bath Murderer', '<p>This module covers the case study of serial killer John George Haigh, commonly known as &lsquo;The Acid Bath Murderer.&rsquo; The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Nightmare Begins</li>\r\n<li>The Crimes</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders committed by Haigh, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The McSwann Murders</li>\r\n<li>- The Henderson Murders</li>\r\n<li>- The Durand-Deacon Murder</li>\r\n<li>The Forensic Evidence</li>\r\n<li>The Defence</li>\r\n<li>Prison Visits</li>\r\n<li>Psychiatric Evaluation</li>\r\n<li>The Trial</li>\r\n<li>Haigh&rsquo;s Confirmed Victims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(505, 'Module Six - Who was the Boston Strangler?', '<p>This module covers the case study of the serial killer and Rapist Albert De Salvo, commonly known as &lsquo;The Boston Strangler. &rsquo; The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>Warning Signs</li>\r\n<li>The Measuring Man</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders and attempted murders committed by Haigh, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The Anna Slesers Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Helen Blake Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Attempted Murder of Gertrude Gruen</li>\r\n<li>The Green Man</li>\r\n<li>The Arrest</li>\r\n<li>Who was the Strangler?</li>\r\n<li>Victims of the Boston Strangler</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(506, 'Module Seven - The Yorkshire Ripper', '<p>This module covers the case study of serial killer Peter Sutcliffe, commonly known as &lsquo;The Yorkshire Ripper. &rsquo; The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders committed by Sutcliffe, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The Wilma McCann Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Jean Jordan Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Jaqueline Hill Murder</li>\r\n<li>Mapping the Murders</li>\r\n<li>The Arrest</li>\r\n<li>The Trial</li>\r\n<li>The Yorkshire Ripper Murders and Surviving Victims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(507, 'Module Eight - John Wayne Gacy', '<p>This module covers the case study of serial killer John Wayne Gacy. The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>The Warning Signs</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders committed by Gacy, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The Tim McCoy Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Gregory Godzik Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The John Szyc Murder</li>\r\n<li>The Robert Donnelly Abduction</li>\r\n<li>The Disappearance of Robert Piest</li>\r\n<li>The Investigation</li>\r\n<li>The Trial</li>\r\n<li>Known Victims of John Wayne Gacy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(508, 'Module Nine - The Muswell Hill Murderer', '<p>This module covers the case study of serial killer Dennis Nilsen. The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>The Warning Signs</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders and attempted murders committed by Nilson, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The Stephen Dean Holmes Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Attempted Murder of Paul Nobbs</li>\r\n<li>- The John Howlett murder</li>\r\n<li>The Blocked Drain</li>\r\n<li>Conviction</li>\r\n<li>Some of Nilsen&rsquo;s Victims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(509, 'Module Ten - Doctor Death', '<p>This module covers the case study of serial killer Frederick Harold Shipman. The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>The Warning Signs</li>\r\n<li>Early Suspicions</li>\r\n<li>An outline of numerous murders committed by Shipman, including;</li>\r\n<li>- The Kathleen Grundy Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Pamela Hillier Murder</li>\r\n<li>- The Winifred Mellor Murder</li>\r\n<li>Building the Case</li>\r\n<li>The Trial</li>\r\n<li>The Aftermath</li>\r\n<li>List of Shipman&rsquo;s confirmed victims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(510, 'Module Eleven - The Dunblane Massacre', '<p>This module covers the case study of mass murderer Thomas Hamilton. The content aims to build a criminal profile on the killer, through the critical exploration his life and traits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Early Years</li>\r\n<li>The Warning Signs</li>\r\n<li>The Dunblane Massacre</li>\r\n<li>The Aftermath</li>\r\n<li>The Cullen Enquiry</li>\r\n<li>Hamilton&rsquo;s Victims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(511, 'Module Twelve - Conclusion', '<p>This module provides further information on profiling criminals. There is a significant focus on the complexities of profiling process, particularly with regards to the difficulties and the problems that people are likely to face.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered within this module include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Problems with Profiling</li>\r\n<li>Difficulties of Definition</li>\r\n<li>Psychopathy, Violence and Anti-Social Personality Disorder</li>\r\n<li>Geographic Profiling</li>\r\n<li>The British Approach</li>\r\n<li>Differences in Approach</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(512, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(513, 'Module One - The history of reflexology', '<p>This introductory module studies a history of reflexology, looking at who discovered it and how it has progressed through the years. An overview of modern day reflexology is then examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Understanding the history of reflexology</li>\r\n<li>How reflexology is used in modern day</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(514, 'Module Two - Understanding the bodily systems', '<p>This module examines the different bodily systems and studies each one in turn to provide a general overview of how the body works.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Different systems of the body</li>\r\n<li>How bodily systems work</li>\r\n<li>Names and positions of the bones and muscles within the body</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(515, 'Module Three - The principles of reflexology', '<p>This module teaches about the channels, meridians and energy within the body. The content looks at relevant areas such as yin and yang and also studies chakras and the meaning of subtle energy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The 10 energy zones</li>\r\n<li>Meridians within the body</li>\r\n<li>Yin and Yang</li>\r\n<li>Subtle energy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(516, 'Module Four - The benefits of reflexology', '<p>This module considers how reflexology affects the body, the benefits it gives to the recipient and how it can help to reduce stress and create wellbeing.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Stress and how it affects us</li>\r\n<li>Stress reduction</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(517, 'Module Five - The reflex areas for hands and feet', '<p>This module explores how to map the areas of the feet and hands for a reflexology treatment, looking at relevant considerations such as reflex zones.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reflexology zones</li>\r\n<li>Mapping foot and hand to give a reflexology treatment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(518, 'Module Six - Foot relaxation techniques and desserts', '<p>This module is focused on the different types of techniques that are used within&nbsp;reflexology treatment and examines the various steps in which to apply these.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Basic techniques</li>\r\n<li>Foot desserts/ relaxation techniques</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(519, 'Module Seven - Conditions of the feet and contraindications', '<p>This module considers the conditions or problems that you will discover on the client&rsquo;s feet and examines how these should be dealt with.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of problems and conditions that are associated with the feet</li>\r\n<li>Reflexology and specific conditions</li>\r\n<li>Contraindications of performing reflexology</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(520, 'Module Eight - Step by step treatments', '<p>This module is concerned the various actions to take for a treatment and considers the process from greeting the client to the potential after effects of a treatment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Greeting your client</li>\r\n<li>Taking information</li>\r\n<li>Working the feet</li>\r\n<li>Aftercare and the healing crisis</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(521, 'Module Nine - Treatments for specific ailments', '<p>This module studies how to perform treatments for specific illnesses and conditions that a client may be suffering from and looks at which reflex points should be worked on to help relieve symptoms.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of illness that a client can be suffering from</li>\r\n<li>Reflex points</li>\r\n<li>Treatment sessions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(522, 'Module Ten - Professionalism', '<p>This module considers the importance of acting professional within your business and studies relevant considerations, such as; good hygiene, presentation and preparation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preparation for client</li>\r\n<li>Hygiene and personal appearance</li>\r\n<li>Client interaction</li>\r\n<li>Business situations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(523, 'Module Eleven - How to run your own business', '<p>This concluding module provides a step by step guide to starting your own reflexology business and examines how to run it when everything is in place.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Where to run a business from</li>\r\n<li>Treatment room design</li>\r\n<li>Appointment booking and structure</li>\r\n<li>Basic accounts</li>\r\n<li>Business advertising and promotion</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(524, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(525, 'Module One - Special Educational Needs (SEN) Overview', '<p>This first module considers what is meant by the term &lsquo;Special Educational Needs&rsquo; (SEN) and other relevant terms. It provides a brief overview of how Special Educational Needs affects schools and looks particular at areas such as; Ofsted and SEN, the Common Assessment Framework (CAF) and EAL.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining SEN</li>\r\n<li>History of SEN Since the 1944 Education Act, incorporating the changing of Attitudes to SEN</li>\r\n<li>Ofsted and SEN</li>\r\n<li>The Common Assessment Framework (CAF)</li>\r\n<li>SEN Assessment Tools Commonly Used in Mainstream Schools</li>\r\n<li>EAL and SEN</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(526, 'Module Two - SEN Provision in Schools and Policies', '<p>This module studies the SEN Code of Practice (England) and looks at how it impacts on schools and relevant settings, through the examination of areas such as; the Children and Families Act (2014), child protection and the SENCo role.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>New SEN Code of Practice (CoP)</li>\r\n<li>Children and Families Act (2014)</li>\r\n<li>Disability and the Equality Act (2010)</li>\r\n<li>Child Protection &ndash; Safeguarding Children in Education</li>\r\n<li>Special Schools versus Mainstream Schools</li>\r\n<li>SENCo Role</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(527, 'Module Three - SENCo Role and Outside Agencies', '<p>In this module, we shall consider how the role of the SENCo has evolved and how the 2014 Code of Practice will affect the role. We shall look at how the SENCo works with other agencies and look at some of the common agencies that may be involved with schools.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The SENCo Role and Working with Other Agencies</li>\r\n<li>Educational Psychologists</li>\r\n<li>CAMHS (Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services)</li>\r\n<li>Speech and Language Therapy Service</li>\r\n<li>Physiotherapy</li>\r\n<li>Occupational Therapy</li>\r\n<li>Sensory Support Teachers</li>\r\n<li>Inclusion Support Services</li>\r\n<li>Family Liaison Officers (School)</li>\r\n<li>Social Services</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(528, 'Module Four - Some Common SEN Conditions Found in Schools', '<p>This module examines the common traits/symptoms for various SEN conditions and looks to raise awareness of how a diagnosis is made and also how educational settings can work to help children and young people overcome some of the difficulties that they face.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Broad Areas of Need</li>\r\n<li>Communication and Interaction</li>\r\n<li>Cognition and Learning</li>\r\n<li>Social, Emotional and Behavioural Difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Sensory and/or Physical Needs</li>\r\n<li>Other Conditions</li>\r\n<li>Traits Common to All of the Above Difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Case Studies</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(529, 'Module Five - Behaviour', '<p>This module looks to examine the meaning of behaviour and how this relates to SEN in schools. The materials then go on to outline the various ways in which behaviour that could been seen as challenging can be managed by the SENCo.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Challenging Behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Positive Behaviour Reinforcement</li>\r\n<li>Developing Positive Relationships</li>\r\n<li>Transition</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(530, 'Module Six - Inclusive Education', '<p>This concluding module explores the meaning of inclusive education and studies the numerous ways in which this can be achieved, through study of areas such as; inclusive education aims inclusive models and the use of relevant case studies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Inclusive Education in Mainstream Settings</li>\r\n<li>Inclusive education aims</li>\r\n<li>Historical Timeline Leading to Inclusion in Schools in England</li>\r\n<li>Inclusion models</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(531, 'Module One - Introduction to Sports Psychology', '<p>This introductory module aims to provide learners with an overview of the study of psychology in a sporting context. The knowledge contained looks to define this subject area and explores a broad overview of relevant areas such as research methods and design.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining psychology</li>\r\n<li>Ethics</li>\r\n<li>The work of sports psychologists</li>\r\n<li>Research methods</li>\r\n<li>Design</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(532, 'Module Two - Aspects of Sports Personalities', '<p>This module studies the common personality traits of those who participate in sport and how these interlink with their sport and performance. A range of relevant areas are explored, such as; attitudes, traits and behaviour patterns.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Personality measurement</li>\r\n<li>Personality and performance</li>\r\n<li>Attitudes</li>\r\n<li>Nach &amp; Naf</li>\r\n<li>Mood states</li>\r\n<li>Trait</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour patterns</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(533, 'Module Three - Motivation and Goal Setting', '<p>This module looks at the concept of motivation and setting goals in sport. What drives sporting individuals and how they strive towards these aspirations is critically assessed and the knowledge contained studies areas of relevance such as; Intrinsic/ Extrinsic motivation and competition.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Intrinsic/ Extrinsic motivation</li>\r\n<li>Competition and motivation</li>\r\n<li>Goal setting</li>\r\n<li>Theoretical background</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(534, 'Module Four - Stress and Anxiety', '<p>This module explores the link between stress and anxiety in relation to sport. These psychological conditions are explained in a sporting context, through the examination areas such as, arousal levels, causes of stress and how these can impact sporting performance.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Causes of stress</li>\r\n<li>Anxiety measurement and performance</li>\r\n<li>Forms of anxiety</li>\r\n<li>Stress and sporting performance</li>\r\n<li>Anxiety strategies</li>\r\n<li>Theories of stress and anxiety</li>\r\n<li>Stress and anxiety research</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(535, 'Module Five - Relaxation in Sport', '<p>This module is focussed on the state of relaxation and assesses the importance of this action in relation to sport. Numerous areas of importance such as, diversions of the nervous system and relaxation techniques, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Arousal and relaxation</li>\r\n<li>Diversions of the nervous system</li>\r\n<li>Relaxation techniques</li>\r\n<li>Effectiveness of relaxation on sporting performance</li>\r\n<li>Theories of anxiety/ arousal</li>\r\n<li>Research study</li>\r\n<li>Defining anxiety</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(536, 'Module Six - Aggression in Sport', '<p>This module is concerned with the behavioural act of aggression and assesses its presence within individuals participating in sport. The knowledge contained explores pertinent issues such as; types of aggression, aggression measurement and ways of reducing aggression.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Definitions of aggression</li>\r\n<li>Types of aggression</li>\r\n<li>Measuring aggression</li>\r\n<li>Theories of aggression</li>\r\n<li>Participant and spectator aggression in sport</li>\r\n<li>Reducing aggression in sport</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(537, 'Module Seven - Burnout', '<p>This module studies the state of burnout, a condition commonly associated with sport in which the participant feels a state of physical, mental and emotional exhaustion. The knowledge contained explores a number of important issues, such as; what causes burnout and how the condition may affect sporting performance.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining burnout</li>\r\n<li>Causes of burnout</li>\r\n<li>Burnout and psychological theories</li>\r\n<li>Burnout and psychological research</li>\r\n<li>Burnout implications for psychology and sport</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(538, 'Module Eight - Hypnosis in Sport', '<p>This module focusses on the practice of hypnosis and studies how this can be applied to achieve particular mental states in order to influence behaviour within a sporting environment. The knowledge contained critiques this technique and looks at relevant areas such as; the phases on hypnosis and psychological research.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining hypnosis</li>\r\n<li>The phases of hypnosis</li>\r\n<li>Hypnosis and psychological theories</li>\r\n<li>Hypnosis and psychological research</li>\r\n<li>Hypnosis implications for psychology and sport</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(539, 'Module Nine - Imagery in Sport', '<p>This module details the process of applying imagery to a sporting environment to help enhance performance. The knowledge contained looks at numerous areas such as; mental practice and developing imagery skills.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining imagery in sport</li>\r\n<li>Mental practice</li>\r\n<li>Measuring and explaining imagery</li>\r\n<li>Effectiveness of imagery in sport</li>\r\n<li>Developing imagery skills</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(540, 'Module Ten - Positive and Negative Thinking in Sport', '<p>This concluding module looks broadly at the process of positive and negative thinking and assesses its significance in relation to sporting performance. The knowledge contained examines relevant areas such as; theories of positive and negative thinking and the impact of having self-confidence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Definition of positive and negative thinking</li>\r\n<li>Different views on what constitutes positive and negative thinking</li>\r\n<li>Psychological theories connected with positive and negative thinking</li>\r\n<li>Psychological research findings on self-confidence, self-efficacy and positive and negative self-talk</li>\r\n<li>Positive and negative thinking: Self-confidence, self-efficacy and positive and negative self-talk</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(541, 'Module One - Understanding Drug Use; Facts, Effects, Symptoms and Attitudes', '<p>This unit allows you to develop an understanding of a range of substances that may be misused. This unit will require learners to demonstrate an awareness of the effects, signs and symptoms of a range of substances.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Facts and paraphernalia associated with substances</li>\r\n<li>Signs and effects of substances</li>\r\n<li>Attitudes and values relating to drug use</li>\r\n<li>Sources of information on drug use</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(542, 'Module Two - Understanding Response to Substance Misuse: Legislation, Harm Reduction and Interventions', '<p>This unit allows you to study legislation and government policies related to substance misuse. Learners will also be required to demonstrate effective responses in emergency situations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation relating to substance misuse</li>\r\n<li>Methods of correctly responding to drug use</li>\r\n<li>Harm reduction and drug strategies</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(543, 'Module Three - Understanding Alcohol and Drug Use in Young People', '<p>In this unit, you will be studying a range of effects associated with alcohol and drug use, particularly in young people. Attitudes towards substance use and factors that influence substance misuse will also be studied within this unit.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The effects of alcohol misuse on the physical, emotional and psychological health of young people</li>\r\n<li>The potential social and family problems associated with drugs and alcohol consumption in young people</li>\r\n<li>Sources of and the importance of alcohol and drugs education for young people</li>\r\n<li>Attitudes held by young people about drugs and alcohol</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(544, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(545, 'Module One - Understand diabetes', '<p>The aim of this unit is to allow the learner to have an understanding of the two types of diabetes, how the body is affected by the illness and what can cause diabetes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The function of glucose in the blood</li>\r\n<li>The function of insulin in the blood</li>\r\n<li>Understanding diabetes</li>\r\n<li>The risk factors of developing type 2 diabetes</li>\r\n<li>How diabetes is confirmed</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(546, 'Module Two - Prevention and early intervention of Type 2 Diabetes', '<p>The unit looks at how to delay the onset of diabetes and to give an understanding of how diet and lifestyle affects diabetes and how it can be controlled.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Delay the onset</li>\r\n<li>The importance of a balanced diet with type 2 diabetes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(547, 'Module Three - Understand the initial care of diabetes', '<p>This unit studies the various ways in which to detect certain problems with the diabetic client. It also teaches how to manage diabetes with lifestyle and medication.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The social impact of diabetes</li>\r\n<li>Working with individuals to manage diabetes</li>\r\n<li>How diabetes is monitored</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(548, 'Module Four - Understand the treatment and management of diabetes', '<p>This unit instructs the learner about the management of diabetes and how to understand what treatments are offered to the clients if they have any of the complications associated with the condition.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How diabetes is treated</li>\r\n<li>Hypoglycaemia (low blood glucose)</li>\r\n<li>Hyperglycaemia (high blood glucose)</li>\r\n<li>Diabetes complications</li>\r\n<li>Complications associated with diabetes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(549, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(550, 'Module One - Understand Children’s and Young People’s Development', '<p>This introductory unit provides a thorough insight into the development of children and young people, exploring numerous avenues such typical child development, factors affecting this and responding to developmental problems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Expected child development from birth-19 years</li>\r\n<li>Factors affecting child development</li>\r\n<li>Monitoring child development</li>\r\n<li>Early intervention</li>\r\n<li>Possible transition effects</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(551, 'Module Two - Understand How to Safeguard the Wellbeing of Children and Young People', '<p>This unit details the potential issues that can impact on a child and young person&rsquo;s wellbeing, covering issues such as child abuse and bullying and also provides guidance on how to safeguard against these problems in line with relevant legislation, guidelines, polices and procedures.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation, guidelines, policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>Working in partnership with organisations</li>\r\n<li>Children and young people&rsquo;s safety and protection in the work setting</li>\r\n<li>Child Protection and Safeguarding</li>\r\n<li>Child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Bullying</li>\r\n<li>Supporting child safety and well-being</li>\r\n<li>E-safety</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(552, 'Module Three - Support Children and Young People\'s Health and Safety', '<p>This unit is focussed on delivering knowledge on how to support the maintenance of children and young people&rsquo;s health and safety in a school environment, exploring areas such as identifying and reducing risks and responding to emergencies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Safe environments</li>\r\n<li>Risks</li>\r\n<li>Accidents, emergencies and illness in work settings</li>\r\n<li>Risk Assessments</li>\r\n<li>Legislation, guidelines, policies and procedure</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(553, 'Module Four - Engage in Personal Development in Health, Social Care, or Children and Young People\'s Settings', '<p>This unit details the importance keeping up to date with current practices and ensuring you are aware of any new initiatives taking place in the educational sector, exploring areas such as work reflection and identifying learning opportunities.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Work role competence</li>\r\n<li>Reflection</li>\r\n<li>Evaluating performance</li>\r\n<li>Personal development plan</li>\r\n<li>Learning opportunities</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(554, 'Module Five - Support Learning Activities', '<p>This unit looks at all the methods that need to be implemented and evaluated in order to effectively support learning activities in an educational setting, focussing on key areas such as statutory and non-statutory frameworks.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning learning activities</li>\r\n<li>Preparing learning activities</li>\r\n<li>Supporting learning activities</li>\r\n<li>Learner participation and progress</li>\r\n<li>Evaluation of learning activities</li>\r\n<li>Supporting literacy, numeracy and ICT</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(555, 'Module Six - Promote Children and Young People\'s Positive Behaviour', '<p>This unit explores the link between children and young people&rsquo;s behaviour and aims to instil an understanding of the different reasons for displayed behaviours and how this understanding can be used to promote, manage and respond to them, following appropriate procedures.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>Promoting positive child behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Managing inappropriate behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Responding to challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour and behaviour policy reviews</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(556, 'Module Seven - Develop Professional Relationships with Children, Young People, and Adults', '<p>This unit explains the steps that should be taken in order to develop professional relationships with different people in an educational setting and provides specific guidance on sharing relevant information with both young people and adults.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Professional relationships with children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Communicating with children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Professional relationships with adults, including parents and outside agencies</li>\r\n<li>Supporting children and young people in developing relationships</li>\r\n<li>Policies and procedures for confidentiality, sharing information and data protection</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(557, 'Module Eight - Promote Equality, Diversity, and Inclusion in Work with Children and Young People', '<p>This unit examines issues surrounding equality, diversity and inclusion of children and young people within an educational setting. You will be equipped with information on areas such as relevant laws and the impact of prejudice and discrimination.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Promoting equality and diversity in work with children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Impact of prejudice and discrimination on children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Inclusion and inclusive practices</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(558, 'Unit Nine - Support Assessment for Learning', '<p>This unit centres on the usage of appropriate frameworks in order to support the assessment of children and young people&rsquo;s learning in an education setting, focussing on areas such as assessment strategies and reviewing assessment for learning.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Purpose and characteristics of assessment for learning</li>\r\n<li>Assessment strategies</li>\r\n<li>Reviewing strategies and achievements</li>\r\n<li>Reviewing assessment for learning</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(559, 'Module Ten - Communication and Professional Relationships with Children, Young People, and Adults', '<p>This unit centres on the usage of appropriate frameworks in order to support the assessment of children and young people&rsquo;s learning in an education setting, focussing on areas such as assessment strategies and reviewing assessment for learning.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Purpose and characteristics of assessment for learning</li>\r\n<li>Assessment strategies</li>\r\n<li>Reviewing strategies and achievements</li>\r\n<li>Reviewing assessment for learning</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(560, 'Module Eleven - Schools as Organisations', '<p>This unit explores how schools are established as organisations and focusses on relevant areas such as the varying structures, different ways of doing things and applicable roles and responsibilities.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Education structure</li>\r\n<li>Roles and responsibilities in schools</li>\r\n<li>School ethos, mission, aims and values</li>\r\n<li>School legislation</li>\r\n<li>School policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>School operations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(561, 'Module One - Information, advice or guidance in practice', '<p>This introductory unit looks at the action of providing information, advice or guidance to satisfy the requirements of different clients and studies relevant considerations, such as; client type, job boundaries and client records.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Differences between information, advice and guidance</li>\r\n<li>Meeting the information, advice or guidance requirements of clients</li>\r\n<li>Boundaries of your job role when meeting the needs of clients</li>\r\n<li>Keeping client records</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(562, 'Module Two - Developing interaction skills for information, advice or guidance', '<p>This unit studies the importance of developing suitable interaction skills in order to provide effective advice to clients. The materials are predominantly concerned with the use of communication and also consider areas such as; promises, confidentiality and impartiality.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Client interaction</li>\r\n<li>Keeping promises</li>\r\n<li>Communication skills</li>\r\n<li>Values, beliefs and attitudes</li>\r\n<li>Confidentiality</li>\r\n<li>Impartiality</li>\r\n<li>Skills and development needs</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(563, 'Module Three - Signposting and referral in information, advice or guidance', '<p>This unit is concerned with the process which takes place in a situation when an organisation is unable to provide a client with the appropriate information, advice or guidance that they require.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Differences between signposting and referral</li>\r\n<li>Benefits of signposting and referral</li>\r\n<li>When to signpost and refer</li>\r\n<li>How to signpost and refer</li>\r\n<li>Monitoring and evaluating client referrals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(564, 'Module Seven - Managing information', '<p>This unit looks at the process of managing information that may be required by clients. The materials examine how to ensure information is stored and made available when needed, in line with legal requirements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Resources available to clients</li>\r\n<li>Importance of storing and retrieving information</li>\r\n<li>Information systems and their main features</li>\r\n<li>Legal and organisational requirements</li>\r\n<li>Methods used to store and retrieve information</li>\r\n<li>Updating and maintaining information</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(565, 'Module Fourteen - Operating within networks to support information, advice or guidance', '<p>This concluding unit studies the method of working alongside other organisations, known as networks, in order to satisfy client requirements and achieve common goals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of networks</li>\r\n<li>Our organisations as a network</li>\r\n<li>Networks operating within codes of practice and principles</li>\r\n<li>Roles within networks</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining and evaluating own role within a network</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(566, 'Module One - Mental health and mental health issues', '<p>This unit introduces the concept of mental health and provides an overview of the different types of mental health related issues and also relevant legislative considerations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The concept of mental health</li>\r\n<li>Common types of mental health problems and illnesses</li>\r\n<li>The legislation and guidance that applies to those with mental health problems</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(567, 'Module Two - Introduction to duty of care in health, social care or children’s and young people’s settings', '<p>This unit is concerned with the responsibilities of an individual to provide suitable care for those with mental health problems, in their care.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Implications of duty of care</li>\r\n<li>Support available for addressing dilemmas that may arise about duty of care</li>\r\n<li>How to respond to complaints</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(568, 'Module Three - Valuing equality and diversity', '<p>This unit studies the important task of abiding to appropriate values regarding the equal treatment of those with mental health issues and ensuring their differences are embraced.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Aspects of equality</li>\r\n<li>Aspects of diversity</li>\r\n<li>Aspects of discrimination</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(569, 'Module Four - Approaches to care and management in mental health', '<p>This unit is focussed on the suitable approaches which should be taken in order to ensure those with mental health issues are cared for in the most effective way for them.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The key features of the care planning process</li>\r\n<li>Aspects of good practice in the care planning process</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(570, 'Module Five - Understanding change and support in relation to mental health', '<p>This unit considers how the needs of an individual with a mental health issue can change and the materials examine how this can planned for and managed when they occur.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How mental health change occurs</li>\r\n<li>The role of others in the individual&rsquo;s mental health change</li>\r\n<li>The treatment options available to manage mental health problems</li>\r\n<li>How to access information to support understanding of mental health issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(571, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(572, 'Module One - Equality and diversity in society', '<p>This introductory unit aims to establish some of the key definitions and concepts associated with equality and diversity in society and looks at relevant considerations, such as; stereotyping, prejudice and discrimination.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What equality is</li>\r\n<li>What diversity is</li>\r\n<li>The effects of stereotyping and labelling within society</li>\r\n<li>The effects of prejudice and discrimination within society</li>\r\n<li>The ways in which people might choose to describe themselves</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(573, 'Module Two - Equality and diversity in the community', '<p>This unit allows you to apply understanding of equality and diversity to your own community, and to do some investigative work to discover the nature and extent of diversity around you.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The extent of the diversity within a community</li>\r\n<li>The value to communities in creating and maintaining a diverse environment</li>\r\n<li>The potential inequality that can occur within a community</li>\r\n<li>Support services and groups</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(574, 'Module Three - Equality and diversity in the workplace', '<p>This unit looks at how the knowledge gained from previous modules can be applied with a work environment and looks at relevant consideration, such as; monitoring and protection of rights.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The meaning of equality and diversity in the workplace</li>\r\n<li>How equality and diversity is monitored in the workplace</li>\r\n<li>How the rights of individuals are protected in the workplace</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(575, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(576, 'Module One - Understanding Roles, Responsibilities and Relationships in Education and Training', '<p>This unit will help you understand your own role, responsibilities and boundaries in relation to working with learners. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Teaching roles and responsibilities in education and training</li>\r\n<li>Ways to maintain a safe and supportive learning environment</li>\r\n<li>The relationships between teachers and other professionals in education and training</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(577, 'Module Two - Understanding and Using Inclusive Teaching and Learning Approaches in Education and Training', '<p>This unit describes the features of inclusive teaching and learning and compares the strengths and limitations of teaching and learning approaches in relation to meeting individual learner needs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Features of inclusive teaching and learning</li>\r\n<li>Teaching and learning approaches</li>\r\n<li>Assessment methods</li>\r\n<li>Engaging and motivating learners</li>\r\n<li>Ground rules with learners</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(578, 'Module Three - Session Planning and Micro Teach Skills', '<p>This unit will help prepare you to demonstrate good practice in session planning skills and prepare you to deliver a successful micro teach session.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How to devise an inclusive teaching and learning plan</li>\r\n<li>Teaching and learning approaches, resources and assessment methods</li>\r\n<li>Learner feedback and communication</li>\r\n<li>Delivery assessment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(579, 'Module Four - Understanding assessment in education and training', '<p>This unit will help you to understand the use of assessment in education and training, the importance of giving effective feedback and keeping robust records of assessment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of assessment</li>\r\n<li>Strengths and limitations of assessment methods</li>\r\n<li>Involving others in the assessment process</li>\r\n<li>Learner feedback</li>\r\n<li>Record keeping</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(580, 'Module 1 - Creative Writing and You', '<p>This introductory module begins to explore the relationship between creative writing and individuals. The knowledge contained looks at pertinent areas of relevance such as; why people choose to write, their experiences of writing and what types of text people write. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reasons for writing</li>\r\n<li>First experience of writing</li>\r\n<li>Experience of writing</li>\r\n<li>What you write</li>\r\n<li>When and where you write</li>\r\n<li>The course and your aims</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(581, 'Module 2 - Exploring Different Texts and Genres', '<p>This module explores the range of different types of texts and genres that currently exist in the field of creative writing and examines areas of relevance, such as; defining different genres, sub-genres and critical analysis. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Creative writing genres</li>\r\n<li>Sub-genres</li>\r\n<li>Creative writing conflict</li>\r\n<li>Critical analysis</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(582, 'Module 3 - Starting to Write', '<p>This module is focussed on the initial practice of putting pen to paper for the first time to write your text, exploring useful techniques such as; writing style, creating characters and writers block. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Writing in the first, second and third person</li>\r\n<li>Writers block</li>\r\n<li>Writing style</li>\r\n<li>Dialogue</li>\r\n<li>Creating a believable character</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(583, 'Module 4 - The Short Story', '<p>This module focusses specifically on the form of concise fictional prose known as the short story, and examines multiple areas of relevance such as; its structure and techniques on how to write this style of text. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The short story genre</li>\r\n<li>Elements of the short story</li>\r\n<li>How to write a short story</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(584, 'Module 5 - Poetry', '<p>This module is concerned with the unique type of imaginative writing laid out in lines, known as poetry. In order to aid learner understanding of this writing style, the knowledge contained examines areas of relevance, such as; rhyming, different poem forms and free verse. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining poetry</li>\r\n<li>Rhyming verse</li>\r\n<li>Free verse</li>\r\n<li>Different poem forms</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(585, 'Module 6 - Writing for Radio', '<p>Having looked specifically at the printed word thus far, this module now looks at behind the scenes writing; focussing on the writing required for radio. The knowledge contained looks at areas such as; what skills are required, writing short stories for radio and radio feature structure. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Radio writing skills</li>\r\n<li>Writing a short story for radio</li>\r\n<li>Writing radio poems</li>\r\n<li>Radio feature structure</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(586, 'Module 7 - The Novel', '<p>This module studies the well-known text type of the invented story known as a novel and explores the production of this creative endeavour though the study of relevant areas, such as; novel writing skills, location and plotting the novel. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Skills needed for novel writing</li>\r\n<li>Novel history</li>\r\n<li>Novel location</li>\r\n<li>Plotting the novel</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(587, 'Module 8 - Life Writing', '<p>This module shifts focus from the study of fictional texts to the non-fictional process of writing about one&rsquo;s life. The knowledge contained details techniques on how to write in this manner and explores areas of relevance, such as: the life writing genre and plotting a biography. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The life writing genre</li>\r\n<li>The sub-genre of the biography</li>\r\n<li>Plotting a biography</li>\r\n<li>Writing a biography</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(588, 'Module 9 - Writing for Children', '<p>The study of this module is writing for children. The module challenges the common belief that writing for young people is easy and examines the process of applying this specialised writing technique, though the study of areas such as; myths, age and story writing. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Myths</li>\r\n<li>History</li>\r\n<li>The genre</li>\r\n<li>The age</li>\r\n<li>Poems</li>\r\n<li>Story writing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(589, 'Module 10 - Non-fiction Writing', '<p>This module explores the practice of writing on the basis of fact, known as non-fiction and focusses specifically on the practice of journalism, through the examination of areas such as; non-fiction requirements, research and interviews. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Non-fiction writing requirements</li>\r\n<li>Journalism</li>\r\n<li>Writing news stories</li>\r\n<li>Research</li>\r\n<li>Interviews</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(590, 'Module 11 - Scriptwriting', '<p>This module is concerned with the loose working document which enables a cast of actors to perform for an audience, known as a script. In order to aid learner understanding of this unique type of writing, areas such as; the history of drama, scriptwriting skills and script layouts are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The history of drama</li>\r\n<li>Scriptwriting skills</li>\r\n<li>Script layouts</li>\r\n<li>Writing a script</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(591, 'Module 12 - The Editing Process', '<p>Having focussed solely on the actual writing of your text, this module now examines the practise of revising and amending your text, an important process known as editing. Learners are given guidance on efficient practice, through the study of areas such as; editing considerations, types of editing and legal reasons for editing. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The editing process</li>\r\n<li>Editing considerations</li>\r\n<li>Legal reasons for editing</li>\r\n<li>Types of editing</li>\r\n<li>What should be cut out?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(592, 'Module 13 - Getting Published', '<p>Given that previous modules have covered the writing process, this module now looks at the part that comes after; the task of seeing work through to print. The knowledge contained looks at the difficulty of getting published and provides guidance on success with this process, through the study of areas such as; planning, marketing your work and types of publishing. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of publishing</li>\r\n<li>Preparing manuscripts</li>\r\n<li>Marketing your work</li>\r\n<li>Planning</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(593, 'Module 14 - Being a Writer', '<p>This concluding module ties up all the previous knowledge gained from the course and examines what it means to be a writer when all the necessary skills have been acquired. The content looks at relevant areas such as; how to keep motivated, sticking to a writing calendar and seeking support for writing. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Motivation</li>\r\n<li>Practising your writing skills</li>\r\n<li>Planning your writing calendar</li>\r\n<li>Support for writers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(594, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email <a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(595, 'Module One - Introduction – what is media?', '<p>This course is concerned with the mass and varied communications industry that is the media. The materials explore a range of sectors that make up the media industry, focussing on the role of platforms such as; the news, advertising and film and examines how such areas affect us as consumers.</p>', 1),
(596, 'Module Two - Advertising', '<p>This module focusses specifically on the media platform of advertising. Essentially advertising is the art of producing a text and showing this to the public with the aim of encouraging them to buy a product. The materials assess this methodology, examining different techniques and how they are designed to influence the consumer.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Criticism of advertising</li>\r\n<li>Audience theories</li>\r\n<li>Charity campaigning &ndash; introduction</li>\r\n<li>Shock campaigns</li>\r\n<li>Covert advertising &amp; marketing</li>\r\n<li>Celebrity endorsement</li>\r\n<li>Viral marketing</li>\r\n<li>Guerrilla marketing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(597, 'Module Three - Broadcast TV', '<p>This module studies the prevalence of arguably the most influential media form, television. The materials look at the most popular TV genres and apply some media theory to the texts as well as applying the key concepts.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Background on institutions</li>\r\n<li>Sitcoms</li>\r\n<li>Intertextuality</li>\r\n<li>Soaps</li>\r\n<li>Case study: Spooks - the appeal of the spy series</li>\r\n<li>My Mad Fat Diary</li>\r\n<li>Top Gear</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(598, 'Module Four - Film', '<p>This module explores the media art form of film and looks in detail at how these productions are constructed for audience consumption, focussing on relevant considerations, such as; narrative, binary oppositions and post modernism.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Narrative</li>\r\n<li>Media texts</li>\r\n<li>The cause and effect chain</li>\r\n<li>Plot and story in practice</li>\r\n<li>Comprehending time</li>\r\n<li>Binary oppositions</li>\r\n<li>The Field theory Plot Structure</li>\r\n<li>Goal-oriented plots</li>\r\n<li>Hollywood versus British films</li>\r\n<li>Independent films</li>\r\n<li>Post modernism</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(599, ' Module Five - Practical production piece', '<p>This module differs somewhat to previous modules in that it gives you the opportunity to apply the skills you have already learned. You will be required to produce a practical piece of either a short video or 3 different print media texts, and the information in the text will provide you with guidance on how to do so.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Key concepts</li>\r\n<li>Finished product</li>\r\n<li>Evaluation</li>\r\n<li>Planning and pre-production</li>\r\n<li>Audience research</li>\r\n<li>Brief</li>\r\n<li>Pre-production</li>\r\n<li>Additional notes to help</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>:</p>', 1),
(600, 'Module Six - Representation - a theoretical perspective', '<p>This module explores the concept of representation within a media text. Simply put representation is concerned with how something is being portrayed and this module examines a range of media texts to determine how particular places and people etc. are presented to a target audience.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Representation of London and the British people</li>\r\n<li>The Western media and the representations of African conflicts</li>\r\n<li>Kidulthood, 2007, Menhaj Huda, and a history of teenage portrayal</li>\r\n<li>Case study on the representation of the working class focusing on &lsquo;This is England&rsquo;, Meadows, 2007</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(601, 'Module Seven - Genre - an institutional and theoretical perspective', '<p>This module assesses the method of classifying media texts, known as genre. The materials explore the various different types of genres available and examines typical traits which constitute a particular genre.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hybrids</li>\r\n<li>How do genres adapt to changing social economic and political contexts?</li>\r\n<li>In what ways does this film &lsquo;Children of Men&rsquo; 2006 reflect social concerns and ideologies of today?</li>\r\n<li>Horror case study with a focus on The Descent, Neil Marshall 2005</li>\r\n<li>In the beginning</li>\r\n<li>The horror scenes</li>\r\n<li>The alternative ending</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(602, 'Module Eight - News', '<p>This module studies the important media form that is news. News organisations are responsible for communicating world events regarded as being in the public interest, to the public and does so via platforms such as; newspapers, broadcast TV and online. The materials examine this process and looks at how the news influences public perceptions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Newspapers</li>\r\n<li>Broadsheet versus tabloid</li>\r\n<li>News institutions</li>\r\n<li>The newsroom</li>\r\n<li>An industrial process</li>\r\n<li>Galtung and Ruge&rsquo;s News Values</li>\r\n<li>Moral panics</li>\r\n<li>Media violence</li>\r\n<li>Karl Marx and the ownership of the news</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(603, 'Module Nine - New Media', '<p>This module is solely concerned with the virtual world that is the new media. The materials look specifically at the prevalence of (relatively) new and emerging media technologies such as; YouTube, tablets and social networking and assesses the significant impact these are having on the media industry.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The internet</li>\r\n<li>Impact of new media</li>\r\n<li>YouTube</li>\r\n<li>The entertainment industry and the &copy;opyright</li>\r\n<li>Social networking</li>\r\n<li>Privacy</li>\r\n<li>iphone and the smart phone</li>\r\n<li>Tablets</li>\r\n<li>Games</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(604, 'Module Ten - Extended essay', '<p>For this concluding module you will either pull together everything you have learnt so far and apply your learning to an essay question of your choice, or you can undertake another piece of practical coursework. The materials look to provide valuable advice on completing this final assignment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Essay stages</li>\r\n<li>Preparing to begin</li>\r\n<li>Suggested topics</li>\r\n<li>10 steps to a top-flight essay</li>\r\n<li>Conducting independent research</li>\r\n<li>Evaluating your research</li>\r\n<li>The seven sins of flawed research</li>\r\n<li>Citing</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(605, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(606, 'Module One - The Key Features of Child Development and Developmental Needs of Children 0-8 Years, Inclusive of Individual and Special Needs', '<p>This introductory module studies the process of initial child development and how this differs between those with special needs and those without, though the examination of relevant areas such as; special needs, transitions and the effects of discrimination.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The main development of a child from birth to 19 Years</li>\r\n<li>The social, economic, and environmental factors affecting development</li>\r\n<li>Genetic and hereditary factors affecting development</li>\r\n<li>Children&rsquo;s overall developmental needs</li>\r\n<li>Special Needs</li>\r\n<li>Transitions</li>\r\n<li>Policies to meet diversity within the work-based environment</li>\r\n<li>Inclusion within the Work-Based Environment</li>\r\n<li>Effects of Discrimination</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(607, 'Module Two - Providing for Children’s Physical Needs, Inclusive of Health and Safety', '<p>This module is concerned with the importance of meeting a child&rsquo;s physical needs such as nutrition and rest and also ensuring that their health and safety is maintained. The knowledge contained examines ways in which these requirements should be achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Meeting the children&rsquo;s nutritional needs</li>\r\n<li>Meeting children&rsquo;s rest and sleep needs</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour in children</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour attributed to specific special needs</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining appropriate hygiene procedures</li>\r\n<li>Childhood illnesses</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining a safe and secure environment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(608, 'Module Three - Learning through Play for Child Development', '<p>This module focusses on the practise of play, examining how its various types have a great importance in the process of child development and the knowledge contained provides advice on how appropriate play should be promoted and organised.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of play and their importance in relation to child development</li>\r\n<li>Observation and planning</li>\r\n<li>Every Child Matters and the Birth to Three Matters Framework</li>\r\n<li>The Early Years Foundation Stage</li>\r\n<li>Available resources in relation to Health and Safety, and Diversity and Inclusion</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(609, 'Module Four - Safeguarding and Promoting the Welfare of Children', '<p>This module studies the sensitive subject area of child abuse and examines the role of the nursery nurse in relation to having an awareness of when this may be happening to any child in their care and what to do in these instances.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is safeguarding?</li>\r\n<li>Definitions of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>The main categories of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Signs and symptoms of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Procedures to follow in the case of child protection concerns</li>\r\n<li>Documentation</li>\r\n<li>Sources of support</li>\r\n<li>Some practical guidance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(610, 'Module Five - Legal Responsibilities of the Nursery Nurse and Responsibilities for Working Together', '<p>This concluding module focusses on the legal responsibilities mandatory to those looking after children and details specific guidance on complying with areas such as; OFSTED requirements and following procedures for admission and collection.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Nursery nurse legislation</li>\r\n<li>Legal responsibilities of the nursery nurse</li>\r\n<li>Procedures for admission and collection</li>\r\n<li>Legal implications of nursery nursing</li>\r\n<li>Policies and procedures to meet OFSTED requirements</li>\r\n<li>Working in partnership with parents and other professionals</li>\r\n<li>The nursery nurse responsibilities for building positive relationships with parents and other professionals</li>\r\n<li>Exploring contacts for support for work-based services</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(611, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(612, 'Module One - Why am I overweight?', '<p>This introductory module explores some of the possible reasons why individuals may be overweight and considers issues such as; barriers to healthy eating, abnormal eating habits and the connection between food and feelings.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The differences between normal weight, overweight and obesity</li>\r\n<li>The health risks associated with obesity</li>\r\n<li>Reasons for weight gain</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to healthy eating</li>\r\n<li>The connection between food and feelings</li>\r\n<li>Why abnormal eating habits develop</li>\r\n<li>Help and information available for sufferers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(613, 'Module Two - What should my weight be?', '<p>This module considers what is classified as a healthy weight for individuals and examines the various ways of establishing this information and then monitoring it.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Body Mass index (BMI)</li>\r\n<li>The limitations of the bathroom scale</li>\r\n<li>What type of user are you?</li>\r\n<li>Other forms of weight monitoring</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(614, 'Module Three - The reasons for losing weight', '<p>This module is concerned with what motivates individuals to lose weight and examines considerations, such as; body shapes, body image and the connection between how we are feeling and what we eat.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Different types of body shapes</li>\r\n<li>How our body image affects the way we feel and look at others</li>\r\n<li>Health risks associated with weight gain</li>\r\n<li>The connection between how we are feeling and what we eat</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(615, 'Module Four - Different diet types', '<p>This module is concerned with the various types of diets available and examines the specific benefits and pitfalls associated with different options in order to instil you with the knowledge on choosing what is best for your client&rsquo;s needs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of diets</li>\r\n<li>Glycemic index diet</li>\r\n<li>Calorie counting</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(616, 'Module Five - Nutritional composition', '<p>This module studies the finer details about food, looking at how they are made up and what they contain. This aims to provide a better understanding of how to plan a healthy, balanced diet.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What particular foods are made up of and what they contain</li>\r\n<li>The differences between foods and how they are broken down by the body</li>\r\n<li>How to lose weight whilst still feeling full after eating</li>\r\n<li>Foods that make you feel lethargic and want more</li>\r\n<li>Government guidelines in relation to the consumption of vitamins and minerals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(617, 'Module Six - The Food Pyramid', '<p>This module examines the weight management tool which was created to give us an indication of what foods we should have in our diets and the amount of servings we should have per day.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purpose of the food pyramid</li>\r\n<li>The \'5-a-day\' rule</li>\r\n<li>Types of fruit and vegetable and the seasons in which they are at their best</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(618, 'Module Seven - Additives, preservatives and E numbers', '<p>This module looks at the prevalence of additional substances that are added to food, known as additives, preservatives and E numbers. The materials look at how they have no nutritional value and provides guidance on how to manage a healthy diet around foods that contain these.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Food additives</li>\r\n<li>E numbers</li>\r\n<li>Flavour enhancers</li>\r\n<li>Use-by dates</li>\r\n<li>How to read food labels</li>\r\n<li>Nutritional information</li>\r\n<li>Ingredients</li>\r\n<li>Food allergies and intolerances</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(619, 'Module Eight - Fats, salts and sugars', '<p>This module is focussed on the occurrence of fat, salt and sugars within food and examines their prevalence before considering ways in which these can be reduced in order to aid a healthy lifestyle.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of sugars that we eat and the range of names that they go by</li>\r\n<li>Types of fat that we consume</li>\r\n<li>How to reduce the number of bad fats in our diet</li>\r\n<li>How to increase the good, healthy fats which have many health benefits</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(620, 'Module Nine - Vitamins and minerals', '<p>This module teaches about the nutrients in food known as vitamins and minerals and details what food contains what, what different nutrients do and how they affect the body.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Naturally occurring vitamins and what they do</li>\r\n<li>Trace minerals and Macrominerals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(621, 'Module Ten - Portion sizes', '<p>This module looks at the task of organising recommended portion sizes when preparing food and considers how this will help you to maintain a healthy lifestyle.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How we do not always realise that we are eating more than needed</li>\r\n<li>How to cut down on portion sizes without feeling as though you are being deprived of the foods that you enjoy</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(622, 'Module Eleven - Planning your diet programme', '<p>This module studies the process of arranging a suitable diet that best suits your weight management goals and looks at considerations such as; lunch, snacks and vegetarian diets.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Breakfasts</li>\r\n<li>Lunch</li>\r\n<li>Dinners</li>\r\n<li>Snacks</li>\r\n<li>Daily serving recommendations</li>\r\n<li>Vegetarian diets</li>\r\n<li>Vegan diets</li>\r\n<li>Hitting a plateau</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(623, 'Module Twelve - Home cooking or eating out', '<p>This module studies the suitable cooking methods you can use to help reduce the amount of fat in your diet and also looks at how to choose the healthiest options when eating out.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Cooking methods</li>\r\n<li>Healthy food preparation for fruit and vegetables</li>\r\n<li>Healthy food preparation for bread, breakfast cereals, potatoes, rice and pasta</li>\r\n<li>Healthy food preparation for meat, fish and alternatives</li>\r\n<li>Healthy food preparation for milk and dairy foods</li>\r\n<li>Healthy food preparation for foods containing fats and foods containing sugars</li>\r\n<li>Dining in with others</li>\r\n<li>Choices we make when eating out</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(624, 'Module Thirteen - Daily records and charts', '<p>This module is concerned with the various tools which are used to help track your weight management progress and studies methods such as; using a food diary and keeping weight loss charts.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Food diary</li>\r\n<li>Weight loss charts</li>\r\n<li>Measurements</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(625, 'Module Fourteen - The importance of fitness', '<p>This module moves away from the specific focus on food and considers the other major factor in weight management, which is exercise. The materials examines the importance partaking in activity; looking at the benefits that can be sought and considers the various types of exercises that individuals can do.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The benefits of exercise</li>\r\n<li>Why we need to exercise</li>\r\n<li>Aerobic exercise</li>\r\n<li>Exercising with others</li>\r\n<li>Exercise in the office</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(626, 'Module Fifteen - Keeping the weight off', '<p>As previous modules have mainly been concerned with methods for losing weight, the concluding module considers various techniques which should help you to maintain a healthy weight on a long term basis.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eating slowly</li>\r\n<li>Limit sugary drinks</li>\r\n<li>Eat more fruit</li>\r\n<li>Eat little and often to burn more weight</li>\r\n<li>Increase your activity levels</li>\r\n<li>Keep your blood sugar levels steady</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t eat out of habit</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(627, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(628, 'Module One - Legislation and guidance', '<p>This module introduces the learner to the UK legislation and guidance that exists to protect everyone involved in medications in schools and the materials cover important considerations, such as; the legal duties, responsibilities and roles required of those involved in medical care in schools and the possible consequences of not following the relevant legislation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Key points of current legislation and guidance relating to medication</li>\r\n<li>Key points of current legislation and guidance relating to keeping safe at work</li>\r\n<li>Legal duties, roles and responsibilities of all involved in medical care in schools</li>\r\n<li>Possible consequences of not following relevant legislation and guidance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(629, 'Module Two - Medical conditions and medications', '<p>This module considers the diverse range of medical conditions that children could have that may require assistance in the school setting and examines the range of treatment options which should be used to help treat each condition.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The different types of medicine available and why they are used</li>\r\n<li>The different routes by which medications can be administered</li>\r\n<li>Types of conditions which may need support in schools and the medicines used to treat them</li>\r\n<li>Know what to do if a child has, specific and potentially life-threatening conditions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(630, 'Module Three - Administering medications in schools', '<p>This final module studies the process of administering medications in schools and examines important considerations, such as; how to store and dispose of drugs, the 5 rights of medication administration and common side effects of specific medications.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How medicines should be stored in school</li>\r\n<li>Medication disposal</li>\r\n<li>Supporting a learner who self-medicates</li>\r\n<li>Routes medication can take into the body</li>\r\n<li>The importance of medication consent</li>\r\n<li>The 5 Rs</li>\r\n<li>Side effects of common medications</li>\r\n<li>Fostering good relationships between parents/school/child</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(631, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(632, 'Module One - Principles of the causes and spread of infection in health care settings', '<p>This unit looks at how infection is caused and examines the various ways in which it can spread in a health care settings.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How infection is caused</li>\r\n<li>How infection can spread</li>\r\n<li>The chain of infection</li>\r\n<li>Health Care Associated Infections (HCAI)</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(633, 'Module Two - Principles of the importance of personal hygiene and health in the prevention and control of infection in health care settings', '<p>This unit highlights the importance of personal hygiene and health in preventing infection in a healthcare setting and studies areas of relevance, such as; effective hand washing and personal protective equipment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of personal hygiene in the prevention and control of infection in a workplace setting</li>\r\n<li>The importance of effective hand washing</li>\r\n<li>The principles of using Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(634, 'Module Three - Principles of decontamination, cleaning and waste management in health care settings', '<p>This unit considers the importance of cleaning, decontamination and waste management to prevent infection in a healthcare setting and studies areas of relevance, such as; decontamination, sterilisation and safely handling sharps.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of maintaining a clean environment</li>\r\n<li>Roles and responsibilities in relation to cleaning, decontamination and waste management</li>\r\n<li>The principles of decontamination processes</li>\r\n<li>The sterilisation process</li>\r\n<li>How to safely handle laundry</li>\r\n<li>The principles of effective waste management</li>\r\n<li>How to safely handle sharps</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(635, 'Module Four - Principles of infection prevention and control in a health care setting', '<p>This unit is concerned about why infection control is needed and examines the policies, roles and responsibilities which relate to this practice.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The purpose of infection control</li>\r\n<li>How regulations inform policy and practice relating to infection control</li>\r\n<li>The roles and responsibilities relating to infection control</li>\r\n<li>The role of risk assessments in relation to infection control</li>\r\n<li>The principles of infection control procedures</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(636, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(637, 'Module One - Explore and understand roles in safeguarding and promoting the welfare of children and young people', '<p>This module looks broadly at the numerous processes in place to help ensure child safety and welfare is maintained, examining areas such as; what constitutes abuse, different multi-agency teams and reporting procedures. These areas are then explained in relation to your own responsibilities.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Abuse</li>\r\n<li>What is a &lsquo;safe and healthy&rsquo; environment?</li>\r\n<li>Multi agency teams and other agencies?</li>\r\n<li>Communicating effectively and developing working relationships with other practitioners and professionals?</li>\r\n<li>Establishing rapport and respectful relationships with children, young people, their families and carers</li>\r\n<li>Involving others and seeking advice and support</li>\r\n<li>Reporting procedures</li>\r\n<li>The impact of aggression, anger and violence from carers on practice and how to manage this</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(638, 'Module Two - Understand legislation and policies designed to safeguard children and young people', '<p>This module is concerned specifically with the numerous laws that are enforced to help protect children from harm and promote their wellbeing. It is important that those caring for children are aware and abide by relevant legislation and the materials contained provide guidance on the considerations that must be made.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Children Act 1989, amended 2004</li>\r\n<li>Local Safeguarding Children Boards Regulations (2006)</li>\r\n<li>The Crime and Disorder Act 1998</li>\r\n<li>The Data Protection Act 1998 and Freedom of Information Act 2000</li>\r\n<li>Special Educational Needs (SEN) Code of Practice 2001</li>\r\n<li>The Equality Act (2010)</li>\r\n<li>Health and Safety at Work Act 1974</li>\r\n<li>How are children and young people protected by law</li>\r\n<li>The Common Assessment Framework (CAF)</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(639, 'Module Three - Develop personal skills to contribute to the safeguarding of children and young people', '<p>This module provides guidance on the types of skills which are required in order to contribute appropriately to the safety and wellbeing of children. It is essential that care workers are fully aware of what their role entails and this module examines important considerations to ensure that individuals work most effectively to promote positive outcomes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The roles, responsibilities &amp; values of family members</li>\r\n<li>How parents can ensure positive outcomes for their children and factors on parenting</li>\r\n<li>The role of other family members</li>\r\n<li>Strategies for promoting personal safety for children and young people and the parental role</li>\r\n<li>Personal vulnerability and how professionals can protect themselves from allegations of abuse</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(640, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(641, 'Module One - What are social, emotional and behavioural difficulties?', '<p>This unit looks at the types of issues that are regarded as social, emotional and behavioural difficulties in education and considers relevant factors such as; different types of difficulty, difficulty triggers and the link between difficulties and communication.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What are social, emotional and behavioural difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Types of social, emotional and behavioural difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Triggers to social, emotional and behavioural difficulties</li>\r\n<li>How are social, emotional and behavioural difficulties linked to communication?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(642, 'Module Two - Exploring the issues', '<p>This unit is concerned with the multiple issues that can arise in an education setting (both for the learner and everyone else) due to social, emotional and behavioural difficulties and considers various approaches which can be implemented to help combat these problems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Considering social, emotional and behavioural difficulties and their impact on the classroom</li>\r\n<li>An exclusive approach to social, emotional and behavioural difficulties</li>\r\n<li>An inclusive approach to social, emotional and behavioural difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Early identification of social, emotional and behavioural difficulties</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(643, 'Module Three - Understanding Misbehaviour', '<p>This unit explores the action of misbehaving and examines the reasons why we as humans decide to act in a certain way. This acts as a starting point in understanding how and why individuals might misbehave in an educational setting.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Models of behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Goal-directed behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour out of our control</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(644, 'Module Four - SEBD strategies, interventions and approaches', '<p>This unit introduces us to SEBD strategies and approaches operational in mainstream and non-mainstream education and those involved in interventions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>SEBD strategies</li>\r\n<li>SEBD interventions</li>\r\n<li>SEBD approaches</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(645, 'Module Five - Direct and indirect bullying behaviours', '<p>This unit studies the types of behaviours that can be regarded as bullying, before going on to consider how bullying affects children with SEN. The materials then look at the legislation and strategies that are in place to help reduce the prevalence of bullying and support victims.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Direct and in-direct bullying</li>\r\n<li>Bullying and its effects on children with SEN</li>\r\n<li>Relevant legislation and support programmes: Anti-bullying</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(646, 'Module Six - Improving classroom achievement', '<p>This unit determines the various methods which can be used to help promote achievement in the classroom for those with social, emotional and behavioural difficulties and considers relevant factors, such as; good practice, governing bodies and understanding the challenge.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The challenge for educators</li>\r\n<li>Guidance or codes for SENCOs</li>\r\n<li>Good practice case studies</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(647, 'Module Seven - Issues for the education of pupils identified as having ADHD', '<p>This unit will consider some of the issues in education of pupils with ADHD, looking at some case studies and key strategies for supporting students with ADHD.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Issues in education of pupils with ADHD</li>\r\n<li>Case studies- ADHD in class</li>\r\n<li>Key strategies for supporting students with ADHD in class</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(648, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(649, 'Module One - Provide Support for Learning Activities', '<p>This module explores the various factors that need to be considered and implemented in order to effectively provide support for the delivery of learning activities.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The basic stages of child development</li>\r\n<li>Factors that promote or inhibit effective learning</li>\r\n<li>Learning and teaching styles</li>\r\n<li>The learning environment</li>\r\n<li>Roles and responsibilities</li>\r\n<li>Planning, delivery and evaluation of learning activities</li>\r\n<li>How to provide support for learning activities</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(650, 'Module Two - Support Children’s Development', '<p>This module details the processes of a child&rsquo;s development and highlights the ways in which the teaching assistant should support this.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Basic principles of children&rsquo;s and young people&rsquo;s development</li>\r\n<li>Children&rsquo;s physical development and skills</li>\r\n<li>Children&rsquo;s communication and intellectual development</li>\r\n<li>Social and emotional development</li>\r\n<li>The role of play in children&rsquo;s development</li>\r\n<li>Supporting children and young people through transitions in their Lives</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(651, 'Module Three - Help to Keep Children Safe', '<p>This module outlines the various factors that a teaching assistant must take into consideration to ensure that children within a learning setting are kept safe.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Prepare and maintain a safe environment</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with accidents, emergencies and illness</li>\r\n<li>Support the safeguarding of children from abuse</li>\r\n<li>Encourage children&rsquo;s positive behaviour</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(652, 'Module Four - Contribute to Positive Relationships', '<p>This module addresses the various ways in which a teaching assistant can conduct themselves in order to promote and enforce positive and effective communication within learning settings.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Communicate, interact with and respond to children</li>\r\n<li>Communicate, interact and respond to adults</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(653, 'Module Five - Provide Effective Support for your Colleagues', '<p>This module provides guidance on how teaching assistants can conduct themselves to ensure that they provide effective support for their colleagues.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Maintain working relationships with your colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Develop your effectiveness in a support role</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(654, 'Module Six - Use Information and Communication Technology to Support Pupils\' Learning', '<p>This module provides guidance as to the multiple areas that need to be considered when using ICT to support a pupil&rsquo;s learning.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Emerging technologies</li>\r\n<li>ICT curriculum</li>\r\n<li>Supporting the learning of children with special educational needs</li>\r\n<li>Planning, monitoring and evaluating the use of ICT resources</li>\r\n<li>ICT assessment</li>\r\n<li>Planning an ICT environment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(655, 'Module Seven - Support a Child with Disabilities or Special Education Needs', '<p>This module provides information regarding children with various disabilities or special education needs and details the various ways in which a teaching assistant can support these pupils.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What are special needs?</li>\r\n<li>Legislation</li>\r\n<li>Support children with disabilities or SEN by providing care and encouragement</li>\r\n<li>Provide support to help the child to participate in activities and experiences</li>\r\n<li>Removing barriers to learning for pupils with communication and interaction difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Using alternative and augmentative communication to assist children/young people through use of all their available senses</li>\r\n<li>Planning for each child or young person&rsquo;s individual requirements in partnership with other colleagues</li>\r\n<li>The importance of a good partnership with parents when supporting children and young people with SEN</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(656, 'Module Eight - Support Children and Young People\'s Play', '<p>This module outlines the various techniques and actions that should be enforced when considering to support children in learning settings to engage in play.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Theories concerning play and child development</li>\r\n<li>The role of the adult in supporting children and young people&rsquo;s play</li>\r\n<li>Assessing children and young people&rsquo;s stage of development</li>\r\n<li>Involving children and young people in creating play environments</li>\r\n<li>Ending play sessions</li>\r\n<li>Children and young people&rsquo;s departure</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(657, 'Module Nine - Provide Displays', '<p>This module provides guidance and outlines various factors that should be considered when setting up displays within a learning setting.</p>\r\n<p>Areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Set up displays</li>\r\n<li>Maintain and dismantle displays</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(658, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(659, 'Module One - Preparing to Lead the Team', '<p>This introductory module explores what exactly it means to be a team leader. It looks at the team leading role, how to oversee the development of a team and some of the key responsibilities involved in effectively working as a team leader.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Key leadership roles</li>\r\n<li>The benefits of working with colleagues</li>\r\n<li>The team leader\'s role in health, safety and security</li>\r\n<li>The team leader\'s role in procuring resources</li>\r\n<li>The team leader\'s role in customer service</li>\r\n<li>How information is managed</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(660, 'Module Two - Support Development of Self and Team Members', '<p>This module is concerned with the process of facilitating development of both yourself and those who make up your team. As a team leader it is your job to strive for team success, however this module examines developmental strategies (for the whole team) to achieve this, rather than doing everything yourself.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The performance requirements of the team leader\'s role</li>\r\n<li>Measuring progress against agreed personal objectives</li>\r\n<li>Communicating the team\'s purpose and objectives to team members</li>\r\n<li>Supporting team members</li>\r\n<li>Monitoring the team\'s progress against agreed objectives</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(661, 'Module Three - Communication and the Team Leader', '<p>This module focusses specifically on the essential team leading tool that is communication. It looks at what constitutes effective communication and examines techniques for good practice, before stressing the positive influence these can have on the team leading role.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of effective communication</li>\r\n<li>The importance of effective communication with the team and colleagues</li>\r\n<li>How to present information to a team</li>\r\n<li>How to give clear instructions</li>\r\n<li>How to take part in a meeting</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(662, 'Module Four - Equality, Diversity and the Team Leader', '<p>This module studies issues surrounding equality and diversity in relation to the team leading role. The materials look at how society is made up of an array of different groups and then examines how various different people should be included and supported.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The required support of disabled team members or colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Supporting ethnic diversity</li>\r\n<li>Supporting minority groups</li>\r\n<li>Promoting minority groups</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(663, 'Module Five - Motivating the Team', '<p>This concluding module looks at the nature of motivation and its importance in terms of managing a team that thrives. The materials explore how team members can be inspired to work for a team, through the study of areas such as; motivational theory, delegation and recognition.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Motivational theory</li>\r\n<li>Use of delegation as a motivational tool</li>\r\n<li>The importance of development activities motivation</li>\r\n<li>The importance of individual and team recognition in motivation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(664, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(665, 'Module One - Myths & Facts', '<p>This introductory module outlines a range of facts about individuals who have a visual impairment, considering some of the common myths surrounding the issues and practicalities that people face and also studies other common health conditions associated with sight loss.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Common visual impairment related myths</li>\r\n<li>Statistics</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(666, 'Module Two - How the Eye Works & Eye Conditions', '<p>This module provides a basic insight into how the human eye works and details a range of common eye conditions that can cause a visual impairment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Everyday workings of the eye</li>\r\n<li>Eye conditions and how they affect vision</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(667, 'Module Three - Visual Impairment Registration', '<p>This module outlines not only the certification and registration process but also examines a life-changing experience of coming to terms with their visual impairment as told by someone who knew nothing about the process and their pathway.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Registering your sight loss</li>\r\n<li>How vision is tested and measured</li>\r\n<li>Types of visual impairment</li>\r\n<li>Causes of visual impairment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(668, 'Module Four - Communication & Assistance', '<p>This module studies the appropriate actions to take in order to ensure effective communication is achieved with someone who has a visual impairment. This guidance aims to give you confidence to approach individuals and offer assistance if necessary.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Verbal communication</li>\r\n<li>Tips for assisting people who are visually impaired</li>\r\n<li>Clues to visual impairment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(669, 'Module Five - Mobility', '<p>This module contains information on mobility aids and how they are used. It also outlines techniques necessary to be able to guide a person who is visually impaired safely and confidently.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mobility aids</li>\r\n<li>Guide dogs</li>\r\n<li>Sighted guides</li>\r\n<li>Other aids to orientation &amp; mobility</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(670, 'Module Six - Low Vision', '<p>This module is about what most people with a visual impairment turn to first - low vision aids and looks at common items such as; magnifiers, CCTV and filters.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Magnifiers</li>\r\n<li>Monoculars</li>\r\n<li>Magnifying glasses</li>\r\n<li>Max TV glasses</li>\r\n<li>Mono mouse</li>\r\n<li>CCTV</li>\r\n<li>Filters</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(671, 'Module Seven - Assistive Equipment', '<p>This module concentrates on the equipment available to assist someone with a visual impairment to do things that we all take for granted, such as; using money or even the simple task of pouring a cup of coffee.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Money management</li>\r\n<li>Kitchen equipment</li>\r\n<li>Identifying clothes</li>\r\n<li>Labels</li>\r\n<li>Signature guides</li>\r\n<li>Writing frames</li>\r\n<li>Pen friend</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(672, 'Module Eight - Technology', '<p>This module studies the equipment and technologies available to help improve the accessibility options for people who are blind and visually impaired.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Braille</li>\r\n<li>Moon</li>\r\n<li>Typewriter</li>\r\n<li>The PC</li>\r\n<li>Specialist software</li>\r\n<li>Accessibility software packages</li>\r\n<li>Tablets and phones</li>\r\n<li>ICT</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(673, 'Module Nine - Social Interaction & Leisure Recreation', '<p>This module will enable you to understand that having a visual impairment or being blind, for the most part, will not inhibit your ability to socialise or take part in many leisure activities.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Digital skills</li>\r\n<li>Young and visually impaired</li>\r\n<li>Audio description and touch tours</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to socialising</li>\r\n<li>Accessible hotels</li>\r\n<li>Blind sports</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(674, 'Module Ten - Legislation & Support', '<p>This module is concerned with the various laws enforced which offer protection and opportunities to those who have a visual impairment. It also considers how these laws affect organisations in terms of their responsibilities regarding the treatment of relevant individuals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Human Rights Act 1995</li>\r\n<li>Equality Act 2010</li>\r\n<li>Health and Social Care Act 2012</li>\r\n<li>Care Act 2014</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(675, 'Module Eleven - Organisations & Support', '<p>This module explains the roles of people involved in the visual impairment sector and also looks at the organisations that are available to assist and support people with a visual impairment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Organisations Supporting People with a Visual Impairment</li>\r\n<li>Rehabilitation Officer</li>\r\n<li>Counselling</li>\r\n<li>Sight-loss Charities &amp; Organisations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(676, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(677, 'Module One - Theories of Crime (I) – Psychological', '<p>This module introduces the array of psychological theories that can be used to explain criminal activity and explores numerous perspectives surrounding areas such as; psychodynamic theories, effects of the media on learning and personality and crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Psychodynamic theories</li>\r\n<li>Behaviourist theories</li>\r\n<li>Differential Association Theory</li>\r\n<li>Social learning theory</li>\r\n<li>Effects of the media on learning</li>\r\n<li>Control theories</li>\r\n<li>Personality and crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(678, 'Module Two - Theories of Crime (II) – Biological', '<p>This module examines the range of biological theories that can be used to asses criminal activity and explores perspectives around areas such as; genetic factors and chromosomal studies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Biological theories of offending</li>\r\n<li>Somatotype theories of offending</li>\r\n<li>Genetic factors</li>\r\n<li>Chromosomal studies</li>\r\n<li>Gender differences &amp; crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(679, 'Module Three - Theories of Crime (III) – Sociological', '<p>This module introduces the sociological theories that can be applied to examine the prevalence of criminal activity and explores relevant areas such as; social factors and labelling theory.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Methodological approaches</li>\r\n<li>Social factors</li>\r\n<li>Labelling theory</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(680, 'Module Four - Theories of Crime (IV) – Developmental', '<p>This module again studies theories of crime, this time focussing on developmental perspectives though the study of areas such as; criminal careers, control theories and moral development theories.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Criminal careers</li>\r\n<li>Key longitudinal studies</li>\r\n<li>Moffitt Dual Developmental Pathway Theory</li>\r\n<li>Control theories</li>\r\n<li>Piaget\'s moral development theory</li>\r\n<li>Moral development theories</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(681, 'Module Five - Substance Misuse (Drugs, Alcohol & Crime)', '<p>This module looks at substance abuse and examines relevant areas such as drug use as recreation and more importantly the strong link between drugs, alcohol and crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Substance misuse and crime</li>\r\n<li>An illegal act</li>\r\n<li>A causal relationship?</li>\r\n<li>Heroin - a historical context</li>\r\n<li>Typology of drug abusers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(682, 'Module Six - Violence & Violent Offences', '<p>This module studies violence and looks to assess the act of committing violent offences though the exploration of areas such as; frustration and aggression, explanation models and mental health.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Crime, violence and aggression</li>\r\n<li>Frustration &amp; aggression</li>\r\n<li>Frustration and violence</li>\r\n<li>Explanation models</li>\r\n<li>Mental health and violence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(683, 'Module Seven - Sex Offences', '<p>The focus of this module is inappropriate sexual behaviour that constitutes a criminal offence and the knowledge contained looks to explore this prevalence, though the study of areas such as; risk factors, theoretical explanations and the justice gap.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Rape, sexual assault, sexual violence and sex offending</li>\r\n<li>Risk factors</li>\r\n<li>Theoretical explanations</li>\r\n<li>Evolutionary and feminist perspectives on rape</li>\r\n<li>The justice gap</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(684, 'Module Eight - Arson', '<p>This module studies the concept of fire related crime and aims to explore the possible reasons behind engaging in this act, looking at areas of relevance such as; measuring arson, the evolutionary psychology of fire learning and interaction theories.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Measuring arson</li>\r\n<li>Developmental stages of fire-setting</li>\r\n<li>Possible motives</li>\r\n<li>Evolutionary psychology of fire learning</li>\r\n<li>Social &amp; environmental theories</li>\r\n<li>Interaction theories</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(685, 'Module Nine - Stalking', '<p>This module studies the behaviour of stalking individuals, exploring this act in relation to criminal activity and assessing the psychology behind this through the study of areas such as; legislation, victims of stalkers and stalking limitations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation</li>\r\n<li>Who are stalkers?</li>\r\n<li>Typology of stalkers</li>\r\n<li>Victims of stalkers</li>\r\n<li>Psychological explanations</li>\r\n<li>Stalking &ndash; the limitations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(686, 'Module Ten - Serial Murder', '<p>This module looks to explore the reasoning behind why people continually commit murder and examines areas of relevance such as; mass murders, serial murder explanations and case studies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mass murderers</li>\r\n<li>Serial murder</li>\r\n<li>Explanations for serial murder</li>\r\n<li>Serial killer case study</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(687, 'Module Eleven - Terrorism', '<p>This module looks at assessing the act of terrorism through a psychological perspective and examines numerous areas of relevance to this idea, such as; terror groups and hate.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining terrorism</li>\r\n<li>Psychological aspects of terrorism</li>\r\n<li>Terrorism research</li>\r\n<li>Different terror groups</li>\r\n<li>Hate</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(688, 'Module Twelve - Mental Health & Crime', '<p>This module explores the relationship between mental health conditions and criminal activity through the study of relevant areas, such as; Schizophrenia, amnesia and psychopathy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schizophrenia</li>\r\n<li>Dissociative Identity Disorder</li>\r\n<li>Amnesia</li>\r\n<li>Psychopath</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(689, 'Module Thirteen - Offender Profiling', '<p>This module looks specifically at the process of profiling criminal offenders and examines a multitude of the relevant areas, such as; the typological approach, profiling in Britain and investigative psychology.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The history of profiling</li>\r\n<li>Profiling &amp; the FBI</li>\r\n<li>Organised/disorganised offender</li>\r\n<li>The typological approach</li>\r\n<li>Profiling in Britain</li>\r\n<li>Changes in the investigation of crime</li>\r\n<li>Investigative psychology</li>\r\n<li>The behavioural investigative advisor</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(690, 'Module Fourteen - Geographical Profiling', '<p>This module examines the establishment of crime related traits through the application of geographical profiling, which involves the study of a criminal&rsquo;s activity space. Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The North American approach</li>\r\n<li>The British approach</li>\r\n<li>Differences in approach</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(691, 'Module Fifteen - Police Interviewing – The Suspect & The Witness', '<p>This module details the role of conducting various types of interviews in the police profession and examines areas of relevance such as; investigative suspect interviewing and the enhanced cognitive interview.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Investigative interviewing- the suspect</li>\r\n<li>Investigative Interviewing- the witness</li>\r\n<li>Cognitive interview</li>\r\n<li>Enhanced Cognitive Interview</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(692, 'Module Sixteen - Detecting Deception (Lie Detection, Polygraph etc.)', '<p>This module studies the deceptive act of lying and more specifically its strong link with crime. The content contained looks to explore why people lie and the various methods used to detect and measure crime related lying.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why do people lie?</li>\r\n<li>Ekman&rsquo;s theory of lie detection</li>\r\n<li>Verbal</li>\r\n<li>Statement validity analysis (SVA)</li>\r\n<li>The polygraph</li>\r\n<li>Criticisms</li>\r\n<li>Countermeasures</li>\r\n<li>Polygraph &amp; sex offenders</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(693, 'Module Seventeen - Eyewitness Testimony', '<p>This concluding module looks at the occurrence of eyewitnesses at the scene of a crime and examines their credibility in relation the criminal investigation, through the study of areas such as; eyewitness memory and conceptual systems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eyewitness memory</li>\r\n<li>Conceptual systems</li>\r\n<li>Perception, memory and eyewitness testimony</li>\r\n<li>Personal perception and memory</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(694, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(695, 'Module One - Supporting the Teacher', '<p>This introductory module focusses on the numerous areas of practice which should be considered in order to provide effective support to the teacher.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: The Learning Environment</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Pupil Behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Observing and Recording</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(696, 'Module Two - Supporting the Pupil', '<p>This module examines the importance of a learner&rsquo;s needs in an educational setting and establishes the actions that should be taken in order to provide effective support to all learners.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: Care and Support</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Health and Hygiene</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Child Protection</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(697, 'Module Three - Supporting the Curriculum', '<p>This module explores the structure of the school curriculum, examining the various ways in which this can be supported and how pupils can be supported to achieve its requirements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: The National Curriculum</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Planning and Evaluating</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Assisting Pupils during all Learning Activities</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(698, 'Module Four - Supporting the School', '<p>This module is concerned with a school&rsquo;s requirements along with the compulsory procedures they have in place and examines how a teaching assistant can support the school to achieve and maintain these requirements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: Legal Requirements</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: School Organisation</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Policies and Procedures</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(699, 'Module Five - Supporting ICT in the Classroom', '<p>This module looks specifically at the use of ICT within a school settings and examines the numerous ways in which a teaching assistant can support in the use and maintenance of relevant ICT equipment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: Preparation and Maintenance of ICT Equipment</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Supporting the Use of ICT Equipment</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Keeping Pupil Records</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(700, 'Module Six - Supporting Pupils with Special Educational Needs', '<p>This module details the need for special educational requirements within a school setting and examines how teaching assistants should help in utilizing services to support pupils who require specialised support.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: Inclusion and Special Educational Needs</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Support for Learners</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(701, 'Module Seven - Supporting Literacy Development', '<p>This module focusses specifically on the stages of learner literacy development at school and provides guidance on how teaching assistants can help to promote learning during this process.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: Supporting the Development of Reading Skills</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Supporting the Development of Writing Skills</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Supporting the Development of Speaking and Listening Skills</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(702, 'Module Eight - Supporting Numeracy Development', '<p>This module studies how learners at school develop numeracy skills and examines the numerous ways in which a teaching assistant can help to promote this learning process.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: Supporting the Development of Number Skills</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Supporting the Development of Problem Solving and Data Handling Skills</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Supporting the Understanding of Measures, Shape, and Space</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(703, 'Module Nine - Working with Others', '<p>This concluding module looks at a teaching assistant&rsquo;s requirement to work with a range of different people within the work setting and provides guidance on how to do so effectively.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Element 1: Working in Teams</li>\r\n<li>Element 2: Working with Colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Element 3: Working with Other Professionals and Parents</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(704, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(705, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(706, 'Module One - Introduction', '<p>As the title suggests this opening section provides a brief overview of what the course materials will entail. It briefly details areas that will be considered, such as; NLP techniques, integrating skills and applying toolbox techniques.</p>', 1),
(707, 'Module Two - History of NLP', '<p>This chapter is principally concerned with providing a historical context to the world of NLP. The materials examine a range of successful psychotherapists who have shaped this study and looks at how their perspectives can be applied when looking at the future of this field.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dr Milton Erickson</li>\r\n<li>Dr Fritz Perls</li>\r\n<li>Dr Carl Rogers</li>\r\n<li>Gregory Bateson</li>\r\n<li>Alfred Korzybski</li>\r\n<li>Looking forward</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(708, 'Module Three - Your Role as an NLPer, Including Stages of Change', '<p>This chapter highlights what it means to be an NLPer. It explores your responsibility to help empower an individual through the focus on choices. The materials examine the various processes that the role would entail, looking specifically at areas such as; the precontemplation stage, preparation stage and action stage.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Your role as an NLPer</li>\r\n<li>Precontemplation stage</li>\r\n<li>Contemplation stage</li>\r\n<li>Preparation stage</li>\r\n<li>Action stage</li>\r\n<li>Maintenance and relapse prevention</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(709, 'Module Four - The Four Pillars of Wisdom', '<p>This chapter is specifically focussed on four areas that are applied by NLPers to ensure clients are provided with positive outcomes. These areas, known as the four pillars of wisdom entail tactics such as; facilitating goals and being effective in your communications methods. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Rapport</li>\r\n<li>Well formed outcome</li>\r\n<li>Sensory acuity</li>\r\n<li>Behavioural flexibility</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(710, 'Module Five - The Presuppositions', '<p>This chapter is concerned with the starting point for NLP techniques. This encompasses a set of beliefs which can be used as a template for working with a client. The materials study each belief in detail and examines how each may relate to a client\'s trail of thought.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The map is not the territory</li>\r\n<li>If one person can do something, anyone can learn to do it</li>\r\n<li>The mind and body are part of the same system</li>\r\n<li>People already have all the resources they need</li>\r\n<li>Communication</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour is based on the positive intent of the perpetrator</li>\r\n<li>People make the best choices with the information available to them</li>\r\n<li>There is no failure only feedback</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(711, 'Module Six - Rapport', '<p>This chapter studies rapport, which is the nature of achieving meaningful interaction between two or more people. The materials explore the importance of gaining rapport and examines a range of ways in which this can be achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Our map of the world</li>\r\n<li>Filters</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(712, ' Module Seven - Perception of Your World is Your Reality', '<p>This chapter is chiefly concerned with an NLP technique which encourages individuals to alter their perceptions, in order to help provide a more positive perspective of their life. The materials look at exactly what this concept entails and examines how you can apply this to clients.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Your perception of the world is your reality</li>\r\n<li>The larger your reality, the more choices you have in life</li>\r\n<li>Ah ha! Moments</li>\r\n<li>Appreciating another person\'s reality</li>\r\n<li>What you don\'t know you know</li>\r\n<li>Innovation is exploring \'what you don\'t know you don\'t know\'</li>\r\n<li>Different perspectives</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(713, 'Module Eight - Communicating with NLP', '<p>This chapter studies the essential aspect of NLP that is communication. The materials examine a range of techniques which can be applied to promote effective communication and looks at what positive outcomes can be achieved when these are successfully implemented.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sensory based predicates</li>\r\n<li>Increasing rapport using representational systems</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(714, 'Module Nine - Eye Accessing Cues', '<p>This chapter explores a specific NLP tool which can be used to gain an indication of a client\'s response. It is concerned with the use of eye patterns and how these may indicate truthfulness or congruence. The materials examine what signs to look out for and how these can be appropriately interpreted.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eye access chart</li>\r\n<li>People\'s eyes do not always move</li>\r\n<li>Using eye patterns to assess truthfulness or congruence</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(715, 'Module Ten - Preferred Representational Systems', '<p>This chapter looks at the methods by which individuals interpret what is being said to them. The materials define the different methods used and look at how you should applied a client\'s preferred method, in order to obtain positive outcomes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Lead and preferred representational systems</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(716, 'Module Eleven - Mirroring and Matching', '<p>This chapter is focussed on an NLP technique known as mirroring and matching, which is essentially a method of imitating client traits in order to make you more relatable and thus encourage rapport. The materials examine how this technique can be achieved and how this can influence your interactions with a client.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining mirroring and matching</li>\r\n<li>Effective ways to mirror and match your clients to build rapport</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(717, 'Module Twelve - Sub-modalities', '<p>This chapter expands on knowledge gained from the previous module in relation to representational systems and explores how these can be broken down further into sub-modalities. These sub-modalities are primarily concerned with the intricacies of visual, auditory and kinaesthetic senses and the materials examine how these are affected and can therefore be applied to different individuals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is meant by the term sub-modality</li>\r\n<li>How to use sub-modalities to facilitate change in a client</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(718, 'Module Thirteen - Underpinning Knowledge', '<p>This chapter examines the NLP meta-model technique which involves using a set of informal questions to uncover information, challenge and expand the limits to a person\'s map of the world. How effective implementation of this methodology can impact the client, is also explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Origin of the meta-model</li>\r\n<li>12 meta model patterns</li>\r\n<li>Distortions</li>\r\n<li>Generalisations</li>\r\n<li>Deletions</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(719, 'Module Fourteen - Getting to Know You and Others', '<p>This chapter looks at the importance of an NLPer gaining self-understanding before beginning to understand others. The materials outline methods for gaining self-awareness and highlights how this awareness will positively aid your work with clients.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Understanding not just your clients but yourself as well</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(720, 'Module Fifteen - Meta Programmes', '<p>This chapter studies the process by which individual\'s process information and filter out unwanted data. The materials look at how NLPers can gain an awareness of this process and use it to ensure individuals are only conveyed messages they desire.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Proactive/ reactive</li>\r\n<li>Options/ procedures</li>\r\n<li>Internal/ external</li>\r\n<li>Global/ detail</li>\r\n<li>Extrovert/ introvert</li>\r\n<li>Thinker/ feeler</li>\r\n<li>Sensory/ intuitive</li>\r\n<li>Judger/ perceiver</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(721, 'Module Sixteen - Personalities', '<p>This chapter is concerned with the development of personality. The materials look at how we all obtain our own identity and considers the various factors that dictate how this is shaped. This understanding is then applied within the context of clients in order to give NLPers an awareness of how to work with different types of people.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The socialite</li>\r\n<li>The go getter</li>\r\n<li>The analyst</li>\r\n<li>The empathic</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(722, 'Module Seventeen - What do People Value', '<p>This chapter focusses on the things that people value. It looks at the concept of human motivation and emotional needs and examines how human behaviour is tailored to fulfilling these objectives. It then goes on to explore how an NLPer can create more choices to enable clients to satisfy their needs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How our values affect our motivation</li>\r\n<li>How our personality links with our values</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(723, 'Module Eighteen - Developing Your Life’s Purpose', '<p>This chapter explores the process of developing a purpose in life. It examines the power having something to strive towards and how this can help aid recovery. The importance of applying this tool as an NLPer dealing with clients is then emphasised.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How having a life\'s purpose can motivate us to overcome difficulties</li>\r\n<li>How having a life\'s purpose can aid in recovery</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(724, ' Module Nineteen - Logical Levels and Identifying Change', '<p>This chapter studies an NLP model that is concerned with understanding change for you and for helping others. It looks at breaking down various parts of information, such as; purpose, behaviour and environment and explains how this can help clients make positive changes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How logical levels impact change</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(725, 'Module Twenty - Setting POWERful Goals', '<p>This chapter is concerned with the creation of goals and how you as an NLPer can help clients structure suitable targets which will help them achieve positive outcomes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The goal</li>\r\n<li>Purpose</li>\r\n<li>Observations</li>\r\n<li>Where is the power?</li>\r\n<li>Ecology/ evidence check</li>\r\n<li>Route ahead</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(726, 'Module Twenty One - Reframing- Finding the Silver Lining', '<p>This module examines the 6 step process which encourages client\'s to pin point their behaviours and consider replacing these with more desirable ones in order to achieve a more positive outcome.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The concept of finding the silver lining</li>\r\n<li>Reframing example</li>\r\n<li>Six-Step Reframe</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(727, 'Module Twenty Two -NLP Toolbox – Introduction', '<p>This concluding chapter brings together all of the knowledge detailed so far and looks at specific NLP tools which can be applied to each methodology to ensure the best outcomes for clients are achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fast mental reprogramming</li>\r\n<li>The swish pattern- changing habits</li>\r\n<li>Changing personal history</li>\r\n<li>Anchoring- Overcoming negative emotion</li>\r\n<li>Visualisation- Creating future memories</li>\r\n<li>The fast phobia cure- overcome fear</li>\r\n<li>Metaphors- overcoming resistance</li>\r\n<li>Circle of Excellence</li>\r\n<li>Pain management</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(728, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(729, 'Module One - The key features of child development and developmental needs of children 0-8 years inclusive of individual and special needs', '<p>This introductory module studies the process of initial child development and how this differs between those with special needs and those without, though the examination of relevant areas such as; special needs, transitions and the effects of discrimination.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The main development of a child from birth to 8 years</li>\r\n<li>Social, economic and environmental factors affecting development</li>\r\n<li>Genetic and hereditary factors affecting development</li>\r\n<li>Children&rsquo;s overall developmental needs</li>\r\n<li>Special needs</li>\r\n<li>Transitions</li>\r\n<li>Policies to meet diversity within the childminding sector</li>\r\n<li>Inclusion within the childminding sector</li>\r\n<li>Effects of discrimination</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(730, 'Module Two  - Providing for children’s physical needs inclusive of health and safety', '<p>This module is concerned with the importance of meeting a child&rsquo;s physical needs such as nutrition and rest and also ensuring that their health and safety is maintained. The knowledge contained examines ways in which these requirements should be achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Meeting the children&rsquo;s nutritional needs</li>\r\n<li>Meeting children&rsquo;s rest and sleep needs</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour in children</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour attributed to specific special needs</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining appropriate hygiene procedures</li>\r\n<li>Childhood illnesses</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining a safe and secure environment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(731, 'Module Three - Learning through play for child development', '<p>This module focusses on the practise of play, examining how its various types have a great importance in the process of child development and the knowledge contained provides advice on how appropriate play should be promoted and organised.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of play and their importance in relation to child development</li>\r\n<li>Observation and planning</li>\r\n<li>Every Child Matters and the Birth to Three Matters Framework</li>\r\n<li>The Early Years Foundation Stage</li>\r\n<li>Available resources in relation to Health and Safety, and Diversity and Inclusion</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(732, 'Module Four - Safeguarding and promoting the welfare of children', '<p>This module studies the sensitive subject area of child abuse and examines the role of the childminder in relation to having an awareness of when this may be happening to any child in their care and what to do in these instances.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is safeguarding?</li>\r\n<li>Definitions of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>The main categories of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Signs and symptoms of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Procedures to follow in the case of child protection concerns</li>\r\n<li>Documentation</li>\r\n<li>Sources of support</li>\r\n<li>Some practical guidance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(733, 'Module Five - Legal responsibilities of the childminder and responsibilities for working together', '<p>This concluding module focusses on the legal responsibilities mandatory to those looking after children and details specific guidance on complying with areas such as; OFSTED requirements and following procedures for admission and collection.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Childminder&rsquo;s legislation</li>\r\n<li>Legal responsibilities of the childminder</li>\r\n<li>Procedures for admission and collection</li>\r\n<li>Legal implications of childminding</li>\r\n<li>Policies and procedures to meet OFSTED requirements</li>\r\n<li>Working in partnership with parents and other professionals</li>\r\n<li>The childminder&rsquo;s responsibilities for building positive relationships with parents and other professionals in relation to</li>\r\n<li>Exploring contacts for support for childminding services</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(734, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(735, 'Module One - Understand how to contribute to monitoring the health of individuals affected by health conditions', '<p>This introductory unit aims to promote an understanding of the importance of monitoring the health of individuals affected by health conditions and studies areas of relevance, such as; carrying out observations and reporting changes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Health monitoring</li>\r\n<li>Carrying out observations</li>\r\n<li>Record and reporting observations</li>\r\n<li>Responding to changes in an individual&rsquo;s condition</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(736, 'Module Two - Arthritis awareness', '<p>In this unit, learners will gain an understanding of what arthritis is and the treatment options and support services available. Learners will also understand the impact arthritis can have on an individual and how the condition can be managed.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What arthritis is</li>\r\n<li>Treatment options and support services</li>\r\n<li>Experience of living with arthritis and strategies for managing the condition</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(737, 'Module Three - Dementia awareness', '<p>This unit explores what the term dementia means, the condition&rsquo;s common causes and the medical and social models associated with it. In addition, the materials examine factors that relate to an individual&rsquo;s experience of dementia.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What dementia is</li>\r\n<li>Key features of the theoretical models of dementia</li>\r\n<li>Factors relating to an individual&rsquo;s experience of dementia</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(738, 'Module Four - Stroke awareness', '<p>This unit studies what happens during a stroke, the importance of stroke management, how to recognise a stroke and the risk factors associated with a stroke.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What a stroke is</li>\r\n<li>How to recognise a stroke</li>\r\n<li>The management if risk factors for stroke</li>\r\n<li>The importance of emergency response and treatment for stoke</li>\r\n<li>The management of stroke</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(739, 'Module Five - Introductory awareness of sensory loss', '<p>This unit is concerned with situations in which an individual experiences a loss of senses and examines considerations such as; why sensory loss occurs, the effect this can have on an individual and the steps needed to overcome this.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Factors that impact on an individual with sensory loss and steps that can be taken to overcome these</li>\r\n<li>The importance of effective communication for individuals with sensory loss</li>\r\n<li>The main causes and conditions of sensory loss</li>\r\n<li>How to recognise when an individual may be experiencing sight and/or hearing loss</li>\r\n<li>How to report concerns about sensory loss</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(740, 'Module Six - Parkinson’s disease awareness', '<p>This concluding unit looks at what Parkinson&rsquo;s disease is and the treatment options and support services available. The materials then go on to examine the impact of Parkinson&rsquo;s on an individual and how the condition can be managed.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What Parkinson&rsquo;s disease is</li>\r\n<li>Treatment options and support services that are available to individuals with Parkinson&rsquo;s disease</li>\r\n<li>The experience of living with Parkinson&rsquo;s disease and strategies for managing the condition</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(741, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(742, 'Module One - Social Order Maintenance in Celtic & Roman Britain', '<p>This introductory chapter explores the transition of human life into the structured approach which was adopted in Celtic and Roman Britain. The content looks at the potential triggers for warfare and barbarianism and how these were avoided through factors such as the formation of community groups and political control.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Celtic order maintenance</li>\r\n<li>Roman order maintenance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(743, 'Module Two - Inequality before the Law', '<p>Following the establishment of Celtic &amp; Roman&rsquo;s organised society explored in chapter 1, this chapter looks at how Britain gradually fell into a period of chaos and strife following their departure. The contributing factors towards this, such as: the Christian church influence, English law and brutal punishment, are explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Chaos and confusion</li>\r\n<li>The Introduction of the Danelaw</li>\r\n<li>Norman Law</li>\r\n<li>The King\'s Power</li>\r\n<li>The King\'s Peace</li>\r\n<li>Violent crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(744, 'Module Three - Criminalisation, Victims and the Role of the State', '<p>This chapter examines the role of the state in the 18th century in achieving order maintenance. The content looks at the numerous problems and inconsistencies that occurred during this period and focusses on particular issues such as a lack of equality and a limited understanding of the causes of crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The priorities of 18th century law</li>\r\n<li>Punishment and the poor</li>\r\n<li>The failure of government measures against crime</li>\r\n<li>A more enlightened approach to criminality</li>\r\n<li>A time of change</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(745, 'Module Four - Classicism and Positivism', '<p>As the first 3 chapters focussed on historical background of crime, this chapter goes on to examine some of the differing theories that can be used to assess the nature of crime and establish the possible reasons why people commit it.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A history of classicism</li>\r\n<li>Beccaria\'s Theory</li>\r\n<li>A history of positivism</li>\r\n<li>Lombroso\'s theory</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(746, 'Module Five - The Anglo American Model and the Chicago School of Criminology', '<p>This chapter moves on to examine the specific models used to accumulate criminological research in different countries and explains how to interpret this research and assess significant differences between models.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The emergence of an American Model</li>\r\n<li>The Anglo American Model</li>\r\n<li>The Chicago School</li>\r\n<li>Oscar Newman &ndash; Defensible space</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(747, 'Module Six - Anomie, Social Control & Deviant Subculture Theories', '<p>This chapter progresses in theme with earlier chapters with regards to examining relevant criminological theories. The focus here is &lsquo;Anomie&rsquo; (the theory of lawnessness), &lsquo;Strain theory&rsquo; (an unbalance of societal expectations to opportunities) and &lsquo;Deviant subculture theories&rsquo; (autonomy and affluence).</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Anomie</li>\r\n<li>Durkheim and the theory of Anomie</li>\r\n<li>Merton\'s Strain theory</li>\r\n<li>Deviant subculture theories</li>\r\n<li>Consolidation of causes of crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(748, 'Module Seven - Administrative Criminology', '<p>This chapter looks at the concept of Administrative criminology, a term which categorises criminological perspectives the government wish to highlight, such as: mugging, violence and burglary.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Perspectives of administrative criminology</li>\r\n<li>Routine activity theory</li>\r\n<li>Rational choice theory</li>\r\n<li>Crime prevention theory</li>\r\n<li>Crime science</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(749, 'Module Eight - Labelling Theory and Critical Criminology', '<p>This chapter is focussed on 2 specific theories &lsquo;Labelling&rsquo; and &lsquo;Critical Criminology&rsquo; and examines relevant issues such as: the influence on society on a criminal act and the relationship of power and crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Labelling theory</li>\r\n<li>Critical Criminology</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(750, 'Module Nine - Chapter 9', '<p>This chapter in concerned with the theory of right realism, which explores the notion of criminal activity being associated with the individual rather than being a bi product of social influence.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Right realism</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(751, 'Module Ten - Left Idealism and Left Realism', '<p>This chapter explores the theoretical notions of left idealism (the idea of crimes being committed by the powerless as an act of legitimate resistance) and left realism (the idea that crime occurs due to expectation over opportunity) and examines the differences between these two schools of thought.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Left idealism</li>\r\n<li>Left realism</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(752, 'Module Eleven - Feminist Criminology', '<p>This chapter focusses on the feminist approach to examining crime. The knowledge explores multiple considerations, such as: the main areas of research undertaken by feminist criminology, relevant view points and the development of the feminist approach.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gender - why are women are less likely than men to commit crime?</li>\r\n<li>Gender stereotyping</li>\r\n<li>Research and statistics &ndash; why are research findings on men generalised to women?</li>\r\n<li>Causes of female offending</li>\r\n<li>The effect of treatment of women deviants on offending rates</li>\r\n<li>More recent research findings</li>\r\n<li>Female representation in the criminal justice system</li>\r\n<li>Black feminism</li>\r\n<li>Contemporary feminist criminology</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(753, 'Module Twelve - Ethnicity and Crime', '<p>This chapter looks at the relationship between ethnicity and crime and explores pertinent issues such a difference in the treatment of black people and the prevalence of racism within the criminal justice system.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ethnicity and criminalisation</li>\r\n<li>Statistics and perception of crimes</li>\r\n<li>Discrimination</li>\r\n<li>Under-representation of black people in the criminal justice system</li>\r\n<li>Black people as victims of crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(754, 'Module Thirteen - Mentally Disordered Offenders and the Criminal Justice System', '<p>This chapter examines the relationship between mentally disordered offenders and the criminal justice system through the exploration of relevant areas such as: the police, court and probation approaches to mentally disordered people.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mentally disordered offenders and the community</li>\r\n<li>Mentally disordered offenders and the police</li>\r\n<li>Mentally disordered offenders and the Crown Prosecution Service</li>\r\n<li>Mentally disordered offenders and the courts</li>\r\n<li>Mentally disorder offenders and the probation service</li>\r\n<li>Mentally disordered offenders in prisons</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(755, 'Module Fourteen - Young Offenders and the Criminal Justice System', '<p>This chapter examines the relationship between youth offenders and the criminal justice system through the exploration of relevant areas such as diversionary approaches and the incarceration of young offenders.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What works?</li>\r\n<li>Treatment or punishment</li>\r\n<li>Restorative justice</li>\r\n<li>Effectiveness of government policies</li>\r\n<li>Young offenders after conviction</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(756, 'Module Fifteen - Children and Criminology', '<p>This chapter studies the reality of children committing serious crime, with a specific focus on child killers. Relevant issues such as common factors, poor parenting and responsibility are examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Child soldiers &amp; terrorists</li>\r\n<li>Children who Kill (USA)</li>\r\n<li>Identifying potential killer children</li>\r\n<li>Children who kill (UK)</li>\r\n<li>Criminals or victims</li>\r\n<li>Is there an answer?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(757, 'Module Sixteen - Agencies of Social Control', '<p>The Agencies of Social Control structure is considered in this chapter and relevant areas such as: what is meant by policing, other agencies involved in the process and different levels of screening, training and supervision, are all explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Police and policing</li>\r\n<li>Public policing</li>\r\n<li>Specialist police forces</li>\r\n<li>Ports police</li>\r\n<li>Independent police forces</li>\r\n<li>Local authority parks police</li>\r\n<li>Bodies of police without constabulary powers</li>\r\n<li>UK border agency</li>\r\n<li>Her Majesty\'s Revenue and Customs</li>\r\n<li>Service police</li>\r\n<li>Private policing: Security companies</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(758, 'Module Seventeen - The National Probation Service', '<p>This chapter studies the implementation of the National Probation Service and examines its key objectives and roles such as; engaging offenders in unpaid community work for the purpose of providing a proper punishment and to aid rehabilitation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A brief history</li>\r\n<li>The National Probation Service</li>\r\n<li>Intermittent custody</li>\r\n<li>Tasks in the probation service</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(759, 'Module Eighteen - Incarceration and Punishment', '<p>This chapter explores the process of incarceration and punishment by examining its origin&rsquo;s and critiquing specific areas of relevance, such as: political and economic motives, imprisonment as a strategy and prison populations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>National Offender Management Service</li>\r\n<li>The early penal system</li>\r\n<li>Prison overcrowding - earlier solutions</li>\r\n<li>A more enlightened approach</li>\r\n<li>Earlier treatment of mentally disordered offenders</li>\r\n<li>Penalising the poor</li>\r\n<li>The modern prison service</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(760, 'Module Nineteen - White Collar Crime', '<p>This chapter defines the complex nature of white collar crime through the examination of relevant areas, such as: what is meant by inside trading and the concept of money laundering.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Insider trading</li>\r\n<li>Money laundering</li>\r\n<li>Other types of white collar crime</li>\r\n<li>The problem with white collar crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(761, 'Module Twenty - Violent Crime', '<p>This chapter focusses specifically on the occurrence of violent crime and examines relevant issues such as: why people fear it, society groups likely to be victims and government reactions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fear of violent crime</li>\r\n<li>Key actions</li>\r\n<li>Homicide</li>\r\n<li>Knife crime</li>\r\n<li>Gun and gang crime</li>\r\n<li>Domestic and sexual violence</li>\r\n<li>Sexual crimes</li>\r\n<li>Government initiatives</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(762, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(763, 'Module One - Understanding customer service', '<p>This introductory module gives an insight into what it means to provide customers with an appropriate level of service and explores the range of things to consider when applying this practice, such as; customer expectations, the service chain and communication.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Customer expectations</li>\r\n<li>Service offers</li>\r\n<li>Service chain</li>\r\n<li>Effective teamwork and service partnerships</li>\r\n<li>Private sector/public sector and not-for-profit organisations</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Communication</li>\r\n<li>Policies and procedures</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(764, 'Module Two - Knowing the customer service rules', '<p>This module focusses specifically on the numerous rules which are put in place to protect consumers to ensure that they are provided with an appropriate service&nbsp;and looks at how customer service providers need to abide by the relevant regulations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Development and improvement to customer service</li>\r\n<li>Quality improvement cycle</li>\r\n<li>The PESTEL analysis</li>\r\n<li>Authorisation</li>\r\n<li>Involving others</li>\r\n<li>External regulations and legislation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(765, 'Module Three - Making customer service personal', '<p>This module explores the practice of providing a tailored service to different customers depending on their personal requirements and explores numerous considerations, such as; using customer cues and information to develop personal service and balancing and managing customer service time.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Systems and procedures for providing the personal touch</li>\r\n<li>Using customer cues and information to develop personal service</li>\r\n<li>Letting customers know that you understand and are there to help</li>\r\n<li>Identifying non-standard opportunities to help customers</li>\r\n<li>Identifying customers with particular personal service needs</li>\r\n<li>Balancing and managing customer service time</li>\r\n<li>Making extra efforts to provide a more personal service</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(766, 'Module Four - Improving the customer relationship', '<p>This module studies the interaction process between the customer and the individual offering the service and examines multiple ways in which this relationship can be improved, through the focus on areas such as; customer feelings and alternative solutions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Improving communication with your customers</li>\r\n<li>Taking the initiative</li>\r\n<li>Customers&rsquo; feelings</li>\r\n<li>Customer expectations</li>\r\n<li>Reasons why you might have to say no</li>\r\n<li>Alternative solutions</li>\r\n<li>Exceeding customer expectations to develop the relationship</li>\r\n<li>Make customers aware</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(767, 'Module Five - Monitoring and solving customer service problems', '<p>This module details the good practice of monitoring customer service problems and examines ways in which problems should be solved through the exploration of relevant areas such as; recognising the problem, when to pass on a problem and taking action to avoid future customer problems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Solve immediate customer service problems</li>\r\n<li>Recognise the problem</li>\r\n<li>System or equipment or procedure failure</li>\r\n<li>When to pass on a problem and work with others</li>\r\n<li>Identifying and solving repeated customer service problems</li>\r\n<li>Taking action to avoid customer service problems reoccurring</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(768, 'Module Six - Processing Customer Service Complaints', '<p>This module studies how those working in customer service should deal with complaints, examining areas of relevance such as; types of complaint, keeping colleagues informed and record keeping.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Signs of customer dissatisfaction</li>\r\n<li>Types of complaint</li>\r\n<li>Dealing effectively with a complaint</li>\r\n<li>Solving customer complaints</li>\r\n<li>Escalating complaints</li>\r\n<li>Keep colleagues informed</li>\r\n<li>Record keeping</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(769, 'Module Seven - Working with others to improve customer service', '<p>This module details the practice of working with other people to help improve the way in which customer service is provided, examining areas of relevance such as; constructive complaints, working positively with others and the negative effects of change.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Improve customer service by working with others</li>\r\n<li>Constructive ideas</li>\r\n<li>Monitor your own performance when improving customer service</li>\r\n<li>Monitor the joint performance when improving customer service</li>\r\n<li>Work positively with others</li>\r\n<li>Negative effects of change</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(770, 'Module Eight - Promoting continuous improvement in customer service', '<p>This module looks at the ways in which customer service can be continually improved, examining relevant areas individuals should consider, such as; feedback from customers, keeping people informed and collecting feedback on changes.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Plan improvements in customer service based on customer feedback</li>\r\n<li>Feedback from your customers</li>\r\n<li>Discuss ideas for improvements with others</li>\r\n<li>Implement changes in customer service</li>\r\n<li>Keep everyone informed</li>\r\n<li>Changes</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(771, 'Module Nine - Developing customer service skills', '<p>This concluding module progresses on the knowledge gained from the previous modules to establish ways in which individuals can develop their acquired customer service skills, examining areas of relevance such as; reviews, opportunities and benefits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Develop your own customer service skills</li>\r\n<li>Personal development plan</li>\r\n<li>Reviews</li>\r\n<li>Plan the development of others in customer service</li>\r\n<li>Identifying training needs</li>\r\n<li>Plan and organise activities</li>\r\n<li>Coach others in customer service</li>\r\n<li>Opportunity</li>\r\n<li>Progress</li>\r\n<li>Benefits</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(772, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(773, 'Module One - Cyber-dependent Crime (I) - Hacking & Hacktivism', '<p>This introductory module is focussed on one of the most widely analysed and debated forms of cybercrime that involves illegal activities such as illicit lock-picking and manipulation of worldwide phone/computer systems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hacking</li>\r\n<li>What do hackers actually do?</li>\r\n<li>Hacktivism</li>\r\n<li>Why do they do it?</li>\r\n<li>Developmental Psychology Theories</li>\r\n<li>Ethical Hacking</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(774, 'Module Two - Cyber-dependent Crime (II) – Malware', '<p>This module is concerned with the creation and use of computer codes and programmes that cause various degrees of disruption to the targeted operation or damage to data. The materials study the most common methods used, the differences between them and the impact they can have on the victim.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Viruses</li>\r\n<li>Anti-virus providers</li>\r\n<li>Worms</li>\r\n<li>Trojans</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(775, 'Module Three - Cyber-dependent Crime (III) - DDoS Attacks', '<p>This module studies the specific cybercrime that involves flooding an online service with bogus traffic, thereby keeping real users from using the service. The materials consider relevant factors involved in this crime, such as; the main processes involved in the DDos attacks, the weaknesses of them and who the typical type of culprit is.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What denial-of-service attacks are</li>\r\n<li>The main processes involved in DDoS attacks</li>\r\n<li>The weaknesses in the majority of DDoS attacks</li>\r\n<li>The difference between DoS and DDoS attacks</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(776, 'Module Four - Cyber-enabled Crime (I) - Cyber-Frauds, Scams & Cons', '<p>This module looks at the widespread cybercrime that preys on those who fall for the criminal&rsquo;s deceit. This is of course the targeting of communications that intend to scam, con or defraud the victim and the module studies the most common ways criminals try to do this and how effective their methods are.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Advanced Fee Fraud</li>\r\n<li>Why do Nigerian scammers say they are from Nigeria?</li>\r\n<li>&lsquo;Fake escrow&rsquo; or &lsquo;Auction&rsquo; Scams</li>\r\n<li>Phishing and Spoofing</li>\r\n<li>Romance Scams</li>\r\n<li>Cyberfrauds, scams &amp; cons: The advantages for cybercriminals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(777, 'Module Five - Cyber-enabled Crime (II) – Theft', '<p>This module provides an insight into cybercriminal activities that are implemented with the aim to steal from the target victim and the materials study prevalent methods such as; internet auction frauds and identity theft.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Internet auction frauds</li>\r\n<li>Theft of computer resources</li>\r\n<li>Identity Theft</li>\r\n<li>Types of e-crime carried out on social networks</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(778, 'Module Six - Cyber-enabled Crime (III) - Sex Offending', '<p>his module covers the sensitive subject area of online sex offending and considers what exactly constitutes this type of crime. The materials study issues such as paedophilia and grooming and examines strategies which are used to help reduce this type of crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Internet Sex Offending</li>\r\n<li>Paedophilia &amp; Grooming</li>\r\n<li>Proliferation of indecent images of children (IIOC)</li>\r\n<li>Investigation of Online Child Sexual Exploitation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(779, 'Module Seven - Cyber-enabled Crime (IV) – Cyberterrorism', '<p>This module considers one of the most pressing cybercrime concerns of modern times, that is the use of technology to facilitate terrorism. The module considers issues such as; defining cyberterrorism, objectives of cyberterrorism and how to tackle the problem.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Towards a definition of cyberterrorism</li>\r\n<li>Different Cyberterrorist Groups</li>\r\n<li>Objectives of Cyberterrorism</li>\r\n<li>Cyberterrorism vs Cybercrime</li>\r\n<li>Towards an understanding of Cyberterrorism</li>\r\n<li>Defining hate</li>\r\n<li>Defining ignorance</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(780, 'Module Eight - Cyberstalking', '<p>This module studies the repeated and persistent attempt by an individual to harass an individual using the internet or an open network. The materials examine the type of individual who might engage in this criminal activity and considers the varying methods used and their level of severity.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Cyberstalker&rsquo;s Profile</li>\r\n<li>Typology of stalkers</li>\r\n<li>The victims</li>\r\n<li>Psychological explanations</li>\r\n<li>Stalking- the limitations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(781, 'Module Nine - Cyberbullying', '<p>This module studies the act of bullying through the use of technology. The materials look at how this differs from conventional bullying, the various online platforms that can be used to facilitate it and how the typical cyberbully perpetrator differs from your typical bully.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Cyberbullying vs bullying</li>\r\n<li>Types of Cyberbullying &amp; Cyberbully</li>\r\n<li>A psychology of Cyberbullying</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(782, 'Module Ten - Organised Cybercrime', '<p>This module now considers cybercrime on a larger scale and examines the types and prevalence of organised cybercrime. The materials look at illegal activities such as human or drug trafficking and considers how criminals utilize online methods to help assist with crimes such as these.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Forms of organised crime</li>\r\n<li>Social engineering</li>\r\n<li>Human trafficking</li>\r\n<li>The organised criminals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(783, 'Module Eleven - Virtual ‘Pirates’: Intellectual property, copyright & piracy', '<p>This module examines the widespread issue whereby individuals obtain and in some cases distribute copyrighted materials. Many individuals are guilty of engaging in this criminal activity, known as Virtual Piracy, and the materials look at what constitutes a crime of this nature and why it is so common in people who would not necessarily be associated with other types of crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Movie Piracy &amp; illegal downloading</li>\r\n<li>Music Piracy &amp; illegal downloading</li>\r\n<li>Internet Piracy of Computer Software</li>\r\n<li>Illegal sharing of copyrighted book content</li>\r\n<li>Revealing the Pirates</li>\r\n<li>Contemporary Copyright Theft</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(784, ' Module Twelve - e-Crime Investigation (I) - Legislation', '<p>This module is concerned with the various laws that are enforced within the UK to try and combat cybercrime. The materials look at which acts of legislation are in force to tackle specific types of cybercrime and examines the effectiveness of each law.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation- Harassment</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Stalking</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Identity Theft &amp; Fraud</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Internet Sex Offending</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Hacking</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Jurisdiction issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(785, 'Module Thirteen - e-Crime Investigation (II) - Digital Evidence', '<p>This module details the importance of obtaining and analysing digital evidence in order to help assist with cybercrime investigations. The materials examine relevant considerations in this process, such as; where to obtain evidence and how to preserve evidence so it is appropriate for court proceedings.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of Digital evidence</li>\r\n<li>Digital evidence- where can it be found</li>\r\n<li>ACPO evidence gathering principles</li>\r\n<li>Digital evidence- the legal perspective</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(786, 'Module Fourteen - e-Crime Investigation (II) – Investigative Strategy & Procedure', '<p>This module is focussed on the procedures in place to investigate cybercrimes and studies the specific actions which are implemented in order to successfully solve a crime, such as; investigative Units and the UK Cyber Security Strategy. The problems associated with tackling these types of crimes is then explored.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Investigative procedure</li>\r\n<li>Investigative Units</li>\r\n<li>Investigation of online child sexual exploitation</li>\r\n<li>The UK Cyber Security Strategy</li>\r\n<li>Investigative problems</li>\r\n<li>Investigative case study</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(787, 'Module Fifteen - Cyber Security – The Threat', '<p>This module considers a wider perspective of cybercrime in relation to the prevention measures we have in place and how effective these may be in relation to the nature of the threat we face from ever evolving cybercriminal activities.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Governmental non-police organisations</li>\r\n<li>Multi-agency cross-sector partnerships</li>\r\n<li>The future of cybersecurity</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(788, 'Module Sixteen - Reducing Cyber Risk', '<p>This concluding module looks at the types of measures that we can take in order to help reduce the risk of cybercrime occurring and the materials focus on areas of relevance, such as; technical protection and additional security measures which can be made.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Basic technical protection from cyber attacks</li>\r\n<li>ICT use and risk in an educational setting</li>\r\n<li>Additional security measures</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(789, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(790, 'Module One - Perceptions of deafness: What is deafness?', '<p>This introductory module explores the condition of hearing loss for individuals. It looks at areas such as; what causes deafness, how people react to people who have hearing problems and signs which may indicate an individual is hard of hearing.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Descriptions of types of hearing loss</li>\r\n<li>Acceptable terminology</li>\r\n<li>Generally unaccepted terms</li>\r\n<li>Describing degrees of hearing loss</li>\r\n<li>Clues which may indicate deafness</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(791, 'Module Two - Communicating with Lip-readers', '<p>This module studies methods individuals can use to aid communication with those hard of hearing, who can lipread. The materials examine a range of considerations of relevance to this process, such as; speech, learning to lipread cued speech.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Communication methods</li>\r\n<li>Written English</li>\r\n<li>Speech</li>\r\n<li>Visible letters and words</li>\r\n<li>Learning to lipread</li>\r\n<li>Cued speech</li>\r\n<li>Speaking to a lip-reader</li>\r\n<li>Choosing an appropriate room</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(792, 'Module Three - Communicating with Deaf Sign Language Users', '<p>This module is focussed in how best to communicate with hard of hearing individuals, who use sign language systems. The materials explore the types of sign language systems used, examines significant differences between each process and looks at the main strategies for learning and implementing the techniques.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sign language systems</li>\r\n<li>British sign language (BSL)</li>\r\n<li>Differences between BSL and English</li>\r\n<li>Advantages and disadvantages of written English</li>\r\n<li>Learning BSL</li>\r\n<li>Facial expression and lip patterns</li>\r\n<li>Communication strategies</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(793, 'Module Four - Assistive Aids', '<p>This module looks at the equipment which is available to support deaf people and where it can be acquired; examining particular aids such as; telephones, doorbells and subtitles.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hearing aids</li>\r\n<li>Induction loops and infrared systems</li>\r\n<li>Telephones</li>\r\n<li>Text communication</li>\r\n<li>Doorbells</li>\r\n<li>Television subtitles</li>\r\n<li>Cinema/ theatre subtitles</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(794, 'Module Five - Communication Professionals', '<p>This module is concerned with the numerous professionals who help to facilitate support for those who are hard of hearing, and the materials examine relevant people, such as; the interpreter, note-takers and lip-speakers.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Teacher of the Deaf (TOD)</li>\r\n<li>Interpreter</li>\r\n<li>Translator</li>\r\n<li>Communication Support Workers</li>\r\n<li>Note-takers</li>\r\n<li>Speech-to-text reporters</li>\r\n<li>Lip-speakers</li>\r\n<li>Communication professional</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(795, 'Module Six - Deaf Community and Culture', '<p>This module explores the population of deaf people as a community who have their own culture and the materials examine relevant areas such as; deaf culture social norms and deaf clubs.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The deaf community</li>\r\n<li>Deaf culture</li>\r\n<li>How does Deaf culture affect being part of the hearing world?</li>\r\n<li>Deaf clubs and other activities</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(796, 'Module Seven - Legislation', '<p>This module examines the numerous laws that are in place to protect the rights of deaf individuals, and the materials focus on areas such as; the Equality Act 2010, types of discrimination and reasonable adjustments.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Background history</li>\r\n<li>Equality Act 2010</li>\r\n<li>What is disability?</li>\r\n<li>Types of discrimination</li>\r\n<li>Making reasonable adjustments</li>\r\n<li>The Human Rights Act 1988 (HRA)</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(797, 'Module Eight - Organisations Supporting People with Hearing loss', '<p>This concluding module studies information on organisations which support people with hearing loss and explains about the work they carry out.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>National organisations</li>\r\n<li>Regional organisations</li>\r\n<li>Umbrella organisations</li>\r\n<li>Local organisations</li>\r\n<li>Online organisations</li>\r\n<li>Commercial companies</li>\r\n<li>Educational materials</li>\r\n<li>Advisory organisations and service providers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(798, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(799, 'Module One - Equality and diversity in society', '<p>This introductory unit aims to establish some of the key definitions and concepts associated with equality and diversity in society and looks at relevant considerations, such as; stereotyping, prejudice and discrimination.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What equality is</li>\r\n<li>What diversity is</li>\r\n<li>The effects of stereotyping and labelling within society</li>\r\n<li>The effects of prejudice and discrimination within society</li>\r\n<li>The ways in which people might choose to describe themselves</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(800, 'Module Two - Equality and diversity in the community', '<p>This unit allows you to apply understanding of equality and diversity to your own community, and to do some investigative work to discover the nature and extent of diversity around you.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The extent of the diversity within a community</li>\r\n<li>The value to communities in creating and maintaining a diverse environment</li>\r\n<li>The potential inequality that can occur within a community</li>\r\n<li>Support services and groups</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(801, 'Module Three - Equality and diversity in the workplace ', '<p>This unit looks at how the knowledge gained from previous modules can be applied with a work environment and looks at relevant consideration, such as; monitoring and protection of rights.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The meaning of equality and diversity in the workplace</li>\r\n<li>How equality and diversity is monitored in the workplace</li>\r\n<li>How the rights of individuals are protected in the workplace</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(802, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(803, 'Module One - Destination Management', '<p>This introductory module explores the specialised role of destination management in terms of providing travel itineraries for clients who require fully exclusive and managed travel, incentive packages and events.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is destination management?</li>\r\n<li>Marketing a destination management company</li>\r\n<li>The role of the destination management company</li>\r\n<li>Key competencies of a destination management company</li>\r\n<li>The itinerary</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(804, 'Module Two - Introduction to the Event Planning Process', '<p>This module introduces the construct of the event planning process and focusses on relevant considerations such as; the event market in Great Britain and the role of the event planner.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The event market in Great Britain</li>\r\n<li>The role of the event planner</li>\r\n<li>Key competences of an event planner</li>\r\n<li>Event planner code of ethics</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(805, 'Module Three - The Venue ', '<p>This module focuses on the process of choosing and organising an appropriate venue to suit your client&rsquo;s needs and examines relevant considerations such as; types of venue, insurance and hiring marquees.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Choosing a venue</li>\r\n<li>Types of venue</li>\r\n<li>Booking the venue for the event</li>\r\n<li>Overnight accommodation</li>\r\n<li>Insurance</li>\r\n<li>Hiring marquees</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(806, 'Module Four - Catering', '<p>This module examines the need for catering at an event and provides guidance on how to arrange and coordinate this process effectively through the focus on areas such as; receptions, wine and dietary requirements,</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Choosing a caterer</li>\r\n<li>Catering options</li>\r\n<li>Receptions</li>\r\n<li>Quantities guidelines</li>\r\n<li>The running order of an event</li>\r\n<li>Dietary requirements</li>\r\n<li>Wine</li>\r\n<li>Other beverages</li>\r\n</ul>', 1);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(807, 'Module Five - Entertainment', '<p>This module looks at the relevance of implementing successful entertainment to suit the requirements of events and looks at numerous considerations of relevance such as; music, themes and speeches.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Music</li>\r\n<li>Requirements for musicians, bands and DJs</li>\r\n<li>Speeches</li>\r\n<li>Toasts</li>\r\n<li>Extra touches to an event</li>\r\n<li>Entertainment budget planner</li>\r\n<li>Theming an event</li>\r\n<li>Flowers and the florist</li>\r\n<li>Locating and using other suppliers of party equipment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(808, 'Module Six - Photographic and Audio-Visual Requirements', '<p>This module examines the role of an event planner in advising about how to engage a photographer, what to look for, when photographs should be needed and at what point they should be taken.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Photography</li>\r\n<li>Videography</li>\r\n<li>Video diary</li>\r\n<li>Webcams</li>\r\n<li>Visual projection</li>\r\n<li>Sound projection</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(809, 'Module Seven - Staging the Event', '<p>After mainly focussing on event preparations, this module looks specifically at the actual staging of the event. The knowledge details an array of relevant considerations such as: staffing, registration and seating plans.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Getting organised</li>\r\n<li>Staffing an event</li>\r\n<li>Delegate packs</li>\r\n<li>Registration</li>\r\n<li>Clearing up</li>\r\n<li>Compiling lists of invitees</li>\r\n<li>Enclosures with invitations</li>\r\n<li>Receiving replies</li>\r\n<li>Seating plans</li>\r\n<li>International travel considerations</li>\r\n<li>Health and safety considerations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(810, 'Module Eight - Preparing Event Proposals', '<p>This module examines the importance for you as an event planner, to produce and maintain portfolios and proposals based on all the events that you have been involved with.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Creating an event portfolio</li>\r\n<li>The types and styles of portfolio</li>\r\n<li>The first meeting</li>\r\n<li>Creating an event proposal</li>\r\n<li>The importance of contractual obligations</li>\r\n<li>Contracts with suppliers</li>\r\n<li>Budgeting</li>\r\n<li>Negotiating with suppliers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(811, 'Module Nine - Marketing and Selling your Events Planning Service', '<p>This module is concerned with the importance of promoting and marketing your event planning services and details relevant guidance on how to do this effectively.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Analysing your business strengths and weaknesses</li>\r\n<li>Developing a marketing campaign</li>\r\n<li>Undertaking market research</li>\r\n<li>Marketing strategy</li>\r\n<li>Marketing action plan</li>\r\n<li>Preparing to negotiate a contract</li>\r\n<li>During negotiations</li>\r\n<li>Closing negotiations and follow-up</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(812, 'Module Ten - Setting up your Business', '<p>This module examines the process of setting up your own event planning business and details important guidance on issues such as; company structure, premises and fees.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Company structure</li>\r\n<li>Company names</li>\r\n<li>Company advice</li>\r\n<li>Premises</li>\r\n<li>Deciding on your fee</li>\r\n<li>Fixed and variable costs</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(813, 'Module Eleven - Preparing your own Task Lists and Action Plans', '<p>This concluding module aims to equip learners with effective techniques for planning their time and organising event planning responsibilities through the exploration of task lists and action plans.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Introduction to task lists</li>\r\n<li>First meeting</li>\r\n<li>Second meeting</li>\r\n<li>Third meeting</li>\r\n<li>Final meeting</li>\r\n<li>Action plan for the day</li>\r\n<li>After the event</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(814, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 1),
(815, 'Module One - Promote effective communication for and about individuals', '<p>This module is concerned with the role as a care worker, in identifying ways of communicating difficult, complex and sensitive issues, in a variety of settings and situations and focusses on areas of relevance such as; supporting individuals to communicate and updating records.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Effective communication</li>\r\n<li>Communicating difficult, complex and sensitive issues</li>\r\n<li>Supporting individuals to communicate</li>\r\n<li>Update and maintain records and reports</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(816, 'Module Two - Promote, monitor and maintain health, safety and security in the work environment', '<p>This module is focussed on how to ensure safe working practices in the role as a health worker are maintained and examines areas of importance such as; minimising risks arising from emergencies and ensuring safety and security of the working environment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Safety and security of the working environment</li>\r\n<li>Health and safety in the working environment</li>\r\n<li>Minimising risks arising from emergencies</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(817, 'Module Three - Promote choice, well-being and the protection of all individuals', '<p>This module looks at how healthcare workers should apply themselves to ensure individuals are supported through positive relationships that promotes important areas such as; choice, independence and protection.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Supportive relationships that promote choice and independence</li>\r\n<li>Diversity and difference of individuals and key people</li>\r\n<li>Protection of all individuals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(818, 'Module Four - Contribute to care planning and review', '<p>The main focus of this module is the assessment, development, implementation and review of individual care plans, and the knowledge contained focusses on the various methods used in order to implement this process successfully.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Assessing the needs and preferences of individuals</li>\r\n<li>The development and implementation of care plans</li>\r\n<li>Reviewing care plans</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(819, 'Module Five - Support individuals to access and use services and facilities', '<p>This module studies the various ways in which the care worker can help to assist individuals in their care to choose, access and use a wide range services and facilities that they may need, such as; transport, meals and personal care.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Supporting individuals to select, access and use services and facilities</li>\r\n<li>Enabling individuals to select, access and use services and facilities</li>\r\n<li>Enabling individuals to evaluate services and facilities used</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(820, 'Module Six - Identify the individual at risk of skin breakdown and undertake the appropriate risk assessment', '<p>This module looks at how individuals in a care setting can develop pressure related breakdown of the skin and examines how the risk of this development is managed though the use of tailored assessment tools; examining areas of relevance such as; reporting, review and evaluation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Individuals at risk of skin breakdown</li>\r\n<li>Risk assessment</li>\r\n<li>Reporting, reviewing and updating risk assessment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(821, 'Module Seven - Administer medication to individuals', '<p>This module is concerned with how individuals working in a health care setting need to prepare, administer and monitor the effects of medication to individuals in their care and also looks at how to produce appropriate records and store medication.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Preparing to administer medication to individuals</li>\r\n<li>Administer, report on and monitor individual&rsquo;s medication</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(822, 'Module Eight - Support individuals through the process of dying', '<p>This concluding module explores the sensitive issue of supporting individuals in care through the process of dying and looks a range of important factors such as; appropriate communication, physical support and emotional support.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Supporting individuals to prepare for death</li>\r\n<li>Supporting individuals through the process of dying</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(823, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(824, 'Module One - Explain the Principles of Healthy Eating', '<p>The aim of this Module is to explain the principles of healthy eating. This will include how diet is linked to health, components of a healthy diet, nutrients in food and also healthy food preparation.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How diet is linked to health</li>\r\n<li>Components of a healthy diet</li>\r\n<li>Nutrients in food and their role in maintaining health</li>\r\n<li>Healthy food preparation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(825, 'Module Two - Consider Nutritional Needs of Different People', '<p>The aim of this Module is to explore the nutritional needs of a variety of individuals. This will include nutritional needs of children, young and older people, special dietary requirements and barriers to healthy eating.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Nutritional needs of children and young people</li>\r\n<li>Nutritional needs of older people</li>\r\n<li>Special dietary requirements</li>\r\n<li>Barriers to healthy eating</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(826, 'Module Three - Use Nutritional Information to Plan Healthy Diets for Individuals', '<p>The aim of this Module is to explore how to use food and nutrition information to plan a healthy diet. We will look at food labelling, food additives and how we can apply principles of healthy eating to our diet.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Food labelling</li>\r\n<li>Food additives</li>\r\n<li>Apply principles of healthy eating</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(827, 'Module One - What is Media?', '<p>This module introduces the mass industry, known as the media. The materials look at its mass audience reach and examines the various elements which are used in the construct of media texts. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Control and regulation</li>\r\n<li>Semiotics</li>\r\n<li>Denotation and connotation</li>\r\n<li>Audience</li>\r\n<li>Institution</li>\r\n<li>Binary oppositions</li>\r\n<li>Ideology</li>\r\n<li>Narrative</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(828, 'Module Two - What is Marketing?', '<p>This module provides an introductory overview to the subject of marketing. It defines exactly what marketing entails and examines areas such as; business values and famous marketing campaigns.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How can marketing benefit a business?</li>\r\n<li>Business values</li>\r\n<li>Famous marketing campaigns</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(829, 'Module Three - Representation - a theoretical perspective', '<p>This module explores the concept of representation within a media text. Simply put, representation is concerned with how something is being portrayed and this module examines a range of media texts to determine how particular places and people etc. are presented to a target audience.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Representation of London and the British people</li>\r\n<li>An alternative view of London</li>\r\n<li>The representation of the working class, focusing on \'This is England\', Meadows, 2007</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(830, 'Module Four - Genre - an institutional and theoretical perspective', '<p>This module assesses the method of classifying media texts, known as genre. The materials explore the various different types of genres available and examines typical traits which constitute a particular genre.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hybrids</li>\r\n<li>Case study: Mars Attacks! 1996</li>\r\n<li>How do genres adapt to changing social economic and political contexts?</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(831, 'Module Five - News and Advertising', '<p>This module studies the two different media forms of news and advertising. The news is concerned with the communication of world events, regarded as being in the public interest and advertising is concerned with the use of communication to help sell a product. Both types of media often interlink and this module explores this relationship.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The target audience of newspapers</li>\r\n<li>Ideologies</li>\r\n<li>The target audience of adverts</li>\r\n<li>Covert advertising</li>\r\n<li>Advertising campaigns</li>\r\n<li>Media and behaviour</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(832, 'Module Six - Broadcast TV and Film', '<p>This module considers the two mass media forms that are both visually consumed. Broadcast TV and film are arguably the biggest media forms and are both studied in terms of their role in entertaining the target consumer.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Media techniques used in TV shows</li>\r\n<li>The role of characters in broadcast TV</li>\r\n<li>TV and audience</li>\r\n<li>Media techniques used in film</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(833, 'Module Seven - Traditional Marketing', '<p>This module is focused on the study of traditional methods for marketing and explores well established techniques that utilize avenues such as; television advertising, public relations (PR) and personal selling.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Print advertising</li>\r\n<li>Television advertising</li>\r\n<li>Radio advertising</li>\r\n<li>Direct marketing</li>\r\n<li>Sales promotions</li>\r\n<li>Public Relations (PR)</li>\r\n<li>Word-of-mouth</li>\r\n<li>Personal selling</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(834, 'Module Eight - New Marketing', '<p>This module is concerned with the sub-branch of marketing that involves the promotion of products or brands, as well as communication with stakeholders, via different forms of electronic media. This method is known as digital marketing and it encompasses a range of areas, such as; blogging, SEO and social networking.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Website</li>\r\n<li>Social media</li>\r\n<li>Visual</li>\r\n<li>Video</li>\r\n<li>Networking</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(835, 'Module Nine - The Marketing Mix', '<p>This module explores the tool used by businesses and marketers when promoting products and services, known as the marketing mix. This encompasses four key elements known as the four P\'s and the materials contained examines each of these in detail.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Product - defining the brand</li>\r\n<li>Price - establishing a market position</li>\r\n<li>Place - identifying the target market</li>\r\n<li>Promotion - reaching customers</li>\r\n<li>Extended marketing mix</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(836, 'Module Ten - Creating and Implementing a Marketing Strategy', '<p>This module looks at the steps that should be made when you plan to get started with your marketing efforts. It examines relevant areas, such as; the importance of self-assessment and provides guidance on creating an appropriate strategy for achieving your goals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>SWOT analysis</li>\r\n<li>Your marketing strategy</li>\r\n<li>Evaluation</li>\r\n<li>Consistency, control and goals</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(837, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(838, 'Module One - Areas of Mediation', '<p>This introductory module provides an overview of the various avenues for mediation and aims to equip learners with an understanding of the mediation process.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Family mediation</li>\r\n<li>Community mediation</li>\r\n<li>Workplace mediation</li>\r\n<li>Victim/ offender mediation</li>\r\n<li>The mediation process</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(839, 'Module Two - Communication', '<p>This module details the essential need for efficient communication when providing mediation services and explains relevant techniques to effectively implement this skill.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Active Listening</li>\r\n<li>Verbal Communication</li>\r\n<li>Non Verbal Communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(840, 'Module Three - Understanding the Mediation Process', '<p>Expanding on the knowledge provided in the first module, this module focuses specifically on the mediation process, examining areas such as: referrals, confidentiality and ground rules.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Referrals</li>\r\n<li>Practice Standards for Mediators</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(841, 'Module Four - Types of Mediation', '<p>This module focusses specifically at the different types of mediation and aims to instil learner understanding through the examination of various case studies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Case study 1: A Family Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Case study 2: A community mediation</li>\r\n<li>Case study 3: A workplace mediation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(842, 'Module Five - Family Mediation', '<p>The course now begins to look at each mediation type in turn and this module first examines family mediation. The materials contained focus on relevant issues such as: family communication breakdown and a lack of contact.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The process</li>\r\n<li>A positive and safe environment</li>\r\n<li>Age appropriate language</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(843, 'Module Six - Community Mediation', '<p>This module now focusses on community mediation and explores relevant issues such as: the disputes that arise between residential neighbours and how these can be caused be a multitude of factors.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Boundaries</li>\r\n<li>Children and Young People</li>\r\n<li>Animals</li>\r\n<li>Parking</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(844, 'Module Seven - Workplace Mediation', '<p>This module now focusses on workplace mediation and explores relevant issues such as: the impact that conflict can have in the workplace and the ways in which disputes can be resolved.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bullying</li>\r\n<li>Redundancy</li>\r\n<li>Dismissal</li>\r\n<li>Staff Morale</li>\r\n<li>Promotion</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(845, 'Module Eight - Victim/Offender Mediation', '<p>This module now focusses on victim/offender mediation and explores relevant issues such as: the types of crime that victim/offender mediation can help, victim priority and benefits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Case Study</li>\r\n<li>Background</li>\r\n<li>Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Follow Up</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(846, 'Module Nine - Other Types of Mediation', '<p>Having focussed on the main avenues and strategies for mediation, this module now looks at some of the lesser known types of mediation and also examines areas such as: evaluation and the case summary sheet.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Peer Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Global Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Consumer Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Evaluation</li>\r\n<li>A Natural Victim?</li>\r\n<li>Mediation Words and Phrases</li>\r\n<li>Case Summary Sheet</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(847, 'Module Ten - Summary', '<p>This concluding module looks back and examines the course as a whole to consolidate and recap on all the skills you have learned so far. The pertinent points from all the modules are summarised.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Family Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Workplace Mediation</li>\r\n<li>Victim/Offender Mediation</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(848, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(849, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(850, 'Module One - The Wedding Planning Process', '<p>This introductory module establishes the concept of marriage through the exploration of areas such as its history and general trends, before then examining the key roles of a wedding planner.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>History of Marriage</li>\r\n<li>General Wedding Trends</li>\r\n<li>The Wedding Market in Great Britain</li>\r\n<li>The role of the Wedding Planner</li>\r\n<li>Key competences of a Wedding Planner</li>\r\n<li>Wedding Planner code of ethics</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(851, 'Module Two - The Marriage Ceremony', '<p>This module studies the necessities of the Marriage Ceremony and provides guidance on relevant considerations such as: the required documentation, wedding vows and the wedding rings.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Law of Marriage</li>\r\n<li>Required Documentation</li>\r\n<li>The Ceremony</li>\r\n<li>Civil Partnerships</li>\r\n<li>Marriages Abroad</li>\r\n<li>Wedding Vows</li>\r\n<li>Rings</li>\r\n<li>Pre-Nuptial Agreements</li>\r\n<li>Wills and Testaments</li>\r\n<li>Roles Required at a Wedding</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(852, 'Module Three - The Venue', '<p>This module looks at the process of arranging the wedding venue/s. The materials contained explore relevant areas such as: the types of venues that may be considered, insurance and engaging in venue site visits.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Choosing a Venue</li>\r\n<li>Types of Venues</li>\r\n<li>The Law Applicable to Licensed Venues</li>\r\n<li>Booking the Venue for the Wedding Reception</li>\r\n<li>Overnight Accommodation</li>\r\n<li>Insurance</li>\r\n<li>Hiring Marquees</li>\r\n<li>Site Visits at Venues</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(853, 'Module Four - Themes', '<p>This module examines how the application of a designated theme can add value to a wedding. The materials contained suggest an array of theme related ideas and provides guidance on relevant areas such as flowers and party equipment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Theme a wedding</li>\r\n<li>Seasonal Themes expanded</li>\r\n<li>Flowers and the Florist&rsquo;s Role at a Wedding</li>\r\n<li>Locating and using other suppliers of party equipment</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(854, 'Module Five - Catering', '<p>This module examines the whole process of arranging food and drink at a wedding. The materials contained provide guidance on what should be included, and details the organisational factors needed to effectively implement a successful catering schedule.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Choosing a Caterer</li>\r\n<li>The Reception Drinks And Canap&eacute;s</li>\r\n<li>Quantities Guidelines</li>\r\n<li>Wedding meals</li>\r\n<li>The Running Order of the Wedding Reception</li>\r\n<li>Dietary Requirements</li>\r\n<li>Wedding Cakes</li>\r\n<li>Wine</li>\r\n<li>Other Beverages</li>\r\n<li>Corkage Charges</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(855, 'Module Six - Printed material and wedding gift lists', '<p>This module considers the process of constructing relevant written communications for a wedding. A range of relevant areas such as: guest lists, invitations and seating plans are examined and guidance how to produce these effectively is detailed.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Guest List</li>\r\n<li>Invitations</li>\r\n<li>Enclosures with Invitations</li>\r\n<li>Receiving Replies</li>\r\n<li>Order of Service</li>\r\n<li>Wedding List</li>\r\n<li>Thank You Letters</li>\r\n<li>Seating Plans</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(856, 'Module Seven - Entertainment', '<p>This module details the entertainment requirements which are likely to be appropriate when organising a wedding. The materials contained look at pre wedding and wedding day arrangements, exploring areas such as: Stag/Hen party, the music and speeches.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Stag Party and Hen Night</li>\r\n<li>The First Dance</li>\r\n<li>Music during the Wedding</li>\r\n<li>Requirements for Musicians, Bands and DJ&rsquo;s</li>\r\n<li>Speeches</li>\r\n<li>Toasts</li>\r\n<li>Children at a Wedding</li>\r\n<li>Extra Touches to a Wedding</li>\r\n<li>Entertainment Budget Planner</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(857, 'Module Eight - Transportation', '<p>This module aims to equip learners with knowledge on the different types of transport which may be required at a wedding and provides guidance on the booking and management of these arrangements.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Parties requiring transportation</li>\r\n<li>Horse Drawn Carriages</li>\r\n<li>Bridal Cars</li>\r\n<li>International Travel Considerations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(858, 'Module Nine - Photography', '<p>This module explores the practice of capturing all the desired moments from a wedding, through photographs and other methods. The materials contained examine relevant areas such as, providing advice and discussing requirements with suppliers.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Photography</li>\r\n<li>Videographer</li>\r\n<li>Video Diary</li>\r\n<li>Webcams</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(859, 'Module Ten - Bridal Party Attire', '<p>This module considers how different people will dress for a wedding and provides appropriate information on relevant areas such as: styles of wedding dress, health and beauty considerations and male attire. The materials contained should equip learners with the knowledge needed to give appropriate advice.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Bride&rsquo;s Dress</li>\r\n<li>Veils and Headdress Pieces</li>\r\n<li>Bridal Accessories</li>\r\n<li>Male Attire</li>\r\n<li>Health and Beauty Arrangements</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(860, 'Module Eleven - Preparing wedding proposals', '<p>This module examines how to construct and use wedding proposals with potential/new clients. The materials contained explore relevant areas such as: creating a portfolio, creating a proposal, contractual obligations and the importance of implementing these effectively.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Creating your Wedding Portfolio</li>\r\n<li>The Types and Styles of Portfolio</li>\r\n<li>Your First Meeting</li>\r\n<li>Creating a Wedding Proposal</li>\r\n<li>The Importance of Contractual Obligations</li>\r\n<li>Contracts with Suppliers</li>\r\n<li>Budgeting</li>\r\n<li>Negotiating with Suppliers</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(861, 'Module Twelve - Marketing and selling your Wedding Planning Service', '<p>Having now examined the wedding planning process, this module looks at appropriate approaches such as: a marketing strategy, an action plan and negotiations that should be implemented in order to effectively market and sell your services to potential clients.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Analysing your Strengths and Weaknesses</li>\r\n<li>Developing a marketing campaign</li>\r\n<li>Undertaking market research</li>\r\n<li>Marketing Strategy</li>\r\n<li>Marketing Action Plan</li>\r\n<li>Preparing to Negotiating a Contract</li>\r\n<li>During the Negotiations</li>\r\n<li>Closing the Negotiations and Follow Up</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(862, 'Module Thirteen - Setting up your business', '<p>Having now studied the process of planning a wedding and promoting your services, this module examines how to establish and maintain a successful wedding planner business. The materials contained focus on specific areas of consideration, such as: company structure, premises and fees.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Company Structure</li>\r\n<li>Company Names</li>\r\n<li>Company Advice</li>\r\n<li>Premises</li>\r\n<li>Deciding on your Fee</li>\r\n<li>Fixed and Variable Costs</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(863, 'Module Fourteen - Preparing your own Task Lists and Action Plans', '<p>This concluding module aims to teach learners about suitable techniques to organise their wedding planning responsibilities, as discussed in previous modules. The materials contained explain how to create task lists and action plans, and provides guidance on when to use them.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Introduction to Task Lists</li>\r\n<li>The First Meeting</li>\r\n<li>Second Meeting</li>\r\n<li>Third meeting</li>\r\n<li>Fourth meeting</li>\r\n<li>Action Plan for the Wedding Day</li>\r\n<li>After the Wedding</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(864, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(865, 'Module One - Understand Children’s and Young People’s Development', '<p>This introductory unit provides a thorough insight into the development of children and young people, exploring numerous avenues such typical child development, factors affecting this and responding to developmental problems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Expected child development from birth-19 years</li>\r\n<li>Factors affecting child development</li>\r\n<li>Monitoring child development</li>\r\n<li>Early intervention</li>\r\n<li>Possible transition effects</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(866, 'Module Two - Understand How to Safeguard the Wellbeing of Children and Young People', '<p>This unit details the potential issues that can impact on a child and young person\'s wellbeing, covering issues such as child abuse and bullying and also provides guidance on how to safeguard against these problems in line with relevant legislation, guidelines, policies and procedures.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation, guidelines, policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>Working in partnership with organisations</li>\r\n<li>Children and young people\'s safety and protection in the work setting</li>\r\n<li>Child Protection and Safeguarding</li>\r\n<li>Child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Bullying</li>\r\n<li>Supporting child safety and well-being</li>\r\n<li>E-safety</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(867, 'Module Three - Communication and Professional Relationships with Children, Young People, and Adults', '<p>This unit provides guidance on developing professional relationships with a range of people in an educational setting and places a specific focus on the role of effective communication and its importance.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Principles of positive relationships with children, young people and adults</li>\r\n<li>Communication with children, young people and adults</li>\r\n<li>Legislation, policies and procedures for confidentiality and sharing information, including data protection</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(868, 'Module Four - Schools as Organisations', '<p>This unit explores how schools are established as organisations and focusses on relevant areas such as the varying structures, different ways of doing things and applicable roles and responsibilities.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Education structure</li>\r\n<li>Roles and responsibilities in schools</li>\r\n<li>School ethos, mission, aims and values</li>\r\n<li>School legislation</li>\r\n<li>School policies and procedures</li>\r\n<li>School operations</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(869, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(870, 'Completion', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(871, 'Completion', '<p>Once you have completed your last module, please email&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:support@ncchomelearning.co.uk\">support@ncchomelearning.co.uk</a>&nbsp;(note: do not email the support team unless your last module has been marked as passed).</p>', 0),
(872, 'test', '<p>test</p>', 0),
(873, 'Knowledge and Exam', '<p>Please download the underpinning knowledge to understand this course. Once you are confident that you have a full understanding of the subject area, please complete the exam.</p>', 0),
(874, 'Module 1 - Introduction', '<p id=\"yui_3_17_2_1_1515153262378_103\">This module is a detailed introduction defining exactly what counselling is, focussing<strong>&nbsp;</strong>on its specific functions. To enhance this knowledge the module goes on to detail the history of the subject area before discussing why counselling might be needed. &nbsp;Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What counselling is and isn&rsquo;t</li>\r\n<li>How counselling differs from other helping skills (such as advice-giving, guidance, befriending, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Core skills involved in counselling</li>\r\n<li>Confidentiality issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(875, 'Module 2 - Models and approaches of helping', '<p>This module explores all the ins and outs relating to the theoretical techniques which are applied, in order to help individuals deliver effective counselling practice to their clients. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Counselling approaches &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>The principles of skilled helping</li>\r\n<li>The use and effects of questions</li>\r\n<li>Challenges to clients&rsquo; views</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(876, 'Module 3 - Working with feelings', '<p>This module summarises how the role of thoughts and particularly flawed thinking can affect people. The content goes on to explore the various ways in which thoughts can be challenged and how you can help motivate people to make a change. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul id=\"yui_3_17_2_1_1515153262378_109\">\r\n<li>Exploring the subject of change: its impacts and challenges</li>\r\n<li>Consideration of Boundaries and Ethics</li>\r\n<li>Setting goals, planning action &ndash; and dealing with resistance</li>\r\n<li id=\"yui_3_17_2_1_1515153262378_108\">Ending the counselling skills relationship &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(877, 'Module 4 - Goals and moving on', '<p>This module expands on previous knowledge to establish a counsellor&rsquo;s role in helping aid client recovery, through the implementation of numerous techniques. Following this the content goes on to explore counselling as a career. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Supervision: its importance in good practice</li>\r\n<li>Competence in record-keeping</li>\r\n<li>The importance of Continuing Personal Development (CPD) and taking care of YOU</li>\r\n<li>Using your counselling skills&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(878, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through the Underpinning Knowledge you should of&nbsp;gained the Knowledge to take the Exam.</p>', 0),
(879, 'Module One - Introducing Research Methods', '<p>This introductory module looks at the forensic psychologist&rsquo;s role in conducting research in order to inform a criminal case. Relevant areas such as; different types of research projects, experiments and research methods, are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Research design</li>\r\n<li>Exploratory, descriptive and explanatory projects</li>\r\n<li>Standardising the experiment</li>\r\n<li>Research methods</li>\r\n<li>Instruments</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(880, 'Module Two - Introducing Basic Statistics', '<p>This module studies the forensic psychologist&rsquo;s role in applying statistical probabilities to behaviours and events in order to obtain an understanding of criminal probability. Relevant techniques such as creating a likert scale and a histogram are examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Probability</li>\r\n<li>Independent variable</li>\r\n<li>Relative frequency</li>\r\n<li>Likert scale</li>\r\n<li>Histogram</li>\r\n<li>Random Sample and population</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(881, 'Module Three - Psychology and Violent Crime', '<p>This module examines the relationship between violent crime and psychological processes, critiquing particular mental illness explanations for crime and exploring the impact of areas such as anti-social lifestyles and football hooliganism.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schizophrenia and violence</li>\r\n<li>Psychopathy and violence</li>\r\n<li>Interpersonal traits</li>\r\n<li>Anti-social lifestyle</li>\r\n<li>Frustration and violence</li>\r\n<li>Football hooliganism</li>\r\n<li>Expressive aggression</li>\r\n<li>Instrumental aggression</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(882, 'Module Four - Serial Killers', '<p>This module focusses on the exploration of different types of serial killer traits and covers a number of pertinent examples in order to gain a varied understanding of serial killer behaviour.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Frederick Harold Shipman murders</li>\r\n<li>The Yorkshire Ripper murders</li>\r\n<li>The Alton Coleman murders</li>\r\n<li>The Beverley Allit murders</li>\r\n<li>Causality and serial murder</li>\r\n</ul>', 1),
(883, 'Module Five - Crime and Substance Abuse', '<p>This module covers the issue of substance misuse and examines how this impacts upon criminal activity. Relevant areas such as the social and economic costs of substance misuse and government approaches are examined.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Drug legality</li>\r\n<li>Costs of legal substance abuse</li>\r\n<li>The link between crime and substance abuse</li>\r\n<li>Government approaches to substance abuse related crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(884, 'Module Six - Child Abuse', '<p>This module details the criminal act of child abuse in its many forms such as; physical, emotional, sexual or as a result of neglect and looks at pertinent issues such as the signs of abuse and what effect these may have.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Signs of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Effects of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Sexual offending explanations</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(885, 'Module Seven - The Evidence of Children', '<p>This module looks at the rare usage of children in criminal proceedings and highlights the specific actions involved in this process before examining the multiple issues that this process can create.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Interviewing child witnesses</li>\r\n<li>Sources of child suggestibility</li>\r\n<li>A child&rsquo;s fitness to act as a witness</li>\r\n<li>Evidence of children in court</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(886, 'Module Eight - Criminal Responsibility and Psychiatric Defences', '<p>This module focusses on the assessment of a criminal&rsquo;s state of mind in determining whether they have any mental illnesses which would be likely to affect their sentencing procedures, in accordance with modern day laws.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The conflicting roles of the forensic psychologist</li>\r\n<li>Defining mental disorder</li>\r\n<li>Unfitness to plead</li>\r\n<li>The Domestic Violence, Crime and Victims Act, 2004</li>\r\n<li>Infanticide</li>\r\n<li>Diminished responsibility</li>\r\n<li>Not guilty by reason of insanity</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(887, 'Module Nine - Mental Disorder as a Defence', '<p>This module looks at the occurrence of special mental disorders which have been used to support a defensive claim of diminished responsibility or freedom from a criminal conviction and examines in which instances a claim is valid.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dissociative identity disorder (Multiple personality disorder)</li>\r\n<li>Amnesia</li>\r\n<li>Post-traumatic stress disorder</li>\r\n<li>Dangerous and severe personality disorder</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(888, 'Module Ten - Eyewitness Testimony', '<p>This module focusses on eyewitness accounts of criminal activity, looking at the types of memories that are likely to be reaffirmed and examines their uses and possible problems with reliability.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eyewitness memory</li>\r\n<li>Conceptual memories</li>\r\n<li>Perception, memory and eyewitness testimony</li>\r\n<li>Personal perception and memory</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(889, 'Module Eleven - Psychology in a Correctional Setting', '<p>This module is concerned with the study of prisoner mental health assessment and explores a number of relevant issues such as; suicides in prison, the psychological effect of imprisonment and re-offending.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Beginning the sentence</li>\r\n<li>Suicides in prison</li>\r\n<li>The psychological effects of imprisonment</li>\r\n<li>Re-offending and risk assessment</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(890, 'Module Twelve - Psychology and Police Selection, Recruitment and Training', '<p>This module studies the recruitment process involved in the selection of appropriate candidates for the police force. A range of relevant areas are covered such as; police training, personality tests and the police curriculum.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Selection and the police personality</li>\r\n<li>Psychology and police training</li>\r\n<li>Student officer training</li>\r\n<li>Curriculum</li>\r\n<li>The Professional Investigation Programme</li>\r\n<li>Police promotion</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(891, 'Module Thirteen - Police Stress', '<p>This module explores the relationship between stress and the police force and examines areas of relevance such as factors that contribute to stress and stress research.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining stress</li>\r\n<li>Stress factors</li>\r\n<li>Stress research</li>\r\n<li>Stress in the workplace</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(892, 'Module Fourteen - The Decision to Assist', '<p>This module assesses the behaviour of individuals in relation their response to witnessing a crime in public places. Relevant areas such as the different types of public responses and the behaviour of the authorities are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The unresponsive bystander</li>\r\n<li>An impulsive bystander</li>\r\n<li>Models for bystander behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour of the authorities</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(893, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read all the underpinning Knowledge you will have the required information to complete the Exam.</p>', 1),
(894, 'Module One - What is Autism?', '<p>his introductory module defines what the term Autism actually means and explores the common problems associated with this condition in addition to the potential strengths that people with autism may have.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Triad of Impairments</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social interaction</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social communication and language</li>\r\n<li>Problems with social imagination</li>\r\n<li>Sensory problems</li>\r\n<li>Asperger\'s Syndrome</li>\r\n<li>The strengths of children with autism</li>\r\n<li>Conditions related to autism</li>\r\n<li>Who has autism</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(895, 'Module Two - Autism and Education', '<p>This module studies the occurrence of autism in children within educational environments, looking at how to be aware of this and provide appropriate support to help with the numerous barriers that these children may face.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Educational service for autistic children</li>\r\n<li>Key principles of good practice in education</li>\r\n<li>Recognising ASC\'s in Schools</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(896, 'Module Three - What is Challenging Behaviour?', '<p>This module looks specifically at the different types of behaviour that children with autism may present in an educational environment that could be seen as challenging, focusing on why these may occur and how they can be controlled.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reasons children with autism display challenging behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Challenging behaviours</li>\r\n<li>Physical causes of challenging behaviour</li>\r\n<li>Labelling and challenging behaviour</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(897, 'Module Four - Learning Styles and Autism', '<p>This module looks at the range of varying learning styles which can be applied to individuals with autism to help promote their positive learning experience in a learning environment.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Different learning styles</li>\r\n<li>Typical autism associated learning styles</li>\r\n<li>Key features of learning styles</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(898, 'Module Five - Supporting Understanding of Other People', '<p>This module is concerned with how people working in an educational setting can help children with autism to gain an understanding of other people through the focus on relevant areas such as eye contact, turn taking and play.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Using eyes for communication</li>\r\n<li>Shared attention with others</li>\r\n<li>Feeling other people\'s emotions</li>\r\n<li>Making and maintaining friends and relationships</li>\r\n<li>Personal space and proximity</li>\r\n<li>Turn taking</li>\r\n<li>Understanding other people think differently than us</li>\r\n<li>Understanding facial expressions and body language</li>\r\n<li>Play</li>\r\n<li>Different settings</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(899, 'Module Six - Supporting Communication', '<p>This module highlights problems that children with autism are likely to experience with regards to applying communication skills and how these can be identified and dealt with in terms of staff providing appropriate support to individuals.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Visual communication</li>\r\n<li>Intensive interaction</li>\r\n<li>Verbal communication</li>\r\n<li>Musical communication</li>\r\n<li>Awareness of own communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(900, 'Module Seven - Building Positive relationships and achieving diversity', '<p>This module studies the concerning realisation that children with autism may be vulnerable to bullies and examines the ways in which teachers can help to support children in building positive relationships to reduce this vulnerability.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bullying</li>\r\n<li>Why are children with autism vulnerable to bullying?</li>\r\n<li>Positive relationships</li>\r\n<li>The circle of friends approach</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(901, 'Module Eight - Supporting work and the curriculum', '<p>This concluding module examines the ways in which teachers can provide appropriate support to help children with autism achieve in school subjects, focusing on relevant factors such as structured time and promoting the hidden curriculum.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The hidden curriculum</li>\r\n<li>The planned curriculum</li>\r\n<li>The National Curriculum</li>\r\n<li>Supporting Literacy</li>\r\n<li>Supporting Numeracy</li>\r\n<li>Support during IT</li>\r\n<li>Support throughout the school day</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(902, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read all the underpinning Knowledge you will have the required information to complete the Exam.</p>', 1),
(903, 'Module One - Legislation covering Speech, Language and Communication (SLC) Difficulties in Education', '<ul>\r\n<li>What is meant by speech, language and communication (SLC) difficulties?</li>\r\n<li>Legislation</li>\r\n<li>Prevalence of SLC amongst children and young people</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(904, 'Module Two - To Support a Child or Young person with Speech, Language and Communication difficulties in Education', '<p>This module provides an overview for teachers of the main types of speech, language and communication difficulties that pupils may present within mainstream schools along with brief examples as to how pupil needs can be met.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of speech, language and communication</li>\r\n<li>Identifying and supporting the behaviours of pupils with speech, language and communication difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Supporting mechanisms for speech, language and communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 0);
INSERT INTO `topic` (`id`, `name`, `summary`, `required`) VALUES
(905, 'Module Three - Teaching strategies to support Speech, Language and Communication Difficulties', '<p>This module looks at the planning of activities used to support speech, language and communication difficulties in education, considering areas such as; activity strategies and pragmatic use of language to assist with speech, language and communication difficulties.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Activity strategies</li>\r\n<li>Identifying and supporting the social use of language in speech, language and communication difficulties</li>\r\n<li>Pragmatic use of speech, language and communication difficulties</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(906, 'Module Four - Additional resources for Speech, Language and Communication difficulties in Education', '<p>This module studies the additional resources which can be made available to help assist with speech, language and communication difficulties in education and considers signs which may indicate that these resources are required.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What if things aren&rsquo;t working?</li>\r\n<li>Further support for parents/carers/settings</li>\r\n<li>Inclusion Development Programme supporting children with Speech, Language and Communication needs: Guidance for practitioners in the Early Years Foundation Stage</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(907, 'Module Five - English as an Additional Language', '<p>This module is concerned with the different speech, language and communication strategies used to help achieve effective communication for someone who has English as an additional language.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Structure and staffing</li>\r\n<li>Family and community</li>\r\n<li>The child&rsquo;s voice</li>\r\n<li>The importance of home languages</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(908, 'Module Six - Relationships to Dyslexia, Dyspraxia and ADHD with Speech, Language and Communication Difficulties', '<p>This concluding module explores the relationship between Dyslexia, Dyspraxia and ADHD, considering their often overlapping nature and establishes learning techniques which can be implemented to help combat the problems associated with the conditions.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The relationship between Dyslexia and Speech, Language and Communication</li>\r\n<li>The relationship between Dyspraxia and Speech, Language and Communication</li>\r\n<li>The relationship between ADHD and Speech, Language and communication</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(909, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through the Underpinning Knowledge you should of gained the Knowledge to take the Exam.</p>', 1),
(910, 'Unit One - The key features of child development and developmental needs of children 0-8 years inclusive of individual and special needs', '<p>This introductory module studies the process of initial child development and how this differs between those with special needs and those without, though the examination of relevant areas such as; special needs, transitions and the effects of discrimination.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The main development of a child from birth to 8 years</li>\r\n<li>Social, economic and environmental factors affecting development</li>\r\n<li>Genetic and hereditary factors affecting development</li>\r\n<li>Children&rsquo;s overall developmental needs</li>\r\n<li>Special needs</li>\r\n<li>Transitions</li>\r\n<li>Policies to meet diversity within the childminding sector</li>\r\n<li>Inclusion within the childminding sector</li>\r\n<li>Effects of discrimination</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(911, 'Unit Two - Providing for children’s physical needs inclusive of health and safety', '<p>This module is concerned with the importance of meeting a child&rsquo;s physical needs such as nutrition and rest and also ensuring that their health and safety is maintained. The knowledge contained examines ways in which these requirements should be achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Meeting the children&rsquo;s nutritional needs</li>\r\n<li>Meeting children&rsquo;s rest and sleep needs</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour in children</li>\r\n<li>Behaviour attributed to specific special needs</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining appropriate hygiene procedures</li>\r\n<li>Childhood illnesses</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining a safe and secure environment</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(912, 'Unit Three - Learning through play for child development', '<p>This module focusses on the practise of play, examining how its various types have a great importance in the process of child development and the knowledge contained provides advice on how appropriate play should be promoted and organised.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of play and their importance in relation to child development</li>\r\n<li>Observation and planning</li>\r\n<li>Every Child Matters and the Birth to Three Matters Framework</li>\r\n<li>The Early Years Foundation Stage</li>\r\n<li>Available resources in relation to Health and Safety, and Diversity and Inclusion</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(913, 'Unit Four - Safeguarding and promoting the welfare of children', '<p>This module studies the sensitive subject area of child abuse and examines the role of the childminder in relation to having an awareness of when this may be happening to any child in their care and what to do in these instances.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is safeguarding?</li>\r\n<li>Definitions of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>The main categories of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Signs and symptoms of child abuse</li>\r\n<li>Procedures to follow in the case of child protection concerns</li>\r\n<li>Documentation</li>\r\n<li>Sources of support</li>\r\n<li>Some practical guidance</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(914, 'Unit Five - Legal responsibilities of the childminder and responsibilities for working together', '<p>This concluding module focusses on the legal responsibilities mandatory to those looking after children and details specific guidance on complying with areas such as; OFSTED requirements and following procedures for admission and collection.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Childminder&rsquo;s legislation</li>\r\n<li>Legal responsibilities of the childminder</li>\r\n<li>Procedures for admission and collection</li>\r\n<li>Legal implications of childminding</li>\r\n<li>Policies and procedures to meet OFSTED requirements</li>\r\n<li>Working in partnership with parents and other professionals</li>\r\n<li>The childminder&rsquo;s responsibilities for building positive relationships with parents and other professionals in relation to</li>\r\n<li>Exploring contacts for support for childminding services</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(915, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through all the Underpinning Knowledge you will have gained the knowledge to take the exam.</p>', 1),
(916, 'Module One - Working Effectively with Other People', '<p>This introductory module looks at how individuals should apply themselves in order to work effectively with other people in the business environment, studying areas of relevance such as; communication, work goals and plans.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of working effectively with other people</li>\r\n<li>Working with others to achieve positive outcomes</li>\r\n<li>Effective communication</li>\r\n<li>Communicating with colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Work goals and plans</li>\r\n<li>The strengths of others</li>\r\n<li>Team diversity</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(917, 'Module Two - Carrying out your Responsibilities effectively', '<p>This module explores effective ways in which individuals should carry out their job and examines relevant areas that should be considered, such as; effective communication, planning work and contribution.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Importance of effective communication</li>\r\n<li>Focussing on the communication of others</li>\r\n<li>Clear and accurate information</li>\r\n<li>Communication adaption</li>\r\n<li>Discussion and meeting contribution</li>\r\n<li>Written information</li>\r\n<li>Planning work</li>\r\n<li>Work targets</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(918, 'Module Three - Work within your Business Environment', '<p>This module is focussed on the type of work and considerations relevant to an administrator&rsquo;s role and examines areas such as; employment law, the contract of employment and working to achieve your organisation&rsquo;s purpose and values.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Responsibilities at work</li>\r\n<li>How your role relates to organisational structure</li>\r\n<li>Policies, procedures, systems and organisational values</li>\r\n<li>Employment law</li>\r\n<li>Your contract of employment</li>\r\n<li>Working to achieve your organisation&rsquo;s purpose and values</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(919, 'Module Four - Health and Safety', '<p>This module is concerned with health and safety in the workplace and how this affects individuals working in an administrative role. The contained knowledge examines areas of relevance such as; workplace hazards, dealing with risks and safe working practices and the specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legal duties required by the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974</li>\r\n<li>Your health and safety duties as defined by specific legislation covering your job role</li>\r\n<li>Workplace hazards</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with risks</li>\r\n<li>Your responsibility for health and safety in your job description</li>\r\n<li>Suppliers&rsquo; and manufacturers&rsquo; instructions for the safe use of office equipment, materials and products</li>\r\n<li>The safe working practices for your job role</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(920, 'Module Five - Managing Customer Relations', '<p>This module studies the process of liaising with customers in a business, and explores how this relates to those working in administration, through the examination of areas such as; customer needs, customer relations and customer complaints.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who customers are</li>\r\n<li>Effective and efficient customer service</li>\r\n<li>Positive working relationships with customers</li>\r\n<li>Customer needs</li>\r\n<li>Quality standards</li>\r\n<li>Customer problems</li>\r\n<li>Customer complaints</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(921, 'Module Six - Storing, Retrieving and Archiving Information', '<p>This module details the steps involved in processing information in a business and examines areas that administrators should consider, such as; collecting information, accessing information systems and providing information within agreed timescales.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Information systems and their main features</li>\r\n<li>Legal and organisational requirements covering the security and confidentiality of information</li>\r\n<li>Collecting information</li>\r\n<li>Accessing information systems</li>\r\n<li>Accurate information</li>\r\n<li>Information system problems</li>\r\n<li>Providing information in the required format and agreed timescales</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(922, 'Module Seven - Using IT effectively to exchange information', '<p>This module studies the use of IT facilities in a business and examines how those working in administration need to efficiently utilise communication software such as email, in order to exchange information.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Send and receive emails using an address book</li>\r\n<li>Email archiving and compression</li>\r\n<li>Email problems and how to avoid them</li>\r\n<li>How to keep the difficulties of sending &amp; receiving large emails to a minimum</li>\r\n<li>Email storage limitations</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(923, 'Module Eight - Operating Office Equipment', '<p>This concluding module looks at the use of office equipment in a business environment and details what is relevant to those working in administration and how this should be used safely.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Types of office equipment, their features and use</li>\r\n<li>Relevant equipment and resources</li>\r\n<li>Following manufacturers&rsquo; instructions when operating equipment</li>\r\n<li>Limiting waste</li>\r\n<li>Keeping equipment clean and hygienic</li>\r\n<li>Equipment faults</li>\r\n<li>Meeting work standards and deadlines</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(924, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through the Underpinning Knowledge you should of gained the Knowledge to take the Exam.</p>', 1),
(925, 'Module One - Idea to reality, why set up in the first place', '<p>This module provides learners with an introduction to the steps of transforming an idea into a realistic business proposition, highlighting the various factors that should be considered and implemented.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Getting started</li>\r\n<li>Getting organised</li>\r\n<li>Developing a plan</li>\r\n<li>Motivation</li>\r\n<li>Role models</li>\r\n<li>Business success and failure</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(926, 'Module Two - Market Research - What do you need to know?', '<p>This module outlines the various factors that you need to know when conducting research into the market. The module aims to give a detailed overview that answers questions such as: &lsquo;who or what is the competition? Who are their customers? What is generally happening in the marketplace? How much completion is there? How big is the market?&rsquo;</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is Market Research?</li>\r\n<li>Where to start?</li>\r\n<li>Conducting telephone or face to face research</li>\r\n<li>Ways of conducting market research</li>\r\n<li>How to manage data</li>\r\n<li>Analysing your strengths and weaknesses</li>\r\n<li>Marketing</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(927, 'Module Three - Business Legalities for the Entrepreneur', '<p>This module details the various legalities that must be considered, implemented and abided by when starting up and running your own business.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legal form</li>\r\n<li>Deciding on a business name</li>\r\n<li>Taking legal advice</li>\r\n<li>Trade Marks</li>\r\n<li>Legislation</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(928, 'Module Four - Business Planning', '<p>This module looks at the complexities of project planning and provides ideas on how you can manage each aspect through to successful conclusion. The module also explains how project planning is essential to ensure that your business gets off to a smooth start.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Project planning</li>\r\n<li>What is a project?</li>\r\n<li>Project types</li>\r\n<li>Project stages</li>\r\n<li>Implementation and control</li>\r\n<li>Project closure</li>\r\n<li>Problems, issues and solutions</li>\r\n<li>Post project plan review</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(929, 'Module Five - Customer Service', '<p>This module explains the importance of having good customer service in order to run a successful business and explores the various factors that should be considered and implemented in order to ensure that this is achieved.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What is a customer?</li>\r\n<li>When you are a customer</li>\r\n<li>What customers expect</li>\r\n<li>Who are your customers?</li>\r\n<li>The need for exceptional customer service</li>\r\n<li>Identify your customer&rsquo;s expectations and needs</li>\r\n<li>Representing your business</li>\r\n<li>Providing customers with information on products or services</li>\r\n<li>Customer feedback</li>\r\n<li>Ways of improving customer service</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(930, 'Module Six - Working with a Team', '<p>This module explains the implications of acquiring a business team and provides guidance on being a successful leader to ensure the effective running of your business.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Leading a team</li>\r\n<li>Leading and motivating</li>\r\n<li>Leadership styles</li>\r\n<li>Organising yourself and your time</li>\r\n<li>Setting objectives</li>\r\n<li>Planning</li>\r\n<li>Decision making</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining the quality of work</li>\r\n<li>Feedback and working relationships</li>\r\n<li>Help individuals to develop performance</li>\r\n<li>Develop yourself</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(931, 'Module Seven - Managing Operations', '<p>This module establishes and provides guidance on how to manage the various operations that need to be maintained in order for your business to run efficiently and sustain.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Where should you work from?</li>\r\n<li>Security</li>\r\n<li>Health and safety</li>\r\n<li>Finance</li>\r\n<li>Coping with the day to day minutiae</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(932, 'Module Eight - Writing a Business Plan', '<p>This module enables you to consider the knowledge gained from the rest of the course and explores the various ways in which you can implement this effectively by providing detailed guidance on constructing a successful business plan.</p>\r\n<p>Areas which are covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>So, what should be in a business plan?</li>\r\n<li>Getting the pitch right</li>\r\n<li>Tips for success</li>\r\n<li>Constructing your business plan</li>\r\n<li>What to do next?</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(933, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through the Underpinning Knowledge you should of gained the Knowledge to take the Exam.</p>', 1),
(934, 'Module One - Theories of Crime (I) – Psychological', '<p>This module introduces the array of psychological theories that can be used to explain criminal activity and explores numerous perspectives surrounding areas such as; psychodynamic theories, effects of the media on learning and personality and crime. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Psychodynamic theories</li>\r\n<li>Behaviourist theories</li>\r\n<li>Differential Association Theory</li>\r\n<li>Social learning theory</li>\r\n<li>Effects of the media on learning</li>\r\n<li>Control theories</li>\r\n<li>Personality and crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(935, 'Module Two - Theories of Crime (II) – Biological', '<p>This module examines the range of biological theories that can be used to asses criminal activity and explores perspectives around areas such as; genetic factors and chromosomal studies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Biological theories of offending</li>\r\n<li>Somatotype theories of offending</li>\r\n<li>Genetic factors</li>\r\n<li>Chromosomal studies</li>\r\n<li>Gender differences &amp; crime</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(936, 'Module Three - Theories of Crime (III) – Sociological', '<p>This module introduces the sociological theories that can be applied to examine the prevalence of criminal activity and explores relevant areas such as; social factors and labelling theory.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Methodological approaches</li>\r\n<li>Social factors</li>\r\n<li>Labelling theory</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(937, 'Module Four - Theories of Crime (IV) – Developmental', '<p>This module again studies theories of crime, this time focussing on developmental perspectives though the study of areas such as; criminal careers, control theories and moral development theories.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Criminal careers</li>\r\n<li>Key longitudinal studies</li>\r\n<li>Moffitt Dual Developmental Pathway Theory</li>\r\n<li>Control theories</li>\r\n<li>Piaget\'s moral development theory</li>\r\n<li>Moral development theories</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(938, 'Module Five - Substance Misuse (Drugs, Alcohol & Crime)', '<p>This module looks at substance abuse and examines relevant areas such as drug use as recreation and more importantly the strong link between drugs, alcohol and crime.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Substance misuse and crime</li>\r\n<li>An illegal act</li>\r\n<li>A causal relationship?</li>\r\n<li>Heroin - a historical context</li>\r\n<li>Typology of drug abusers</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(939, 'Module Six - Violence & Violent Offences', '<p>This module studies violence and looks to assess the act of committing violent offences though the exploration of areas such as; frustration and aggression, explanation models and mental health.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Crime, violence and aggression</li>\r\n<li>Frustration &amp; aggression</li>\r\n<li>Frustration and violence</li>\r\n<li>Explanation models</li>\r\n<li>Mental health and violence</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(940, 'Module Seven - Sex Offences', '<p>The focus of this module is inappropriate sexual behaviour that constitutes a criminal offence and the knowledge contained looks to explore this prevalence, though the study of areas such as; risk factors, theoretical explanations and the justice gap.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Rape, sexual assault, sexual violence and sex offending</li>\r\n<li>Risk factors</li>\r\n<li>Theoretical explanations</li>\r\n<li>Evolutionary and feminist perspectives on rape</li>\r\n<li>The justice gap</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(941, 'Module Eight - Arson', '<p>This module studies the concept of fire related crime and aims to explore the possible reasons behind engaging in this act, looking at areas of relevance such as; measuring arson, the evolutionary psychology of fire learning and interaction theories.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Measuring arson</li>\r\n<li>Developmental stages of fire-setting</li>\r\n<li>Possible motives</li>\r\n<li>Evolutionary psychology of fire learning</li>\r\n<li>Social &amp; environmental theories</li>\r\n<li>Interaction theories</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(942, 'Module Nine - Stalking', '<p>This module studies the behaviour of stalking individuals, exploring this act in relation to criminal activity and assessing the psychology behind this through the study of areas such as; legislation, victims of stalkers and stalking limitations.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation</li>\r\n<li>Who are stalkers?</li>\r\n<li>Typology of stalkers</li>\r\n<li>Victims of stalkers</li>\r\n<li>Psychological explanations</li>\r\n<li>Stalking &ndash; the limitations</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(943, 'Module Ten - Serial Murder', '<p>This module looks to explore the reasoning behind why people continually commit murder and examines areas of relevance such as; mass murders, serial murder explanations and case studies.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mass murderers</li>\r\n<li>Serial murder</li>\r\n<li>Explanations for serial murder</li>\r\n<li>Serial killer case study</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(944, 'Module Eleven - Terrorism', '<p>This module looks at assessing the act of terrorism through a psychological perspective and examines numerous areas of relevance to this idea, such as; terror groups and hate.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Defining terrorism</li>\r\n<li>Psychological aspects of terrorism</li>\r\n<li>Terrorism research</li>\r\n<li>Different terror groups</li>\r\n<li>Hate</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(945, 'Module Twelve - Mental Health & Crime', '<p>This module explores the relationship between mental health conditions and criminal activity through the study of relevant areas, such as; Schizophrenia, amnesia and psychopathy.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Schizophrenia</li>\r\n<li>Dissociative Identity Disorder</li>\r\n<li>Amnesia</li>\r\n<li>Psychopathy</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(946, 'Module Thirteen - Offender Profiling', '<p>This module looks specifically at the process of profiling criminal offenders and examines a multitude of the relevant areas, such as; the typological approach, profiling in Britain and investigative psychology.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The history of profiling</li>\r\n<li>Profiling &amp; the FBI</li>\r\n<li>Organised/disorganised offender</li>\r\n<li>The typological approach</li>\r\n<li>Profiling in Britain</li>\r\n<li>Changes in the investigation of crime</li>\r\n<li>Investigative psychology</li>\r\n<li>The behavioural investigative advisor</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(947, 'Module Fourteen - Geographical Profiling', '<p>This module examines the establishment of crime related traits through the application of geographical profiling, which involves the study of a criminal&rsquo;s activity space.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The North American approach</li>\r\n<li>The British approach</li>\r\n<li>Differences in approach</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(948, 'Module Fifteen - Police Interviewing – The Suspect & The Witness', '<p>This module details the role of conducting various types of interviews in the police profession and examines areas of relevance such as; investigative suspect interviewing and the enhanced cognitive interview.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Investigative interviewing- the suspect</li>\r\n<li>Investigative Interviewing- the witness</li>\r\n<li>Cognitive interview</li>\r\n<li>Enhanced Cognitive Interview</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(949, 'Module Sixteen - Detecting Deception (Lie Detection, Polygraph etc.)', '<p>This module studies the deceptive act of lying and more specifically its strong link with crime. The content contained looks to explore why people lie and the various methods used to detect and measure crime related lying.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why do people lie?</li>\r\n<li>Ekman&rsquo;s theory of lie detection</li>\r\n<li>Verbal</li>\r\n<li>Statement validity analysis (SVA)</li>\r\n<li>The polygraph</li>\r\n<li>Criticisms</li>\r\n<li>Countermeasures</li>\r\n<li>Polygraph &amp; sex offenders</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(950, 'Module Seventeen - Eyewitness Testimony', '<p>This concluding module looks at the occurrence of eyewitnesses at the scene of a crime and examines their credibility in relation the criminal investigation, through the study of areas such as; eyewitness memory and conceptual systems.</p>\r\n<p>Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Eyewitness memory</li>\r\n<li>Conceptual systems</li>\r\n<li>Perception, memory and eyewitness testimony</li>\r\n<li>Personal perception and memory</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(951, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through the Underpinning Knowledge you should of gained the Knowledge to take the Exam.</p>', 1),
(952, 'witness testimonies', '', 1),
(953, 'Module One - Facial and Skincare', '<p>This introductory module explores the structure of skin and looks at how its health and condition is essential to those provides beauty therapy services. The knowledge contained looks at the process of implementing facials and explains how to deal with facial skin issues. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Facial treatments</li>\r\n<li>Skin structure</li>\r\n<li>Skin types</li>\r\n<li>Skin analysis</li>\r\n<li>Treatments</li>\r\n<li>Contra-indications</li>\r\n<li>Conditions</li>\r\n<li>Mask therapy</li>\r\n<li>Massage&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(954, 'Module Two - Eyelash and Eyebrow Treatments', '<p>This module is focussed on the types of treatment available for eyelash and eyebrows and examines considerations that should be taken when engaging clients with services such as eyelash tinting, eyebrow shaping and applying false lashes. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Skin test</li>\r\n<li>Eyelash tinting</li>\r\n<li>Contra-indications</li>\r\n<li>Eyebrow tinting</li>\r\n<li>Eyebrow shaping</li>\r\n<li>False eyelashes</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(955, 'Module Three - Manicure and Hand Treatments', '<p>This module looks specifically at the hands in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained examines the nails in relation to maintaining hand health when providing services such as; manicures and nail art. Specific areas covered include: &nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Nail facts</li>\r\n<li>Common nail problems</li>\r\n<li>Nail disorders</li>\r\n<li>Manicure consultation</li>\r\n<li>Manicure procedure</li>\r\n<li>Enamelling the nails</li>\r\n<li>Nail art</li>\r\n<li>Nail piercing&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(956, 'Module Four - Pedicure and Foot Treatments', '<p>This module specifically studies the feet in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained looks at health care considerations of the feet and explores treatments such as, pedicures, Garra Rufa fish pedicures and artificial nails. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Common Foot and Nail Diseases</li>\r\n<li>Pedicure procedures</li>\r\n<li>Foot care products</li>\r\n<li>Luxury and Specialist Hand, Foot, and Nail Treatments</li>\r\n<li>Garra Rufa Fish Pedicures</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n<li>Artificial nails&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(957, 'Module Five - Waxing and Temporary Methods of Hair Removal', '<p>This module explores the practice of hair removal in relation to providing beauty treatments. The knowledge contained examines a range of relevant subject areas such as; the types and colour of hair, strong hair growth and waxing. Specific areas covered include:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Body and facial hair</li>\r\n<li>Hair colour</li>\r\n<li>Causes of Superfluous and Strong Hair Growth</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with male clients</li>\r\n<li>Waxing</li>\r\n<li>Hair growth cycle</li>\r\n<li>Effects of different methods of removal on the hair</li>\r\n<li>Bleaching</li>\r\n<li>Permanent Methods of Hair Removal</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(958, 'Module Six - Advanced Nail Techniques', '<p>This module is concerned with the application of more advanced nail beauty techniques when offering treatments and examines how to practice procedures such as; gel nails, fibreglass nails and acrylic nails. Specific areas covered include: &nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Allergies</li>\r\n<li>Gel nails</li>\r\n<li>Fibreglass nails</li>\r\n<li>Acrylic nails</li>\r\n<li>General Homecare Advice for Artificial Nails</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(959, 'Module Seven - Make-Up Application to the Face', '<p>This module studies the practice of applying make up to the face as part of beauty therapy treatment and looks at a range of relevant considerations such as; conducting a make-up consultation, product usage and treatment times. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Make-up consultation</li>\r\n<li>Record Card and Treatment Plan</li>\r\n<li>Product Formulations</li>\r\n<li>Mineral Make-up</li>\r\n<li>Product Use and Information</li>\r\n<li>Preparation for Make-up</li>\r\n<li>Client Preparation</li>\r\n<li>Brushes and tools</li>\r\n<li>Make-up application</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(960, 'Module Eight - Science and Cosmetology', '<p>This module details the make-up of products used and made available when providing beauty therapy services and also relevant sterilisation, hygiene and safety issues that also need to be considered when providing treatments. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Products for the skin</li>\r\n<li>Results</li>\r\n<li>Cost</li>\r\n<li>Convenience</li>\r\n<li>Animal testing</li>\r\n<li>Ingredients</li>\r\n<li>Products</li>\r\n<li>Sterilisation and hygiene</li>\r\n<li>Safety&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(961, 'Module Nine - Anatomy and Physiology', '<p>This module now looks at the biological terms that individuals working in the beauty industry should have an understanding of, in order to provide safe and effective treatments. Important subject areas such as; blood, tissue and muscles are examined. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Anatomical terms</li>\r\n<li>Cells</li>\r\n<li>Tissue</li>\r\n<li>Blood</li>\r\n<li>The lymphatic system</li>\r\n<li>The human skeleton</li>\r\n<li>Muscles</li>\r\n<li>The skin</li>\r\n<li>Hair</li>\r\n<li>Other body systems&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(962, 'Module Ten - Health and Safety', '<p>This module looks specifically at health and safety when working in a beauty therapy setting and examines important areas that need to be considered, such as; the Health and Safety at Work Act 1974, safety signs and waste disposal. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Health &amp; safety at work act (HASAW) 1974</li>\r\n<li>Acts applicable to all workplaces</li>\r\n<li>Manual handling operations regulations 1992</li>\r\n<li>Control of substances hazardous to health regulations 2002 (COSHH)</li>\r\n<li>Safety signs</li>\r\n<li>Accidents/ injuries and disease</li>\r\n<li>Hazard management</li>\r\n<li>Maintaining hygiene&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Salon environment</li>\r\n<li>Waste disposal&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(963, 'Module Eleven - Consultation', '<p>This module details the practice of providing consultations to clients as part of the beauty therapy process to ensure needs are met, and examines important factors such as; the record card, skin consultation and methods of communication. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Record card</li>\r\n<li>Consultation for facial treatments</li>\r\n<li>Signs of skin ageing</li>\r\n<li>Skin consultation</li>\r\n<li>Methods of communication&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(964, 'Module Twelve - Promotions and Retailing', '<p>This module explores the process of selling your services when working in beauty therapy. This broad term encompasses the selling actual products over the counter in addition to promoting the actual treatments that you provide. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Retailing in the beauty salon</li>\r\n<li>Setting and meeting targets</li>\r\n<li>Consumer legislation&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(965, 'Module Thirteen - Reception', '<p>This module is concerned with the reception duties required in order to run successful beauty services and examines important considerations, such as; welcoming clients, dealing with complaints and insurance. Specific areas covered include:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Salon systems and operations</li>\r\n<li>The reception area</li>\r\n<li>Welcoming clients</li>\r\n<li>Treatment times</li>\r\n<li>Dealing with complaints</li>\r\n<li>Insurance</li>\r\n<li>Employment law</li>\r\n<li>Security</li>\r\n<li>Stock</li>\r\n<li>Emergency procedures&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(966, 'Module Fourteen - Career Opportunities and Continuing Professional Development', '<p>This concluding module draws upon the knowledge conveyed in the previous modules and examines how to apply what you have learned to career opportunities and professional development within your role. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Employability: Skills for finding and keeping a job</li>\r\n<li>Code of conduct</li>\r\n<li>Code of ethics</li>\r\n<li>Code of practice</li>\r\n<li>Personal and professional development</li>\r\n<li>Time management</li>\r\n<li>Team work</li>\r\n<li>Curriculum Vitae</li>\r\n<li>Further techniques&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(967, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through the Underpinning Knowledge you should of&nbsp;gained the Knowledge to take the Exam.</p>', 1),
(968, 'Module 1 - Cyber-dependent Crime (I) - Hacking & Hacktivism', '<p>This introductory module is focussed on one of the most widely analysed and debated forms of cybercrime that involves illegal activities such as illicit lock-picking and manipulation of worldwide phone/computer systems. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Hacking What do hackers actually do?</li>\r\n<li>Hacktivism Why do they do it?</li>\r\n<li>Developmental Psychology</li>\r\n<li>Theories Ethical Hacking</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(969, 'Module 2 - Cyber-dependent Crime (II) – Malware', '<p>This module is concerned with the creation and use of computer codes and programmes that cause various degrees of disruption to the targeted operation or damage to data. The materials study the most common methods used, the differences between them and the impact they can have on the victim. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Viruses</li>\r\n<li>Anti-virus providers</li>\r\n<li>Worms</li>\r\n<li>Trojans</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(970, 'Module 3 - Cyber-dependent Crime (III) - DDoS Attacks', '<p>This module studies the specific cybercrime that involves flooding an online service with bogus traffic, thereby keeping real users from using the service. The materials consider relevant factors involved in this crime, such as; the main processes involved in the DDos attacks, the weaknesses of them and who the typical type of culprit is. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What denial-of-service attacks are</li>\r\n<li>The main processes involved in DDoS attacks</li>\r\n<li>The weaknesses in the majority of DDoS attacks</li>\r\n<li>The difference between DoS and DDoS attacks</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(971, 'Module 4 - Cyber-enabled Crime (I) - Cyber-Frauds, Scams & Cons', '<p>This module looks at the widespread cybercrime that preys on those who fall for the criminal&rsquo;s deceit. This is of course the targeting of communications that intend to scam, con or defraud the victim and the module studies the most common ways criminals try to do this and how effective their methods are. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Advanced Fee Fraud Why do Nigerian scammers say they are from Nigeria?</li>\r\n<li>&lsquo;Fake escrow&rsquo; or &lsquo;Auction&rsquo; Scams</li>\r\n<li>Phishing and Spoofing</li>\r\n<li>Romance Scams</li>\r\n<li>Cyberfrauds, scams &amp; cons: The advantages for cybercriminals</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(972, 'Module 5 - Cyber-enabled Crime (II) – Theft', '<p>This module provides an insight into cybercriminal activities that are implemented with the aim to steal from the target victim and the materials study prevalent methods such as; internet auction frauds and identity theft. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Internet auction frauds</li>\r\n<li>Theft of computer resources</li>\r\n<li>Identity Theft</li>\r\n<li>Types of e-crime carried out on social networks</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(973, 'Module 6 - Cyber-enabled Crime (III) - Sex Offending', '<p>This module covers the sensitive subject area of online sex offending and considers what exactly constitutes this type of crime. The materials study issues such as paedophilia and grooming and examines strategies which are used to help reduce this type of crime. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<p>Internet Sex Offending</p>\r\n<p>Paedophilia &amp; Grooming</p>\r\n<p>Proliferation of indecent images of children (IIOC)</p>\r\n<p>Investigation of Online Child Sexual Exploitation</p>', 0),
(974, 'Module 7 - Cyber-enabled Crime (IV) – Cyberterrorism', '<p>This module considers one of the most pressing cybercrime concerns of modern times, that is the use of technology to facilitate terrorism. The module considers issues such as; defining cyberterrorism, objectives of cyberterrorism and how to tackle the problem. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Towards a definition of cyberterrorism</li>\r\n<li>Different Cyberterrorist Groups</li>\r\n<li>Objectives of Cyberterrorism</li>\r\n<li>Cyberterrorism vs Cybercrime</li>\r\n<li>Towards an understanding of Cyberterrorism</li>\r\n<li>Defining hate</li>\r\n<li>Defining ignorance</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(975, 'Module 8 - Cyberstalking', '<p>This module studies the repeated and persistent attempt by an individual to harass an individual using the internet or an open network. The materials examine the type of individual who might engage in this criminal activity and considers the varying methods used and their level of severity. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The Cyberstalker&rsquo;s Profile</li>\r\n<li>Typology of stalkers</li>\r\n<li>The victims</li>\r\n<li>Psychological explanations</li>\r\n<li>Stalking- the limitations</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(976, 'Module 9 - Cyberbullying', '<p>This module studies the act of bullying through the use of technology. The materials look at how this differs from conventional bullying, the various online platforms that can be used to facilitate it and how the typical cyberbully perpetrator differs from your typical bully. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<p>Cyberbullying vs bullying</p>\r\n<p>Types of Cyberbullying &amp; Cyberbully</p>\r\n<p>A psychology of Cyberbullying</p>', 0),
(977, 'Module 10 - Organised Cybercrime', '<p>This module now considers cybercrime on a larger scale and examines the types and prevalence of organised cybercrime. The materials look at illegal activities such as human or drug trafficking and considers how criminals utilize online methods to help assist with crimes such as these. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Forms of organised crime</li>\r\n<li>Social engineering</li>\r\n<li>Human trafficking</li>\r\n<li>The organised criminals</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(978, 'Module 11 -Virtual ‘Pirates’: Intellectual property, copyright & piracy', '<p>This module examines the widespread issue whereby individuals obtain and in some cases distribute copyrighted materials. Many individuals are guilty of engaging in this criminal activity, known as Virtual Piracy, and the materials look at what constitutes a crime of this nature and why it is so common in people who would not necessarily be associated with other types of crime. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Movie Piracy &amp; illegal downloading</li>\r\n<li>Music Piracy &amp; illegal downloading</li>\r\n<li>Internet Piracy of Computer Software</li>\r\n<li>Illegal sharing of copyrighted book content</li>\r\n<li>Revealing the Pirates</li>\r\n<li>Contemporary Copyright Theft</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(979, 'Module 12 -e-Crime Investigation (I) - Legislation', '<p>This module is concerned with the various laws that are enforced within the UK to try and combat cybercrime. The materials look at which acts of legislation are in force to tackle specific types of cybercrime and examines the effectiveness of each law. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Legislation- Harassment</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Stalking</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Identity Theft &amp; Fraud</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Internet Sex Offending</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Hacking</li>\r\n<li>Legislation- Jurisdiction issues</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(980, 'Module 13 -e-Crime Investigation (II) - Digital Evidence', '<p>This module details the importance of obtaining and analysing digital evidence in order to help assist with cybercrime investigations. The materials examine relevant considerations in this process, such as; where to obtain evidence and how to preserve evidence so it is appropriate for court proceedings. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The importance of Digital evidence</li>\r\n<li>Digital evidence- where can it be found</li>\r\n<li>ACPO evidence gathering principles</li>\r\n<li>Digital evidence- the legal perspective</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(981, 'Module 14 - e-Crime Investigation (II) – Investigative Strategy & Procedure', '<p>This module is focussed on the procedures in place to investigate cybercrimes and studies the specific actions which are implemented in order to successfully solve a crime, such as; investigative Units and the UK Cyber Security Strategy. The problems associated with tackling these types of crimes is then explored. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<p>Investigative procedure</p>\r\n<p>Investigative Units</p>\r\n<p>Investigation of online child sexual exploitation</p>\r\n<p>The UK Cyber Security Strategy</p>\r\n<p>Investigative problems</p>\r\n<p>Investigative case study</p>', 0),
(982, 'Module 15 - Cyber Security – The Threat', '<p>This module considers a wider perspective of cybercrime in relation to the prevention measures we have in place and how effective these may be in relation to the nature of the threat we face from ever evolving cybercriminal activities. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Governmental non-police organisations</li>\r\n<li>Multi-agency cross-sector partnerships</li>\r\n<li>The future of cybersecurity</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(983, 'Module 16 - Reducing Cyber Risk', '<p>This concluding module looks at the types of measures that we can take in order to help reduce the risk of cybercrime occurring and the materials focus on areas of relevance, such as; technical protection and additional security measures which can be made. Specific areas covered include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Basic technical protection from cyber attacks</li>\r\n<li>ICT use and risk in an educational setting</li>\r\n<li>Additional security measures</li>\r\n</ul>', 0),
(984, 'Exam', '<p>Once you have read through the Underpinning Knowledge you should of&nbsp;gained the Knowledge to take the Exam.</p>', 0);
